<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<H2>Random House v. Joan Collins</H2> 

<P><A HREF="excerpt.html">Excerpt of Joan Collins Manuscript</A><BR>
An excerpt from "Hell Hath No Fury" by Joan Collins.</P>

<P><A HREF="contract.html">Contract Between Joan Collins and Random House</A><BR>
What did Joan Collins agree to when she signed a multi-million dollar book deal with Random House? Read the contract to find out.</P>

<P><A HREF="affirm2.html">Joan Collins Dec. 11 Affirmation</A><BR>
According to Joan Collins, she submitted the complete manuscript for "A Ruling Passion," on schedule. The manuscript follows the outline she devised with Random House editor Rosemary Cheetham, she said. But after Cheetham resigned, her new editor lost faith in the project and told her "nobody is interested" in the book's characters. To back out of the contract, the publisher created the ploy that she didn't finish her work on time, Collins said. In this Dec. 11, 1995 affirmation in support of motion for a summary judgment, Collins recounts her deteriorating relationship with her publisher.</P>

<P><A HREF="affirm1.html">Joan Collins Jan. 3 Affirmation</A><BR>
After topless photos of her appeared in The Globe in 1991, Joan Collins sued the tabloid newspaper for damages, claiming that she suffered such aggravation that she was unable to continue writing. Random House is trying to use this claim against her, maintaining that it is proof that she did not submit a complete manuscript for "A Ruling Passion." In this Jan. 3, 1996 affirmation Joan Collins says, "I now realize that I was mistaken when I made those statements."</P>

<P><A HREF="answer3.html">Joan Collins Amended Answer to Complaint</A><BR>
In this third amended answer to Random House's second complaint, Joan Collins and her production company claim that she submitted her manuscripts on or ahead of schedule even though Random House never provided the editorial assistance it was required to provide. Collins says she is entitled to paid advances and is countersuing for additional advances that she claims were never paid. The document was filed Nov. 30, 1995.</P>

<P><A HREF="answer2.html">Joan Collins' Answer to Complaint</A><BR>
This is Joan Collins' answer to the complaint in the Random House lawsuit. Her personal answer and the answer from her company were filed separately (see below).</P>

<P><A HREF="answer1.html">Answer from Joan Collins' Company</A><BR>
This is the answer from Joan Collins' company to the complaint in the Random House lawsuit. Included in this document are counter-claims against Random House and cross-claims against Ms. Collins' agent, Irving "Swifty" Lazar.</P>

<P><A HREF="complaint.html">Joan Collins Complaint</A><BR>
This is the (second amended) complaint in the matter of Random House v. actress/author Joan Collins, wherein the publisher claims it is owed a refund of the advance money it paid Ms. Collins for her latest book, alleging that the manuscript she delivered was unusable. Also named in the complaint is Ms. Collins' agent, Irving "Swifty" Lazar.</P>
