<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A HREF="/map/library.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/library.gif" ISMAP ALT="Court TV Library" BORDER="0"></A>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<P>Dallas Cowboy's owner Jerry Jones calls the NFL's licensing organization a "price fixing cartel" in this Nov. 6, 1995 complaint. In 1993 and 1994, merchandise with his team's logo generated more than 20% of the revenue of all licensed NFL merchandise. He complains that it is unfair for the Cowboys to share this revenue equally with other teams.</P>
<HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT>
<PRE>
UNITED STATES DISTRICT COURT 
SOUTHERN DISTRICT OF NEW YORK 
 
 
DALLAS COWBOYS FOOTBALL CLUB, LTD.; 
TEXAS STADIUM CORPORATION; PRO SILVER 
STAR, LTD.; JWJ CORPORATION; and 
JERRAL W. JONES, 
 
Plaintiffs, 
 
- against - 
 
NATIONAL FOOTBALL LEAGUE TRUST, THROUGH 
ITS TRUSTEES; PAUL TAGLIABUE, 
DANIEL ROONEY, AND DOES 1-20, AS TRUSTEES 
OF THE NATIONAL FOOTBALL LEAGUE TRUST; 
NATIONAL FOOTBALL LEAGUE PROPERTIES, INC.; 
NATIONAL FOOTBALL LEAGUE; PAUL TAGLIABUE; 
NEAL AUSTRIAN; SARA LEVINSON; ROGER 
HEADRICK; J. WAYNE WEAVER; STEVE GUTMAN; 
DANIEL ROONEY; TAYLOR SMITH; 
DOES 21-60; B&B HOLDINGS; THE 
FIVE SMITHS, INC.; BUFFALO BILLS, INC.; 
RICHARDSON SPORTS, L.P.; 
CHICAGO BEARS FOOTBALL CLUB, INC.; 
CINCINNATI BENGALS, INC.; CLEVELAND 
BROWNS FOOTBALL CO.; PDB SPORTS, INC.; 
DETROIT LIONS, INC.; GREEN BAY PACKERS 
INC.; HOUSTON OILERS, INC.; 
INDIANAPOLIS COLTS, INC.; JACKSONVILLE 
JAGUARS, LTD; KANSAS CITY CHIEFS FOOTBALL 
CLUB, INC.; MIAMI DOLPHINS, INC.; NEW 
ENGLAND PATRIOTS, L.P.; NEW ORLEANS 
LOUISIANA SAINTS, L.P.; NEW YORK FOOTBALL 
GIANTS, INC.; NEW YORK JETS FOOTBALL CLUB, 
INC.; MINNESOTA VIKINGS FOOTBALL CLUB, INC.; 
PHILADELPHIA EAGLES, L.P.; PITTSBURGH 
STEELER SPORTS, INC.; SAINT LOUIS RAMS 
FOOTBALL CO.; CHARGERS FOOTBALL COMPANY; 
SAN FRANCISCO FORTY NINERS; SEATTLE 
SEAHAWKS, INC.; BUCCANEERS, L.P.; 
and PRO-FOOTBALL, INC.,    
 
Defendants. 
 
 
JURY TRIAL DEMANDED 
 
VERIFIED COMPLAINT 
FOR DAMAGES AND 
INJUNCTIVE AND 
DECLARATORY RELIEF 
95 Civ. __________ 
 
 
          Plaintiffs Dallas Cowboys Football Club, Ltd., 
Texas Stadium Corporation, Pro Silver Star, Ltd., JWJ 
Corporation, and Jerral W. Jones, by and through their 
attorneys, allege upon knowledge as to their own acts and 
otherwise upon information and belief, as follows: 
 
Preliminary Statement 
 
1.    Abuses by trusts like the Standard Oil Trust were 
among the driving forces behind enactment of the Sherman 
Antitrust Act in 1890.  Yet in 1982, the National Football 
League created the aptly-named  NFL Trust  to control the 
licensing of the marks of the NFL's member clubs.  The NFL 
Trust is a classic price-fixing cartel that has eliminated 
free competition among NFL clubs.  The cartel has harmed 
consumers, forced new NFL owners (such as plaintiffs) to 
cede control over licensing to the Trust, harassed 
plaintiffs for opposing the cartel, and tolerated 
mismanagement by its exclusive licensee, NFL Properties. 
Plaintiffs ask the Court to dismantle the NFL Trust and 
replace it with free market competition. 
 
2.   Plaintiffs are ready, willing, and able to compete 
vigorously with others in a free marketplace.  Breaking up 
the illegal cartel will permit plaintiffs and other member 
clubs to engage in spirited competition with one another 
(and with the NFL) in the licensing of professional football 
marks.  Ending the cartel will also benefit consumers by 
making the licensing process more responsive to consumer 
demand. 
 
3.   The NFL defendants have tried to expand the cartel's 
reach even beyond the broad rights granted to it by 
contract.  In the 1982 agreements setting up the cartel, 
each member club retained for itself, for example, the 
independent right to choose what apparel and marks its 
coaches, owners, and players would wear during football 
games.  The NFL defendants have nevertheless claimed for 
themselves the purported right to dictate what marks may and 
may not appear on the clothing worn by club personnel during 
games.  Plaintiffs ask the Court to issue a declaration 
correcting the NFL defendants  false claims on this critical 
issue. 
 
4.   Plaintiffs have suffered substantial monetary losses as 
a result of defendants  unlawful conduct.  Most obviously, 
the NFL cartel has prevented the Dallas Cowboys from 
independent commercial use of its marks during many years 
when those marks have been of substantial value.  The NFL 
defendants have caused plaintiffs further losses by falsely 
claiming (and selling to others) the right to determine what 
apparel member club personnel will wear during football 
games and by harassing plaintiffs in their routine business 
operations.  These losses have been compounded by the NFL 
defendants  waste of the income generated by the cartel 
through bloated administrative expenditures.  Plaintiffs 
seek $200 million in actual damages, trebled under the 
federal antitrust laws, in addition to an amount to be 
determined at trial for the NFL defendants  breaches of 
contract and common law duties.  Because the NFL defendants 
misconduct is egregious, deliberate, and malicious, 
plaintiffs further seek $150 million in punitive damages for 
violations of the NFL defendants  common law duties. 
 
Nature of the Action 
 
5.   Plaintiffs bring this action for compensatory, treble, 
and punitive damages, and for injunctive and declaratory 
relief, based on violations of Sections 1 and 2 of the 
Sherman Antitrust Act, as well as for breach of contract, 
breach of fiduciary duty, violation of common law due 
process, tortious interference with prospective economic 
advantage, and unjust enrichment.  Plaintiffs also bring 
derivative claims, on behalf of the NFL Trust and NFL 
Properties, for breaches of contract, for breach of 
fiduciary duty, and for negligence, waste, and 
mismanagement.  Finally, plaintiffs seek a declaratory 
judgment of non-infringement under the Lanham Act and other 
applicable laws with regard to matters challenged by 
defendant NFL Properties in litigation now pending in this 
Court. 
 
Jurisdiction and Venue 
 
6.   This Court has jurisdiction over the subject matter of 
this action pursuant to 28 U.S.C. Sections 1331 (federal 
question), 1337 (commerce and antitrust regulations), 1338 
(trademark and related cases), and 1367 (supplemental 
jurisdiction).  Plaintiffs  federal claims arise under 
Sections 1 and 2 of the Sherman Antitrust Act, 15 U.S.C. 
Sections 1 and 2, and under the Lanham Act, 15 U.S.C. 
Sections 1051 et seq., and are instituted pursuant to 
Sections 4, 12, and 16 of the Clayton Act, 15 U.S.C. 
Sections 15, 22, and 26, and the Declaratory Judgment Act, 
28 U.S.C. Section 2201. 
 
7.    Venue in this District is proper under 28 U.S.C. 
Section 1391(b)(2) and (3) and 15 U.S.C. Sections 15 and 22. 
 
 
Parties 
 
8.   Plaintiff Dallas Cowboys Football Club, Ltd. ( Cowboys 
Partnership ) is a Texas limited partnership with its 
principal place of business in Irving, Texas.  The Cowboys 
Partnership owns, among other things, the mark  Dallas 
Cowboys,  a federally registered service mark.  The Cowboys 
Partnership is a shareholder of NFL Properties and a 
beneficiary of the NFL Trust. 
 
9.   Plaintiff Texas Stadium Corporation is a Delaware 
corporation with its principal place of business in Irving, 
Texas.  Texas Stadium Corporation operates Texas Stadium, 
owns a long-term leasehold for Texas Stadium and the 
surrounding land, and owns the leasehold improvements. 
Texas Stadium is among the best-known facilities in Texas. 
The Stadium is used almost every day of the year for events, 
including rock concerts, revival meetings, county fairs, 
high school sports playoffs, monster truck and motocross 
races, art festivals, trade shows, wedding receptions, and 
Girl Scout events. 
 
10.  Plaintiff Pro Silver Star, Ltd. ( Pro Silver Star ) is 
a Texas limited partnership with its principal place of 
business in Irving, Texas.  Pro Silver Star has acted as the 
agent for the Cowboys Partnership, Texas Stadium 
Corporation, Jones, and the head coach of the Cowboys with 
respect to certain advertising and promotional services, and 
is a party to certain agreements for such services. 
 
11.  JWJ Corporation is a Texas corporation with its 
principal place of business in Irving, Texas.  JWJ 
Corporation is the sole general partner and majority owner 
of the Cowboys Partnership. 
 
12.  Jerral W. Jones ( Jones ) is an individual.  In 1989, 
Jones acquired a controlling interest in the Cowboys 
Partnership, which he subsequently transferred to JWJ 
Corporation.  Jones is currently the sole stockholder of JWJ 
Corporation.  Jones also owns indirect interests in Texas 
Stadium Corporation and Pro Silver Star. 
 
13.  Defendant NFL Trust is a New York trust formed for the 
purpose of jointly controlling, with certain limited 
exceptions, the right to use or license the trademarks, 
trade names, logos, and service marks (collectively  marks ) 
of NFL member clubs and the NFL itself. 
 
14.  Defendant National Football League (the  NFL ) is an 
unincorporated association with its headquarters in New 
York, New York.  Each NFL club is a member of the NFL. 
 
15.  Defendant National Football League Properties, Inc. ( 
NFL Properties ) is a California corporation with its 
principal place of business in New York, New York.  NFL 
Properties was created in 1963 for the purpose of 
conducting, on a joint basis, commercial exploitation of the 
marks of the NFL and its member clubs. 
 
16.  The following listed defendants own and operate 28 of 
the 30 existing NFL member clubs, which play home games in 
the cities listed below (collectively the  member clubs ): 
 
 
