17.  Paul Tagliabue is the Commissioner of the NFL. 
 
18.  Neil Austrian is the President of the NFL. 
 
19.  Sara Levinson is the President of NFL Properties. 
 
20.  Roger Headrick is the chairman of the Executive 
Committee of NFL Properties, and on information and belief, 
J. Wayne Weaver, Steve Gutman, Daniel Rooney, and Taylor 
Smith are members of that committee. 
 
21.  On information and belief, Paul Tagliabue and Daniel 
Rooney are Trustees of the NFL Trust.  Does 1-20 are current 
or former Trustees of the NFL Trust whose identities are 
presently unknown to plaintiffs. 
 
22.  Does 21-40 are current or former officers or agents of 
NFL Properties, or members of its Executive Committee, whose 
identities are presently unknown to plaintiffs. 
 
23.  Does 41-60 are current or former officers or agents of 
the NFL, whose identities are presently unknown to 
plaintiffs. 
 
24.   In this Complaint, the term  NFL Defendants  means the 
NFL, NFL Properties, the NFL Trust, and the individual 
defendants employed by or acting as Trustees, officers, or 
agents of those entities, including Paul Tagliabue, Neil 
Austrian, Sara Levinson, Roger Headrick, J. Wayne Weaver, 
Steve Gutman, Daniel Rooney, Taylor Smith, and Does 1-60. 
 
Relevant Markets 
 
25.  For purposes of plaintiffs  antitrust claims, the 
relevant product markets include (a) the market for rights 
to use the marks of major league professional football clubs 
and otherwise to affiliate with major league professional 
football for purposes of advertising and promoting goods and 
services ( professional football sponsorship market ) and 
(b) the market for rights to use the marks of major league 
professional football clubs on apparel and other goods ( 
professional football merchandise market ). 
 
26.  The professional football sponsorship market involves 
the sale of rights to affiliate a company or product with 
professional football to promote the company or product. The 
market includes, for example, the sale of corporate 
sponsorships for individual professional football clubs and 
for the NFL; the sale of the right to use the marks of 
professional football clubs and the NFL in advertisements 
and promotions; and the sale of rights to have coaches, 
players, and  other club personnel wear particular apparel 
and logos during games ( sideline rights ).  At competitive 
prices, rights of this type have no close substitutes and 
are not reasonably interchangeable in use with any other 
products or rights, and the prices of rights of this type 
are not highly elastic with respect to prices of other 
products or rights. 
 
27.  The professional football merchandise market involves 
the sale of rights  to use the marks of professional 
football clubs or the NFL on apparel and other goods.  The 
market includes, for example, the sale of the right to use 
Dallas Cowboys or Chicago Bears logos, or the NFL Shield, on 
T-shirts, football jerseys, toys, home products, and 
sporting goods.  At competitive prices, rights of this type 
have no close substitutes and are not reasonably 
interchangeable in use with any other products or rights, 
and the prices of rights of this type are not highly elastic 
with respect to prices of other products or rights. 
 
28.  The relevant geographic market for assessing 
competition in the professional football sponsorship market 
and the professional football merchandise market is the 
United States.  Defendants have market power in the 
professional football sponsorship market and market power 
and monopoly power in the professional football merchandise 
market.  On information and belief, there are also local and 
regional submarkets of both the professional football 
sponsorship market and the professional football merchandise 
market. 
 
The NFL's Control over Major League Professional Football 
 
29.  Defendants  market power in the relevant product 
markets is derived in whole or in part from the NFL's 
position as the only significant provider of major league 
professional football in the United States.  Since the 
National Football League and the American Football League 
merged in 1966, all efforts to establish a football league 
to compete with the NFL have failed. 
 
30.  There are substantial barriers to entry into 
professional football and thus to entry into the 
professional football sponsorship market and professional 
football merchandise market.  As a result, the NFL and its 
member clubs are essentially the only sources of 
professional football marks in the United States. 
 
Interstate Commerce 
 
31.  The anticompetitive conduct alleged herein has taken 
place in interstate commerce and has restrained trade and 
commerce among the States.  Among other things, the products 
in the professional football sponsorship market and the 
professional football merchandise market are sold and/or 
licensed in interstate commerce.  Defendants  conduct has 
restrained trade and commerce among the States in these 
markets. 
 
DEFENDANTS UNLAWFUL CONDUCT 
 
A.   Defendants Creation of the Licensing Cartel 
 
32.  In or about 1982, the member clubs of the NFL formally 
established a cartel to control the licensing of the marks 
of all NFL clubs ( Club Marks ), as well as league-wide 
marks ( NFL Marks ), such as the NFL Shield and the phrase 
Super  Bowl.   The initial vehicle for establishment of the 
cartel was a Trust Agreement, entered into by the owners of 
all but two of the NFL member clubs, which created the NFL 
Trust.  In that Agreement, the clubs promised not to compete 
with one another, the NFL, or the newly created cartel in 
the commercial exploitation of their marks (subject to 
limited exceptions).     
 
33.  Pursuant to the same scheme, the NFL Trust 
simultaneously granted an exclusive license (as part of the 
License Agreement ) to defendant NFL Properties to 
administer the cartel.  The License Agreement requires NFL 
Properties to, among other things, use its best efforts to 
utilize and develop the Club Marks for the benefit of the 
Trust and its member club beneficiaries, which were intended 
third  party beneficiaries of the License Agreement.  Two 
member clubs (the Miami Dolphins and the Oakland Raiders) 
chose not to be parties to the Trust Agreement, but have 
licensed  their marks directly to NFL Properties. 
 
34.   On information and belief, in or about 1993, 
defendants Tagliabue and Austrian assumed effective control 
of NFL Properties. 
 
35.  Absent judicial relief, the cartel will continue to 
control the marketing of all Club Marks and NFL Marks, 
precluding (with only limited exceptions) competition among 
the clubs, and between the clubs and the NFL, in the 
licensing of professional football marks until at least 
March 31, 2004. 
 
36.  Pursuant to the Trust and License Agreements, NFL 
Properties pays the NFL Trust the proceeds from NFL 
Properties agreements with sponsors and licensees, after 
subtracting NFL Properties  fees and expenses.  The 
Trustees, in turn, have used a substantial portion of the 
net proceeds received from NFL Properties to pay expenses of 
the NFL. 
 
37.  After these and other deductions, the Trust distributes 
to each beneficiary/club an equal share of the net profits, 
regardless of the individual value of that club's marks, the 
club's contribution (if any) to the value of its marks, the 
club's efforts (if any) to promote itself and its marks, and 
the club's investment (if any) in creating a positive 
association with its marks. 
 
38.  The NFL, NFL Trust, and NFL Properties provide 
virtually no information to members, beneficiaries, 
shareholders, or  directors about those entities  operations 
and finances. Nevertheless, the little information these 
entities do provide shows that the amounts spent on 
administrative expenses are, to all appearances, 
extraordinarily and wastefully high. 
 
39.  In fiscal year 1994, for example, NFL Properties spent 
64% of its gross revenues for direct costs and 
administrative expenses.  Only 36% of NFL Properties  gross 
revenues was actually paid to the Trust as net proceeds.  Of 
that money, a substantial percentage was paid to the NFL, a 
small amount was contributed to charity, and  only a small 
portion was distributed to the clubs.  On information and 
belief, from January 1989 to the fall of 1994, no cash 
payments  at all were made by the Trust to the beneficiary 
clubs. 
 
40.  The marks of the member clubs are not of equal, or even 
comparable, value.  The marks of a relative handful of clubs 
generally account for the bulk of the revenues in any given 
year. On information and belief, for example, during 1993 
and 1994 more than 20% of the revenue generated by NFL 
Properties from licensed product sales was generated solely 
by products bearing Cowboys marks.  Despite this substantial 
contribution, however, the Cowboys Partnership is entitled 
to only one-thirtieth of the distributed profits of NFL 
Properties.  In contrast, as of June 1995, the combined 
sales of licenses to the marks of 20 of the 30 member clubs 
generated, according to published reports, only about 30% of 
the revenue of NFL Properties (or 1.5% each).  
 
41.  Because of the cartel and the substantial expenses it 
deducts at each stage, each club receives only about a penny 
or less for every additional dollar of revenue generated by 
the licensing of that club's marks.  As a result, the cartel 
deprives individual clubs of meaningful incentives to 
promote the sale of  their own team's marks.  
 
42.  In the absence of the cartel established by the Trust 
Agreement and License Agreement, the NFL member clubs would 
compete with one another, and with the NFL, in the 
professional football sponsorship market and the 
professional football merchandise market, leading to 
competitive pricing and increased output. 
 
B.   The Absence of Procompetitive Business Justification 
 
43.  In some respects, it is important and desirable for the 
members of a sports league, such as the NFL, to cooperate 
with one another.  For example, it is necessary and 
reasonable that member clubs agree on a common schedule, on 
rules of play, and on enforcement of those rules. 
 
44.  In other respects, however, concerted conduct 
constitutes an unreasonable restraint on trade and stifles 
desirable economic incentives.  Indeed, in other 
professional sports, individual clubs conduct licensing of 
club marks independently to a substantial degree. 
Independent licensing by each team increases competition and 
provides incentives to engage in spirited marketing and 
promotional efforts and greater investment in the marks. 
The establishment and maintenance of the NFL licensing 
cartel has needlessly inhibited these efforts in the markets 
at issue here. 
 
45.  In litigation recently commenced against some of the 
plaintiffs in the Southern District of New York, NFL 
Properties has recited various supposed benefits of the 
cartel. These supposed benefits are pretextual, or can 
reasonably be achieved without restraining competition or in 
a less restrictive manner, and do not reasonably justify the 
anticompetitive joint conduct of the cartel.  The cartel is 
not reasonably necessary to serve any legitimate, 
procompetitive goal. 
 
46.  For example, the cartel is not reasonably necessary to 
maintain competitive balance in team performance among the 
member clubs.  First, the cartel regulates only a relatively 
small source of club revenue.  The overwhelming bulk of club 
revenue derives from equally-shared television rights fees, 
which are not controlled by the NFL licensing cartel and are 
not challenged in this lawsuit.  Second, the equal sharing 
of profits does not in fact lead to competitive balance. 
Indeed, the sharing of profits can create just the opposite 
effect, leaving poor-performing teams with no incentive to 
spend more on players or to strive to improve.  According to 
a published study, for example, the Tampa Bay Buccaneers won 
fewer games than any other team in the NFL between 1980 and 
1990, but enjoyed the highest level of profitability of any 
team during that same period.  Third, the purported interest 
in achieving competitive balance among member clubs can 
readily be achieved in a much less restrictive and 
anticompetitive manner, through devices such as player 
drafts favoring less successful teams, a salary cap, and the 
like. 
 
47.  The cartel hinders efficiency, rather than enhances it, 
by creating an incentive for free-riding.  The equal 
distribution of profits generated from the licensing of Club 
Marks, regardless of the value of any particular club's mark 
or the quantity of sales, diminishes the incentives for 
individual clubs to promote their marks competitively and to 
invest in their marks.  Individual club owners know that 
they will share equally in the profits of the cartel, 
regardless of their own contribution.  Similarly, each club 
owner knows that it will receive only about a penny or less 
for every additional dollar of revenue it generates through 
the promotion of its marks.  The cartel thus leaves 
individual club owners with little reason to invest in such 
promotion. 
 
48.  The  cartel also retards efficiency by  limiting the 
incentive and opportunity for individual clubs to enhance 
the value of their marks by providing complementary products 
and services, such as public appearances by club personnel, 
to Club Mark licensees. 
 
49.  The cartel's exclusive control over the marks of all 
NFL Clubs, and the bundling of those marks as a single 
package, does not produce a superior product.  Many 
licensees would prefer to buy the right to use the marks of 
only a few member clubs and have no interest in purchasing 
the marks of other clubs.  As the NFL's director of 
corporate communications, Chris Widmaier, has publicly 
admitted,  sponsors have told us that they d be happy if NFL 
Properties went away  because the cartel limits their 
ability to choose what marks to purchase and forces them to 
increase their overall spending. 
 
C.   Defendants  Enforcement of the Cartel 
 
(1)  Imposition of Cartel Membership on New Owners and New 
Clubs   
 
50.  The NFL requires the approval of no fewer than 
three-fourths of its member clubs before allowing any person 
to purchase an existing NFL club.  Similarly, a new club may 
become a member of the NFL only if three-fourths of the 
member clubs approve. 
 
51.  The NFL and its member clubs also maintain the right to 
cancel an owner's franchise or otherwise punish an owner of 
a club for failing to abide by the NFL Constitution and 
Bylaws or for engaging in conduct deemed  detrimental to the 
welfare of the League.   A decision by the NFL to cancel or 
terminate a franchise is, under Section 8.13(B) of the NFL's 
Constitution and Bylaws, final, conclusive, and 
unappealable. 
 
52.  Since 1982, any person wishing to acquire a controlling 
interest in an existing or new NFL club, including 
plaintiffs Jones and JWJ Corporation, have been required to 
assent to the cartel's control over licensing of the club's 
marks, subject to certain rights reserved by the club.  This 
power to preclude any person from acquiring an NFL team 
without first consenting to the cartel arrangement provides 
the NFL and its member clubs with a potent tool to restrain 
competition in the professional football sponsorship market 
and the professional football merchandise market. 
 
53.  Plaintiffs JWJ Corporation and Jones did not own, 
manage or control the Cowboys franchise in 1982, when the 
cartel was created.  Texas Stadium Corporation, JWJ 
Corporation, Jones, and Pro Silver Star are not, and have 
never been, parties to the Trust Agreement or License 
Agreement. 
 
(2)  Punishment and Retaliation for Opposition to the Cartel 
 
54.  Although plaintiffs have at all times complied with 
their contractual and other legal obligations, plaintiffs 
have objected to the anticompetitive conduct of the cartel 
and have publicly and privately advocated abolishing or 
limiting the cartel.  Plaintiffs  expression of these views 
has prompted repeated and continuing efforts by the NFL 
Defendants to punish and retaliate against plaintiffs.  The 
NFL and NFL Properties have, in a blatantly discriminatory 
fashion, manipulated their internal administrative processes 
to reward clubs that have toed the cartel's line, and to 
punish plaintiffs for advocating reform.  These defendants 
acts of wrongful discrimination against plaintiff Cowboys 
Partnership and Jones include, but are not limited to, the 
following: 
 
55.  In February 1995, the President of the NFL, defendant 
Neil Austrian, wrote to plaintiffs about a proposed deal 
between Pro Silver Star and a distributor of Snapple fruit 
juice beverages.  Mr. Austrian's letter made clear that the 
NFL intended to apply a different and harsher set of rules 
to plaintiffs than to other NFL member clubs.  Mr. Austrian 
first candidly acknowledged that  [t]here is no legal 
prohibition on owners, coaches or players endorsing 
products, even products that compete with those of our 
sponsors.   While admitting the lack of any such legal 
prohibition, however, Mr. Austrian asserted that  an owner 
with your profile  should not engage in such a transaction, 
and threatened to  take action  if plaintiffs proceeded with 
the transaction.  (Emphasis  added.)  On this blatantly and 
facially discriminatory basis, the NFL harassed plaintiffs 
and sought to prevent them from entering into a lawful 
transaction with the Snapple distributor. 
 
56.  In 1994, the NFL employed numerous roadblocks to impede 
the Cowboys  plans to modify the uniforms worn by Cowboys 
players.  The NFL's objections were based on an NFL rule 
that the Cowboys Partnership had complied with and that the 
NFL had, in any event, readily waived for other NFL clubs. 
The NFL ultimately forced plaintiffs to agree to purchase 
from NFL Properties  licensees any unsold merchandise using 
the previous uniform design, a requirement that, on 
information and belief, the NFL had never before imposed on 
any club. 
 
57.  During 1993 and 1994, the NFL and NFL Properties 
repeatedly harassed plaintiffs about transactions between 
plaintiff Pro Silver Star and Apex One, an apparel 
manufacturer licensed by NFL Properties.  In these 
transactions, plaintiffs   lawfully agreed,  among other 
things, to have Cowboys personnel wear uniforms and other 
apparel manufactured by Apex in return for a sponsorship 
payment.  On  information and belief, these defendants 
attempted to force  NFL Properties  Pro Line apparel 
licensees, including Apex One, to agree not to enter into 
contracts similar to that between Pro Silver Star and Apex. 
 
58.  On information and belief, NFL Properties has cemented 
allegiance to the cartel by arbitrarily permitting favored 
clubs to enter into sponsorship agreements for product 
categories that are covered by NFL Properties' national 
sponsorship agreements, allowing these clubs to retain for 
themselves the proceeds of such agreements.  At the same 
time, NFL Properties has discriminated against plaintiffs by 
repeatedly denying them permission to enter into similar 
agreements. 
 
59.  In 1994, the NFL advocated adoption of an arbitrary and 
unfair revenue  sharing system that would have required the 
Cowboys Partnership  to pay far more than any other  club, 
and that, on information and belief, would have resulted in 
a net shifting of funds to clubs in some of the largest 
markets in the nation. 
 
60.  In 1995, the NFL Defendants forced plaintiffs to  cover 
certain commercial signage in Texas Stadium, citing an NFL 
rule about  low  stadium signage.   When the NFL defendants 
discovered that stadiums other than Texas Stadium refused to 
comply with this  rule, however, the NFL Defendants stopped 
enforcing it. 
 
61.  The NFL has threatened to punish plaintiffs by limiting 
opportunities for the Cowboys to play in high-profile, 
nationally telecast games, such as the Thanksgiving Day game 
or Monday Night Football games. 
 
62.  In the fall of 1995, the NFL Defendants caused the NFL 
Management Council to apply the salary cap provisions of the 
Collective Bargaining Agreement to the Cowboys  contract 
with Deion Sanders in a restrictive manner that had never 
before been applied to any other player with a similar 
contract. 
 
63.  Defendant NFL Properties has harassed plaintiffs about 
lawful licensing transactions that Jones, Pro Silver Star, 
and Texas Stadium Corporation have entered into with Dr 
Pepper Bottling Company of Texas ( Dr Pepper ), Pepsico ( 
Pepsi ), Nike, Inc. ( Nike ) and American Express Travel 
Related Services Company, Inc. ( American Express ). 
Defendants  campaign of harassment and intimidation has 
culminated in NFL Properties filing suit in the United 
States District Court for the Southern District of New York 
(Civil Action 95-7951) against the Cowboys Partnership, 
Jones, and Texas Stadium Corporation in September 1995 ( the 
NFL Properties lawsuit ).  In this meritless lawsuit, NFL 
Properties seeks damages of $500 million.  The lawsuit is 
calculated to intimidate plaintiffs and to silence their 
advocacy of abolition or limitation of the cartel. 
 
64.  The NFL Properties lawsuit is objectively baseless in 
that no reasonable person could realistically expect success 
on the merits.  The critical factual allegations of the 
lawsuit -- such as allegations that plaintiffs licensed Dr 
Pepper, Pepsi, or American Express to use Club Marks or NFL 
Marks -- are demonstrably false.  Even after the plaintiffs 
conclusively demonstrated to NFL Properties the falsity of 
the central allegations in the lawsuit, NFL Properties has 
continued to pursue the action. 
 
65.  The baselessness of the NFL Properties lawsuit is also 
demonstrated by the fact that Foxboro Stadium, in which the 
New England Patriots play, entered into a transaction with 
Pepsi that is essentially identical to the Pepsi/Texas 
Stadium transaction attacked in the NFL Properties lawsuit. 
Yet far from filing a $500 million lawsuit against the New 
England Patriots, the NFL has recognized the lawfulness of 
the Pepsi/Foxboro Stadium transaction and taken no steps to 
oppose it. 
 
66.  The NFL Properties lawsuit was not brought to obtain a 
judgment, but to interfere with the business relationships 
of plaintiffs, to retaliate against plaintiffs for their 
opposition to the cartel, and to chill others from joining 
in that opposition.  In discussing the Texas Stadium 
contract with Pepsi, for example, defendant Tagliabue stated 
that  [t]he key thing is not so much the pouring rights but 
some of [Jones ] rhetoric attacking NFL Properties. 
 
D.   The Cartel's Efforts to Expand its Control 
 
67.  The Trust Agreement and License Agreement together 
(unlawfully) grant NFL Properties most rights to exploit 
Club Marks and NFL Marks commercially.  The rights granted 
by the clubs to the cartel, are, however, limited in certain 
respects. The NFL Defendants have nevertheless sought to 
exercise rights expressly reserved to the clubs in the 
Agreements, in order to protect and expand the cartel and in 
an effort to monopolize the professional football 
sponsorship market and the professional football merchandise 
market. 
 
68.  Under the Trust Agreement and the License Agreement, 
each club retained the right to determine what apparel its 
players, coaches, and other club personnel will wear during 
football games, including apparel bearing Club Marks or 
third party marks.  The Trust Agreement expressly reserved 
to each club (including  the Cowboys Partnership)   the 
exclusive right to use Club Marks in connection with the 
presentation of football exhibitions.   (Emphasis added.) 
At the time the Agreements were entered into in 1982, as 
now, by far the most significant aspect of the  presentation 
of football exhibitions  was through television.  The clubs, 
including the Dallas Cowboys, thus explicitly retained the 
exclusive right to control the  use of Club Marks  during 
presentation of football exhibitions  on television or 
otherwise.  In addition, the Trust and License Agreements 
did not grant the NFL Trust or NFL Properties any right 
whatsoever to control what third party marks may appear on 
apparel worn by club personnel (or guests of clubs) during 
football exhibitions.  Nonetheless, the NFL Defendants have 
unlawfully attempted to expand the cartel by purporting to 
exercise control over the apparel worn by club personnel and 
others during  NFL games. 
 
69.  In a May 1995 letter, defendant NFL, through defendant 
Tagliabue, conceded that  there [is] no NFL rule . . . 
dealing with the wearing of NFL Properties-licensed apparel 
by coaches on team sidelines during games,  and acknowledged 
that the only possible legal basis for NFL Properties 
claimed right to control the sidelines is  the member clubs 
grant of rights to NFL Properties and Properties  role in 
managing the . . . licensing program.   Since the  member 
clubs  grant of rights to NFL Properties  (in the Trust 
Agreement) does not include any sideline rights, this letter 
is an admission that the clubs, and not NFL Properties, are 
entitled to determine what apparel their personnel will wear 
during games. 
 
70.   The NFL has nevertheless repeatedly used its power 
over the clubs in an unlawful effort to coerce compliance 
with the cartel's efforts to dictate what apparel club 
personnel wear during games.  For example, the NFL has 
wrongfully refused to approve the contracts between the 
Cowboys Partnership and its coaches unless the contracts 
include a clause granting NFL Properties control over the 
apparel worn by the coaches -- a right that in fact belongs 
to each club.  Because the NFL has abused its power in this 
way, the Cowboys Partnership has, since February 1995, been 
unable to obtain NFL approval (which is required by the NFL 
Constitution and Bylaws) for the contracts with its head 
coaches and assistant coaches.  Plaintiffs have thus been 
forced to take the risk that some of its most important 
assets -- such as the Cowboys  contract with its head coach 
-- could be held unenforceable by a court. 
 
71.  The NFL and NFL Properties, acting jointly, wrongfully 
coerced plaintiffs to convey to NFL  Properties a total of 
$1 million belonging  to plaintiffs from contracts with Apex 
One relating to sideline rights. 
 
72.  NFL Properties has reportedly entered  into an 
agreement with Nike in which NFL Properties grants to Nike 
the right to provide Cowboys personnel  with Nike-branded 
apparel  to  be worn during Cowboys games.  On information 
and belief, Nike agreed to pay NFL Properties many millions 
of dollars for the right to have Cowboys personnel wear such 
apparel.   It is plaintiffs, however, and not NFL 
Properties, that have the right to enter into that 
transaction with Nike.  Plaintiffs have lost many millions 
of dollars of revenues to which they are entitled as a 
result of NFL Properties  wrongful claim to these rights, 
and NFL Properties has unlawfully benefitted by the same 
amount. 
 
E.   Anticompetitive Effects of the Cartel and Injury to 
Plaintiffs 
 
73.  As a direct, actual, probable, and intended result of 
defendants  unlawful agreements and conduct, defendants have 
substantially lessened competition in the professional 
football sponsorship market and the professional football 
merchandise market.  Output is lower than it would otherwise 
be  and is unresponsive to consumer preferences.  But for 
the unlawful restrictions imposed by the cartel, plaintiffs, 
among others, would offer for sale many licensing 
opportunities not now available in the marketplace. 
 
74.  As the direct, actual, probable and intended result of 
defendants  unlawful agreements and conduct, plaintiffs and 
others have been denied the right to compete freely in the 
professional football sponsorship market and the 
professional football merchandise market.  Plaintiffs have 
been denied the right to profits to which they were, or 
should have been, entitled as the owner of the Cowboys marks 
and other property; have been denied the right to enter into 
economically efficient and beneficial business arrangements; 
and will continue to suffer injury through at least March 
2004, absent judicial relief. Plaintiffs have also suffered 
substantial injury from the NFL Defendants  repeated efforts 
to punish and harass plaintiffs for their opposition to the 
cartel; from the NFL Defendants  efforts  to expand the 
cartel by interfering with plaintiffs  legitimate business 
activities; and from the NFL Defendants  imposition  of 
significant costs on plaintiffs, including the costs of 
defending sham  litigation attacking lawful business 
activities. 
 
75.  As  the direct, actual, probable, and intended result 
of defendants  unlawful agreements and conduct, the cartel 
has unlawfully created and maintained a monopoly in the 
professional football merchandise market by denying 
individual member clubs the right freely to compete in the 
market. 
 
76.  The cartel has also diminished incentives to create 
innovative products in the professional football sponsorship 
market and the professional football merchandise market, to 
market products and to promote NFL member clubs nationally, 
and otherwise to compete vigorously in the professional 
football sponsorship market and the professional football 
merchandise market. 
 
77.  The Trust and License Agreements that are now in place, 
and defendants  continuing conduct,  present a significant 
threat of future injury to plaintiffs in particular and 
competition in general. 
 
F.  Mismanagement 
 
78.  In part because it does not face the rigors of 
competition, the NFL licensing cartel, like other cartels, 
has been run with little regard for efficiency.  As a 
result, contrary to their obligations under the Trust and 
License  Agreements and the common law,  the NFL Defendants 
have failed to exercise their best efforts to utilize the 
NFL Marks and the Club Marks for the benefit of the member 
clubs.  The Trustees of the NFL Trust, in addition, have, in 
violation of their fiduciary duties, been grossly negligent 
in failing to ensure that NFL Properties has managed  Trust 
assets appropriately. 
 
79.  As a result of these breaches of duty, NFL Properties 
and the NFL have incurred excessive overhead and expenses, 
far beyond what is reasonably necessary to accomplish their 
business purposes.  These excessive expenses directly reduce 
the licensing royalties available to be distributed to the 
Cowboys Partnership and other clubs. 
 
80.  The NFL Defendants  toleration of unjustifiable 
expenditures and incompetent practices in the management of 
the Trust assets has harmed plaintiffs by diminishing the 
revenues ultimately distributed to the clubs and the value 
of plaintiff Cowboys Partnership's investment in NFL 
Properties. 
 
81.  These practices have been largely concealed from 
plaintiffs because the NFL Defendants have failed to provide 
Cowboys Partnership, as an NFL member club and a beneficiary 
of the Trust, or Jones, as a shareholder and (from 1989 to 
June 1995) a director of NFL Properties, with material 
information about the operations and finances of the NFL, 
the NFL Trust, or NFL Properties.  For example, these 
plaintiffs have been provided with little or no information 
concerning (a) the operating, administrative, and overhead 
expenses of the NFL, NFL Properties, or the NFL Trust; (b) 
reports  prepared by outside counsel, auditors, and other 
consultants hired to investigate allegations of 
mismanagement, waste, and abuse at NFL Properties; and (c) 
reports by outside accountants about internal accounting 
controls. 
 
82.  Plaintiffs have been injured in their business and 
property by the NFL Defendants  failure to provide this 
information, in part because the lack of adequate and timely 
information available to directors, shareholders, and 
beneficiaries has contributed to the gross mismanagement of 
NFL Properties.    
 
G.    Discriminatory Treatment 
 
83.  The NFL Defendants are obligated, pursuant to the Trust 
and License Agreements, the NFL's Constitution and Bylaws, 
the Rules of the NFL, and the common law, to treat each 
member club, including plaintiffs  Cowboys Partnership, and 
each club owner, in  a fair, consistent, and equitable 
manner.  As described above, the NFL Defendants have 
repeatedly breached that duty by applying, interpreting and 
seeking to enforce provisions of those agreements in an 
arbitrary, inconsistent, and discriminatory manner against 
plaintiffs Cowboys Partnership and Jones. 
 
84.  The NFL Defendants have thus deliberately and 
repeatedly treated plaintiffs Jones and Cowboys Partnership 
in a manner different -- and far more harsh -- than NFL 
clubs that are in favor with the NFL bureaucracy.  This 
conduct is arbitrary, capricious, and motivated by malice 
towards plaintiffs, and is unlawful both under the governing 
contracts (such as the Trust Agreement) and the common law. 
 
85.  The NFL Defendants  tortious conduct and breaches of 
fiduciary duty have been intentional and deliberate, 
malicious, wanton, reckless and in deliberate disregard of 
the rights of others.  This misconduct has been egregious, 
has involved a high degree of moral culpability, moral 
turpitude and wanton dishonesty, and has been aimed at 
plaintiffs and at the public generally. 
 
86.  Defendants  misconduct is causing irreparable injury to 
plaintiffs, and unless enjoined, will continue to do so. 
Plaintiffs have no adequate remedy at law with respect to 
future misconduct by defendants. 
 
COUNT I 
 
(Violation of Section 1 of the Sherman Act) 
 
Restraint of Trade in the Professional Football Sponsorship 
Market 
 
87.  Plaintiffs repeat and reallege paragraphs 1  through 86 
as though fully set forth herein. 
 
88.  By reason of the foregoing, since at least as early as 
October 1, 1982 and continuing through the present, 
defendants have acted in concert with the purpose, intent, 
and effect of unreasonably restraining trade and commerce in 
the professional football sponsorship market.  Defendants 
operate a horizontal cartel, through which the NFL member 
clubs have agreed not to compete with each other and thereby 
to fix prices and to reduce output below competitive levels 
in the professional football sponsorship market.  Through 
the Trust and License Agreements, the operation of the NFL, 
and defendants  conduct, defendants have, with only limited 
exceptions, precluded all competition for the licensing of 
Club and NFL Marks. 
 
89.  Defendants have also conspired to expand this cartel 
and further to restrain competition.  Their acts in 
furtherance of this plan include, for example, refusing to 
approve certain club contracts, harassing plaintiffs over 
other lawful business activities, and engaging in other 
wrongful acts set forth above to block plaintiffs from 
exercising their legal right to license and/or sell products 
not subject to the cartel's control, such as sideline 
rights. 
 
90.  The intentional and anticompetitive conduct by which 
defendants have unreasonably restrained output in the 
professional football sponsorship market is not reasonably 
necessary to further any legitimate, procompetitive goal of 
the NFL, NFL Properties, or the member clubs. 
 
91.  Defendants  anticompetitive conduct has directly and 
proximately caused injury and damage to plaintiffs  business 
and property, as set forth above.  Plaintiffs will continue 
to be so injured unless defendants are enjoined from 
continuing to engage in the foregoing violations of law. 
 
92.  The actual, probable, and intended effects of the 
foregoing acts and practices, and the continuing course of 
defendants  anticompetitive conduct, has caused injury to 
consumers and to competition in the professional football 
sponsorship market, as set forth above. 
 
COUNT II 
 
(Violation of Section 1 of the Sherman Act) 
 
Restraint of Trade in the Professional Football Merchandise 
Market 
 
93.  Plaintiffs repeat and reallege paragraphs 1 through 92 
as though fully set forth herein. 
 
94.   By reason of the foregoing, since at least as early as 
October 1, 1982 and continuing through the present, 
defendants have acted in concert with the purpose, intent, 
and effect of unreasonably restraining trade and commerce. 
Defendants operate a horizontal cartel, through which the 
NFL member clubs have agreed not to compete with each other 
and thereby to fix prices and to reduce output below 
competitive levels in the professional football merchandise 
market.  Through the Trust and License Agreements, operation 
of the NFL, and defendants  conduct, defendants have, with 
only limited exceptions, precluded all competition for the 
licensing of the Club and NFL Marks. 
 
95.   The intentional and anticompetitive conduct by which 
defendants have restrained output in the professional 
football merchandise market is not reasonably necessary to 
the furtherance of any legitimate, procompetitive goal of 
the NFL, NFL Properties, or the member clubs. 
 
96.   Defendants  anticompetitive conduct has directly and 
proximately caused injury and damage to plaintiffs  business 
and property, as set forth above.  Plaintiffs will continue 
to be so injured unless defendants are enjoined from 
continuing to engage in the foregoing violations of law. 
 
97.  The actual, probable, and intended effects of the 
foregoing acts and practices, and the continuing course of 
defendants  anticompetitive conduct, has caused injury to 
consumers and to competition in the professional football 
merchandise market, as set forth above. 
 
COUNT III 
 
(Violation of Section 2 of the Sherman Act) 
 
Attempt to Monopolize the Professional Football Sponsorship 
Market 
 
98.   Plaintiffs repeat and reallege paragraphs 1 through 97 
as though fully set forth herein. 
 
99.   Since at least as early as October 1, 1982 and 
continuing through the present, defendants have engaged in 
the conduct alleged herein with the specific intent to 
monopolize the professional football sponsorship market. 
Through their control of professional football, and through 
the Trust and License Agreements, defendants have been able 
to obtain, with only limited exceptions, exclusive control 
over all Club and NFL Marks.  These marks constitute the 
principal goods in the professional football sponsorship 
market.  Not content with this substantial control of that 
market, defendants have attempted to expand their control of 
the market, and to monopolize the professional football 
sponsorship market, by, for example, refusing to approve 
certain club contracts, harassing plaintiffs over lawful 
business activities, and engaging in other wrongful acts set 
forth above to block plaintiffs from exercising their legal 
rights to license and/or sell products not subject to the 
cartel's control, such as sideline rights. 
 
100.  Defendants  purpose and goal is to monopolize the 
professional football sponsorship market and to limit output 
in that market. 
 
101.  There is a dangerous probability that defendants will 
succeed in monopolizing the professional football 
sponsorship market.  Defendants already exercise almost 
exclusive control over Club and NFL Marks, which constitute 
the principal goods in the market.  Moreover, all product 
suppliers in the professional football sponsorship market 
necessarily do business either directly or indirectly with 
the NFL.  The NFL, in turn, is capable of using, and has 
used, its control over professional football to coerce and 
control product suppliers from freely competing with NFL 
Properties in the professional football sponsorship market. 
 
102.  Defendants  anticompetitive conduct has directly and 
proximately caused injury and damage to plaintiffs  business 
and property, as set forth above.  Plaintiffs will continue 
to be so injured unless defendants are enjoined from 
continuing to engage in the foregoing violations of law. 
 
103.  The actual, probable, and intended effects of the 
foregoing acts and practices, and the continuing course of 
defendants  anticompetitive conduct, has caused injury to 
consumers and to competition in the professional football 
sponsorship market, as set forth above. 
 
COUNT IV 
 
(Violation of Section 2 of the Sherman Act) 
 
Conspiracy to Monopolize the Professional Football 
Sponsorship Market 
 
104.  Plaintiffs repeat and reallege paragraphs 1 through 
103 as though fully set forth herein. 
 
105.  Since at least as early as October 1, 1982 and 
continuing through the present, defendants have conspired 
and combined with one another to monopolize trade and 
commerce in the professional football sponsorship market. 
The substantial terms of the conspiracy were, among others, 
that members of the cartel would transfer to the NFL Trust 
(and then to NFL Properties) the right to license all Club 
Marks and NFL Marks; that, with only limited exceptions, 
members of the cartel would not compete in the licensing of 
Club Marks and NFL Marks; and that the NFL and its member 
clubs would not grant a franchise, or permit the transfer of 
an existing franchise, to any person or company unwilling to 
join the cartel.  Defendants have also conspired and 
combined with one another to intimidate and coerce the 
plaintiffs from competing in the professional football 
sponsorship market, such as through the lawful sale of 
sideline rights. 
 
106.  In furtherance of the combination and conspiracy, 
defendants committed the acts set forth herein, including, 
without limitation, agreeing (with only limited exceptions) 
to license Club Marks and NFL Marks exclusively through the 
NFL cartel, refusing to approve certain club contracts, 
harassing plaintiffs over other lawful business activities, 
and engaging in other wrongful acts set forth above to block 
plaintiffs from exercising their legal rights to license 
and/or sell products not controlled by the cartel, such as 
sideline rights. 
 
107.  Defendants specifically intended that the effect of 
their unlawful combination and conspiracy would be to 
achieve and maintain a monopoly in the professional football 
sponsorship market. 
 
108.  Defendants  anticompetitive conduct has directly and 
proximately caused injury and damage to plaintiffs  business 
and property, as set forth above.  Plaintiffs will continue 
to be so injured unless defendants are enjoined from 
continuing to engage in the foregoing violations of law. 
 
109.  The actual, probable, and intended effects of the 
foregoing acts and practices, and the continuing course of 
defendants  anticompetitive conduct, has caused injury to 
consumers and to competition in the professional football 
sponsorship market, as set forth above. 
 
COUNT V 
 
(Violation of Section 2 of the Sherman Act) 
 
Attempt to Monopolize the Professional Football Merchandise 
Market 
 
110.  Plaintiffs repeat and reallege paragraphs 1 through 
109 as though fully set forth herein. 
 
111.  Since at least as early as October 1, 1982 and 
continuing through the present, defendants have engaged in 
the conduct alleged herein with the specific intent to 
monopolize the professional football merchandise market. 
Through their control of professional football, and through 
the Trust and License Agreements, defendants have been able 
to obtain, with only limited exceptions, exclusive control 
over all Club and NFL Marks.  These marks constitute the 
principal goods in the professional football merchandise 
market.  
 
112.  Defendants  purpose has been and, to the extent not 
already accomplished, continues to be to monopolize the 
professional football merchandise market and to limit output 
in that market. 
 
113.  There is a dangerous probability that defendants will 
succeed in monopolizing the professional football 
merchandise market.  Defendants already exercise almost 
exclusive control over Club and NFL Marks, which constitute 
the principal goods in the market.  Moreover, all product 
suppliers in the professional football merchandise market 
necessarily do business either directly or indirectly with 
the NFL.  The NFL, in turn, is capable of using, and has 
used, its control over professional football to coerce and 
control product suppliers from freely competing with NFL 
Properties in the professional football merchandise market. 
 
114.  Defendants  anticompetitive conduct has directly and 
proximately caused injury and damage to plaintiffs  business 
and property, as set forth above.  Plaintiffs will continue 
to be so injured unless defendants are enjoined from 
continuing to engage in the foregoing violations of law. 
 
115.  The actual, probable, and intended effects of the 
foregoing acts and practices, and the continuing course of 
defendants  anticompetitive conduct, has caused injury to 
consumers and to competition in the professional football 
merchandise market, as set forth above. 
 
COUNT VI 
 
(Violation of Section 2 of the Sherman Act) 
 
Conspiracy to Monopolize the Professional Football 
Merchandise Market 
 
116.  Plaintiffs repeat and reallege paragraphs 1 through 
115 as though fully set forth herein. 
 
117.  Since at least as early as October 1, 1982 and 
continuing through the present, defendants have conspired 
and combined with one another to monopolize trade and 
commerce in the professional football merchandise market. 
The substantial terms of the conspiracy were, among others, 
that members of the cartel would transfer to NFL Properties 
the right to license all Club Marks and NFL Marks; that, 
with only limited exceptions, members of the cartel would 
not compete in the licensing of Club Marks and NFL Marks; 
and that the NFL and its member clubs would not grant a 
franchise, or permit the transfer of an existing franchise, 
to any person or company unwilling to join the cartel. In 
addition, defendants have conspired and combined with one 
another to attempt to intimidate plaintiffs and to deter 
them from criticizing the professional football merchandise 
cartel. 
 
118.  In furtherance of the combination and conspiracy, 
defendants committed the acts set forth herein, including, 
without limitation, agreeing (with only limited exceptions) 
to license Club Marks and NFL Marks exclusively through the 
NFL cartel. 
 
119.  Defendants specifically intended that the effect of 
their unlawful combination and conspiracy would be to 
achieve and to maintain a monopoly in the professional 
football merchandise market. 
 
120.  Defendants  anticompetitive conduct has directly and 
proximately caused injury and damage to plaintiffs  business 
and property, as set forth above.  Plaintiffs will continue 
to be so injured unless defendants are enjoined from 
continuing to engage in the foregoing violations of law. 
 
121.  The actual, probable, and intended effects of the 
foregoing acts and practices, and the continuing course of 
defendants  anticompetitive conduct, has caused injury to 
consumers and to competition in the professional football 
merchandise market, as set forth above. 
 
COUNT VII 
 
(Violation of Section 2 of the Sherman Act) 
 
Monopolization of the Professional Football Merchandise 
Market 
 
122.  Plaintiffs repeat and reallege paragraphs 1 through 
121 as though fully set forth herein. 
 
123.  Since at least as early as October 1, 1982 and 
continuing through the present, defendants have engaged in 
acts, practices, and a continuing course of conduct that 
defendants intended would, and that did, acquire, maintain, 
and perpetuate the cartel's monopoly in the professional 
football merchandise market. 
 
124.  In furtherance of this violation, defendants have 
engaged on a continuing basis in the following exclusionary, 
anticompetitive, and monopolistic practices, among others: 
(a) defendants have used their control over professional 
football to exclude competitors from the professional 
football merchandise market; (b) defendants have sought to 
coerce and intimidate plaintiffs to prevent them from 
criticizing defendants  monopoly power in the professional 
football merchandise market; (c) the member clubs have 
conveyed to the NFL Trust and NFL Properties the exclusive 
rights (with only limited exceptions) to license the Club 
Marks; and (d) defendants have agreed not to compete with 
one another in the professional football merchandise market. 
 
 
125.  Defendants  anticompetitive conduct has directly and 
proximately caused injury and damage to plaintiffs  business 
and property, as set forth above.  Plaintiffs will continue 
to be so injured unless defendants are enjoined from 
continuing to engage in the foregoing violations of law. 
 
126.  The actual, probable, and intended effects of the 
foregoing acts and practices, and the continuing course of 
defendants  anticompetitive conduct, has caused injury to 
consumers and to competition in the professional football 
merchandise market, as set forth above. 
 
COUNT VIII 
 
(Lanham Act and related laws) 
 
Declaration of Rights 
 
127.  Plaintiffs repeat and reallege paragraphs 1 through 
126 as though fully set forth herein. 
 
128.  The Trust Agreement and License Agreement do not 
purport to, and do not, grant the NFL Trust or NFL 
Properties any right to control licensing of the names or 
logos of the stadiums in which NFL teams play. 
 
129. The NFL Defendants have long recognized that stadiums 
in which NFL teams play are entitled to market themselves 
(and to license their own marks) for financial gain. The 
stadium in which the San Francisco 49ers play their home 
games, for example, which was formerly known as Candlestick 
Park, has recently been renamed  3Com Park  in return for a 
payment of money by 3Com Corporation, a computer technology 
firm.  The stadium in which the St. Louis Rams will soon 
play is named the Trans World Dome  in exchange for 
multi-million dollar payments to the Rams.  And the owners 
of the domed stadium in Indianapolis, Indiana in which the 
Indianapolis Colts play (formerly called the Hoosier Dome) 
have renamed it the  RCA Dome in return for a package of 
financial incentives provided by the manufacturer of RCA 
products, Thomas Consumer Electronics.  On information and 
belief, the NFL and NFL Properties have not challenged this 
highly publicized transaction even though RCA sells many 
products that compete directly with those of Sony 
Corporation, which has paid NFL Properties for the exclusive 
national rights to use Club Marks and NFL Marks in 
connection with consumer electronic products. 
 
130.  Stadiums have also entered into marketing agreements 
in which corporate sponsors have obtained the right to 
associate themselves in other ways with stadiums in which 
NFL teams play.  For example, the owners of Foxboro Stadium, 
where the New England Patriots play, entered into an 
agreement with Pepsi in August 1995 in which Pepsi gained 
the right to advertise itself (both inside and outside the 
stadium) as the  Official Cola of Foxboro Stadium.   The 
stadium is owned by Robert Kraft, who also owns the 
Patriots. 
 
131.  The NFL has not objected to any of these arrangements, 
and could not responsibly do so since the transactions do 
not involve licensing of any Club Marks or NFL Marks. 
 
132.  Texas Stadium Corporation, Pro Silver Star, and Jones 
have entered into transactions with Dr Pepper, Pepsi, Nike, 
and American Express in which Texas Stadium Corporation has 
licensed these sponsors to use the Stadium's own marks. 
These transactions do not involve licensing of the right to 
use any NFL Mark or Club Mark.  The transactions are 
consistent with the plaintiffs  purported obligations to the 
NFL cartel and are lawful. 
 
133.  Although the transactions with Dr Pepper, Pepsi, Nike, 
and American Express are lawful, defendant NFL Properties 
has filed a lawsuit against several of the plaintiffs 
demanding $500 million in damages.  The NFL Defendants 
discriminatory and improper motives are shown by the fact 
that they have taken no action against the essentially 
identical Pepsi/Foxboro Stadium deal, even though the press 
release announcing the Foxboro Stadium transaction twice 
refers to the stadium as the  home of the New England 
Patriots.   (Emphasis added.) 
 
134.  Defendants have no contractual or other right to 
control any licensing transaction that does not involve the 
use of an NFL Mark or Club Mark.  Plaintiffs  may therefore 
lawfully enter into transactions in which they license third 
parties to affiliate themselves with Texas Stadium.  Among 
other things, the transactions between plaintiffs and Pepsi, 
Dr Pepper, American Express, and Nike are entirely lawful. 
If (contrary to fact) defendants might have had any 
conceivable basis for objecting to such transactions, they 
have long since waived any such right, and are barred by 
estoppel and other equitable doctrines from enforcing any 
such right, in light of their long-standing approval of, or 
knowing acquiescence in, similar transactions entered into 
by others. 
 
135.  As discussed above, plaintiff Cowboys Partnership 
retained all rights to control the use of Cowboys marks in 
the exhibition of football games, including the right to 
control the apparel worn by Cowboys personnel on the 
sidelines.  Plaintiffs may therefore lawfully enter into 
transactions that relate to the apparel worn by Cowboys 
personnel on the sidelines, such as the contract between 
certain of the plaintiffs and Nike.  Plaintiffs, and not 
defendants, are also entitled to agree to wear the marks and 
logos of third parties, such as Nike, on the uniforms of 
Cowboys personnel. 
 
136.  Plaintiffs are therefore entitled to a declaration 
that the Pepsi, Dr Pepper, Nike, and American Express 
transactions are entirely lawful, and that they are entitled 
to enter into transactions that include, among other terms, 
(a) licensing third parties to affiliate themselves with 
Texas Stadium and (b) agreeing to wear particular apparel 
during football games, including apparel bearing the marks 
and logos of third parties.  There is a real and actual 
controversy about these matters.  Absent a declaration from 
the Court, the uncertainty as to plaintiffs  rights caused 
by defendants wrongful and continuing misconduct will 
continue, to the injury of plaintiffs. 
 
COUNT IX 
 
Breach of Trust and License Agreements 
 
(NFL Trust, Trustees, and NFL Properties) 
 
137.  Plaintiffs repeat and reallege paragraphs 1 through 
136 as though fully set forth herein. 
 
138.  The NFL Trust, its Trustees, and NFL Properties are 
obligated by the Trust and License Agreements to utilize and 
administer the Trust assets so as to avoid waste and 
incompetence in the management of the proceeds.  This 
obligation arises under the express terms of the Agreements, 
and under the implied covenants of good faith and fair 
dealing inherent in those  Agreements.  It was in 
consideration of this obligation, among others, that the 
clubs entered into the Trust and chose NFL Properties as the 
Trust's exclusive licensing agent. 
 
139.  Instead of maximizing distributions to the clubs 
(and/or to charity) from licensing the Club Marks, these 
defendants have wasted these valuable assets through the 
acts of mismanagement and waste described above.  These 
defendants  failure to manage these assets properly has 
caused great financial harm to plaintiff  Cowboys 
Partnership and its owners, plaintiffs JWJ Corporation and 
Jones. 
 
140.  These defendants, acting individually and in concert, 
have breached, and are continuing to breach, the obligations 
owed to plaintiff Cowboys Partnership and its owners as 
parties to, and/or intended third party beneficiaries of, 
the  Trust and License Agreements. 
 
141.  As described above, these defendants have also 
breached their obligations to plaintiff  Cowboys Partnership 
and its owners by  selling to third parties,  such as Nike, 
rights  that in fact belong to the Cowboys Partnership under 
the Trust  Agreement. 
 
142.  Plaintiff Cowboys Partnership and its owners have been 
injured by reason of these breaches in an amount presently 
unknown, but which will be proven at trial. 
 
143.  These defendants  activities and continuing breaches 
of the Trust and License Agreements are causing irreparable 
harm to plaintiff Cowboys Partnership and its owners and, 
unless restrained, will continue to do so. 
 
COUNT X 
 
Breach of NFL Governing Instruments 
 
(NFL, Tagliabue, Austrian and Does 41-60) 
 
144.  Plaintiffs repeat and reallege paragraphs 1 through 
143 as though fully set forth herein. 
 
145.  The Constitution and Bylaws, Rules and other 
agreements of the NFL, and the covenant of good faith and 
fair dealing implied therein, obligate defendants NFL, 
Tagliabue, Austrian, and other officials (Does 41-60) to 
treat each member club and owner in a fair, consistent, and 
equitable manner. 
 
146.  By engaging in the discriminatory and retaliatory 
conduct alleged above, these defendants have violated their 
obligations under these agreements. 
 
147.  Plaintiffs Cowboys Partnership, JWJ Corporation, and 
Jones have been injured by reason of these breaches in an 
amount presently unknown, but which will be proven at trial. 
 
148.  These defendants  activities and continuing breaches 
of these obligations are causing irreparable harm to 
plaintiff Cowboys Partnership and its owners, and unless 
restrained, will continue to do so. 
 
COUNT XI 
 
Breach of Fiduciary Duty 
 
(Trustees of NFL Trust) 
 
149.  As Trustees of the NFL Trust, defendants Paul 
Tagliabue, Daniel Rooney, and Does 1-20, owe the 
beneficiaries of the NFL Trust, including plaintiff Cowboys 
Partnership and its owners, the utmost duty to act in good 
faith in the best interest of the beneficiaries of the Trust 
and to protect their interests in the Trust assets.  It was 
in consideration of this duty, among others, that the clubs 
entered into the Trust Agreement. 
 
150.  The Trustees have breached those duties by, among 
other things, their gross negligence and recklessness and 
willful default in (a) failing to exercise oversight and 
control of the licensing and other activities of the Trust's 
exclusive licensing agent, NFL Properties; (b) failing to 
exercise oversight and control of the excessive expenses 
charged by NFL Properties against revenues derived from 
licensing the marks; (c) on nformation and belief, paying 
excessive amounts of the revenues received by the Trust to 
the NFL; (d) failing to arrange a tax- efficient structure 
for exploitation of the Club Marks; (e) failing to provide 
the beneficiaries of the Trust with an accurate and 
informative accounting of the Trust's activities; and (f) 
failing to prevent the above-described campaign of 
discrimination and harassment by NFL Properties against 
plaintiff Cowboys Partnership.    
 
151.  Plaintiffs Cowboys Partnership, JWJ Corporation, and 
Jones have been injured by reason of these breaches in an 
amount presently unknown, but which will be proven at trial. 
 
 
152.  The Trustees  activities and continuing breaches of 
their fiduciary duties are causing irreparable harm to these 
plaintiffs and, unless restrained, will continue to do so. 
 
COUNT XII 
 
Breach of Fiduciary Duty 
 
(NFL Properties) 
 
153.  Plaintiffs repeat and reallege paragraphs 1 through 
152 as though fully set forth herein. 
 
154.  As the exclusive licensing agent of the NFL Trust, 
defendant NFL Properties owes the NFL Trust and its 
beneficiaries, including plaintiff Cowboys Partnership, the 
utmost duty to act in good faith in the best interest of the 
Trust and its beneficiaries, and to protect their interests 
in the Trust Property.  It was in consideration of this 
duty, among others, that the clubs entered into the Trust 
Agreement and chose NFL Properties as the Trust's exclusive 
licensing agent. 
 
155.  NFL Properties has breached those duties by, among 
other things, (a) its gross negligence and recklessness in 
(1) engaging in mismanagement and wasteful spending, and (2) 
failing to arrange a tax-efficient structure for 
exploitation of the Club Marks; (b) its intentional 
participation in a conspiracy with other NFL Defendants to 
punish and selectively enforce rules against the Cowboys 
Partnership; and (c) its reckless failure to provide 
plaintiffs Cowboys Partnership and Jones with access to 
basic information concerning NFL Properties  finances and 
operations. 
 
156.  Plaintiff Cowboys Partnership has been injured by 
reason of these breaches in an amount presently unknown, but 
which will be proven at trial. 
 
157.  NFL Properties  activities and continuing breaches of 
its fiduciary duties are causing irreparable harm to 
plaintiff Cowboys Partnership and, unless restrained, will 
continue to do so. 
 
COUNT XIII 
 
Breach of Fiduciary Duty 
 
(NFL, Tagliabue, Austrian, Does 41-60) 
 
158.  Plaintiffs repeat and reallege paragraphs 1 through 
157 as though fully set forth herein. 
 
159.  Defendant National Football League, its Commissioner 
(Tagliabue), President (Austrian), and other officials (Does 
41-60) owe the member clubs, including plaintiff Cowboys 
Partnership and its owners, the utmost fiduciary duty to act 
in good faith in the best interests of the League and its 
member clubs, and to protect their interests. 
 
160.  As discussed above, on information and belief, 
defendants Tagliabue and Austrian assumed effective control 
of NFL Properties in or about 1993. 
 
161.  These defendants have breached those fiduciary duties 
by, among other things, (a) their gross negligence and 
recklessness in failing to exercise oversight and control of 
the licensing activities of NFL Properties and its 
employees; (b) their gross negligence and recklessness in 
failing to prevent mismanagement and wasteful spending; and 
(c) their intentional discrimination against plaintiffs by, 
among other things, selectively enforcing rules against 
plaintiff Cowboys Partnership and authorizing the filing of 
meritless claims against plaintiffs. 
 
162.  Plaintiffs Cowboys Partnership, JWJ Corporation, and 
Jones have been injured by reason of these breaches in an 
amount presently unknown, but which will be proven at trial. 
 
163.  The activities and continuing breaches of fiduciary 
duties by these defendants are causing irreparable harm to 
these plaintiffs, and, unless restrained, will continue to 
do so. 
 
COUNT XIV 
 
Breach of Common Law Due Process 
 
(NFL, Tagliabue, Austrian, Does 41-60) 
 
164.  Plaintiffs repeat and reallege paragraphs 1 through 
163 as though fully set forth herein. 
 
165.  As an association that controls major league 
professional football in the United States, defendant NFL, 
along with its Commissioner (Tagliabue), President 
(Austrian), and other officials (Does 41-60), owe the NFL's 
member clubs, including plaintiff Cowboys Partnership and 
its owners, a common law duty of due process.  This duty 
requires that the Constitution and Bylaws and rules of the 
NFL be enforced in a fair and nondiscriminatory way. 
 
166.  These defendants have breached this duty by 
threatening to apply, and by actually applying, the NFL's 
Constitution and Bylaws and rules to plaintiffs  conduct in 
an arbitrary, capricious, and discriminatory fashion. 
 
167.  Plaintiffs Cowboys Partnership, JWJ Corporation, and 
Jones have been injured by reason of these breaches in an 
amount presently unknown, but which will be proven at trial. 
 
168.  The activities and continuing breaches of this duty by 
these defendants have deprived plaintiffs Cowboys 
Partnership, JWJ Corporation, and Jones of fundamental 
fairness and substantial property and economic rights, and 
are otherwise causing irreparable harm to plaintiffs. 
Unless restrained, these activities will continue to cause 
irreparable harm to plaintiffs. 
 
COUNT XV 
 
Tortious Interference with Prospective Economic Advantage 
 
(NFL, NFL Properties, Executive Committee members, Levinson, 
Tagliabue, Austrian, and Does 21-60) 
 
169.  Plaintiffs repeat and reallege paragraphs 1 through 
168 as though fully set forth herein. 
 
170.  Plaintiffs Jones, Texas Stadium Corporation and Pro 
Silver Star have sought to raise funds by entering into 
contracts with potential sponsors of Texas Stadium, and have 
invested significant efforts and resources seeking to 
cultivate sponsor relationships.  Defendants are well aware 
of these efforts by plaintiffs. 
 
171.  The above-listed defendants, acting individually and 
in concert, have intentionally interfered with plaintiffs 
efforts to exercise rights that are either (a) expressly 
retained by the Cowboys Partnership under the Trust 
Agreement or (b) not implicated by that Agreement.  Among 
other things, on information and belief, these defendants, 
acting in concert, used their market and monopoly power in 
the market for professional football merchandise to force 
NFL Properties  licensees to alter their contracts with NFL 
Properties to include language inhibiting the licensees from 
entering into contracts similar to that between Pro Silver 
Star and Apex One concerning apparel to be worn by club 
personnel during games. 
 
172.  Similarly, these defendants, acting in concert, have 
used their control over professional football to require NFL 
member clubs to include in their coaches  contracts a 
provision prohibiting the coaches from wearing apparel on 
the sidelines that has not been dictated  by NFL Properties. 
 
173.  These defendants have sought to discourage 
corporations from becoming sponsors of Texas Stadium, and to 
raise plaintiffs  cost of consummating future sponsorship 
deals, by filing a meritless lawsuit attacking several Texas 
Stadium sponsorship transactions.  As set forth above, on 
information and belief, they  have also denied plaintiffs 
valuable business opportunities relating to Club Marks that 
they have granted to clubs favored by the NFL Defendants. 
 
174.  These defendants are aware that plaintiffs sponsorship 
and apparel contracts are an important source of income to 
plaintiffs, and have taken the actions described with 
malice, ill will, and for the purpose of harming plaintiffs 
by interfering with such contracts. 
 
175.  As set forth above, these defendants have also 
arbitrarily denied permission to plaintiffs to engage in 
licensing transactions that defendants have readily 
authorized for favored clubs. 
 
176.  These defendants have no justification or excuse for 
the actions described above, other than the purpose of 
interfering with plaintiffs  lawful business activities. 
 
177.  Plaintiffs have been injured by reason of these 
breaches in an amount presently unknown, but which will be 
proven at trial. 
 
178.  The activities and continuing breaches of this duty by 
these defendants are causing irreparable harm to plaintiffs 
and, unless restrained, will continue to do so. 
 
COUNT XVI 
 
Accounting of NFL Trust 
 
179.  Plaintiffs repeat and reallege paragraphs 1  through 
178  as though fully set forth herein. 
 
180.  Defendants NFL Trust and its Trustees have not 
provided plaintiff Cowboys Partnership and other 
beneficiaries of the NFL Trust an accounting of the funds 
received by its agent, NFL Properties.  Nor have these 
defendants provided the Cowboys Partnership an accounting of 
the funds received by the Trust and disbursed to the NFL or 
other entities, or used for other operations of the Trust. 
 
181.  Plaintiff Cowboys Partnership is entitled to a full 
and complete accounting of the receipts into and 
disbursements by the NFL Trust and its Trustees for each 
year since 1989.  Plaintiff has no adequate remedy at law. 
 
COUNT XVII 
 
Accounting of NFL Properties 
 
182.  Plaintiffs repeat and reallege paragraphs 1  through 
181  as though fully set forth herein. 
 
183.  Defendants NFL Properties, its Executive Committee, 
President, and other officials (Does 21-40) have not 
provided plaintiffs  Cowboys Partnership and Jones or other 
directors or shareholders of NFL Properties an accounting of 
the funds received from licensing revenues and disbursed to 
the NFL Trust or other persons or entities. 
 
184.  Plaintiffs Cowboys Partnership and Jones are entitled 
to immediate access to the books and records of NFL 
Properties, and to a full and complete accounting of the 
receipts into and disbursements by NFL Properties, its 
Executive  Committee,  and its President for each year since 
1989.  Plaintiff has no adequate remedy at law. 
 
COUNT XVIII 
 
Accounting of NFL 
 
185.  Plaintiffs repeat and reallege paragraphs 1  through 
184  as though fully set forth herein. 
 
186.  Defendants NFL, its Commissioner, President, and other 
officials (Does 41-60) have not provided to plaintiff 
Cowboys Partnership an accounting for the funds received 
from licensing revenues or other sources and disbursed on 
behalf of the NFL and its member clubs.  These defendants, 
pursuant to their fiduciary duties to the member clubs and 
the implied duty of good faith and fair dealing inherent in 
the NFL Constitution and Bylaws and the rules adopted 
thereunder, have a duty to provide the member clubs with 
such information. 
 
187.  Plaintiff Cowboys Partnership is entitled to a full 
and complete accounting of the receipts of and disbursements 
by the NFL for each year since 1989.  Plaintiff has no 
adequate remedy at law. 
 
COUNT XIX 
 
(Derivative) 
 
Breach of License Agreement 
 
(NFL Trust, Trustees, NFL Properties, Executive Committee 
members, Levinson, and Does 21-40) 
 
188.  Plaintiffs repeat and reallege paragraphs 1 through 
187  as though fully set forth herein. 
 
189.  This Count is brought derivatively on behalf of the 
NFL Trust. 
 
190.  Pursuant  to the terms of the License Agreement, 
defendant NFL Properties, its Executive Committee, 
President, and other officials (Does 21-40) are obligated to 
use their best efforts to utilize the Trust assets for the 
benefit of the beneficiaries.  This obligation arises under 
the express terms of the License Agreement, and under the 
implied covenants of good faith and fair dealing inherent in 
that Agreement. 
 
191.  These defendants have wasted the Trust's valuable 
assets through acts of mismanagement and waste, as described 
above.  Because these defendants  right to exploit the Trust 
assets is generally exclusive, their failure to manage these 
assets properly has caused great financial harm to 
plaintiffs. 
 
192.  In light of the Trustees  tolerance of such actions, 
to the detriment of the NFL Trust and its beneficiaries, 
their failure to enforce the Trust's rights under the 
License Agreement, their failure to supply plaintiffs with 
even minimal information, and their evident animus towards 
plaintiffs as shown by their repeated acts of discrimination 
and the filing of a $500 million lawsuit against plaintiffs, 
any further demand by plaintiff Cowboys Partnership on the 
Trustees would be futile. 
 
193.  Plaintiffs have not colluded to confer jurisdiction on 
this Court that it  would not otherwise have. 
 
194.  These defendants  activities and continuing breaches 
of their fiduciary duties are causing irreparable harm to 
plaintiff Cowboys Partnership and, unless restrained, will 
continue to do so.  Plaintiff Cowboys Partnership has been 
injured by reason of these breaches in an amount presently 
unknown, but which will be proven at trial. 
 
COUNT XX (Derivative) 
 
Breach of Fiduciary Duty 
 
(NFL Trust, Trustees, NFL Properties, Executive Committee, 
and Does 21-40) 
 
195.  Plaintiffs repeat and reallege paragraphs 1  through 
194  as though fully set forth herein. 
 
196.  This Count is brought derivatively on behalf of the 
NFL Trust. 
 
197.  As the exclusive licensing agent of the NFL Trust, 
defendant NFL Properties, its Executive Committee, 
President, and other officials (Does 21-40) owe the NFL 
Trust and its beneficiaries, including plaintiff Cowboys 
Partnership, the utmost fiduciary duty to act in good faith 
in the best interest of the Trust and its beneficiaries, and 
to maximize and protect their interests in the Trust assets. 
 
198.  These defendants have breached those duties by, among 
other things, (a) their gross negligence and recklessness 
in permitting or engaging in mismanagement  and wasteful 
spending;  (b)  their intentional participation in a 
conspiracy with other NFL Defendants to punish and 
selectively enforce rules against the Cowboys Partnership; 
and (c)  their failure to provide plaintiffs Cowboys 
Partnership and Jones with access to basic information 
concerning NFL Properties  finances and operations. 
 
199.  In light of the Trustees  tolerance of such actions, 
to the detriment of the NFL Trust and its beneficiaries, 
their failure to enforce the Trust's rights, their failure 
to supply plaintiffs with even minimal information, and 
their evident animus towards plaintiffs as shown by their 
repeated acts of discrimination and the filing of a $500 
million lawsuit against plaintiffs, any further demand by 
plaintiff Cowboys Partnership on the Trustees would be 
futile. 
 
200.  Plaintiffs have not colluded to confer jurisdiction on 
this Court that it  would not otherwise have. 
 
201.  These defendants  activities and continuing breaches 
of their fiduciaries duties are causing irreparable harm to 
plaintiffs Cowboys Partnership and Jones and, unless 
restrained, will continue to do to.  These plaintiffs have 
been injured by reason of these breaches in an amount 
presently unknown, but which will be proven at trial. 
 
COUNT XXI (Derivative) 
 
Negligence, Waste and Mismanagement 
 
(Headrick, Weaver, Gutman, Rooney, Smith, Levinson, Does 
21-40) 
 
202.  Plaintiffs repeat and reallege paragraphs 1  through 
201  as though fully set forth herein. 
 
203.  This Count is brought derivatively on behalf of NFL 
Properties. 
 
204.  In performing their responsibilities in connection 
with NFL Properties, defendants Headrick, Weaver, Gutman, 
Rooney, Smith, and Levinson, and Does 21-40, as officers or 
members of the Executive Committee of NFL Properties, owe a 
duty to NFL Properties and its shareholders to manage the 
assets and operations of NFL Properties in good faith, 
according to their best judgment and skill, and in the 
interests of NFL Properties shareholders. 
 
205.  Among other obligations, these defendants owed a duty 
to NFL Properties and its shareholders adequately to manage 
and supervise the activities of NFL Properties and its 
employees, and to ensure that NFL Properties was properly 
and professionally operated to protect the financial 
interests of its shareholders. 
 
206.  These defendants were negligent or grossly negligent, 
and breached those duties through the acts, omissions and 
mismanagement described above. 
 
207.  In light of these defendants  tolerance of such 
actions, to the detriment of NFL Properties and its 
shareholders, their failure to supply plaintiffs with even 
minimal information, and their evident animus towards 
plaintiffs as shown by their repeated acts of discrimination 
and the filing of a $500 million lawsuit against plaintiffs, 
any further demand by plaintiff Cowboys Partnership would be 
futile. 
 
208.  Plaintiffs have not colluded to confer jurisdiction on 
this Court that it  would not otherwise have. 
 
209.  These defendants  activities and continuing negligence 
and mismanagement are causing irreparable harm to plaintiffs 
Cowboys Partnership and Jones and, unless restrained, will 
continue to do so.  These plaintiffs have been injured by 
reason of these breaches in an amount presently unknown, but 
which will be proven at trial. 
 
COUNT XXII 
 
Unjust Enrichment 
 
(NFL Properties) 
 
210.  Plaintiffs repeat and reallege paragraphs 1  through 
209  as though fully set forth herein. 
 
211.  As discussed above, NFL Properties has sold to Nike 
certain highly valuable rights that in fact belong to 
plaintiffs pursuant to the terms of the Trust Agreement.  By 
selling a right that lawfully belongs to plaintiffs, 
defendant NFL Properties has been and will continue to be 
unjustly enriched. 
 
212.  Plaintiffs  are entitled to disgorgement of the 
revenues wrongfully obtained by NFL Properties through this 
transaction. 
 
PRAYER FOR RELIEF 
 
WHEREFORE, plaintiffs respectfully request that the Court 
enter judgment for plaintiffs as follows:   
 
A.  An award to plaintiffs Cowboys Partnership, Texas 
Stadium Corporation, Pro Silver Star, JWJ Corporation, and 
Jones, of three times the damages they sustained as a result 
of defendants  antitrust violations as provided by Section 4 
of the Clayton Act, 15 U.S.C. Section 15, including damages 
sustained by plaintiff during the pendency of this 
litigation and to be sustained in the future, which damages 
are not presently known but amount to at least $200 million, 
trebled to at least $600 million. 
 
B.  An award to plaintiffs of compensatory damages caused by 
defendants  breaches of contract, breaches of fiduciary 
duty, violation of common law due process, tortious 
interference with prospective economic advantage, unjust 
enrichment, and mismanagement, in an amount presently 
unknown but to be determined at trial. 
 
C.  Punitive damages in an amount not less than $150 
million. 
 
D.  Declaratory relief issued pursuant to 28 U.S.C. Sections 
2201-2202 holding that (a) the Trust Agreement constitutes 
an unlawful restraint on trade and commerce in the 
professional football sponsorship market and professional 
football merchandise market, in violation of Section 1 of 
the Sherman Act; (b) defendants have attempted to and 
conspired to monopolize the professional football 
sponsorship market and the professional football merchandise 
market, in violation of Section 2 of the Sherman Act; (c) 
defendants have monopolized the professional football 
merchandise market, in violation of Section 2 of the Sherman 
Act; (d) the NFL member Clubs own the right to license their 
Club Marks as they see fit; (e) the NFL member clubs enjoy 
the right to determine the apparel and marks worn by their 
personnel during football games; and (f) the transactions 
that Texas Stadium Corporation, Pro Silver Star, and Jones 
have entered into with Dr Pepper, Pepsi, Nike, and American 
Express are lawful under the Lanham Act and all other 
applicable laws, and plaintiffs are free to enter into 
similar transactions with other parties. 
 
E.  A preliminary and permanent injunction barring 
defendants, and all persons and entities acting in concert 
with them, from further violating the rights of plaintiffs, 
including but not limited to provisions barring defendants 
from: 
 
(1)  attempting in any way to enforce the Trust Agreement or 
the License Agreement against plaintiffs; 
 
(2)  taking any steps to create or maintain a horizontal 
cartel among competitors in the professional football 
merchandise market or professional football sponsorship 
market; 
 
(3) continuing to attempt, or to  conspire,  to monopolize 
the professional football sponsorship market or the 
professional football merchandise market; 
 
(4) continuing to monopolize the professional football 
merchandise market; 
 
(5)  abusing the NFL's dominant position in professional 
football in the ways described above or otherwise; or 
 
(6)  retaliating against plaintiffs in any way, whether 
through the administration of the NFL or any entity relating 
to the NFL, or otherwise. 
 
F.  An order directing that defendants NFL, NFL  Trust,  and 
NFL Properties prepare a complete accounting of their 
operations, receipts, and disbursements since 1989. 
 
G.  An award of plaintiffs  costs of litigation, including 
reasonable attorneys  fees, as provided by Section 4 of the 
Clayton Act, Section 35(a) of the Lanham Act,  and other 
applicable laws. 
 
H.  An award of pre-judgment and post-judgment interest, as 
provided by law. 
 
I.  An award of the costs of the action. 
 
J.  Such other and further relief as the Court may deem 
just. 
 
 
PLAINTIFFS DEMAND A TRIAL BY JURY. 
 
 
Respectfully submitted, 
 
WILMER, CUTLER & PICKERING 
 
By: /s/Randolph D. Moss 
 
Michael R. Klein 
