<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<P>National Football League Properties, the league's marketing arm, has filed a $300 million lawsuit against the Dallas Cowboys and owner Jerry Jones challenging Jones' sponsorship deals with Pepsi Cola and Nike. The league claims Jones' actions threaten the owners' agreement to award exclusive sponsorship deals and to split the revenues among all the league's teams. Jones has said he agrees in revenue sharing but that big-market teams should have a chance to enter into licensing and marketing deals. The lawsuit was filed September 18, 1995.</P>
<HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT>
<PRE>
UNITED STATES DISTRICT COURT
SOUTHERN DISTRICT OF NEW YORK

NATIONAL FOOTBALL LEAGUE PROPERTIES, INC.,

                                         95 Civ.
                        Plaintiff,

             - against -

DALLAS COWBOYS FOOTBALL CLUB, LTD.,
TEXAS STADIUM CORPORATION, and JERRAL
W. JONES,

VERIFIED COMPLAINT

Defendants.


         Plaintiff National Football League Properties, Inc.
("NFL Properties"), by its undersigned attorneys, for its com-
plaint herein, alleges upon knowledge as to itself and other-
wise upon information and belief, as follows:

    Nature of the Action

         1.   This action seeks relief against defendants Dal-
las Cowboys Football Club, Ltd., Texas Stadium Corporation and
Jerral W. Jones arising out of violations of the provisions of
the Lanham Act, 15 U.S.C.  1051, et seq., and the common law.
Among other things, as alleged below, defendants have engaged
in an unlawful plan and scheme, in violation of contractual and
fiduciary obligations, to misappropriate for themselves valu-
able business opportunities and revenues that rightfully belong
to plaintiff NFL Properties.

               Parties. Jurisdiction and Venue


         2.   Plaintiff NFL Properties is a corporation orga-
nized and existing under the laws of the State of California,
with its principal place of business at 410 Park Avenue, New
York, New York.  NFL Properties was created in 1963 to exploit
commercially the various trademark, trade name, and service
mark rights of the NFL and the NFL's member clubs (the "Member
Clubs") for the benefit of all of the Member Clubs.  NFL Prop-
erties is the marketing arm of the NFL.  It is a close corpora-
tion, and its sole shareholders are the Member Clubs, each of
which owns an equal share.

         3.   Defendant Dallas Cowboys Football Club, Ltd.
("Cowboys Partnership") is a limited partnership formed under
the laws of Texas and has its principal place of business in
Irving, Texas.  Cowboys Partnership is a Member Club of the
NFL, and owns and operates the team known as the Dallas Cow-
boys.  Cowboys Partnership is a shareholder of NFL Properties.
Each of the partners of the Cowboys Partnership is either an
individual person who is a citizen of Texas or a corporation
incorporated under the laws of Texas with its principal place
of business in Texas.

         4.   Defendant Texas Stadium Corporation ("Stadium
Corporation") is a Texas corporation with its principal place
of business in Irving, Texas.  Stadium Corporation operates
Texas Stadium, the home playing field of the Dallas Cowboys.

         5.   Defendant Jerral W. Jones ("Jones") is a citizen
of the State of Texas.  Defendant Jones is the sole stockholder
of JWJ Corporation, the sole general partner of defendant Cow-
boys Partnership and controls defendant Cowboys Partnership.
He is also the sole shareholder of, and controls, defendant
Stadium Corporation.  From March 14, 1990 to June 14, 1995,
Jones was a director of plaintiff NFL Properties, at which
later date he resigned as a director in contemplation of con-
tinuing the implementation of the wrongful plan and scheme de-
scribed in this Complaint.

         6.   Jurisdiction over this action is conferred on
this Court pursuant to 15 U.S.C.  1121, 28 U.S.C.  1331,
1332, 1338(a) and (b), and 1367.  The amount in controversy
exceeds $50,000 exclusive of interests and costs.

         7.   Venue in this district is proper under 28 U.S.C.
1391(b).  A substantial part of the events giving rise to the
claims herein occurred in this District.


         The NFL and the Licensing of Club Marks


         8.   The NFL is an unincorporated association of 30
Member Clubs.  Each of the NFL's Member Clubs, including defen-
dant Cowboys Partnership, owns and operates a professional
football team engaged, jointly with other Member Clubs, in pro-
viding entertainment services by playing competitive football
games in various locations throughout the United States.  Each
Member Club has the right to operate an NFL professional foot-
ball team in a designated territory and to play football games
against other teams according to a schedule and terms arranged
by the NFL.

         9.   NFL football has become a highly successful and
lucrative entertainment product.  The phenomenal success and
popularity of NFL football has resulted from the joint efforts
and close cooperation of the Member Clubs.  Particularly impor-
tant to the NFL's success are joint arrangements that provide
for, among other things, revenue sharing and other mechanisms,
including the college draft and free agency rules, that pre-
serve and enhance competitive balance among the teams fielded
by the Member Clubs.  Through such mechanisms and other joint
arrangements among the Member Clubs, NFL football has become a
highly successful product in the entertainment market, and, as
a result of these and other joint activities, the Member Clubs
have come to enjoy tremendous financial success.

         10.  The cornerstone of the NFL system, however, is
revenue sharing.  To produce competitive games, it is essential
that teams be well-matched.  The NFL and its Member Clubs thus
have a strong interest in having strong, viable teams.  Revenue
sharing is critical to achieve this end:  it ensures that all
NFL Member Clubs, not just those in larger or better situated
markets, will have the financial resources to field a competi-
tive team.

         11.  The Dallas Cowboys franchise itself is a case in
point:  revenue sharing has contributed to its present success.
In 1989, when defendant Jones acquired the Cowboys, the team
was unimpressive.  It had suffered through several mediocre
seasons -- missing the playoffs and compiling a losing record.
During Jones' first season as owner (the 1989-90 season), the
Cowboys went 1-15.  Yet the Cowboys shared equally in the na-
tional revenues of the NFL and the profits of NFL Properties,
receiving the same share as that year's Super Bowl champion,
the San Francisco 49ers.  And the Cowboys also benefited
greatly from the integrated group of agreements entered into by
the Member Clubs.  It picked marquee players like Troy Aikman,
Michael Irvin and Emmitt Smith through the draft.  All the
while, Jones received substantial revenue to operate the Cow-
boys through the NFL's various revenue sharing agreements.  The
system allowed Jones to rebuild the Cowboys into a command-
ing NFL team -- one that has now made three straight trips to the
National Football Conference Championship Game and has won two
of the last three Super Bowls.

     12.  One important source of revenue shared by NFL
Member Clubs is that which derives from the various identifying
marks of the NFL's teams.  These identifying marks -- which
include, among other things, team names, nicknames, logos, col-
ors, insignias, helmet designs, uniform designs, and identify-
ing slogans -- are trademarks, trade names or service marks
protected under federal and state law.  These identifying marks
of the various Member Clubs (hereinafter "Club Marks") have
become extremely valuable.  Also of great value are the identi-
fying marks of the NFL itself (hereinafter "NFL Marks"), such
as the NFL shield design, the mark "NFL", and the names "Super
Bowl," "American Football Conference," and "National Football
Conference."  Manufacturers of consumer products and providers
of consumer services today are willing to pay large sums for
the right to use the Club Marks and NFL Marks to promote their
own goods and services.

         13.  The Member Clubs recognized long ago that the
Club Marks and NFL Marks would be more competitive in the mar-
ket place and that their value would be maximized and thus more
effective in promoting the NFL, if they were licensed as a
package.  Accordingly, in 1963, the Member Clubs created plain-
tiff NFL Properties to market the Club Marks and NFL Marks
jointly; from its existence, NFL Properties has conducted ad-
vertising campaigns and promotional ventures on behalf of the
NFL and all of its Member Clubs.  In 1982, NFL Properties'
ability to market the Club Marks was greatly enhanced by a se-
ries of agreements entered into and approved by the Member
Clubs, including the Dallas Cowboys, to facilitate a long-term
unified program of promotional activities involving the Club
Marks and NFL Marks.  Under these agreements (the "Licensing
Agreements"), each Member Club transferred exclusive rights to
its Club Marks to a trust pursuant to a plan whereby the trust
would then exclusively license all such Club Marks to NFL Prop-
erties; NFL Properties became solely responsible for licensing
the Club Marks for commercial use.   (Two of the Member Clubs
have exclusive licensing agreements directly with NFL Proper-
ties for the commercial use of their Club Marks.)  In addition,
NFL Properties would also exploit the NFL Marks in conjunction
with the Club Marks.  The proceeds of NFL Properties' licensing
activities would be shared equally among all Member Clubs, with
some portion to be used for charitable and educational pur-
poses.  The Licensing Agreements have served as a critical com-
ponent of the joint-venture goals of the NFL.

         14.  Thus, pursuant to a trust agreement dated Octo-
ber 1, 1982 (the "Trust Agreement"), a trust called the NFL
Trust was created by the Member Clubs under New York law.  Un-
der the Trust Agreement, the settlors of the NFL Trust agreed
to transfer exclusive rights to use its Club Marks for com-
mercial purposes (with certain limited exceptions not herein
relevant) to the NFL Trust for a period of years.  Thus, for
example, the predecessor entity to the Cowboys Partnership ex-
ecuted Schedule G to the NFL Trust Agreement, which transferred
the exclusive right to use the Dallas Cowboys' Club Marks to
the NFL Trust.  In 1989, upon purchasing the predecessor en-
tity, defendant Cowboys Partnership assumed all of its
predecessor's obligations under the Licensing Agreements.  And
in 1989 as a condition precedent to Jones' purchase of a con-
trolling interest in defendant Cowboys Partnership, he commit-
ted to participating as a shareholder and licensor in NFL Prop-
erties and as a grantor in the NFL Trust.

         15.  The marks thus exclusively licensed to plaintiff
specifically include all trademarks, service marks and trade
names used in connection with the Dallas Cowboys, including
team names, helmet designs, insignia, uniforms, colors, and
identifying slogans (the "Cowboys Club Marks").  Moreover, as
did the other Member Club signatories to the Trust Agreement,
the defendant Cowboys Partnership's predecessor, in settling
the NFL Trust, further expressly covenanted to grant "no
rights, other than those granted in this [Trust] Agreement, to
any party for any commercial uses of Club Marks."  Schedule G
at page 1, Article 3.  Defendant Cowboys Partnership's prede-
cessor expressly acknowledged that it agreed to this restric-
tion because it recognizes the need for and importance of ongoing
promotional endeavors to maintain and enhance the
public image of the NFL and all of its Member
Clubs[,]  [and] further recognizes that the most ef-
fective means of achieving such widespread promo-
tional exposure is through a unified program of pro-
motional activities involving the Marks of the NFL
and all of its Clubs.

         16.  By the terms of the Trust Agreement, the Member
Clubs expressly contemplated and intended that the Club Marks
would be licensed by the NFL Trust to plaintiff NFL Properties:
Article 1.02 of the Trust Agreement specifically required the
NFL Trust to "enter into a long-term exclusive licensing agree-
ment with [NFL Properties] for the purpose of deriving revenues
from" the Club Marks.  Accordingly, simultaneously with its
creation, the NFL Trust entered into a license agreement dated
October 1, 1982 with plaintiff NFL Properties (the "Club Li-
cense Agreement") that provides plaintiff with "the exclusive
right to license the use of the Trust Property on all types of
merchandise and in connection with all types of advertising and
promotional programs."  As are the other Club Marks, the Cow-
boys Club Marks are included in the "Trust Property" licensed
exclusively to plaintiff.  As a result of the Club License
Agreement, individual Member Clubs have retained no right to
license the Club Marks to third parties (with very limited ex-
ceptions, not at issue here).  Plaintiff NFL Properties, in
short, has the exclusive right to license the Club Marks --
including the Club Marks of the Dallas Cowboys -- for com-
mercial use.

         17.  Plaintiff NFL Properties is also the exclusive
licensing agent for the NFL Marks.  The net effect of the Trust
Agreement and the Club License Agreements is to create an ar-
rangement through which the commercial use of the Club Marks
and the NFL Marks is managed in a unified program for the col-
lective benefit of the NFL's Member Clubs as participants in
the NFL joint venture and as equal shareholders of plaintiff
NFL Properties.  Plaintiff thus licenses the Club Marks and the
NFL Marks to third parties for commercial purposes, and pro-
tects the marks from infringement, dilution, disparagement,
misappropriation, and unfair competition.

         18.  Plaintiff NFL Properties has been extremely ac-
tive in promoting the NFL and the Member Clubs.  It has issued
hundreds of licenses for the use of the Club Marks, and Member
Clubs have enjoyed very substantial and increasing royalty in-
come from those licenses.  Plaintiff has also entered into
agreements with various companies involved in particular prod-
uct categories -- such as soft drinks, charge cards, and many
others -- to be exclusive sponsors of the NFL and its Member
Clubs.  Sponsors are granted the right to use the Club Marks
and NFL Marks in advertising, promotion, packaging and point-
of-sale materials, to promote themselves as an "Official Spon-
sor" of the NFL and, in some cases, as an +'Official Sponsor" of
the Member Clubs.  A sponsor is entitled in its enjoyment of
the use of the Club Marks and NFL Marks to the good faith and
cooperation of the NFL and all of its Member Clubs, including
the Dallas Cowboys.  In its most recent fiscal year, 1994,
plaintiff enjoyed a net profit from such activities of some
$100 million.


         19.  The unified promotional program carried out by
NFL Properties serves vital purposes for the Member Clubs and
the NFL.  First, it promotes the joint business of all Member
Clubs in the presentation of professional football entertain-
ment, by distinguishing and elevating professional football
over other entertainment provided in the United States and
elsewhere throughout the world.  Second, it provides efficiency
and quality control in the overall management of the licensing
arrangements for the Club Marks and the NFL Marks.  Third, it
facilitates collaborative efforts to promote the image and
prestige of the NFL in the creation, development, exploitation
and protection of the intellectual property of the NFL Member
Clubs.  Fourth, it ensures that the collective interests of the
NFL Member Clubs in the exploitation of the Club and NFL Marks
-- the value of which is derived from the collective efforts of
the Member Clubs -- are protected and are not subverted by the
short-term interests of a single Member Club.  Fifth, it gener-
ates revenues from the sale of licensing and sponsorship
rights, which is shared equally among the Member Clubs and has
the effect of furthering the NFL's effort to maintain competi-
tive parity.  NFL Properties' joint promotional efforts have
been a tremendous success and have benefited all of the Member
Clubs, including the Dallas Cowboys.

   The Wrongful Plan and Scheme


         20.  At a point in time not known to plaintiff, de-
fendant Jones decided that he was dissatisfied with the rev-
enue-sharing aspects of NFL Properties.  While continuing to
enjoy all of the other benefits of the NFL joint venture, he
determined to embark upon a wrongful plan and scheme to destroy
the structure and operations of NFL Properties in order to gain
for the Cowboys more than an equal share of licensing revenue
and to deny that revenue to the other Member Clubs.  Pursuant
to this wrongful plan and scheme, defendant Jones, along with
the entities he controls, defendants Cowboys Partnership and
Stadium Corporation, have sought and continue to seek to usurp
the revenue generated from licensing and promotion of the NFL
Marks and Cowboys Club Marks, while continuing to share in all
the other benefits of the NFL joint venture and the revenue it
generates.  The scheme has included, and, unless enjoined, will
continue to include, violations of the Lanham Act; breaches of
the Licensing Agreements; breaches of fiduciary duty to the
Dallas Cowboys' co-joint venturers in the NFL; misappropriation
of the property rights of plaintiff; acts that would wrongfully
destroy and interfere with the value of the Cowboys Club Marks,
the rights to which were transferred to the NFL Trust and to
plaintiff; wrongful tortious interference with contractual
rights of others; and sham transactions ostensibly undertaken
in the name of defendant Stadium Corporation (but in reality
transactions with defendant Cowboys Partnership) designed to
circumvent and evade defendant Cowboys Partnership's obliga-
tions to plaintiff.

         21.  Defendant Jones is fully aware that his usurpa-
tion of the licensing revenue generated by the Cowboys Club
Marks that is presently shared among the Member Clubs would be
the end of joint promotion and marketing of the NFL Marks and
Club Marks and, ultimately, for NFL Properties.  Jones under-
stands that, if defendants are permitted to "cherry-pick" among
the benefits and obligations of the NFL and NFL Properties and
to enter into separate deals with competitors of sponsors or
licensees that have contracted with NFL Properties, the entire
collective marketing and revenue-sharing system of NFL Proper-
ties will unravel.

         22.  And that, indeed, is precisely what will occur
if defendant Jones's wrongful plan and scheme is allowed to
continue:  First, the exclusive sponsors and licensees of the
NFL and NFL Properties will be unwilling to pay major consider-
ation for those rights if the rights can be unilaterally under-
mined by the sponsors' competitors obtaining conflicting rights
directly from defendants to exploit the substantial goodwill of
the Dallas Cowboys.  The value of the Club and NFL Marks to NFL
Properties, and thus to the Member Clubs, will greatly dimin-
ish.  Second, other Member Clubs cannot indefinitely sit idly
by and watch defendant Cowboys Partnership alone enjoy, by the
device of separate "side deals," revenues from the exploitation
of the Cowboys Club Marks while at the same time watching their
own revenue stream diminish as the collective rights of NFL
Properties become less valuable.  Inevitably, the Member Clubs
will have no choice but to seek to abandon the system of joint
promotion.  That is, indeed, defendant Jones's specific intent:
to undermine and to destroy the present joint marketing plan
for Club Marks administered by plaintiff.  As blatantly trum-
peted by defendant Jones:  "My legacy in this league is that
I'm going to be the one that unshackles the merchandise sales."
Or, as reported by The Washington Post on Sunday, September 17,
1995 in its story entitled "The Head Cowboy Tries to Ride
Alone," Jones has stated: "I'm bucking the league in a sense
that I know they don't want clubs to individually make market-
ing agreements of the nature that I'm making.  Who is they?
They is me."  (A copy of The Washington Post story is annexed
to this Complaint as Exhibit "A".)

       23.  To carry out his wrongful plan and scheme, de-
fendant Jones has caused and is threatening to continue to
cause defendant Stadium Corporation. to enter into a series of
highly-publicized contractual arrangements that patently vio-
late defendant Cowboys Partnership's contractual and fiduciary
obligations to NFL Properties.  Although nominally with defen-
dant Stadium Corporation, these arrangements in actuality im-
permissibly exploit the Cowboys Club Marks, the Club Marks and
the NFL Marks, and thus wrongfully misappropriate revenue that
belongs to plaintiff and should be shared among all the Member
Clubs.  The use of Stadium Corporation as a stand-in for the
defendant Cowboys Partnership is manifestly a transparent ruse
and subterfuge designed to permit assertion of a supposed claim
that the transactions are not in violation of the contractual
and fiduciary obligations of defendant Cowboys Partnership.
Any such claim would be patently spurious in that, among other
things:

    (a)  Defendant Jones is the sole owner of defendant
Stadium Corporation, is the sole stockholder of
the general partner of defendant Cowboys Part-
nership, and controls both of these defendants.

    (b)  Defendant Jones has made clear that the opera-
tions of Stadium Corporation and the Cowboys
partnership are one and the same:  "[O]ur orga-
nization is the same people who make all the
decisions with the football team and make them
over at the stadium "

    (c)  Texas Stadium is entirely devoted to the Cow-
boys; it is not used for any other sport, or by
any other team; and it is widely known and held
out as the home of the Dallas Cowboys.

    (d)  Defendants' own marketing materials tout an
"identification with . . . Texas Stadium" as
being a "[s]ponsorship with the Dallas Cowboys."
This is indeed the case:  fans do not root for a
stadium.

    (e)  Defendant Jones has publicly announced that
" I really do want anyone to know that if you're
going to market or be a sponsor of the Dallas
Cowboys/Texas Stadium, I want you to come to
Dallas, not to Park Avenue."

    (f)  Defendant Jones has publicly claimed that rev-
enues ostensibly being received by defendant
Stadium Corporation from the wrongful transac-
tions described in this Complaint would be used
by defendant Cowboys Partnership in the signing
of a star player.

    (g)  Defendant Jones has caused each of defendants
Cowboys Partnership and Stadium Corporation to
act in concert with, and to aid and abet each
other in the carrying out of the wrongful plan
and scheme.

         24.  These willful and wrongful activities are inten-
tionally designed to arrogate exclusively for defendants' valu-
able business opportunities and revenues that rightfully belong
to plaintiff NFL Properties, have caused irreparable harm to
NFL Properties, and threaten to unravel the entire NFL Proper-
ties marketing system.  The activities have also caused ir-
reparable harm to consumers by confusing persons who watch NFL
games and support NFL Member Clubs about whether the NFL or
plaintiff has sponsored, approved of, or affiliated themselves
with, the Cowboys' wrongful activities.  And defendant Jones
has made it clear that he intends to enter into other, similar
marketing and promotional deals, which will have the effect of
further injuring NFL Properties and the NFL joint venture.  By
way of example, see Exhibit A annexed hereto ("Jones said Fri-
day [September 15, 1995] he plans to announce two more Stadium
sponsorship deals in 'the next few business days.'").

         Soft Drink Sponsorship

         25.  The soft-drink product category is one of the
major sponsorship categories available to NFL football and
other professional sports.  Pursuant to a five-year exclusive
licensing and sponsorship agreement with plaintiff dated Febru-
ary 26, 1993, the Coca-Cola Company ("Coca-Cola"), in return
for many millions of dollars in payments, is entitled to the
exclusive right to use the NFL Marks and Club Marks in connec-
tion with the marketing of soft drinks.  The intent of the
agreement is that Coca-Cola soft drinks, and only Coca-Cola
soft drinks, are entitled to be promoted in association with
the NFL and its Member Clubs.

         26.  Defendants have full knowledge of the existence
and terms of plaintiff's licensing and sponsorship agreement
with Coca-Cola, and have acted in intentional and flagrant
derogation of that agreement and of the Licensing Agreements.

        The Dr. Pepper Transaction

         27.  In furtherance of the wrongful plan and scheme,
in or about the Summer of 1995, defendant Jones, ostensibly
acting through defendant Stadium Corporation, solicited a
transaction with Dr. Pepper/Seven-Up Companies, Inc.  ("Dr. Pep-
per") for "pouring rights" for Dr. Pepper soft drinks at Texas
Stadium.  This transaction was solicited by wrongful use of NFL
Marks and Cowboys Club Marks, wrongfully held out to Dr. Pepper
the benefits to be achieved by it from identification and uti-
lization of such marks and the goodwill associated with the NFL
and the Cowboys, and was in violation of the Licensing Agree-
ments and in derogation of plaintiff's exclusive licensing and
sponsorship agreement with Coca-Cola.

         28.  As owner of Texas Stadium, defendant Stadium
Corporation is entitled to select a soft-drink vendor or ven-
dors of its choice to sell soft drinks at stadium events.  The
arrangement contemplated between defendants and Dr. Pepper was,
however, in no way limited to a simple grant of stadium "pour-
ing rights."  Thus, the proposal to Dr. Pepper was to enter
into a "Dallas Cowboys and Dr. Pepper Joint Venture+; to afford
Dr. Pepper a "[s]ponsorship with the Dallas Cowboys through an
identification with the most visible real estate property in
Texas, Texas Stadium."  Such proposed transaction was blatantly
in violation of the Licensing Agreements, whereby defendant
Cowboys Partnership transferred to the Trust, which in turn
licensed to plaintiff, the exclusive right to enter into spon-
sorship agreements with respect to the Dallas Cowboys.  Such
proposed transaction likewise constituted a blatant and wrong-
ful interference with the contractual arrangements between
plaintiff and Coca-Cola whereby Coca-Cola is designated the
exclusive sponsor of the NFL and has the exclusive right to use
the Club Marks with respect to the soft-drink category.

        29.  Further, in wrongfully soliciting Dr. Pepper to
enter into such a +sponsorship" arrangement "with the Dallas
Cowboys," defendants made wrongful use of the Cowboys Club
Marks -- including the Cowboys "Star" logo -- and the NFL Marks
-- including the NFL's "Shield" logo.  Defendants had no right
to make any use of these marks for any such purpose.

         30.  In or about September 1995, upon information and
belief, in response to the proposal, Dr. Pepper in fact entered
into an agreement for the relationship that had been proposed
and described to it by defendants.

         The Pepsi Transaction

         31.  In addition, in furtherance of the wrongful plan
and scheme, in or about August 1995, defendants entered into an
agreement with PepsiCo, Inc.  ("Pepsi"), Coca-Cola's arch rival,
that once again was designed to and does wrongfully exploit the
goodwill of the Dallas Cowboys, the Cowboys Club Marks and the
NFL Marks in violation of the Licensing Agreements and the
rights of Coca-Cola pursuant to its exclusive licensing and
sponsorship agreement with plaintiff.  Once again, although
ostensibly a contractual arrangement with defendant Stadium
Corporation, in actuality the agreement wrongfully granted to
Pepsi sponsorship rights with respect to the Dallas Cowboys and
was designed to permit Pepsi to hold itself out and to be un-
derstood to be the "official cola" of the Dallas Cowboys.
Thus, among other things:

    (a)  Pepsi received the right to market itself as the
"official cola" of "Texas Stadium, home of the
Dallas Cowboys";

    +b)  An executive of defendant Cowboys Partnership
set forth for the press:  "Coke is out of Texas
Stadium.  They have been given the boot";

    (c)  Defendant Jones announced-

  "Our organization is the same people who
  make all the decisions with the football
  team and make them over at the stadium.  So
  what is being said in a way that everybody
  knows is that we sell Pepsi, we Promote
  Pepsi, and we drink Pepsi, in this entire
  organization -- the Cowboys, the stadium.
  everybody" (emphasis added); and

    (d)  At a press conference on August 3, 1995 announc-
ing the Pepsi transaction, defendant Jones as-
sociated in his dress a shirt emblazoned with a
Cowboys Club Mark and boots emblazoned with a
Pepsi logo and flamboyantly posed for the press,
as reflected in a picture in The New York Times.

     32.  Defendants fully understood and intended that
their conduct in entering into the Pepsi transaction was viola-
tive of the rights of plaintiff, and in derogation of the en-
tire NFL Properties' marketing plan.  Defendant Jones publicly
stated that:

    (a)  the transaction was "all about challenging the
status quo" and was an act that "hits [plaintiff
NFL] Properties and Coca-Cola right on the
nose";

    (b)  it was his intention that "ultimately all logos,
the helmet and star associated with the Cowboys
will be handled by the Dallas Cowboys and not
the marketing arm of the NFL [i.e., plaintiff
NFL Properties]"; and

    (c)  "I really do want anyone to know that if you're
going to market or be a sponsor of the Dallas
Cowboys/Texas Stadium, I want YOU to come to
Dallas. not to Park Avenue [the offices of NFL
Properties]."

            Apparel Sponsorships --

            The NIKE Transaction

         33.  The authentic sports apparel category is like-
wise one of major significance in arrangements for NFL sponsor-
ship rights.  In particular, plaintiff NFL Properties has
granted a number of licenses called "PRO LINE" licenses, which
afford licensees exclusive rights to sell apparel and equipment
bearing the Club Marks and the NFL Marks.  Another aspect of
the PRO LINE licenses is the payment by the licensee of a tele-
vision exposure fee.  NFL Member Club players, coaches and
other club personnel are called upon to wear items bearing the
insignia of a particular PRO LINE licensee, which is then cap-
tured by television cameras during the course of games, which
are watched by millions of television viewers.  Defendants are
fully aware of the existence and terms of plaintiff's contrac-
tual agreements with its PRO LINE licensees.

         34.  NIKE, Inc. ("NIKE") is a competitor of
plaintiff's PRO LINE licensees.  Although NIKE is itself a PRO
LINE licensee as to certain products (footwear, gloves and
socks), it is not a PRO LINE licensee as to major items of ap-
parel, for example, headwear, shirts and jackets.  In further-
ance of the wrongful plan and scheme, in or about late August
or early September 1995, defendants entered into an agreement
with NIKE, which was in violation of defendant Cowboys
Partnership's contractual, trust, and licensing obligations,
and the contractual relationships that exist between plaintiff
and competing PRO LINE licensees.

         35.  Once again, defendants purported to act through
the device of an agreement nominally entered into by Stadium
Corporation.  And once again, this was a transparent subter-
fuge:  in truth and in fact, it was a blatant violation of the
contractual and fiduciary obligations of defendant Cowboys
Partnership in that the agreement was intended to, and does,
operate to create an association between NIKE and the Dallas
Cowboys.  In addition, defendants have affirmatively and wrong-
fully acted to disassociate the Cowboys from plaintiff's autho-
rized PRO LINE licensees, and have in bad faith taken actions
to deprive such authorized "PRO LINE" licensees of the benefits
of their rights.

         36.  By way of example:

    (a)  The announcement of the NIKE transaction was
carefully orchestrated to maximize public expo-
sure of a new relationship between NIKE and the
Cowboys, quite apart from anything having to do
with Texas Stadium.

    (b)  The transaction was announced on September 4,
1995, by a press release issued not at Texas
Stadium but at the New Jersey Meadowlands, the
site of the Cowboys' Monday night opening game
for the 1995-96 season, and thus an occasion
guaranteed to capture the large prime-time tele-
vision audience that watched the first regular
season Monday Night Football and to gain ex-
traordinary media exposure.

    (c)  The press release was issued jointly by NIKE and
the Dallas Cowboys and was headlined:  "COWBOYS
OWNER BUCKS NFL AGAIN."

    (d)  The joint press release quoted the Chief Execu-
tive Officer of NIKE as setting forth:

  "This agreement with the Dallas Cowboys
  allows us the opportunity to pursue our
  desire to be associated with one of the
  most popular football teams in America
  while we continue our efforts to work with
  NFL Properties in an official capacity"
  (emphasis added).

    (e)  During the game at the Meadowlands (upon infor-
mation and belief, by defendant Jones' express
order), none of the Cowboys' players, coaches or
other sideline personnel dressed in the apparel
of PRO LINE licensees, including, for the first
half of the game, personnel who had authorized
individual contractual commitments to wear ap-
parel items bearing the logos of such licensees;
and throughout the entirety of the game, the
defendants wrongfully caused to be removed from
Cowboys players' helmets the insignia of
plaintiff's PRO LINE helmet licensee, Riddell,
Inc.

    (f)  During that game, defendant Jones personally
escorted to the Cowboys sideline the NIKE Chief
Executive Officer (Phil Knight), another NIKE
executive, and Monica Seles, the famous profes-
sional tennis player who is a paid NIKE pro-
moter.  Defendant Jones and his companions all
prominently wore NIKE-branded merchandise.

    (g)  The actions of defendants drew intense public
attention to the Cowboys' relationship with NIKE
to the exclusion of Reebok International, Ltd.,
the PRO LINE Licensee of the New York Giants.
Millions of television viewers observed no ap-
parel brand other than NIKE, which diminished
and interfered with Reebok's enjoyment of the
benefits of its PRO LINE license, and damaged
NFL Properties' relationship with Reebok.

    (h)  Thereafter, defendants purposely took further
wrongful and highly publicized actions to ensure
that the public understood that the Cowboys were
affiliating themselves with NIKE as a sponsor --
in derogation of the rights of plaintiff's PRO
LINE licensees.  Thus, at the Cowboys' first
home game of the 1995-96 season, a 30-foot-long
NIKE logo was hung over midfield, to be caught
prominently by the television cameras; and NIKE
logos festooned the stadium portals and were
otherwise ubiquitously in view.

         37.  All of the foregoing conduct constituted blatant
violations of the rights of plaintiff NFL Properties, as well
as violations of contractual and fiduciary obligations of de-
fendants, and of contractual rights of licensees of plaintiff.
In particular, defendants' conduct constituted a blatantly im-
permissible exploitation of the good will of the Dallas Cow-
boys, the Cowboys Club Marks, and the NFL Marks in violation of
the Licensing Agreements and the rights of plaintiff and its
official PRO LINE licensees.

             Other Threatened Wrongful Conduct

  ~      38.  In furtherance of defendant Jones' wrongful plan
and scheme, defendants threaten to engage in additional conduct
in derogation of the rights of NFL Properties, and official NFL
Properties sponsors and licensees.  Upon information and be-
lief, defendants have made other proposals for similar con-
tracts with other companies competing with NFL Properties lic-
ensees.  These proposals, which upon information and belief
make extensive use of NFL Marks and internal NFL Properties
marketing information (without NFL Properties' permission) and
seek to exploit the value and success of the NFL as a whole,
offer advertising and promotional rights that go significantly
beyond the limited licensing rights that the Member Clubs re-
tain under the Trust Agreement.  Upon information and belief,
for example, defendants are negotiating an agreement with
American Express that would make American Express the official
charge card of "Texas Stadium, the home of the Dallas Cowboys."
Such an agreement, as defendants well know, would constitute a
manifest violation of the rights of VISA, which is the official
charge card of the NFL pursuant to a license granted by plain-
tiff NFL Properties earlier in 1995, and would thus constitute
a manifest violation of the rights of plaintiff.  And, on Sep-
tember 17, 1995, it was reported in The Washington Post that
defendant Jones intended to announce two more stadium sponsor-
ship deals in the "'next few business days. (Exhibit A an-
nexed hereto.)  Unless restrained, it is clear that defendants'
wrongful conduct will continue.


            Injury to NFL Properties and the Public

         39.  Defendants' violation of their contractual and
fiduciary obligations to the plaintiff and its exclusive rights
in the Club Marks injures and, unless restrained, will continue
to injure plaintiff NFL Properties in several ways.  Among
other things, defendants' wrongful conduct:  (1)  usurps and
undermines licensing opportunities that would otherwise be
available to plaintiff for the benefit of the NFL Member Clubs;
(2) interferes with plaintiff's ability to conduct a league-
wide unified national licensing and promotional program utiliz-
ing NFL Marks and the Club Marks in order to present to the
public the image and the reality of a national sports enter-
tainment entity; (3) interferes with plaintiff's established
relationships with licensees, threatening the goodwill plain-
tiff holds in those relationships; (4) threatens plaintiff's
ability to ensure that licensed products are of a consistent
high quality that will enhance the public image of the NFL and
its Member Clubs; and (5) jeopardizes and tarnishes the value
of plaintiff's right to use the Club Marks and NFL Marks.  Un-
less restrained, defendants+ continuing wrongful conduct will
continue to cause these harms.

         40.  Thus, as a result of defendants' wrongful plan
and scheme, existing sponsors and licensees of plaintiff NFL
Properties have complained and may want rebates on their li-
censing fees or want to cancel their contracts altogether.
Sponsors and licensees who are in process of renewing their
licenses will choose not to do so.  And future sponsors and
licensees will decide to seek other means of promotion and ad-
vertising.

         41.  Beyond this, members of the public who watch NFL
games on television and in person will be deceived, confused,
misled and defrauded by defendants' activities, which are cre-
ating the false impression that products wrongfully promoted by
defendants in derogation of the rights of plaintiff NFL Proper-
ties and its licensees and sponsors are sponsored, approved or
authorized by not only the Cowboys, but also by the NFL and the
plaintiff.

         42.  Plaintiff NFL Properties has suffered and will
continue to suffer substantial injury as a result of defen-
dants' unlawful conduct, resulting in damages that are not
presently known but are believed to be in excess of $100 mil-
lion.

         43.  Defendants' tortious conduct, breach of fidu-
ciary duty and breaches of contract have been intentional and
deliberate, malicious, wanton, reckless and in deliberate dis-
regard of the rights of others.  This misconduct has been egre-
gious, has involved a high degree of moral culpability, moral
turpitude and wanton dishonesty, and has been aimed at plain-
tiff and at the public generally.

         44.  The injuries that will be suffered by plaintiff
NFL Properties as a result of the continuation of defendants'
unlawful conduct are substantial, not fully compensable in mon-
etary damages and irreparable.  These injuries will be dif-
ficult to ascertain and calculate in monetary terms.  Unless
defendants are restrained, the injuries caused by defendants
wrongful conduct will continue.

             COUNT I

           (Lanham Act)

         45.  Plaintiff repeats and realleges the allegations
of paragraphs 1 through 44 of the Complaint as if fully set
forth herein.

         46 . As alleged above, by virtue of the License
Agreements, defendants have no right whatsoever to license the
Cowboys Club Marks and the NFL Marks for commercial use by
third parties; those rights belong exclusively to plaintiff.

         47.  By making Dr. Pepper a soft-drink sponsor of
Texas Stadium, "the home of the Dallas Cowboys," and by procur-
ing such sponsorship in the manner set forth above, defendants
have caused and are likely to cause a likelihood of confusion,
mistake and deception as to the affiliation, connection or as-
sociation of sponsorship, licensing, endorsement or other ap-
proval by the Dallas Cowboys or the NFL of Dr. Pepper products,
promotions and advertising, in violation of Section 43(a) of
the Lanham Act, 15 U.S.C.  1125(a).

         48.  By making Pepsi a soft-drink sponsor of Texas
Stadium, "the home of the Dallas Cowboys," and by procuring and
promoting such sponsorship in the manner set forth above, de-
fendants have caused and are likely to cause a likelihood of
confusion, mistake and deception as to the affiliation, connec-
tion or association of sponsorship, licensing, endorsement or
other approval by the Dallas Cowboys or the NFL of Pepsi prod-
ucts, promotions and advertising, in violation of Section 43(a)
of the Lanham Act, 15 U.S.C.  1125(a).

         49.  In authorizing NIKE branded apparel to be worn
on the field and on the sidelines during televised NFL games,
and in promoting and advertising such authorization, defendants
have caused and are likely to cause a likelihood of confusion,
mistake and deception as to the affiliation, connection or as-
sociation of sponsorship, licensing, endorsement or other ap-
proval by the Dallas Cowboys or the NFL of NIKE apparel prod-
ucts, promotions and advertising, in violation of Section 43(a)
of the Lanham Act, 15 U.S.C.  1125(a).

       50.  Defendants have created the false and misleading
commercial impression that NIKE has been licensed or otherwise
authorized to use the Cowboys Club Marks, the Club Marks and
the NFL Marks for merchandising and promotion of NIKE apparel
products or is otherwise affiliated, connected or associated
with the Dallas Cowboys or the NFL in violation of Section
43(a) of the Lanham Act, 15 U.S.C.  1125(a).

         51.  Defendants are threatening to enter into ad-
ditional arrangements with other competitors of plaintiff's
licensees.  Defendants' activities are causing irreparable harm
to plaintiff, and, unless restrained, will continue to cause
irreparable harm to plaintiff.  Plaintiff has no adequate rem-
edy at law.


                    COUNT II

      (Breach of Express Provisions of Contract)


         52.  Plaintiff repeats and realleges the allegations
of paragraphs 1 through 44 of the Complaint as if fully set
forth herein.

         53.  Pursuant to the Trust Agreement and the Club
License Agreement, defendant Cowboys Partnership has licensed
the exclusive rights to use all Cowboy Club Marks to NFL Prop-
erties and has expressly agreed to grant no such rights to any
other party for any commercial use of the Cowboy Club Marks.
In particular, the License Agreements provide that all present
or future +'identifying slogans" constitute Cowboys Club Marks:
this includes "Texas Stadium, the Home of the Dallas Cowboys."
Defendants are thus contractually obligated to refrain from
commercially exploiting the "Texas Stadium" mark.  In addition,
as set forth above, defendants' sponsorship agreements ostensi-
bly involving Texas Stadium are in actuality prohibited spon-
sorship agreements for the Dallas Cowboys.

         54.  By entering into and implementing the above-
described agreements with NIKE, Pepsi and Dr. Pepper, defendant
Cowboys Partnership has accordingly breached express provisions
of the Licensing Agreements.

         55.  Defendants have acted, and are continuing to
act, in concert to breach the contractual obligations of defen-
dant Cowboys Partnership  pursuant to the Licensing Agreements.

         56.  Defendants are threatening to enter into ad-
ditional arrangements with other competitors of plaintiff's
licensees.  Defendants' activities are causing irreparable harm
to plaintiff, and, unless restrained, will continue to cause
irreparable harm to plaintiff.  Plaintiff has no adequate rem-
edy at law.


                           COUNT III

                (Breach of Implied Covenant of Good

                   Faith Dealing in Contract)


         57.  Plaintiff repeats and realleges the allegations
of paragraphs 1 through 44 of the Complaint as if fully set
forth herein.

         58.  Inherent in the Licensing Agreements, as in all
agreements, is an implied covenant of good-faith dealing.  By
entering into the agreements with NIKE, Pepsi and Dr. Pepper
described above, by engaging in the subterfuge that the con-
tracts in fact involve rights as to "Texas Stadium," and by
taking the other actions set forth above, defendant Cowboys
Partnership has been acting, and is threatening to continue to
act, in breach of that implied covenant of good-faith dealing
and is openly seeking to destroy the value of the licenses
transferred and the entire marketing plan contemplated and cre-
ated by the Licensing Agreements.

         59.  Defendants have acted, and are continuing to
act, in concert to breach the contractual obligations of defen-
dant Cowboys Partnership  pursuant to the Licensing Agreements.

         60.  Defendants are threatening to enter into ad-
ditional arrangements with other competitors of plaintiff's
licensees.  Defendants+ activities are causing irreparable harm
to plaintiff, and, unless restrained, will continue to cause
irreparable harm to plaintiff.  Plaintiff has no adequate rem-
edy at law.

                   COUNT IV

        (Breach of Obligations As Settlor

         of the NFL Trust Agreement and as

         Licensor of the Cowboys Club Marks)


         61.  Plaintiff reasserts and realleges the allega-
tions of paragraphs 1 through 44 of the Complaint as if fully
set forth herein.

         62.  Defendant Cowboys Partnership as a settlor of
the NFL Trust and owner of the trademarks,-trade names and ser-
vice marks that have been licensed by the NFL Trust exclusively
to plaintiff NFL Properties is obligated to refrain from taking
any steps that will reduce the value of the marks transferred
to the Trust.

         63.  By engaging in the wrongful plan and scheme de-
scribed above, and by threatening to continue the wrongful plan
and scheme, defendant Cowboys Partnership has been acting, and,
unless restrained, will continue to act, to undermine the value
of the NFL Trust licenses and property and to interfere with
plaintiff's rights in such licenses and property.

         64.  Defendants have acted, and are continuing to
act, in concert to undermine the value of the NFL Trust li-
censes and property in violation of the Cowboys Partnership's
obligations as a Settlor of the NFL Trust and as licensor of
the Cowboys Club Marks.

         65.  Defendants are threatening to enter into ad-
ditional arrangements with other competitors of plaintiff's
licensees.  Defendants' activities are causing irreparable harm
to plaintiff, and, unless restrained, will continue to cause
irreparable harm to plaintiff.  Plaintiff has no adequate rem-
edy at law.


                      COUNT V

            (Breach of Fiduciary Duty)


         66.  Plaintiff repeats and realleges the allegations
of paragraphs 1 through 44 of the Complaint as if fully set
forth herein.

         67.  Defendant Cowboys Partnership, as a Member Club
of and joint venturer in the NFL, and as a shareholder in
plaintiff close corporation, has fiduciary duties to act with
undivided loyalty to the joint venture of which, pursuant to
the Licensing Agreements, plaintiff is the marketing arm; to
act in the highest good faith and to deal fairly with the other
Member Clubs; and, to refrain from usurping business opportuni-
ties from plaintiff.  Defendant Jones, as a director of plain-
tiff, had a fiduciary duty to act in the highest good faith and
to deal fairly with plaintiff and the Member Club shareholders
of plaintiffs and to refrain from usurping business opportuni-
ties from plaintiff.

         68.  Through the wrongful plan and scheme described
above, which commenced while defendant Jones was still a direc-
tor of plaintiff, and by threatening to continue the wrongful
plan and scheme, defendants Cowboys Partnership and Jones have
violated and threaten to continue to violate, their fiduciary
obligations, as aforesaid.

         69.  Defendants have acted, and are continuing to
act, in concert to violate defendants Cowboys Partnership's and
Jones' fiduciary obligations, as aforesaid.

         70.  Defendants are threatening to enter into ad-
ditional arrangements with other competitors of plaintiff's
licensees.  Defendants' activities are causing irreparable harm
to plaintiff, and, unless restrained, will continue to cause
irreparable harm to plaintiff.  Plaintiff has no adequate rem-
edy at law.

                   COUNT VI

             (Unjust Enrichment)


         71.  Plaintiff repeats and realleges the allegations
of paragraphs 1 through 44 of the Complaint as if fully set
forth herein.

         72.  Defendants' conduct, directly or through an af-
filiate, in marketing and licensing rights to Cowboys Club
Marks to which plaintiff has been granted exclusive rights pur-
suant to the Licensing Agreements, constitutes unjust enri-
chment to defendants.  Defendants, having benefited from
plaintiff's activities and revenue sharing when the Cowboys
were weak, now seek to "cherry pick" those aspects of the
plaintiff's arrangements, as well as those aspects of the NFL
joint venture arrangements they deem to their advantage, while
rejecting those they deem onerous.  Defendants by means of
their wrongful side deals seek to usurp for themselves more
than their rightful share of licensing and sponsorship revenue
from commercial exploitation of the Club Marks and the NFL
Marks.

         73.  Defendants are threatening to enter into ad-
ditional arrangements with competitors of plaintiff's licens-
ees.  Defendants' activities are causing irreparable harm to
plaintiff, and, unless restrained, will continue to cause ir-
reparable harm to plaintiff.  Plaintiff has no adequate remedy
at law.

                      COUNT VII

            (Misappropriation of Property)


         74.  Plaintiff repeats and realleges the allegations
of paragraphs 1 through 44 of the Complaint as if fully set
forth herein.

         75.  Defendants' conduct, as aforesaid, constitutes
misappropriation of property rights belonging to plaintiff.
Defendants by means of their wrongful side deals seek to usurp
for themselves more than their share of licensing and sponsor-
ship revenue from commercial exploitation of the Club Marks and
the NFL Marks.

         76.  Defendants are threatening to enter into ad-
ditional arrangements with other competitors of plaintiff's
licensees.  Defendants' activities are causing irreparable harm
to plaintiff, and, unless restrained, will continue to cause
irreparable harm to plaintiff.  Plaintiff has no adequate rem-
edy at law.

                  COUNT VIII

           (Tortious Interference)


         77.  Plaintiff repeats and realleges the allegations
of paragraphs 1 through 44 of the Complaint as if fully set
forth herein.


         78.  Defendants' wrongful plan and scheme has inter-
fered with and caused the violation and derogation of contrac-
tual rights granted by plaintiff to its licensees and sponsors.
Defendants knew of the existence and terms of such contractual
rights and have acted purposely, and are threatening to con-
tinue to act purposely, to interfere with and violate such con-
tractual rights.

         79.  Defendants have acted, and are continuing to
act, in concert to interfere with and to violate the contrac-
tual rights of plaintiff's licensees and sponsors.

         80.  Defendants are threatening to enter into ad-
ditional arrangements with other competitors of plaintiff's
licensees.  Defendants' activities are causing irreparable harm
to plaintiff, and, unless restrained, will continue to cause
irreparable harm to plaintiff.  Plaintiff has no adequate rem-
edy at law.

                  Count IX

            (Declaratory Judgment)


         81.  Defendants maintain that they are entitled to
enter into and to continue to enter into contracts that in ef-
fect afford sponsorship rights for the Dallas Cowboys and
rights to the Cowboys Club Marks, provided that they cause the
contracts nominally to be entered into with defendant Stadium
Corporation.  Plaintiff contests this position.  It is the po-
sition of plaintiff that contracts of the nature entered into
by defendants, as described herein, and acts taken by defen-
dants pursuant thereto:  violate the Lanham Act, the contrac-
tual obligations under the Licensing Agreements entered into by
defendant Cowboys Partnership; wrongfully undermine the license
rights transferred by defendant Cowboys Partnership as settlor
of the NFL Trust; are in breach of the fiduciary obligations
defendants owe to plaintiff; unjustly enrich defendants; and
constitute tortious interference with the contractual relation-
ships between plaintiff and its authorized licensees and spon-
sors.  As alleged above, all defendants have been acting in
concert in furtherance of the wrongful plan and scheme.

         82.  A declaratory judgment is necessary here to es-
tablish the rights of the parties:  that defendants are not
entitled to enter into agreements of the nature described
above; that defendants may not, through their wrongful actions,
render the sponsorship and licensing rights of plaintiff's
sponsors and prospective sponsors nugatory; that the contrac-
tual rights of plaintiff and Member Clubs of the NFL will be
honored; that moneys and other benefits will not be improperly
diverted to defendants; and that the other Member Clubs are
entitled to receive their appropriate share of proceeds from
the marketing of the Club Marks and the NFL Marks.  Absent a
declaration from this Court, the uncertainty as to plaintiff's
rights caused by defendants' wrongful and continuing plan and
scheme will continue, to the injury of plaintiff.


       Prayer for Relief


         WHEREFORE, plaintiff NFL Properties respectfully re-
quests that the Court enter judgment for plaintiff:

  I.  Compensatory damages in an amount not presently known
but believed to be in excess of $100 million;

  II.    Trebling of such compensatory damages pursuant to 15
U.S.C.  1117(a);

  III.    Punitive damages in an amount not less than $200 mil-
lion ;

  IV.    Permanently enjoining defendants and all persons and
entities acting in concert with defendants from:

    A.   Any future authorization, license, approval or
sponsorship of any commercial use of Cowboys
Club Marks, Club Marks or NFL Marks likely to
cause confusion, mistake or deception as to the
affiliation, association, connection or other
approval of such use by the Dallas Cowboys or
NFL;

    B.   Directly or indirectly granting any rights for
the commercial use of any Club Mark or NFL Mark,
whether by way of any ostensible grant of spon-
sorship rights as to "Texas Stadium" or other-
wise, except as explicitly reserved to defendant
Cowboys Partnership pursuant to Section 5 of
Schedule G to the Trust Agreement (reserving to
defendant Cowboys Partnership the non-exclusive
right to use Cowboys Club Marks in advertise-
ments in local advertising, the local sections
of game programs, and in its own publications);

    C.   Entering into any agreement (1) similar in na-
ture to the agreements with Dr. Pepper, Pepsi,
and NIKE described in this Complaint, or (2)
that violates the rights conveyed by defendants
to the NFL Trust and to plaintiff;

    D.   Soliciting any licensing or sponsorship agree-
ment or relationship by use of any Club Mark or
NFL Mark; or

    E.   Engaging in any future conduct that interferes
with or violates the contractual rights of
plaintiff.

    V.   Declaring that defendants' wrongful plan and scheme
is in violation of the Lanham Act, the contractual
and property rights of plaintiff and constitutes a
breach of defendants' fiduciary obligations.

  VI.    Awarding reasonable attorney fees to plaintiff pursu-
ant to 15 U.S.C.  1117(a), and awarding costs of the
action to plaintiff.

 VII.    Granting such other and further relief as the Court
may deem just and proper.

Dated:  New York, New York

September 18, 1995

WACHTELL, LIPTON, ROSEN & KATZ

   By

Herbert M. Wachtell (HW 7347)
A Member of the Firm
51 West 52nd Street
New York, New York  10019
(212) 403-1000

Attorneys for Plaintiff
National Football League
Properties, Inc.

Of Counsel:
Herbert M. Wachtell
Robert B. Mazur
George T. Conway III
Vineet Bhatia
</PRE>
