<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<P>In this complaint, the rock band REM alleges that Hershey Food Corp. used the band's trademarked name in connection with the "Kit Kat REM Contest" without authorization. Contest winners received tickets to one of the band's Hershey, PA concerts.  REM's lawyers claim that the band has long refused any form of corporate sponsorship or advertising affiliation because such affiliation would damage the band's credibility.</P>
<HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT>
<PRE>
IN THE UNITED STATES DISTRICT COURT
FOR THE NORTHERN DISTRICT OF GEORGIA
ATLANTA DIVISION

R.E.M./ATHENS, LTD.,         )

)

Plaintiff,       )

)

v.                    )     Civil Action 

)           

HERSHEY FOOD CORPORATION,       )  File No. _____________ 

)

Defendant.       )

VERIFIED COMPLAINT


Plaintiff, R.E.M./Athens, Ltd. ("R.E.M./Athens"), for its Verified
Complaint against Defendant Hershey Food Corporation ("Hershey")
alleges as follows: 1. This is an action at law and in equity for
trademark and service mark infringement, unfair competition, trademark
and service mark dilution and injury to business reputation and
tarnishment, misappropriation of identity, unfair and deceptive trade
practices, and false advertising arising under the Trademark Act of
1946, as amended by the Trademark Law Revision Act of 1989, 15 U.S.C.
 1051 et seq. ("Lanham Act"); the Georgia anti- dilution statute,
O.C.G.A.  10-1-451, and the anti- dilution statutes of other states;
the Georgia Uniform Deceptive Trade Practices Act, O.C.G.A. 
10-1-370 to -375,10-1- 451, and the deceptive trade practices acts of
other states; the Georgia Fair Business Practices Act of 1975,
O.C.G.A.  10-1-390 et seq., and the fair business practices acts of
other states; Georgia's false advertising statute, O.C.G.A. 
10-1-421, and the false advertising statutes of other states;
Georgia's fraudulent misrepresentation statute, O.C.G.A.  23-2-55;
and the common law. 2. R.E.M. is one of the most popular and
successful rock bands in the world.  One major element of R.E.M.s
success is their credibility with their fans, along with the integrity
and independence with which the band conducts its business affairs. 
R.E.M.s credibility is in part a function R.E.M.s policy not to
provide commercial endorsements.  R.E.M. routinely rejects all
commercial, sponsorship or tie-in requests, even those that would be
lucrative in the short-term.  R.E.M.s name and music are not for
sale, and their fans expect and respect the bands position. 
Nevertheless, without the permission or authorization of
R.E.M./Athens, Hershey has pirated the "R.E.M" name and trademark to
promote its KIT KAT candy bar in a manner that is likely to confuse
and deceive the public about an affiliation, connection or association
with R.E.M.  Hershey, as part of its KIT KAT advertising campaign, is
blatantly exploiting the R.E.M. name for crass commercial purposes by
conducting a "KIT KAT R.E.M. concert" sweepstakes contest.  Hersheys
promotional campaign is intended to confuse and deceive the public, is
an outrageous effort to draw on the commercial magnetism of the R.E.M.
name, and tarnishes the R.E.M. name and the artistic integrity they
strive to achieve. JURISDICTION AND VENUE 3. This Court has
jurisdiction over the subject matter and the parties under Section 39
of the Lanham Act, 15 U.S.C.  1121, and under 28 U.S.C.  1331,
1338.  This Court has jurisdiction over Plaintiff's state law claims
under 28 U.S.C.  1338(b) because these claims are joined with
substantial and related claims under federal trademark law, and
pursuant to the doctrine of supplemental jurisdiction, 15 U.S.C. 
1367. 4. Pursuant to 28 U.S.C.  1391, venue is proper in this
district because a substantial part of the acts complained of occurred
and are occurring in this district and in interstate commerce and the
defendant resides here by doing business in this district. THE PARTIES



PLAINTIFF R.E.M./ATHENS

5.
Plaintiff R.E.M./Athens is a Georgia corporation with its principal
place of business at 170 College, Athens, Georgia 30601. 
R.E.M./Athens was incorporated in March 1982.  The shareholders of
R.E.M./Athens include Bill Berry, Peter Buck, Mike Mills, Michael
Stipe, who comprise the band "R.E.M.," and Jefferson Holt.
DEFENDANT HERSHEY 6. On information and belief, Hershey Food
Corporation ("Hershey") is a Delaware corporation with its principal
place of business at 100 Crystal Drive, Hershey, Pennsylvania  17033. 
Hershey is qualified with the Georgia Secretary of State to do
business in Georgia as a foreign, for profit corporation.  Hersheys
registered agent for service of process in Georgia is C.T. Corporation
Systems, 1201 Peachtree Street, N.E., Atlanta, Georgia  30361.
Products offered for sale and sold by Hershey are offered for sale,
distributed, and sold in the State of Georgia. 7. On information and
belief, Defendant transacts business in Georgia, has entered into
contracts with businesses in Georgia and has performed those
agreements in Georgia. Defendants products, including its KIT KAT
candy bar, are offered for sale, distributed, and sold in Georgia.
Defendant has caused tortious injury in the State of Georgia, and
Defendant regularly does and solicits business, engages in other
persistent courses of conduct, and derives substantial revenue from
goods used and consumed in the State of Georgia. BACKGROUND FACTS
R.E.M. THE BAND:  ITS MUSIC AND ITS REPUTATION 8. R.E.M. formed in
1980 in Athens, Georgia.  During the past fifteen years, R.E.M. has
developed a national and international reputation and grown into one
of the premier musical groups in the world. R.E.M.s well-deserved and
hard-earned reputation is reflected in the substantial and valuable
body of good will symbolized by the R.E.M. name and image.  In the
past fifteen years, R.E.M. has released nine albums, which have
worldwide sales in excess of thirty million units. 9. Together with
R.E.M.s popular success has been critical acclaim.  Describing
critical reaction to R.E.M.s first album, Murmur, Tony Fletcher wrote
in Remarks The Story of R.E.M. that 

The all-important taste makers among the press 

were equally excited, paving the bands tour 

across America with a red carpet of glowing 

reviews.  Rolling Stone gave "Murmur" an 

uncommonly high four stars ("intelligent, 

enigmatic, deeply involving . . . it reveals a 

depth and cohesiveness to R.E.M."); Musician 

("R.E.M. has the most hypnotizing sound of any 

group playing rock today"); Record ("music of 

movement and portent, driven with vague

obsession") and the New York Times ("will sound 

as fresh ten years from now as it does today") 

all followed through.

In fact, the writers at Rolling Stone named "Murmur" their album of
the year, and R.E.M. "Best New Artist."  By the 1990s, the critical
acclaim had not subsided.  R.E.M.s "Automatic For the People"
received five stars from Rolling Stone in 1992, and 1994s release,
"Monster," received four and a half stars.  According to Robert
Hilburn, music critic for the L.A. Times, R.E.M. has "reigned for a
decade as America's most acclaimed band."  "How R.E.M. Spells
Success," L.A. Times, p. 4 (Feb. 27, 1994). A Boston Globe column
described R.E.M. as "the best and most enduring American band of the
past 20 years." Matthew Gilbert, "R.E.M. From Murmur to Monster," p.
57 (June 11, 1995).  In June 1995, an article in the Christian Science
Monitor described R.E.M. as "arguably America's hottest rock band,"
noting that "[t]he band is regarded as a patriarch of alternative
rock.  Since the early '80s, other bands have admired R.E.M."  "R.E.M.
Erupts Into A Roar on "Monster" Tour," p. 13 (June 22, 1995).  R.E.M.
has received a significant number of awards in the United States,
including Grammy Awards and MTV Music Awards, as well as international
awards, including multiple Brit Awards (the British equivalent of the
Grammy Awards) for best international band, and other equivalent
professional awards throughout the world. 10. Popular and critical
acclaim is only one part of the R.E.M. story.  Since their inception,
R.E.M. has not provided product endorsements, and over time has turned
down and forgone untold millions of dollars.  In an era when other
bands provide product endorsements for tours, appearances, songs, and
albums, R.E.M. steadfastly and repeatedly has refused to participate
in a practice they personally view as offensive and inappropriate. 
For example, in his book R.E.M. Behind the Mask, Jim Greer writes of
the group's 1989 world tour: 

The band would hit the road shortly . . . for a 

nine-month world tour . . . .  And the band did 

it without the benefit of the seemingly

ubiquitous specter of corporate sponsorship, 

turning down possibly millions of dollars in the 

process.

In November 1994, Amusement Business previewed R.E.M.'s 200 date world
tour, noting "No sponsors will be along for the ride, however," and
quoting R.E.M.'s booking agent as follows 

They're the only band to go into Singapore, 

Taiwan and Hong Kong without any sponsor 

affiliation, including airlines and hotels. 

[T]hey would consider that selling themselves 

out.

"R.E.M. Tour to Cover 200 Markets Worldwide," Amusement Business, at 3
(Nov. 28, 1994).  The same is true in other areas as well.  In a time
when concert venues attract product sponsorships tied to splashing the
corporate name on venue signs, tickets and promotional material,
R.E.M. does its best to minimize any possible association between
R.E.M. and the corporate venue/ticket sponsor. A 1995 article
described R.E.M. as "a band that has in the past embraced populist
causes, as well as avoid corporate sponsorships." Billboard, at 8
(Jan. 14, 1995).  In fact, R.E.M.'s agreements with promoters include
the following as the first condition: 

There will be no sponsorship of any kind, whatsoever. 

R.E.M.'s ability to insist on these limitations and restrictions is
based, in part, on their Contract Rider for concert agreements, which
contains the following clear language: 

The name, logo, photograph or likeness of Artist 

(and the Members, shall not be used or

associated, directly or indirectly, with any 

product (whether sold at the venue or otherwise) 

or service without the Personal Manager's prior 

written approval.  [W]ithout the Personal 

Manager's prior written approval, Promoter shall 

neither represent, nor authorize or permit any 

other person or entity to represent, that this 

Engagement (or a Performance) is being promoted, 

sponsored, co-promoted, co-sponsored by any 

product or service, or by any person or entity 

manufacturing, distributing, selling or

otherwise dealing in or associated, directly or 

indirectly, with any product or service . . . . 

No sign, banner, logo or other material

advertising any product, service, or company 

shall be permitted on, above or near the stage 

at any time after the audience is admitted to 

the Venue.  No advertising, sponsorship, or 

other type of commercial endorsement (including 

the name and/or logo of any sponsor of the 

Venue) shall appear in any flyer, handbill, 

poster or other promotional or publicity 

material relating to, or in any way an

advertisement for, a Performance and/or this 

Engagement.

The Rider agreement further provides in connection with tickets 

Neither the name or Promoter nor Promoter's 

organization, nor the name of the Venue, shall 

appear on the tickets in type larger than ten 

percent (10%) of the size used for the [R.E.M.] 

logo described . . . above.  ABSOLUTELY NO 

ADVERTISING, SPONSORSHIP OR OTHER TYPE OF 

COMMERCIAL ENDORSEMENT (INCLUDING THE NAME 

AND/OR LOGO OF ANY SPONSOR OF THE VENUE) SHALL 

APPEAR ON THE TICKETS WITHOUT COMPANY'S PRIOR 

WRITTEN CONSENT.

R.E.M. insists on these limitations, which are in every agreement.
Part of R.E.M.'s character, personality and image is that they do not
endorse products. R.E.M.'s policy is a public one:  in magazine, radio
and newspaper interviews they have expressed the philosophy that
musical artists should not do commercials because it detracts from
their artistic integrity. 11. As least as early as April 19, 1980, and
long prior to the complained of acts of Defendant, R.E.M./Athens (and
its predecessors) began using, and continuously has used and therefore
acquired rights in, the trademark and service mark "R.E.M." for
entertainment services, recordings and clothing. 12. R.E.M./Athens is
the owner of federal trademark registrations for the following
trademarks: 

Mark -  R.E.M.

Reg. No. - 1,247,934 

Description of Goods

Entertainment services,
namely, live performances by a
vocal and instrumental group


Mark - R.E.M.

Reg. No. - 1,366,598

Description of Goods -
posters; t-shirts

Copies of the Certificate of Registration for these marks are attached
as Exhibits 1-2. 13. R.E.M./Athens' federal registrations for the
R.E.M. marks are, pursuant to Sections 15 and 33(b) of the Lanham Act,
15 U.S.C.  1065, 1115(b), incontestable, and consequently
R.E.M./Athens is entitled to a statutory presumption of "the exclusive
right to use the registered mark" for the goods and services covered
by the registrations. 14. The goods and services offered under the
distinctive and famous R.E.M. mark have been advertised and promoted
throughout the State of Georgia and the United States.  As a result of
the substantial efforts and organizational energy, R.E.M. has achieved
commercial success and favorable recognition and are widely recognized
and accepted by the public. The R.E.M. name and mark have been widely
used and are recognized throughout Georgia and the United States as an
indication of the source of the goods and services offered by the
group.  By virtue of this widespread and continuing use, the R.E.M.
mark has acquired secondary meaning and exclusively identify
R.E.M./Athens, and the group R.E.M., and their goods and services. 
The R.E.M. name and marks and goodwill associated with them are
distinctive and famous marks of inestimable value to R.E.M./Athens.
15. R.E.M.'s success, and continued success, is built on its
credibility with fans, critics, and the public.  Robert Hilburn of the
L.A. Times, attempting to describe the foundation for R.E.M.'s
success, pointed to the fact 

that the band saw that there was a dignity and 

reward in simply making music with character and 

heart rather than in copying the soulless 

commercialism . . . .  After eight studio albums 

. . . R.E.M. stands with its original

independence and vision intact.

A 1994 article in Billboard commented that "Through the years, R.E.M.
has been able to find success while retaining its artistic integrity."
 "Retail, Radio Expect R.E.M.'s Warner Set to Be A "Monster,"" p. 1
(Sept. 10, 1994).  An article in The San Francisco Chronicle analyzed
the importance of this attribute as follows 

Credibility -- or "cred," as the British call it 

-- is the widespread perception that an artist, 

band or individual has the respect not of the 

population at large, but of its peers.



In rock and roll, credibility always has been a 

desirable quality.


But cred has more to do with performance and 

integrity than with attitude or audience.  It is 

. . . remaining true to your beliefs.


Pearl Jam, Nirvana and R.E.M. are considered 

alternative bands by organizations such as 

Billboard and the Grammys, but they sell as 

many, if not more, records than mainstream acts. 

So what distinguishes them as alternative?  The 

answer:  their cred.  In part, it's the notion 

of credibility -- the idea that a band is 

creating a valid artistic statement rather than 

merely selling a contrived, commercial musical 

commodity.

Gina Arnold, "Cashing In On Cred," The San Francisco Chronicle, at 32
(Jan. 22, 1995).  This view of, and appreciation of, R.E.M. is
international.  The Sunday Times (London) noted in July 1995 

For as long as the deals have been struck, 

arguments have raged as to the ethics and 

aesthetics of corporate sponsorship.  For many 

artists less hard-headed about their financial 

objectives than the Rolling Stones or Michael 

Jackson, accepting the sponsor's shilling 

remains the equivalent of sleeping with the 

enemy.  Bruce Springsteen "won't even entertain 

the offers."  Nor will R.E.M. or U2.

Robert Sandall, "Sponsorship's Rocky Road" (July 2, 1995). 16. After
fifteen years, it is difficult to predict with any accuracy the amount
of money that R.E.M. has turned down from commercial endorsements.  It
is not something the group tracks.  Moreover, because most advertisers
are familiar with R.E.M.'s position, R.E.M. does not get as many
requests as it otherwise might receive.  However, using one recent
example, R.E.M. did receive a request from Microsoft's ad agency,
Wieden & Kennedy, to license R.E.M.'s song "It's the End of the World
As We Know It" for advertising use in Microsoft's worldwide brand
campaign. Significantly, Microsoft recently obtained permission
(through Wieden & Kennedy) to use a single Rolling Stones' song,
"Start Me Up," for a fee reported to be as high as $12 million.  Media
reports have emphasized that this deal and the amount involved are
significant because "the Rolling Stones never have before agreed to
have one of the songs they own the rights to be used in commercial
advertising." 

DEFENDANT'S UNAUTHORIZED ACTS

17.
Beginning on or before August 15, 1995, Hershey conducted a contest to
promote its KIT KAT bar.  The promotion included  radio advertising,
which on information and belief was part of a national radio campaign
on stations that play R.E.M.'s music, and thus represent its target
market.  In Atlanta, the radio advertisement aired on WNNX- FM (99.7),
and its text was as follows: 

Kit Kat wants to give you a chance to win a trip 

for two to the September 30th R.E.M. concert at 

Hershey Park Stadium or one of 25 copies of 

R.E.M.'s latest CD.  Be among the first 10,000 

people to call 1-800-455-9200 with your name and 

complete address and you'll be in the running 

for the KIT KAT concert trip to Hershey, 

Pennsylvania.  That's 1-800-455-9200.  Phone 

lines close August 18th.  No purchase necessary. 

Continental U.S. residents, eighteen plus.  For 

details send a self-addressed, stamped envelope 

to:  Kit Kat Rules, Box 535, Seaford, New York, 

11783.

18.
Hershey's "KIT KAT R.E.M. Concert" sweepstakes promotion radio
commercial does not use R.E.M.'s music, but rather includes generic
rock jingle music.  This background music is vastly inferior to
R.E.M.'s music, but unfortunately people likely are to believe that
R.E.M. is performing, or in some manner associated with, this
substandard, watered down, sound-alike accompaniment.  On information
and belief, Hershey and its advertising agency intended that this
background music, together the fact of and text of the commercial,
suggest or imply R.E.M.'s involvement, sponsorship or affiliation with
Hershey's KIT KAT contest. 19. Hershey's KIT KAT/R.E.M. radio
promotion included a toll-free number, which when called provided the
caller with a message and a prompt to leave a name and address to
enter the contest.  The text of the telephone message is as follows: 

Welcome to the Kit Kat R.E.M. concert at 

Hershey Park Stadium sweepstakes line where you 

will register for the chance to attend the 

R.E.M. concert during a four day/three night 

trip for two to Hershey, Pennsylvania September 

28 through October 1 or you could be one of 

twenty-five winners of R.E.M.'s latest CD.  For 

details send a self-addressed, stamped envelope 

to:  Kit Kat Rules, Box 535, Seaford, New York, 

11783.  Now after the tone leave your name and 

full mailing address, including city, state and 

zip code.

20.
Hershey's sales exceed $3,000,000,000 in the United States, and closer
to $4,000,000,000 worldwide. Hershey's KIT KAT wafer bar is a
tremendously popular product.  According to published reports, KIT KAT
is one of the best selling candy bars in the country, and currently
third behind Snickers (M&M/Mars) and Reese's Peanut Butter Cups
(Hershey). 21. Hershey's was founded in 1893 by Milton Hershey, and
was one of the first, if not the first, chocolate manufacturer in the
United States.  According to Hoover's Handbook of American Business,
Mr. Hershey lived until 1945, and during his life he refused to let
Hershey advertise, believing that quality would speak for itself. The
company continued the no-advertising policy after his death until
1970. 22. Today, Hershey's advertising is extensive, and in 1994
Hershey spent in excess of $120 million on advertising.  KIT KAT wafer
bars are promoted heavily. Advertising is a vital component of
Hershey's sales. According to Hoover's Guide to American Businesses,
Hershey started advertising when it felt challenged by Mars for
leadership in chocolate sales.  According to the New York Times,
"[i]in 1992, Hershey pulled ahead of M&M/Mars, which had nosed it out
for the lead the year before.  Hershey's move came largely on the
strength of a spirited advertising campaign tied to its Olympics
sponsorship."  Linda Corman, "All About Chocolate," Sec. 3, p. 10
(Feb. 21, 1993). 23. Hershey is an experienced and influential
advertiser, and in particular is an entity that engages in a
significant amount of sponsorships. By way of example, in February
1995, Brandweek reported Hershey's sponsorship of the then upcoming
NCAA Final Four basketball tournament, noting 


Hershey next month steps up its sports

marketing commitments with a multi-brand 

promotion linked to the NCAA basketball

tournament's Final Four.


Hershey, a new NCAA corporate partner, . . 

. will drop a Final Four-themed FSI with special 

offers on all Hershey loose candy bars, and in 

coming weeks roll out in-store promo materials 

giving consumers a shot at a trip to the annual 

college hoop championship.


The Hershey and Reese's lines, along with 

such Hershey brands as Kit-Kat, Mounds and 

Almond Joy, will be flagged via in-store 

displays, with Final Four-logoed basketballs and 

jackets and tickets to this year's Final Four 

offered to retailers for tailorable local 

giveaways. An instore sweepstakes starts later 

this month, offering consumers a shot at an all- 

expenses-paid trip to next year's event. 


Hershey last fall activated its existing 

sponsorship of the NFL with a similar retail 

promotion. Its other sports ties include a 

Reese's NASCAR sponsorship and a figure skating 

package for its Kisses line.


In addition to contests and promotions with the NCAA Final Four, the
NFL (which included game tickets and merchandise), and NASCAR, Hershey
apparently also has engaged in recent years in sponsorships and joint
promotions with the 1992 Olympics, NCAA College World Series, the
Reese's International Gymnastics Cup (broadcast on ABC's Wide World of
Sports), the New York Road Runners Club (the New York Marathon), and
the U.S. Figure Skating Association.  In early 1995, Hershey sponsored
a "Gump Day" on VH1 with a call-in sweepstakes with callers winning
"Forrest Gump" merchandise and on-air promotional spots. In 1992,
Hershey sponsored a promotion with the Academy of Motion Picture Arts
and Sciences that included tickets to the Oscars presentation. 24.
Promotions and promotional tie-ins, such as that described in the
previous paragraph, are typical in modern advertising, and typical of
Hershey's advertising techniques.  When consumers hear about such
tie-ins, they assume that the corporate sponsor -- Hershey -- and the
object of the tie-in, whether the NCAA, NFL, NASCAR, or R.E.M., are
authorizing or licensing use of their name and marks.  Hershey intends
that consumers believe that an affiliation exists between Hershey and
these other groups. Hershey values these tie-ins because the
association allows Hershey to benefit from the good will possessed and
generated by the other party. 25. Businesses increasingly view groups
such as R.E.M., which may be labeled "Alternative" or "Modern Rock,"
as an entree to the lucrative high school and college age markets.  As
in other areas, advertisers use celebrities to promote their products.
 The more popular the celebrity, the greater the number of people who
recognize him or her, and the greater the visibility for the product. 
Earlier this month Billboard magazine featured a front page story
titled "Madison Avenue Eyes Modern Rock, But Acts Remain Wary." 
However, according to that article 

Yet just as marketers become convinced that an 

alternative association helps loosen wallets, 

most performers riding today's wave are

concerned about cashing in their street

credibility and seem less interested than their 

predecessors in signing on the dotted line. 

Rarely has corporate America had so much trouble 

having its checks cashed.  "There are millions 

of dollars out there, . . . but you have acts 

who want nothing to do with it."

Billboard, p.1, 71 (August 5, 1995).
26.
On information and belief, Hershey's "KIT KAT R.E.M. Concert"
sweepstakes promotion is part of Hershey's effort to attract and to
tap into this young market, and is part of other Hershey efforts.  For
example, Hershey apparently signed on recently as a sponsor for an
"advertiser sponsored" Internet World Wide Web 'mega-site" targeting
college students. 27. Hershey is not currently, and never was,
authorized or licensed by R.E.M./Athens to use the R.E.M. name for any
purposes. 28. Hershey never sought authorization or approval from
R.E.M. for its "KIT KAT R.E.M. Concert" sweepstakes promotion.  On
information and belief, Hershey's failure to seek permission was
based, at least in part, on Hershey's knowledge or understanding that 
R.E.M./Athens would not authorize use of the R.E.M. name for product
endorsements. In other words, Hershey decided that if it could not buy
the name, it would not ask, but it still would appropriate what is not
theirs to sell a product. 29. Despite constructive notice of
R.E.M./Athens' rights, and on information and belief actual knowledge,
Hershey knowingly advertised and promoted its own candy bar using the
R.E.M name.  In running the commercial, and the promotion, Hershey
knowingly took a calculated risk, consciously disregarding the effect
of these actions on R.E.M.'s legally cognizable rights. 30. Hershey's
unauthorized use of the R.E.M. name creates the false and misleading
impression that Hershey's goods are affiliated, connected, related or
associated with R.E.M./Athens, or have the sponsorship, endorsement or
approval of R.E.M./Athens. 31. Because the public associates the
R.E.M. name with R.E.M./Athens, Hershey's unauthorized use of "R.E.M."
presents a substantial likelihood of public confusion, mistake, and
deception. Hershey's unauthorized use also is eroding the public's
exclusive identification of the R.E.M. name, thus diminishing its
distinctiveness, uniqueness, commercial effectiveness and prestigious
connotations. 32. Hershey's unlicensed and unauthorized use of the
R.E.M. name causes a likelihood of confusion and harm to
R.E.M./Athens, and on information and belief has caused actual
confusion.  The specific nature of the infringement is embarrassing,
and its impact is both potentially devastating and difficult to
immediately quantify.  Because of R.E.M.'s public stance against doing
product endorsements, the strong inference of Hershey's "KIT KAT
R.E.M. Concert" is that the group members apparently are hypocrites.
33. Hershey's use and continued use of R.E.M. despite actual and
constructive notice of R.E.M./Athens' rights demonstrates an
intentional, willful, and bad faith intent to create confusion,
mistake and deception of the public and to trade on R.E.M./Athens'
rights and established goodwill, by implying a nonexistent
association, connection, affiliation or relationship with
R.E.M./Athens to the great and irreparable injury of R.E.M./Athens. 


COUNT I

FEDERAL TRADEMARK INFRINGEMENT: SECTION 32(1) OF THE LANHAM ACT 34.
Plaintiff repeats and incorporates the allegations of paragraphs 1
through 33 above as if fully set forth herein. 35. Hershey has
advertised and offered for sale goods in interstate commerce using
designations and representations, including the R.E.M. name, identical
to Plaintiff's federally-registered R.E.M. marks. 36. Hershey's use of
marks identical to Plaintiff's federally-registered R.E.M. marks in
connection with the sale, offering for sale, distribution, and
advertising of Hershey's goods, and on or in connection with such use,
is likely to cause confusion, to cause mistake, or to deceive. 37.
When Hershey engaged in the conduct outlined above, it knew or should
have known of R.E.M./Athens' use of, rights to, and registration of
the R.E.M. marks. Hershey's unauthorized use of these marks for its
own significant commercial benefit demonstrates a willful and bad
faith infringement. 38. Hershey's infringing actions are causing and
are likely to cause substantial injury to the public and to
R.E.M./Athens because these activities are likely to cause confusion,
or to cause mistake, or to deceive purchasers and the public. 39.
Hershey's designations and representations as set forth above, being
false and deceptive and likely to cause confusion, or to cause
mistake, or to deceive, violate Section 32(1) of the Lanham Act, 15
U.S.C.  1114(1). 40. Hershey's conduct is causing and is likely to
cause substantial injury to the public and to R.E.M./Athens, and
R.E.M./Athens is entitled to injunctive relief, and to recover
damages, including without limitation the fair market value of their
services and injury to their good will, professional standing and
future publicity value, and Hershey's profits, all subject to
trebling, costs and reasonable attorneys' fees pursuant to 15 U.S.C.
 1114, 1116 and 1117. COUNT II FEDERAL UNFAIR COMPETITION AND FALSE
ENDORSEMENT: SECTION 43(a) OF THE LANHAM ACT 

41.
Plaintiff repeats and incorporates the
allegations of Paragraphs 1 through 40 above as if fully set forth
herein. 42. Hershey has used and is using in commerce words, terms,
names, symbols, devices and combinations thereof, false designations
of origin, false and misleading descriptions of fact, and false and
misleading representations of fact, including R.E.M.'s name and "sound
alike" music, likely to cause confusion, or to cause mistake, or to
deceive as to the affiliation, connection or association of Hershey
and its goods and commercial activities with Plaintiff R.E.M./Athens.
43. Hershey has used and is using in commerce words, terms, names,
symbols, devices and combinations thereof, false designations of
origin, false and misleading descriptions of fact, and false and
misleading representations of fact, including R.E.M.'s name and "sound
alike" music, likely to cause confusion, or to cause mistake, or to
deceive as to the origin, sponsorship or approval of Hershey and
Hershey's goods and commercial activities by R.E.M./Athens. 44.
R.E.M./Athens has been, is, and likely will continue to be, damaged by
Hershey's false and misleading designations, descriptions and
representations because such false and misleading designations,
descriptions, and representations create a likelihood of confusion,
mistake and deception. 45. Because of Hershey's false and misleading
designations, descriptions and representations, R.E.M./Athens is
suffering damage to its business, reputation, and good will. 46.
Hershey's designations, and representations, being false and
misleading, violate Section 43(a) of the Lanham Act, 15 U.S.C. 
1125(a). 47. Hershey's conduct is causing and is likely to cause
substantial injury to the public and to R.E.M./Athens, and
R.E.M./Athens is entitled to injunctive relief, and to recover
damages, including without limitation the fair market value of their
services and injury to their good will, professional standing and
future publicity value, and Hershey's profits, all subject to
trebling, costs and reasonable attorneys' fees pursuant to 15 U.S.C.
 1114, 1116 and 1117. COUNT III VIOLATION OF THE GEORGIA
ANTI-DILUTION STATUTE AND THE ANTI-DILUTION STATUTES AND LAWS OF OTHER
STATES 

48.
Plaintiff repeats and incorporates the
allegations of paragraphs 1 through 47 above as if fully set forth
herein. 49. R.E.M./Athens is the owner of the distinctive and famous
R.E.M. marks.  Through widespread and favorable public acceptance and
recognition, the R.E.M. name and mark have acquired secondary meaning
and have become associated uniquely with R.E.M./Athens and its goods
and services, and are of inestimable value to R.E.M./Athens as widely-
recognized symbols of its goods and services. 50. Hershey, by using
the R.E.M. mark in connection with and as an advertising and
promotional tool for its products, has diluted the reputation of the
distinctive R.E.M. mark by eroding the public's exclusive
identification of the mark with R.E.M./Athens, thus diminishing its
distinctiveness and effectiveness. 51. Hershey, by using the R.E.M.
name in advertising and promotional material in connection with its
KIT KAT candy bar, and by using inferior rock jingle "sound alike"
music has tarnished and caused injury to the reputation of the
distinctive R.E.M.'s name and mark, thus diminishing its
distinctiveness and value. 52. Hershey's conduct is causing and will
continue to cause irreparable injury to R.E.M.'s goodwill and
reputation, and dilution of the distinctive and valuable quality of
R.E.M.'s name and mark in violation of the Georgia anti- dilution
statute, O.C.G.A.  10-1-451, and the anti- dilution statutes and law
of other states, and R.E.M./Athens is entitled to injunctive relief
and other relief appropriate under the following statutes:  Alabama,
Ala. Code  8-12-17; Arkansas, Ark. Code Ann.  4-71-113; California,
Cal. Bus. & Prof. Code  14330; Connecticut, Conn. Gen. Stat. Ann. 
35-11i(c); Delaware, Del. Code Ann. tit. 6,  3313; Florida, Fla.
Stat. Ann.  495.151; Idaho, Idaho Code  48-512; Illinois, Ill. Rev.
Stat. ch. 765, para. 1035/15; Iowa, Iowa Code Ann.  548.10A;
Louisiana, La. Rev. Stat. Ann.  51:223.1; Maine, Me. Rev. Stat. Ann.
tit. 10,  1530; Massachusetts, Mass. Gen. L. ch. 110B,  12;
Minnesota, Minn. Stat. Ann.  325D.165; Missouri, Mo. Rev. Stat. 
417.061(1); Montana, Mont. Code Ann.  30-13- 334 (1991); Nebraska,
Neb. Rev. Stat.  87-122; New Hampshire, N.H. Rev. Stat. Ann. 
350-A:12; New Mexico, N.M. Stat. Ann.  57-3-10; New York, N.Y. Gen.
Bus. Law  368-d; Oregon, Or. Rev. Stat.  647.107; Pennsylvania, 54
Pa. Cons. Stat. Ann.  1124; Rhode Island, R.I. Gen. Laws.  6-2-12;
Tennessee, Tenn. Code Ann.  47-25-512; Texas, Tex. Bus. & Com. Code
Ann.  16.29; and Washington, Wash. Rev. Code Ann.  19.77 (West
1992); and the common law of certain other states. COUNT IV
MISAPPROPRIATION OF PERSONAL AND CORPORATE IDENTITY 53. Plaintiff
repeats and incorporates the allegations of paragraphs 1 through 52
above as if fully set forth herein. 54. R.E.M./Athens' goods and
services offered under the R.E.M. mark are known for their quality by
consumers and potential consumers and the public.  The group's
identity, name and trademarks, and the identity of the group's
individual members, represent a substantial portion of the vast good
will of R.E.M./Athens and the reputation of the company. 55. As
expressed in the Restatement (Second) of Torts, the interests
protected by a rule against the appropriation of name or likeness is
the interest of the owner "in the exclusive use of his own identity,
insofar as it is represented by his name or likeness."   652C, cmt.
a, at 381 (1977).  Misappropriation occurs when a defendant
appropriates for its "own use or benefit the reputation, prestige,
social or commercial standing, public interest or other values of the
plaintiff's name or likeness."  652C, cmt. c, at 382.  Unlike other
causes of action for an invasion of privacy, a corporation may have
"the same rights and remedies as those to which a private individual
is entitled under the rule stated in  652C."   652I, cmt. c, at 403.
56. By advertising, promoting, and selling their KIT KAT candy bar
using the R.E.M. name, Hershey has appropriated for its own use or
benefit the corporate identity, reputation, prestige, commercial
standing, and good will of R.E.M./Athens and its goods and services,
as well as the personal identity of the group members of R.E.M., and
it has otherwise sought to obtain for itself the values or benefits of
R.E.M.'s identity, reputation and good will. 57. Hershey's
appropriation of R.E.M./Athens' identity, reputation, prestige,
commercial standing, and good will, and the identity of the group's
members, is designed and intended to, and has the effect of,
advertising Hershey's business and products and of serving other
commercial purposes of Hershey. 58. Hershey's acts constitute
misappropriation of R.E.M./Athens' corporate identity, and the
identity of the collective group members under the common law of
Georgia and the common law of the several states. R.E.M./Athens
therefore is entitled to an injunction prohibiting such conduct and
other appropriate relief, including damages. COUNT V VIOLATION OF THE
GEORGIA DECEPTIVE TRADE PRACTICES ACT AND THE DECEPTIVE TRADE
PRACTICES ACTS OF OTHER STATES 

59.
Plaintiff repeats and incorporates the
allegations of Paragraphs 1 through 58 above as if fully set forth
herein. 60. By reason of the acts set forth above, Hershey has
willfully and knowingly engaged in false and deceptive trade practices
in violation of the Georgia Deceptive Trade Practices Act, O.C.G.A. 
10-1-370 to -375; and the deceptive trade practices acts of other
states, by: 

(a) Causing likelihood of confusion or of 

misunderstanding as to the source, sponsorship, 

approval of Hershey's goods;


(b) Causing likelihood of confusion or of 

misunderstanding as to the affiliation,

connection or association of Hershey with, or 

certification by, R.E.M./Athens; and

(c) Engaging in other conduct which similarly 

creates a likelihood of confusion or of

misunderstanding.

In addition to Georgia law, R.E.M./Athens also is entitled to relief
under the unfair and deceptive trade practices acts in other states,
including the following:  Colorado, Colo. Rev. Stat. Ann  6-1-101 to
6-1-105; Delaware, Del. Code Ann. tit. 6,  2531; Hawaii, Haw. Rev.
Stat.  481A-1 to 481A-5; Me. Rev. Stat. Ann. tit. 10,  1211;
Nebraska, Neb. Rev. Stat.  87-301 to 87-306; New Mexico, N.M. Stat.
Ann.  57-12-1 to 57-12-22; Ohio, Ohio Rev. Code Ann.  4165.01 to
4165.04; Oklahoma, Okla. Stat. Ann. tit. 78, 51; and Oregon, Or. Rev.
Stat.  646.605 to 646.656. 61. Hershey's willful and knowing
deceptive trade practices have caused and are likely to cause
substantial injury to the public and to R.E.M./Athens and
R.E.M./Athens is entitled to injunctive relief, damages, attorneys'
fees and other relief pursuant to O.C.G.A.  10-1-370 to -375, and
the law of other states. 

COUNT VI

VIOLATIONS OF THE GEORGIA FAIR BUSINESS PRACTICES ACT 

AND THE FAIR BUSINESS PRACTICES ACTS OF OTHER STATES 

62.
Plaintiff repeats and incorporates the
allegations of Paragraphs 1 through 61 above as if fully set forth
herein. 63. Hershey's unauthorized acts, described above, constitute
unfair and deceptive trade practices in violation of the Georgia Fair
Business Practices Act of 1975, O.C.G.A.  10-1-390 to -407, and the
fair business practices acts in other states, which practices are
injurious to consumers as well as R.E.M./Athens.  These practices
include passing of goods, causing confusion and misunderstanding as to
source, sponsorship or approval, causing confusion and
misunderstanding as to affiliation, connection and association, and
representing goods as having sponsorship, approval and characteristics
that they do not have. 64. Hershey's willful and knowing unfair and
deceptive practices have caused and are likely to cause substantial
injury to the public and to R.E.M./Athens, and R.E.M./Athens is
entitled to injunctive relief, treble damages, and an award of
attorneys' fees under Georgia law, and the fair business practices
laws of other states. 

COUNT VII

VIOLATION OF THE GEORGIA FALSE ADVERTISING STATUTE 

AND THE FALSE ADVERTISING STATUTES OF OTHER STATES 

65.
Plaintiff repeats and incorporates the
allegations of Paragraphs 1 through 64 above as if fully set forth
herein. 66. Hershey's unauthorized acts constitute a material
assertion, representation or statement of fact which is untrue,
deceptive or misleading within the meaning of the Georgia False
Advertising Statute, O.C.G.A.  10-1-421 and the false advertising
statutes in other states. 67. Hershey's false advertising is injurious
to R.E.M./Athens, and R.E.M./Athens, having no adequate remedy at law,
is entitled to injunctive and other relief pursuant to O.C.G.A. 
10-1-423 and the law of other states. 

COUNT VIII

COMMON LAW INFRINGEMENT AND UNFAIR COMPETITION 

68.
Plaintiff repeats and incorporates the
allegations of Paragraphs 1 through 67 above as if fully set forth
herein. 69. Hershey is engaged in advertising, offering for sale and
selling goods using R.E.M.'s name and mark with full knowledge that
their unauthorized use of the name unfairly and deceptively encroaches
upon the rights of R.E.M./Athens. 70. Hershey intentionally has
advertised, promoted and sold their goods in a manner calculated to
mislead and deceive the public. 71. Hershey's conduct constitutes a
violation of O.C.G.A.  23-2-55, and R.E.M./Athens' common law rights
preserved in O.C.G.A.  10-1-372 and  10-1-421, and the law of other
states, and constitutes false advertising, unfair competition and
deceptive trade practices, all of which have damaged and will continue
to damage R.E.M./Athens and the public, to the irreparable injury
thereof, unless restrained by this Court, and R.E.M./Athens has no
adequate remedy at law. 72. Hershey's acts have been and are willful,
intentional, malicious, and in bad faith. 73. Hershey's unfair
competition has caused and is likely to cause substantial injury to
the public and to R.E.M./Athens, and R.E.M./Athens is entitled to
injunctive relief, damages (including punitive damages), and an award
of attorneys' fees pursuant to O.C.G.A.  10-1-373, and the statutes
and common law of other states. WHEREFORE, Plaintiff R.E.M./Athens
prays that this Court grant the following relief: 1.  That Defendant
Hershey, its officers, agents, servants, employees and attorneys, and
all persons in active concert or participation with Hershey be
preliminary and permanently enjoined and restrained from: 


a.  Using the mark "R.E.M." in commercial 

advertising or promotion;

b.  Expressly or by implication, representing to 

the public that Hershey or its goods are 

affiliated, connected, or associated with, or 

sponsored or approved by, R.E.M./Athens; 

c.  Passing off its goods as affiliated, 

connected, or associated with, or sponsored or 

approved by, R.E.M./Athens, Ltd.;

d.  Distributing any solicitation, promotion, or 

advertising materials bearing any the R.E.M. 

name or mark;

e.  Diluting the distinctive quality of the 

R.E.M. name or mark or otherwise injuring the 

reputation associated therewith;

f.  Engaging in false descriptions or false 

representations in violation of Section 43 of 

the Lanham Act and state false advertising 

statutes; and

g.  Otherwise infringing upon the R.E.M. mark or 

unfairly competing in any manner whatsoever. 

2.  That an accounting be ordered and judgment rendered against
Hershey for Hershey's infringement, unfair competition,
misappropriation, and unfair and deceptive practices and that those
profits be trebled pursuant to 15 U.S.C.  1117(a) and O.C.G.A. 
10-1-399(c); 3.  That judgment be entered in favor of Plaintiff
R.E.M./Athens for all damages sustained by Plaintiff on account of
Hershey's infringement, unfair competition and false designation of
the origin of its goods and services, commercial misappropriation, and
other deceptive and unfair business practices and that such damages be
trebled pursuant to 15 U.S.C.  1117(a) and O.C.G.A.  10-1-399(c). 4.
That punitive damages be awarded to Plaintiff R.E.M./Athens by reason
of Hershey's willful, intentional, malicious, and bad faith actions in
order to deter such actions in the future. 5.  That Hershey be
required to deliver up for destruction all inventory, literature,
brochures, flyers, advertising materials, and any other items
incorporating or bearing the "R.E.M." name or mark. 6.  That Hershey
be directed to file with the Court and serve on R.E.M./Athens within
thirty (30) days after entry of a final injunction, a report in
writing under oath setting forth in detail the manner and form in
which Hershey has complied with the injunction; 7.  That Plaintiff
R.E.M./Athens have and recover its costs in this suit, including
reasonable attorneys' fees and expenses; 8.  Pursuant to Rule 38,
Plaintiff R.E.M./Athens demands a trial by jury for all issues so
triable. 9. That Plaintiff R.E.M./Athens have such other and further
relief as the Court deems just and proper. 

Respectfully submitted,





_______________________________
William H. Brewster 080422
Theodore H. Davis, Jr. 212913


KILPATRICK & CODY
1100 Peachtree Street
Atlanta, Georgia 30309-4530
(404) 815-6500


Attorneys for Plaintiff
R.E.M./Athens, Ltd.


