<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<P>In this memo, the NBA Players Association explains the agreement reached June 21 with team owners. This memo covers such issues as the team salary cap and endorsement restrictions on players.  The players voted not to decertify the association in early September.</P>
<HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT>
<PRE>
NATIONAL BASKETBALL PLAYERS ASSOCIATION


August 18, 1995

TO:  ALL PLAYERS

cc: ALL PLAYER AGENTS

FROM: BUCK WILLIAMS
      SIMON P. GOURDINE


===================================


      We want to make certain that every player is fully
informed about the terms of the proposed agreement that has
been reached with the NBA so that each of you will be able
to cast an intelligent vote in the NLRB-conducted
decertification election on August 30th and September 7th.
Please note that our August 10th memo already provided you
with a detailed description of "The Resolution of the
Outstanding Issues Resulting from the Player Rep Mandate of
June 21" (See Part I at pages 1-3 of the August 10th memo);
and (2) a description of the principal[sic] terms of the
June 21st Agreement that were not modified by the August 8th
Agreement (See Part II at pages 3-7 of the August 10th
memo).

      We have now prepared for your further information
another document entitled "III - Miscellaneous Unmodified
Terms from The June 21 Proposed Agreement." This document
sets forth an assortment of less significant proposed terms
that we do not believe will play a critical role in your
evaluation of the overall proposed agreement. If you staple
this document to pages 1-7 of the August 10th memo you will
have in one document the terms agreed upon in the
negotiations, all of which are subject to your approval.

      In accordance with standard practice, the lawyers for
the Players Association and the NBA will get together to
begin the process of incorporating the various terms of the
parties' proposed agreement into the language of a formal,
full-blown collective bargaining agreement In the meantime,
we are enclosing a copy of a one-page letter dated August
18th 1995, from Deputy Commissioner Russ Granik confirming
that the NBA has reviewed in advance the various terms
described in Parts I-III of the documents you now have in
your possession, and has agreed that those terms will form
the basis of a new collective bargaining agreement to be
prepared by the lawyers for the Players Association and the
NBA.

     As you know, we have already begun a series of player
meetings throughout the country to fill you in on the terms
of the proposed agreement. Please make sure to attend and
raise any questions you may have. In the event you are
unable to attend, please call us with your questions.


B.W.
S.P.G.


------------------------------------------------------




III. MISCELLANEOUS UNMODIFIED TERMS FROM THE JUNE 21
PROPOSED AGREEMENT

A. SALARY CAP

-- EXPANSION TEAM SALARY CAP LEVELS

As in the 1988 agreement, the Salary Cap for the expansion
teams will be two-thirds of the regular Salary Cap in the
995- 96 season, three quarters of the regular Salary Cap in
the 1996-97 season. and 100% of the regular Salary Cap in
all subsequent seasons.

-- THE MINIMUM TEAM SALARY WILL BE 75% OF THE CAP.

Teams must carry a payroll that is at least 75% of the
salary cap. If a team does not satisfy that obligation, the
NBA is obligated to make up the difference and disburse
those funds to the players on that team.

-- TRADE RULES HAVE BEEN RELAXED.

Teams may aggregate any number of contracts in a
simultaneous trade.

Teams are allowed an additional $100 000 exception in
simultaneous trades.

Base Year Compensation will apply only to trades. A player's
Base Year Compensation will be phased out over three years
(including bass years already in existence).

-- A TEAM MAY SIGN ANY PLAYER TO A MINIMUM SALARY CONTRACT,
REGARDLESS OF THE SALARY CAP.

-- THE "OVER 35 RULE" HAS BEEN RELAXED.

      A player 33 or 34 years old may sign a 4-year contract
with no over 35" averaging issue.

-- AN INJURED PLAYER'S SALARY WILL DROP OUT OF TEAM SALARY
AFTER TWO YEARS. EVEN IF THE PLAYER CONTINUES TO BE PAID.

-- CLARIFICATION OF "ANTI-CIRCUMVENTION" LANGUAGE OF CURRENT
AGREEMENT.

No performance bonus may be included in a contract that
provides a disincentive to the performance of a player or
attempts to circumvent the Cap.

A team buyout option will be treated as a signing bonus for
Cap purposes, and if the option is not exercised the team's
Cap room will increase by the amount of the buyout option.

The existing anti-circumvention language will be further
clarified with respect to non-basketball-related services.

A player contract may not be renegotiated downward.

B. TRAINING CAMP COMPENSATION

--EACH PLAYER WILL RECEIVE 51,200 PER WEEK AS TRAINING CAMP
COMPENSATION, FOR UP TO FOUR WEEKS. SHOULD THE PLAYER REMAIN
ON THE TEAM AFTER OPENING DAY, THIS COMPENSATION WILL BE
CREDITED AGAINST THE SALARY HE EARNS.

C. ALL STAR GAME

-- ALL-STAR GAME PLAYER PAYMENTS WILL BE INCREASED AS
FOLLOWS:

1996-98:

$12,000 TO EACH PLAYER ON THE WINNING TEAM;
$ 6,000 TO EACH PLAYER ON THE LOSING TEAM

1999-01:

$15,000 TO EACH PLAYER ON THE WINNING TEAM;          
$ 7,500 TO EACH PLAYER ON THE LOSING TEAM

D. NO-TRADE CLAUSES

-- THE AMOUNT OF SERVICE REQUIRED TO NEGOTIATE A NO-TRADE
CLAUSE HAS BEEN REDUCED tO EIGHT YEARS IN THE NBA AND FOUR
YEARS WITH YOUR TEAM.

E. DISCIPLINE

-- MAXIMUM FINE AND SUSPENSION AMOUNTS HAVE BEEN
ESTABLISHED, AND CANNOT BE VARIED BY ANY "TEAM RULES.

   Missed practice -- $1,000 (first two); $2,600 thereafter
   Missed exhibition Game --$4,000
   Missed regular season or playoff game -- 1/82 of salary
   Non-attendance at Rookie Transition Program -- $10,000
   Non-attendance at other mandatory programs -- $5,000
   Maximum Commissioner fine -- $25,000

Maximum, uniform fines for other specific types of Conduct
to be discussed and agreed upon.

Discipline may not be imposed if the player has a reasonable
excuse for the conduct

All fine and suspension money is to be distributed to
charities agreed on by the NBA and the Players Association.

Vague standards of morality and speech in the uniform player
contract and CBA will be limited and more clearly defined.

F. GRIEVANCES

-- NEW GRIEVANCE PROCEDURES WILL BE ESTABLISHED TO. AMONG
OTHER THINGS, SPEED THE TIME IN WHICH A GRIEVANCE IS HEARD,
AND TO PROHIBIT A TEAM FROM KEEPING FINE OR SUSPENSION MONEY
FOR ITSELF WHILE THE GRIEVANCE REMAINS PENDING.

A player may take an appeal to the Impartial Arbitrator if
the total cost of the discipline - whether by fine or
suspension -- is at least $2,000 for discipline imposed by
the team, or $10,000 for off-court discipline imposed by the
Commissioner.

G. UNIFORM TEAM RULES

-- ALL "TEAM RULES" WILL BE MADE UNIFORM.

H. PROMOTIONAL APPEARANCES

-- PAYMENT AND OTHER REQUIREMENTS WILL BE ESTABLISHED FOR
PROMOTIONAL APPEARANCES AND ENDORSEMENTS

A player making a promotional appearance on behalf of the
team must be paid $1,000.

A player who inexcusably fails to appear at a team
promotional appearance may be fined uP to $1,000.

Reasonable, defined limitations will be established
regarding the types of appearances a player may make, the
maximum amount of time a player may be required to spend at
an appearance, and the activities a player may be required
to perform.

A team has the right to designate up to two local (not
national) sponsors and a player may not endorse a local
competitor of those sponsors.

I. ROOKIE SALARY SCALE

-- RULES HAVE BEEN ESTABLISHED FOR DRAFTEES WHO CHOOSE NOT
TO SIGN IN THE NBA:

If a first round pick chooses not to sign in the season in
which he is drafted, if he does sign before one of the next
two seasons, he will be treated for purposes of the rookie
salary scale s if he were just drafted in the immediately
preceding draft, at the same draft position at which he was
actually selected .

If a first round pick or a player drafted before 1995 does
not sign with the team that drafted him for three seasons
(and does not play college basketball in those three
seasons), if he ultimately does sign, he will not be limited
to the scaled amount, but instead can get the greater of the
team's room when he does sign, or the scaled amount for the
season that immediately follows, at the same position at
which he was actually drafted.

-- FOR PURPOSES OF COMPUTING TEAM SALARY, WHEN A ROOKIE IS
DRAFTED, IT WILL BE ASSUMED HE WILL EARN 100% OF THE SCALE
AMOUNT (THOUGH HE MAY NEGOTIATE UP TO 120% OF THE SCALE).

J. TEAM LOAN RULES

-- TEAM LOAN RULES WILL BE REVISED SO THAT PLAYER LOANS MUST
BE REPAID OUT OF ANNUAL COMPENSATION, AND THE PARTIES MUST
CONFIRM THAT THE LOAN HAS BEEN REPAID. THIS DOES NOT APPLY
TO ANY LOANS THAT ARE CURRENTLY OUTSTANDING.

K. COMMITTEE REPRESENTATION

-- THE PLAYERS ASSOCIATION WILL HAVE A REPRESENTATIVE ON THE
LEAGUE COMPETITION COMMITTEE THAT MAY PARTICIPATE AS A
VOTING MEMBER WITH RESPECT TO RULES AND OFFICIATING .

L. INJURED PLAYERS

-- IF A NON-GUARANTEED PLAYER IS INJURED WHILE PLAYING FOR
THE TEAM, HE MUST CONTINUE TO BE PAID FOR THE REMAINDER OF
THE SEASON UNTIL HE IS READY TO PLAY SKILLED BASKETBALL. IF
THE TEAM WISHES TO CUT THE PLAYER FOR LACK OF SKILL, AND THE
PLAYER BELIEVES HE IS NOT YET FIT TO PLAY DUE TO INJURY, AN
IMPARTIAL PHYSICIAN WILL BE CALLED ON TO MAKE THE
DETERMINATION.

M. PRIVACY ISSUES

-- NEW PRIVACY RIGHTS WILL BE ESTABLISHED FOR PLAYERS.

Players or their immediate families (where appropriate) will
have the right to approve the public dissemination of
medical information relating to injuries or illnesses that
are potentially life- or career-threatening or do not arise
from the player's participation In NBA games or practices.

Teams, agents and players are not to disclose publicly
specific financial terms of player contracts.

N. TRAVEL

-- A UNIFORM DEFINITION WILL BE AGREED ON AS TO WHAT
CONSTITUTES "FIRST CLASS" TRAVEL ON CHARTER FLIGHTS.

O. EVENTS AGREEMENT

~-- THE NBA HAS AGREED TO EXTEND THE "EVENTS AGREEMENT" AND
WILL INCREASE THE AMOUNT PAID TO THE PLAYERS FROM $300,000
TO $500,000 A YEAR, AND WILL CONTINUE TO INCREASE THEREAFTER
BY $25,000 A YEAR.

P. GAME TICKETS

-- TEAMS WILL BE EXPRESSLY PROHIBITED FROM PRESSURING
PLAYERS TO PURCHASE GAME TICKETS.

Q. RETIRED PLAYERS

-- THE NBA AND THE PLAYERS ASSOCIATION WILL HAVE CONTINUED
DISCUSSIONS REGARDING EMPLOYMENT AND INDIVIDUAL LICENSING
OPPORTUNITIES fOR RETIRED PLAYERS.


-------------------------------------------------------------

ADDENDUM TO PART III (MISCELLANEOUS UNMODIFIED TERMS)

MDBO MDNM     Please note that we have not yet agreed on
the precise terms of the fourth item in paragraph H,
"PROMOTIONAL APPEARANCES." While our document states that "A
team has the right to designate up to two local (not
national) sponsors. and a player may not endorse a local
competitor of those sponsors," there is not yet a meeting of
the minds between the Players Association and the NBA as to
whether a team may designate two sponsors or three.


-------------------------------------------------------------

National Basketball Association
Russell T. Granik
Deputy Commissioner and
Chief Operating Officer

August 18, 1995


Simon P. Gourdine, Esq.
Executive Director and General Counsel
National Basketball Players Association
1775 Broadway, Room 2401
New York, New York 10019


Dear Simon:

      This letter is to confirm that the National Basketball
Association ("NBA") has reviewed in advance the Players
Associations' description of the terms of the August 8, 1995
proposed agreement between the NBA and the Association -- as
mailed to all NBA players in two parts by letters dated
August 10, 1995 and August 18, 1995 -- and that what is
contained in the Associations' description will form the
basis of a new collective bargaining agreement between the
parties.


Sincerely,

/s/Russ Granik


-------------------------------------------------------------

NATIONAL BASKETBALL PLAYERS ASSOCIATION


August 21, 1995

TO:  ALL PLAYERS

cc: ALL PLAYER AGENTS

FROM: BUCK WILLIAMS
      SIMON P. GOURDINE


===================================

      We all have witnessed the dissension that has
developed among players, agents, and the Union over the past
two months as a result of the decertification initiative.
Fortunately, the dissension was put to some good use: the
Union was able tO use the decertification initiative to
pressure the NBA into improving our earlier agreement to the
great benefit of all players. Now, however, the job is done.
I am writing to ask that we all put the rhetoric and bad
will of the past two months behind us and focus --
uninhibited -- solely on the merits of the proposed
agreement, which we strongly believe is in the best
interests of all players. More specifically, I write to
assure you that if the Players Association succeeds in the
upcoming decertification election, and we have every
confidence that we will, we intend to resume, unchanged in
every respect, the open and cooperative relationship we have
long enjoyed with every player agent.

      It has come to my attention that while many of you
agree that the best interests of the players lie in
defeating decertification and approving the proposed
agreement with the NBA, you may be somewhat hesitant to
throw your full support behind the proposed agreement and
the Union for fear that if the Union wins the upcoming
decertification election, the Union will "retaliate" against
the agent community at large for the role of certain agents
in the decertification initiative. I do not know where this
fear emanates from, and whether it is being exploited by
certain leaders of the decertification movement to forestall
defections from their ranks, but I do know and can give you
my complete assurance that this fear is entirely
unjustified.

      If the Union wins the election, our overriding
objective will be to repair the distasteful dissension among
players that has resulted from the decertification
initiative. To this end, we would no more lash out against
player agents for their role in the decertification effort
than we would harbor a grudge against individual players who
have supported decertification. We fully appreciate the fact
that unity among players cannot be achieved by the pursuit
of any "retaliation" policy that would further divide the
Union and the agent community, and the Union quite simply
has no intention of pursuing any such policy.

      We hope to immediately begin the process of unifying
the players by convincing you to throw your full support
behind the Union and the proposed agreement with the NBA. We
have sent you a copy of all principal and non-
principal[sic] terms of the agreement for your review, and
our staff and I will be contacting as many of you as
possible in the days before the upcoming decertification
election to address any questions that you may have about
the proposed agreement. In the meantime, please evaluate the
proposed agreement on its merits, and not based on any
misplaced fears concerning union "retaliation" against the
agent community.

      I look forward to speaking with you.


S.P.G.



