New York, New York 10153
(212) 310-8000

Civil Action

No.

           CLASS ACTION COMPLAINT

 Plaintiffs, by their undersigned attorneys, for
their Complaint herein allege as follows:

 INTRODUCTION

 1. This action is brought to enjoin violations
by each defendant of the federal antitrust laws and the
common law of torts of the various states with respect to
plaintiffs and similarly situated basketball players who
have entered and will enter into player contracts with NBA
teams, and to redress injuries sustained by plaintiffs and
similarly situated basketball players as a result of
violations by each defendant of the federal antitrust laws.
Plaintiffs are professional athletes who have been employed
by individual teams in the National Basketball Association
("NBA"). Defendants are the NBA and each of its member
teams (the "NBA Defendants"). The NBA Defendants have
jointly agreed and conspired to deny plaintiffs the ability
to market their services as professional basketball players
in a competitive market through a comprehensive set of
anticompetitive restrictions. As a result of defendants'
anticompetitive agreements, plaintiffs and other similarly
situated NBA players are prevented from receiving a
competitive market value for their services and are denied
the freedom of movement available to employees in virtually
every other industry in the United States. Although
defendants were previously held to be protected by the
nonstatutory labor exemption to the antitrust laws as long
as there was a "continuing collective bargaining
relationship," the players in the NBA have chosen to give up
their collective bargaining relationship in order to assert
their rights under the antitrust laws.

 JURISDICTION AND VENUE

 2. These claims arise and are brought under
Sections 1 and 2 of the Sherman Antitrust Act, 15 U.S.C.
1, 2, and the common law of torts of the various states.

 3. This Court has jurisdiction over these claims
pursuant to 28 U.S.C.  1331, 1337 and 1367.

 4. Venue in this action is proper pursuant to 28
U.S.C.  1391 and 15 U.S.C.  22. Each of the defendants
can be found, resides, has an agent, or transacts business
in the District of Minnesota, and the unlawful activities
were carried on in part by one or more of the defendants
within this district.

 THE PARTIES

 5. Plaintiff Patrick Ewing is a professional
basketball player who, since 1985, has been employed in
interstate commerce by defendant Madison Square Garden
Corporation, which owns and operates the New York
Knickerbockers. After the 1996-97 NBA season, his contract
with the Knickerbockers will expire on July 1, 1997.

 6. Plaintiff Michael Jordan is a professional
basketball player who, since 1984, has been employed in
interstate commerce by defendant Chicago Professional Sports
Limited Partnership, which owns and operates the Chicago
Bulls. After the 1995-96 NBA season, his contract with the
Chicago Bulls will expire on July 1, 1996.

 7. Plaintiff Stacey Augmon is a professional
basketball player who, since 1991, has been employed in
interstate commerce by defendant Atlanta Hawks, L.P., which
owns and operates the Atlanta Hawks. After the 1994-95 NBA
season, Mr. Augmon opted-out of his contract with the Hawks,
and is currently a free agent.

 8. Plaintiff Dale Davis is a professional
basketball player who, since 1991, has been employed in
interstate commerce by defendant Pacers Basketball
Corporation, which owns and operates the Indiana Pacers.
Mr. Davis has the right to opt-out of his contract with the
Pacers after the 1995-96 NBA season.

 9. Plaintiff Alonzo Mourning is a professional
basketball player who, since 1992, has been employed in
interstate commerce by defendant Charlotte NBA Limited
Partnership, which owns and operates the Charlotte Hornets.
Mr. Mourning is in the third year of a six year contract,
but has the right to opt-out of his contract after the 1995-
96 NBA season.

 10. Plaintiff Howard Eisley is a professional
basketball player who was selected by the Minnesota
Timberwolves as the 30th pick in the 1994 NBA draft. Mr.
Eisley was employed in interstate commerce by the Minnesota
Professional Basketball Limited Partnership, which owns and
operates the Minnesota Timberwolves, but was released by the
Timberwolves after the All-Star break. Mr. Eisley then
signed with the San Antonio Spurs and was re-released just
prior to the end of the regular season. Mr. Eisley is
currently a free agent.

 11. Plaintiff Stacey King is a professional
basketball player who, since 1989, had been employed in
interstate commerce by defendant Chicago Professional Sports
Limited Partnership, which owns and operates the Chicago
Bulls. In February of 1994, Mr. King was traded to the
Minnesota Timberwolves, which is owned and operated by
defendant Minnesota Professional Basketball Limited
Partnership. His contract with the Timberwolves having
expired, Mr. King is currently a free agent.

 12. Defendant NBA, which maintains its office at
645 Fifth Avenue, New York, New York 10022, is an
unincorporated association consisting of the 29 separately-
owned and operated professional basketball teams listed in
paragraph 14. The NBA is engaged in interstate commerce in
the business of, among other things, operating the sole
major league professional basketball league in North
America.

 13. The other defendants are the 29 NBA member
teams, each of which, upon information and belief, is a
corporation, except where noted below. Upon information and
belief, each of the defendant teams is a separately-owned
and independent entity which operates a professional
basketball franchise for profit under the team name and in
the cities set forth below:

 NBA Defendant, Team Owner; State or Province of Organization,
 Citizenship or Incorporation; Team Name (City)

 Atlanta Hawks, L.P.; Georgia; Atlanta Hawks

 Boston Celtics, Limited Partnership; Massachusetts; Boston
 Celtics

 Charlotte NBA, Limited Partnership; North Carolina; Charlotte
 Hornets

 Chicago Professional Sports, Limited Partnership; Illinois;
 Chicago Bulls

 Nationwide Advertising Service, Inc.; Ohio; Cleveland
 Cavaliers

 Dallas Basketball, Limited; Texas; Dallas Mavericks

 The Denver Nuggets, Limited Partnership; Colorado; Denver
 Nuggets

 Detroit Pistons Basketball Company; Michigan; Detroit Pistons

 Golden State Warriors; California; Golden State Warriors

 Rocket Ball, Ltd.; Texas; Houston Rockets

 Pacers Basketball Corporation; Indianapolis; Indiana Pacers

 LAC Basketball Club, Inc.; California; Los Angeles Clippers

 The Los Angeles Lakers, Inc.; California; Los Angeles Lakers

 The Miami Heat, Limited Partnership; Florida; Miami Heat

 Milwaukee Bucks, Inc.; Wisconsin; Milwaukee Bucks

 Minnesota Professional Basketball, Limited Partnership;
 Minnesota; Minnesota Timberwolves

 Meadowlands Basketball Associates; New Jersey; New Jersey
 Nets

 Madison Square Garden Corporation; New York; New York
 Knickerbockers

 Orlando Magic, Ltd.; Florida; Orlando Magic

 The Philadelphia 76ers Basketball Club, Inc.; Pennsylvania;
 Philadelphia 76ers

 Phoenix Suns Limited; Arizona; Phoenix Suns

 Trail Blazers, Inc.; Oregon; Portland Trail Blazers

 Sacramento Kings, Limited Partnership; California; Sacramento
 Kings

 San Antonio Spurs, Ltd.; Texas; San Antonio Spurs

 Ackerley Communications, Inc.; Washington; Seattle SuperSonics

 Jazz Basketball Investors, Inc.; Utah; Utah Jazz

 Capital Bullets Basketball Club, Inc.; Maryland; Washington
 Bullets

 Toronto Raptors Basketball Club, Inc.; Ontario; Toronto Raptors

 Vancouver Basketball, Limited Partnership; British Columbia;
 Vancouver Grizzlies

 CLASS ACTION

 14. Plaintiffs Patrick Ewing, Michael Jordan,
Stacey Augmon, Dale Davis, Alonzo Mourning, Howard Eisley,
and Stacey King (hereinafter sometimes referred to as the
"class plaintiffs") are representatives of a class, as
defined by Rules 23(b)(1) and (b)(2) of the Federal Rules of
Civil Procedure, and bring this action on behalf of
themselves and the class members as described in paragraph
17 below.

 15. The class represented by plaintiffs is
comprised of (i) all players who have been, are now, or will
be under contract to play professional basketball for an NBA
club at any time from June 28, 1995 to the date of final
judgment in this action and determination of any appeal
therefrom, and (ii) all college and other basketball players
who, as of June 28, 1995, to the date of final judgment in
this action and the determination of any appeal therefrom,
have been, are now, or will be eligible to play basketball
as a rookie for an NBA team.

 16. The class is so numerous and geographically
so widely distributed that joinder of all members is
impracticable. There are questions of law and fact common
to the class. The claims of the plaintiffs are typical of
the claims of the class they represent, and the plaintiffs
will fairly and adequately protect the interests of the
class they represent.

 17. Each person in the class is, has been, and/or
will be subject to uniform agreements, rules and practices
among the defendants restraining competition for players'
services which are or will be uniformly imposed by the NBA
Defendants.

 18. Except for provisions as to individual
compensation and other variations which do not materially
affect this action, the player contracts are substantially
identical throughout the NBA.

 19. In construing and enforcing their uniform
agreements, rules and practices, and in taking the actions
described below, the NBA Defendants have acted, have refused
to act, and will act, on grounds generally applicable to the
class, thereby making appropriate injunctive relief or
corresponding declaratory relief with respect to the class
as a whole.

 20. The prosecution of separate actions by individual
members of the class would create the risk of:

   (a) inconsistent or varying adjudications
 with respect to individual members of the class
 which would establish incompatible standards of
 conduct for the party apposing the class, or

   (b) Adjudications with respect to individual
 members of the class which would as a practical
 matter be dispositive of the interests of other
 class members not parties to the adjudications or
 would substantially impair or impede the ability
 of such absent class members to protect their
 interests.

  NATURE OF INTERSTATE TRADE AND COMMERCE

 21. The primary business in which defendants are
engaged is the operation of major league professional
basketball teams and the sale of tickets and telecast rights
to the public exhibition or the individual and collective
basketball talents of players such as plaintiffs. To carry
on this business, the NBA Defendants must compete with each
other for and retain the professional services of players,
such as plaintiffs, who are signed to play basketball for
one of the NBA defendant teams.

 22. The business of major league professional
basketball is distinct from other professional sports
businesses, as well as from college and minor league
basketball. Its distinguishing features include, but are
not limited to: the rules of the sport and the season during
which it is played, the talents and rates of compensation of
the players, for whom playing basketball is their full-time
profession; the nature and amounts of trade and commerce
involved; and the unique demand for the NBA Defendants'
games by the consuming public, both as ticket purchasers and
as home viewers of and listeners to television and radio.

 23. The NBA Defendants' operation of and
engagement in the business of major league professional
basketball involves a substantial volume of interstate trade
and commerce, including, inter alia, the following
interstate activities: travel; communications; purchases and
movement of equipment; broadcasts and telecasts of league
games; advertisements; promotions; sales of tickets and
concession items; employment of players and referees; and
negotiations for all of the above.

 24. The NBA Defendants' aforesaid interstate
transactions involve collective annual expenditures and
receipts in excess of one billion dollars.

 25. The plaintiffs have been employed by and/or
are seeking new employment with one or more of the defendant
teams in interstate commerce as professional basketball
players in the NBA.

 BACKGROUND

 26. The NBA member teams constitute the only
market in the United States and North America for the
services of major league professional basketball players.
The NBA member teams are the only participants in that
market, and the only potential for competition in that
market is between the separately-owned and independently-
operated NBA teams. However, rather than engaging in
competition for the players' services, the NBA Defendants
are combining and conspiring to eliminate such competition
among themselves for the vast majority of NBA players,
including plaintiffs, through group boycotts and concerted
refusals to deal. This is accomplished by the NBA
Defendants jointly adopting and imposing "rules" and
"policies" that have the purpose and effect of preventing
players from offering their services to other NBA teams in a
competitive market when their player contracts expire, or
from renegotiating with their current team during the term
of their contracts free from unreasonable restrictions upon
those renegotiations.

 The Expired CBA

 27. In 1987, a class of professional basketball
players filed an antitrust lawsuit, Bridgeman. et al. v.
National Basketball Association. et al. (D.N.J. 87-4001),
against the NBA and its member teams challenging the
unilateral implementation of a variety of anticompetitive
restrictions, including a "salary cap." In November of
1988, the United States District Court for the District of
New Jersey approved the Bridgeman Stipulation and Settlement
Agreement ("BSA"). The BSA, along with a new collective
bargaining agreement ("CBA"), substantially modified the
anticompetitive restrictions imposed by the NBA owners, but
did not eliminate them completely. It was agreed to for a
limited period of time by the NBA class in order to provide
some relief to players during their short-lived professional
careers. By its terms, the BSA and the CBA expired on June
23, 1994 -- the day after the last playoff game of the 1994
NBA season.

 The Salary Cap System

 28. The Salary Cap contained in the BSA and CBA
was a system whereby the aggregate salaries of a team's
players were fixed at artificially low levels. A number of
exceptions were provided, but salaries were still depressed
below competitive market levels. The Salary Cap system is a
league-wide price-fixing agreement among competitors to
restrict the wages of all NBA players.

 The NBA Draft

 29. The BSA and CBA also included a so-called
"NBA Draft," which has the purpose and effect of dividing
the market for the most wanted first year, or "rookie,"
player services among the NBA clubs who would otherwise
compete against each other for those players. Under the NBA
Draft, each NBA team is given the right, pursuant to certain
rules and procedures, to choose specific college and other
rookie players with whom the team will have the exclusive
NBA negotiating rights. If a rookie player for any reason
does not wish to sign a contract with or play for the NBA
team which "owns" the rights to him, he may not negotiate
with or play for any other NBA club.

 30. The allocation of negotiating rights
effectuated by the NBA Draft is enforced by a group boycott
and agreement among the NBA Defendants. This group boycott
and agreement takes the form of a concerted refusal to deal
with potential NBA players except through restrictive
anticompetitive practices.

 Restricted Free Agency

 31. The BSA and CBA also included a number of
other anticompetitive restrictions, including restrictions
on the ability of NBA players with less than four years
of NBA experience to market themselves as free agents.
These players were subject to an anticompetitive "Right of
First Refusal" by their previous team.

 The Williams Case And The Continuation Of
The Salary Cap System During The 1994-1995 NBA Season

 32. On June 17, 1994, the NBA filed a lawsuit
against 17 NBA players in the U.S. District Court For The
Southern District of New York, seeking a declaratory
judgment that continued implementation by the NBA and its
teams of the Salary Cap, the NBA Draft, and the so-called
"Right of First Refusal" do not violate the antitrust laws.
National Basketball Association v. Williams, No. 94 Civ.
4488 (KTD) (S.D.N.Y.).

 33. On June 27, 1994, a group of then-current and
prospective NBA players counterclaimed in the Williams
action, alleging that the continued implementation of the
Salary Cap and the Right of First Refusal, and the holding
and subsequent enforcement of the 1994 NBA Draft, violated
Sections 1 and 2 of the Sherman Act, even while the NBA and
the National Basketball Players Association ("NBPA")
continued to negotiate over a potential new CBA. The NBPA
was then the recognized collective bargaining representative
of players who are employed as professional basketball
players by NBA teams. The counterclaims in the Williams
action sought injunctive relief on behalf of the
counterclaim-plaintiffs and an unspecified class, and
damages on behalf of the individual defendants/counterclaim-
plaintiffs. The counterclaims in the Williams action did
not seek relief for any class-wide damages.

 34. on July 1, 1994, Judge Kevin T. Duffy was
assigned the Williams case, and a hearing was conducted on
Friday, July 8, 1994. At the hearing, Judge Duffy informed
the parties that a preliminary injunction hearing that the
counterclaim-plaintiffs had requested would be consolidated
with a one-day trial on the merits, which "trial" was
conducted four days later, with no pre-trial discovery, on
Tuesday, July 12, 1994.

 35. At the "trial," counsel for the NBPA and the
counterclaim-plaintiffs stated that he had no objection to
certification of a class. However, no notice was provided
to the class members prior to that date, or at any other
time in the Williams action.

 36. On July 18, 1994, the district court in
Williams held that the non-statutory labor exemption to the
antitrust laws continued to shield restraints previously
agreed to in an expired CBA from the antitrust laws until
there was no longer a collective bargaining relationship
between the parties. In its opinion, the Williams district
court stated as follows:

 Antitrust immunity exists as long as a collective
bargaining relationship exists. Accordingly, the
NBA is granted the declaration it seeks -- the
continued implementation of these challenged
measures by the NBA do not violate the antitrust
laws as long as the collective bargaining
relationship exists.

 This does not mean that the Players are
"stuck" with these provisions forever. Certainly,
they can attempt to bargain these provisions away
-- including exerting economic pressure by means
of a strike. Or the Players may request
decertification of the NBPA as a collective
bargaining agent. I do not mean by this ruling to
encourage the Players to decertify their union so
that they may bring an antitrust claim. But,
decertification is certainly an option the Players
have. In fact, this is exactly what the National
Football League Players Union did following Powell
II.

 National Basketball Ass'n v. Williams, 857 F. Supp. 1069,
1078 (S.D.N.Y. 1994) (citations omitted) (emphasis added).

 37. On July 21, 1994, the Williams district court
entered judgment in that action. The Judgment stated that
the action was thereby certified as a class action pursuant
to Fed. R. Civ. P. 23(b)(1) and (b)(2) on behalf of and
against a class of NBA players and prospective NBA players
who were defined as follows:

 (1) all basketball players who were, are or will
be under contract to a team in the NBA from the
date of formal expiration of the 1988 Collective
Bargaining Agreement through the date of final
judgment in this action; and (2) all college and
other basketball athletes who, from the date of
formal expiration of the 1988 Collective
Bargaining Agreement through the date of a final
judgment in this action, were, are or will be
eligible under the Constitution and By-Laws of the
NBA to play basketball for an NBA team .

 The Judgment stated "that the NBA's continued implementation
of the college draft, right of first refusal and salary cap
does not violate the antitrust laws as long as it is
implemented as part of a continuing collective bargaining
relationship." (Emphasis added).

 38. On January 24, 1995, the Second Circuit
affirmed the Williams decision, on the basis that the NBA
players had to end their collective bargaining relationship,
if they wanted to pursue their antitrust rights. 45 F.3d
684 (2d Cir. 1995).

 The "No Lockout/No Strike Agreement"

 39. on October 27, 1994, the NBPA and the NBA
executed an agreement pursuant to which, from that date
until the earlier of the day of the last game of the 1995
NBA Finals or the date upon which a "successor collective
bargaining agreement" is executed, the NBA agreed not to
engage in a lockout of the NBPA, and the NBPA agreed not to
engage in "any strikes, cessations or stoppages of work, or
any other similar interference with the operations of the
NBA." The agreement also included a moratorium on player
signings. Upon information and belief, the No Lockout/No
Strike Agreement was subsequently extended by the NBPA and
the NBA to July 1, 1995.

 The Negotiations And The Proposed New Collective
Bargaining Agreement Between The NBPA And The NBA

 40. In and before June 1995, the NBPA and the NBA
engaged in negotiations over the terms of a potential new
collective bargaining agreement. During the course of those
negotiations, numerous players asked the Executive Director
of the NBPA to disclose the potential terms that were being
discussed with the NBA. The Executive Director refused to
disclose those terms.

 41. During this same period, from media reports
and other sources, numerous NBA players became aware of the
terms of a new collective bargaining agreement that had been
negotiated between the NBA and the NBPA Executive Director.
The NBA players learned that the agreement would include
onerous terms that were substantially worse and even more
anticompetitive than the terms of the old BSA and CBA.

 42. On June 21, 1995, NBA players received a
memorandum from the President and Executive Director of the
NBPA. Upon information and belief, the shipping costs of
this mailing, approximately $50,000, was paid by the NBA.
The memorandum stated that "we finally have reached an
agreement in principle on the terms of a new six-year
collective bargaining agreement," and had attached to it a
five page "outline" that the memorandum stated "sets forth
virtually all the proposed terms of this deal." A copy of
that outline is attached hereto as Exhibit A.

 43. The President and Executive Director of the
NBPA also stated in the memorandum that the NBPA's 27 player
representatives would be meeting the next day in Chicago,
"so that they may vote on whether they accept our
recommendation to ratify this deal." (Two of the 29 NBA
teams, Toronto and Vancouver, are new expansion teams, and
do not yet have player representatives). The Executive
Director confirmed in media reports that the new CBA would
not be submitted to the players for a ratification vote, and
that the CBA would be ratified and go into effect if
approved by 21 player representatives the day after the
"outline" of the deal was distributed. Upon information and
belief, not submitting the new CBA to a ratification vote by
all the NBA players was unprecedented, as all prior CBA's in
the NBA were voted on by all NBA players.

 44. Numerous players opposed to the conduct of
the NBPA in its negotiations with the NBA attended the June
22 player meeting in Chicago. At that meeting, the player
representatives attending the meeting voted to table the CBA
that had been presented to them for ratification.

 The Decertification Of The NBPA

 45. On June 21, 1995, the day before the Chicago
meeting, seventeen NBA players filed a petition with the
National Labor Relations Board requesting that an election
be held to "decertify" the NBPA as the collective bargaining
representative of NBA players. In support of the petition,
statements signed by more than 30% of the collective
bargaining unit renouncing the authority of the NBPA were
submitted to the NLRB within 48 hours of the filing of the
petition.

 46. During the past week, NBA players continued
to sign decertification petitions despite the vociferous
opposition of the NBPA's Executive Director and a few of its
officers. On June 28, 1995, the petitioning players
notified the NBA and the NBPA that more than 50% of the
bargaining unit had signed petitions renouncing the
authority of the NBPA to collectively bargain on their
behalf, and copies of those petitions were delivered to the
NBA and NBPA. As a result, because the NBPA is a
voluntarily "recognized" union, rather than a "certified"
union, the NBPA may no longer be voluntarily recognized by
the NBA as having the authority to collectively bargain on
behalf of NBA players, and any collective bargaining
relationship with the NBA has ended. The NBA players no
longer want to engage in, and are no longer represented in,
collective bargaining with the NBA.

 47. As a result, as of July 28, 1995, there is no
collective bargaining representative to shield (under any
ruling) the NBA Defendants' anticompetitive restraints from
antitrust review.

 The NBA's Continued Imposition Of Anticompetitive
Restrictions Upon NBA Players

 48. The NBA and its teams have announced that
they will hold the 1995 NBA Draft on June 28. On July 1,
1995, all player contracts that do not extend beyond the
1994-95 NBA Season will expire. Upon information and
belief, on and after July 1, 1995, the NBA and its member
teams will continue to enforce the market division rules of
the NBA Draft, and will also do one or more of the
following: (i) implement a claimed "lockout" prohibiting
all player signings or player employment; (ii) impose a
system of anticompetitive restraints on player movement,
salaries, and contract signings substantially similar to the
anticompetitive restrictions agreed to in the proposed CBA
that was rejected by the players; or (iii) impose a system
of anticompetitive restraints on player movement, salaries,
and contract signings substantially similar to the terms of
the prior CBA.

 49. Any "lockout" on player signings by the NBA
and its member teams would be an illegal group boycott in
violation of Section 1 of the Sherman Act, under both the
per se rule and the rule of reason standard. Any imposition
of a system of restraints substantially similar to the old
CBA or the restrictions in the proposed CBA would be an
illegal restraint of trade in violation of the Sherman Act.

 COUNT I

 Section 1 of the Sherman Act

 50. Plaintiffs repeat and reallege each of the
allegations contained in paragraphs 1 through 49.

 51. There is a relevant market for the services
of major league professional basketball players in North
America, and a relevant submarket in the United States. The
restrictions imposed by the NBA Defendants substantially
restrain and injure competition in these markets.

 52. The restrictions imposed by the NBA
Defendants constitute an agreement among competitors to
suppress competition for the services of major league
professional basketball players in North America and the
United States, in violation of Section 1 of the Sherman Act.
This system operates as a perpetual horizontal group boycott
and/or horizontal division of markets, which constitutes an
unreasonable restraint of trade. Each of the NBA Defendants
is a participant in this unlawful combination or conspiracy.

 53. The purpose and effect of the anticompetitive
restrictions is to suppress the market for player services
and earn monopoly profits for the NBA owners. No
procompetitive purpose is furnished by these restrictions.

 54. The plaintiffs and class members have
suffered and will suffer antitrust injury to their business
or property by reason of the continuation of this unlawful
combination or conspiracy. The restrictions imposed by the
NBA Defendants injure plaintiffs and class members by
depriving them of the ability to offer their services as
professional basketball players to the teams of their choice
in a free and open market upon first entering the NBA as
rookie players and upon expiration of their player
contracts. This causes them to receive salaries that are
substantially lower than they would have received in the
absence of those restrictions. Veteran players are also
hurt by the NBA draft, which has the effect of lowering the
salaries of all NBA players.

 55. Plaintiffs and class members face threatened
loss or damage by reason of defendants' continued violation
of the antitrust laws when their present contracts expire.

 COUNT II

 Section 2 of the Sherman Act

 56. Plaintiffs repeat and reallege each of the
allegations contained in paragraphs 1 through 49.

 57. There is a relevant market for the services
of major league professional basketball players in North
America, and a relevant submarket in the United States. The
restrictions imposed by the NBA Defendants substantially
restrain and injure competition in these markets.

 58. Defendants possess monopoly power in the
markets for the services of major league professional
basketball players in North America and the United States.

 59. The restrictions imposed by the NBA
Defendants are willfully intended to help defendants acquire
and maintain their monopoly power in the market for the
services of major league professional basketball players in
North America and the United States, in violation of Section
2 of the Sherman Act, by operating as a perpetual horizontal
group boycott and/or horizontal division of markets.

 60. The plaintiffs and class members have
suffered and will suffer antitrust injury to their business
or property by reason of the restrictions imposed by the NBA
Defendants. This system injures plaintiffs and class
members by depriving them of the ability to offer their
services as professional basketball players to the teams of
their choice in a free and open market upon first entering
the NBA as rookie players and upon expiration of their
player contracts. This causes them to receive salaries that
are substantially lower than they would have received in the
absence of those restrictions.

 61. Plaintiffs and class members face threatened
loss or damage by reason of defendants' continued violation
of the antitrust laws when their present contracts expire.

 COUNT III

 Tortious Interference With Prospective Contracts

 62. Plaintiffs repeat and reallege the
allegations contained in paragraphs 1 through 49.

 63. By implementing the aforesaid restrictions
defendants intentionally interfere with plaintiffs' and
class members' rights to enter into prospective contracts
with NBA clubs other than their prior clubs. Absent these
restrictions, plaintiffs and class members would enter into
contracts with other NBA clubs.

 64. The aforesaid conduct violates the antitrust
laws, the common law of torts of the various states, and is
intended to harm the players, and earn monopoly profits for
the NBA owners, by suppressing the market for player
services.

 65. Plaintiffs and class members will be
deprived, by reason of the restrictions imposed by the NBA
Defendants, of the ability to negotiate and obtain more
favorable contract terms, and will receive compensation
substantially less than they would have received if they
were not prevented from entering into contracts with other
NBA teams. Absent such restrictions imposed by the NBA
Defendants, the plaintiffs and class members would be free
to offer their services to other NBA teams in a competitive
market. Plaintiffs and class members will suffer severe and
irreparable harm if they are prevented from offering their
services to other NBA teams in a competitive market.

 PRAYER FOR RELIEF

 WHEREFORE, plaintiffs pray for judgment with
respect to their Complaint as follows:

 1.   Declaring that, as of June 28, 1995, the
restrictions imposed by the NBA Defendants violate  1 and
2 of the Sherman Act:

 2.   Declaring that, as of June 28, 1995, the
restrictions imposed by the NBA Defendants constitute a
tortious interference with prospective contracts;

 3. Enjoining defendants from implementing or
enforcing those restrictions, or any similar restrictions,
which would prevent or restrict rookie players from freely
negotiating or entering into contracts with any NBA club,
and which would prevent or restrict veteran players from
freely negotiating or entering into contracts with any NBA
club after their existing contracts expire;

 4. Awarding plaintiffs and the class they
represent treble the amount of damages they sustained as a
result of the violations of the antitrust laws alleged
herein:

 5. Awarding plaintiffs and the class they
represent the damages they sustained as a result of
defendants' interference with their entering into
prospective contracts;

 6. Enjoining defendants from implementing or
enforcing the restrictions imposed by the NBA Defendants, or
any similar restrictions which would interfere with the
prospective contracts of plaintiffs and the class they
represent with other NBA teams;

 7. Awarding plaintiffs and the class they
represent their costs and disbursements in this action,
including reasonable attorneys' fees;

 8. Granting plaintiffs and the class they
represent such other and further relief as may be
appropriate.

 DEMAND FOR JURY

 Pursuant to Rule 38 of the Federal Rules of Civil
Procedure, plaintiffs demand a trial by jury.

 Dated: June 28, 1995

/s/James W. Quinn
Jeffrey L. Kessler
David G. Feher
Yoav M. Griver
WEIL, GOTSHAL & MANGES
767 Fifth Avenue
New York, New York 10153
(212) 310-8000

 and

/s/Edward M. Glennon, #34503
Charles J. Loyd #174257
LINDQUIST & VENNUM P.L.L.P.
4200 IDS Center
Minneapolis, Minnesota 55402

 Attorneys For Plaintiffs
