<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<P>Two descendants of John Wilkes Booth, who assassinated Abraham Lincoln, petitioned to exhume what is presumed to be Booth's body. They claim that the truth is that someone else is buried in the grave and that Booth survived for decades after the assassination.</P>
<HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT>
<PRE>
VIRGINIA ELEANOR HUMBRECHT KLINE
and
LOIS WHITE RATHBUN

                            * IN THE

                            * CIRCUIT COURT

Petitioners                 * FOR

v.                          * BALTIMORE CITY

ALL DESCENDANTS OF
JOHN WILKES BOOTH,
known or unknown
and
GREEN MOUNT CEMETERY

                            * Case No.: 94297044/CE 18774 1

Respondents 

+ * * * * * * * * * * * *

AMENDED PETITION TO EXHUME THE ALLEGED REMAINS OF
JOHN WILKES BOOTH FROM GREEN MOUNT CEMETERY, CITY OF BALTIMORE

I. PARTIES

1. Virginia Eleanor Humbrecht Kline is a third cousin of John
Wilkes Booth. She is the daughter of Victor Humbrecht and Agnes
Mitchell. (See Exhibit I). Her great-grandmother, Jane Booth,
was a sister of Junius Brutus Booth. Sr., the father of John
Wilkes Booth. Furthermore, Mrs. Kline's Aunt, Cora E. Mitchell,
married Joseph Adrian Booth, the youngest brother of John Wilkes
Booth. (See Exhibit II).

2. Lois White Rathbun is a great-great-niece of John Wilkes
Booth. (See Exhibit III). She is the daughter of Henry C. White
and Lois Fellows Grossmarm. (See Exhibit IV). Her great- great
-grandfather was Edwin Booth, an older brother of John Wilkes
Booth.

II. OTHER INTERESTED NON-PARTIES

3. Nathaniel Orlowek is a religious educator in Silver Spring,
Maryland with a bachelors degree in history from the University
of Maryland and has spent the majority of his life examining the
details of the life and death of John Wilkes Booth. He has been
the focus of articles in such magazines as North South Trader, a
Civil War magazine, and Rolling Stone and such newspapers as The
Philadelphia Inquirer. His research has been prominently
featured on many radio and television programs, including ABC's
20/20 and a 1991 segment of NBC's Unsolved Mysteries.

4. Arthur Ben Chitty obtained his bachelors degree from the
University of the South and a masters from Tulane and is the
historiographer at his undergraduate institution in Sewanee,
Tennessee. He has actively researched the circumstances
surrounding the escape of John Wilkes Booth since the 1950s. His
story and research on the case has appeared in numerous
publications, including the Chattanooga News-Free Press and the
Baltimore Sun, and has been featured on the wire services of
Reuters and Scripps Howard.

5. Frederick Connor Kline, Suzanne Mitchell Kline Flaherty,
Joanne Wildman Kline Hukne, Kurt Victor Kline, Peter Jerome
Kline, Virginia Anne Kline and Kent Fitzgerald Kline are all
children of Virginia Eleanor Humbrecht Kline, and, therefore,
fourth cousins of John Wilkes Booth. They support this Petition.
(See Exhibit V).

6. Eric Hulme and Erin Hulme are grandchildren of Virginia
Eleanor Humbrecht Kline, and, therefore, fifth cousins of John
Wilkes Booth. They support this Petition. (See Exhibit V).

7. Louise H. Edmiston is a third cousin of John Wilkes Booth,
and a sister of Petitioner Virginia Eleanor Humbrecht Kline.
She is the daughter of Victor Humbrecht and Agnes Mitchell. Her
great-grandmother, Jane Booth, was a sister of Junius Brutus
Booth, Sr., the father of John Wilkes Booth. Furthermore, Mrs.
Edmiston's Aunt, Cora E. Mitchell, married Joseph Adrian Booth,
the youngest brother of John Wilkes Booth. Mrs. Edmiston
supports this Petition. (See Exhibit VI).

8. Barbara Edmiston Patterson, Nancy Edmiston Burns and Susan
Edmiston Dupre are daughters of Louise H. Edmiston, and,
therefore, are fourth cousins of John Wilkes Booth. They support
this Petition. (See Exhibit VI).

9. Christopher Burns, Jens Anderson, Jamie Allison Bums, Kyle
Sean Dupre and Tyler Robert Dupre are grandchildren of Louise H.
Edmiston, and, therefore, are fifth cousins of John Wilkes
Booth. They support this Petition. (See Exhibit VI).

10. Marie H. Worster is a third cousin of John Wilkes Booth, and
a sister of Petitioner Virginia Eleanor Humbrecht Kline. She is
the daughter of Victor Humbrecht and Agnes Mitchell. Her great
-grandmother, Jane Booth, was a sister of Junius Brutus Booth,
Sr., the father of John Wilkes Booth. Furthermore, Mrs.
Worster's Aunt, Cora E. Mitchell, married Joseph Adrian Booth,
the youngest brother of John Wilkes Booth. Mrs. Worster supports
this Petition. (See Exhibit VII).

11. Kristin Booth Rathbun is the daughter of Petitioner Lois
White Rathbun, and, therefore, the great-great-great niece of
John Wilkes Booth. Ms. Rathbun supports this Petition. (See
Exhibit VIII).

12. Elizabeth R. Booth, Lisa R. Booth and Lori B. Baskin,
believe themselves to be lawful heirs and direct descendants of
John Wilkes Booth. They are in support of this Petition. (See
Exhibit IX).

13. The Dr. Samuel A. Mudd Society, Inc., operates the Mudd
family farm as an historic site. Dr. Samuel A. Mudd, the
physician who set John Wilkes Booth's broken leg, was convicted
as a co-conspirator in the plot against President Lincoln. The
Society supports this Petition. (See Exhibit X).

14. Mrs. Louise Mudd Arehart is the granddaughter of Dr. Samuel
A. Mudd, and is the President of the Dr. Samuel A. Mudd Society,
Inc. Mrs. Arehart supports this Petition. (See Exhibit X).

15. Dr. John K. Lattimer is a noted Booth historian, the author
of Kennedy & Lincoln (1980), and is in support of the relief
requested in this Petition. (See Exhibit XI).

16. Carol S. Petzold is a member of the House of Delegates, 19th
Legislative District, in the State of Maryland, and supports
this Petition. (See Exhibit XII).

17. Howard A. Denis is a member of the State Senate, Montgomery
County, in the State of Maryland, and supports this Petition.
(See Exhibit XIII).

18. The Mutter Museum of The College of Physicians of
Philadelphia is one of the pre- eminent medical museums in the
United States, and is in support of the relief requested in this
Petition. (See Exhibit XIV).

19. The Smithsonian Institution's Museum of Natural History and
the Armed Forces Institute's National Museum of Health &
Medicine are internationally recognized research and scientific
institutions. Scientists from both institutions have agreed to
conduct the examination of the remains, and are in support of
the relief requested in this Petition. (See Exhibits XV, XVI).

20. Dr. John E. Smialek is the Chief Medical Examiner for the
State of Maryland, and has agreed to assist with the examination
of the remains. Dr. Smialek is in support of the relief
requested in this Petition. (See Exhibit XVII).

III. RELIEF SOUGHT

21. Petitioners seek an Order from the Court authorizing the
disinterment of the alleged remains of John Wilkes Booth from
Green Mount Cemetery, Baltimore, Maryland, for scientific
examination.

22. Petitioners contend that they possess the legal, and
incontestable right, as a matter of consanguinity and public
interest to be granted said relief.

IV. LEGAL STANDING

23. Petitioner Virginia Eleanor Humbrecht Kline, her children
and grandchildren and Petitioner Lois White Rathbun, her
daughter, Louise H. Edmiston, her children and grandchildren,
and Marie H. Worster (hereinafter collectively referred to as
"Booth Relatives") are descendants and legal heirs of John
Wilkes Booth, and possess all lawful rights entitled thereto.

24. The Booth Relatives are the legal heirs referred to in the
Certificate of Ownership (See Exhibit XVIII) executed in 1869 by
Mary Ann Holmes Booth, the mother of John Wilkes Booth, for the
Booth family plot located within the confines of The Green
Mount Cemetery, and, therefore, maintain all legal control over
the plot and remains interred therein.

25. The original Certificate of Ownership to the Booth family
burial plot is in the possession of Mrs. Marie H. Worster, Both
Mrs. Worster and Mrs. Louise Edmiston, who are the sole
remaining siblings of Petitioner Virginia Eleanor Humbrecht
Kline, have submitted letters to the undersigned counsel
granting their permission for the exhumation and examination
of the remains. Permission has also been granted by the family
of Mrs. Edmiston which includes three daughters, one
granddaughter and four grandsons.

26. Twenty-two legal heirs of John Wilkes Booth, therefore, have
granted permission for the exhumation and examination. These
heirs likely constitute the closest living decedents of John
Wilkes Booth, and are of a sufficient number to permit
authorization of the disinterment.

27. A petition was submitted by Petitioners Orlowek and
Chitty on March 8, 1994 for consideration by the State's Attorney
for Baltimore City, Mr. Stuart O. Simms, Esquire, for a waiver
of any criminal penalties under MD. ANN. CODE art. 27, 265
(1992) that may arise from the exhumation of a body. Messrs.
Orlowek and Chitty possess standing as a matter of public
interest, and on the authority of the Booth Relatives who have
granted their permission for the exhumation. Upon information
and belief, the State's Attorney for Baltimore City has no
opposition to the requested relief sought. An Order by this
Court eliminates the necessity to obtain permission from the
State's Attorney. 76 Op.Atty.Gen 27 (1991).

V. PRELIMINARY STEPS TAKEN TO OBTAIN AUTHORIZATION TO EXHUME THE
REMAINS

28. All possible steps have been taken to avoid litigation in
this matter.

29. The Green Mount Cemetery has been approached several times
by Petitioners Orlowek and Chitty, and their counsel, over the
last two years in order to obtain permission to exhume the
remains.

30. On March 8. 1994, Petitioners Orlowek and Chitty submitted
a petition to the State's Attorney for Baltimore City seeking
waiver of any criminal penalties under MD. ANN. CODE art. 27,
265 (1992). A meeting occurred on May 11, 1994, between
Petitioners' counsel, Mark S. Zaid, Mr. Timothy Doory, the Chief
of the Violent Crimes Unit of the State's Attorney's Office, and
Mr. William C. Trimble, the President of Green Mount Cemetery,
to discuss Petitioners' application. Had the Cemetery agreed to
the request of the Petitioners, the State's Attorney was to grant
authorization for the exhumation.

31. At the May 11, 1994 meeting, the Booth Relatives, through
counsel, informed the Cemetery of their legal right to the Booth
family plot, and requested permission to exhume the remains.

32. Rather than grant permission for the exhumation, Green
Mount Cemetery informed Petitioners' counsel of their desire to
have this Court rule on the Petition herein. The Cemetery
asserts it requires a Court Order to adequately protect its
interests.

33. The Petitioners have informed Green Mount Cemetery of their
willingness to place legal notices, in a manner or method
satisfactory to the Court, in order to attempt to notify
additional Booth family members of the relief sought by this
Petition. However, neither the Petitioners, Green Mount Cemetery
or the State's Attorney is under any duty to notify, or obtain
the consent of, additional descendants of the family. Walser v.
Resthaven et al., 93 Md.App. 371 (1993). Nevertheless, as a
showing of good faith, the Petitioners would be willing to place
such notices if requested by the Court.

34. The Petitioners have also agreed to hold Green Mount
Cemetery harmless with respect to any claims or damages arising
from any actions surrounding the exhumation and transport of
the remains. All permits required by law will be obtained by the
Petitioners in cooperation with the Cemetery and relevant
authorities.

VI. LEGAL ANALYSIS

35. By all accounts, this is a unique Petition. Historically,
exhumations are seldom contested alleviating the need for any
court intervention. The issue was one of first impression in
Maryland until 1939 when the Court of Appeals issued its ruling
in Radomer Russ-Pol Unterstitzung Verein v. Posner, 176 Md. 332,
(1939). The Court noted that "it is a matter of common knowledge
that the number of cases cited is infinitesimal as compared
with the number of disinterments which never find their way into
the courthouse." Id. at 334.

36. The Court of Special Appeals in Maryland recently opined
that "respectful disinterments have been looked upon as private
concerns of the deceased's family and the cemetery, if they all
agree ... [and] if there is any disagreement among the family
or the cemetery as to any contemplated ... disinterment, relief
can be afforded in certain circumstances, in either equity or
law, depending upon the nature of the controversy." Walser v.
Resthaven, 93 Md. App. 371, 381- 3g2 (1993).

37. In the rare instances where an exhumation does become one of
dispute, it is likely to involve close relatives of the
deceased. A typical situation would involve a dispute between
the deceased's widow and the deceased's parents or siblings over
interring the body in a location other than where the remains
were first buried. See Dougherty v. Mercantile-Safe Deposit and
Trust Company, 282 Md. 617 (1978).

38. Notwithstanding the factual distinctions between the
typical exhumation in dispute and the request herein (which at
the time of the filing of this application is not being disputed
by any known party with a legal interest), case law
nevertheless provides sufficient guidance and supports a
determination in the Petitioners' favor.

39. In arriving at a determination to authorize disinterment
of a body for a postmortem examination or reinterment
elsewhere, controlling consideration is to given by the courts
to several factors: "(1) the interest of the public; (2) wishes
of the decedent; (3) rights and feelings of those entitled to be
heard by reason of relationship; (4) the rights and principles
of religious bodies or other organizations which granted the
right to inter the body in the first place of burial, and (5)
the question of whether or not consent was given to the burial
in the first place of interment by the one claiming the right of
removal." Theodore v. Theodore, 57 N.M. 434, 259 P.2d 795
(1959).

40. The State of Maryland has recognized these factors as
significant considerations and more recently suggested "the
following factors to be controlling in order of importance: (I)
the wishes of the deceased, (2) the wishes of the widow/widower
and next of kin ... and (3) the regulations of the cemetery."
Dougherty v. Mercantile-Safe Deposit and Trust Company, 282
Md. 617, 620 (1978). See also Radomer Russ-Pol Unterstitzung
Verein v. Posner, 176 Md. 332 (1939).

41. In consideration of these factors; first, regardless of the
identity of the person interred in Green Mount Cemetery, there
are no known expressed wishes of the decedent regarding the
place of his interment.

42. Second, it is likely the closest known living relatives of
John Wilkes Booth have been located and have executed written
permission to allow the exhumation and examination of the
remains. Furthermore, it is the Petitioners' contention that a
sufficient number of relatives of John Wilkes Booth have
granted their permission to justify court authorization of the
exhumation.

43. Third, Green Mount Cemetery, by way of its President,
William C. Trimble, Jr., has informed Petitioners' counsel that
should the exhumation be ordered by the Court, the Cemetery will
abide by such an order.

44. Fourth, the interests of the public are paramount in this
instance. The question of whether Booth survived thirty-eight
years past the assassination of President Lincoln, contrary to
the official historical record of the United States, can not be
taken lightly, nor ignored, considering the long-standing public
interest that has continued for over one hundred years.

45. Hundreds of newspaper articles, magazines and books
published from 1865 to 1994 have explored the theory that Booth
may have escaped capture. The seriousness and intense public
interest still surrounding this controversy is demonstrated by
the prominent individuals and institutions in support of the
exhumation. (See Exhibits XX-XVII).

46. In fact, this issue still receives widespread media
attention today as demonstrated by the publication of a lengthy
feature article by The Philadelphia Inquirer Magazine on October
23, 1994, the day prior to the filing of this Petition. (See
Exhibit XIX).

47. Fifth, the exhumation and examination of the remains buried
in the Booth family plot as John Wilkes Booth is the only means
by which several families will be able to determine their true
and proper lineage. Of course, as stories have circulated
throughout the decades of Booth's escape so, too, has it been
alleged that children were sired by the assassin and that their
descendants continue to live today. These include, for example,
Mrs. Elizabeth R. Booth and her daughters, Lisa and Lori. Their
family history, as it has been handed down in story and in
writing, supports the conclusions asserted by the Petitioners.

48. Furthermore, the Robey family of Maryland clearly has a
vested interest in the exhumation so as to verify whether or not
their ancestor was actually the person killed by federal troops
rather than John Wilkes Booth. There are many other families
that maintain similar interests. Indeed, as recently as the
1980s, a stage actor was billing himself as the great-great
-great- grandson of John Wilkes Booth; having descended from the
family of Izola Forrester, who purported in her 1937 book This
One Mad Act to be the granddaughter of Booth. Hanchett,
William, The Lincoln Murder Conspiracies 242 (1983).

49. Finally, historic exhumations have, in the last decade,
received considerable support. This is primarily due to the
advancement of science and technology and, in particular, the
existence of DNA testing. Where serious historical questions
persist regarding the identity or circumstances surrounding the
death of historical figures, the courts or the governing
authoritative powers have permitted an exhumation to occur.

50. In recent years highly publicized exhumations have been
authorized on such individuals as Lee Harvey Oswald (question of
identity), the accused assassin of President John F. Kennedy,
see Eddowes v. Curry, 599 S.W.2d 367 (1980); Eddowes v. Oswald,
621 S.W.2d 843 (1981); President Zachary Taylor (circumstances
of death); Dr. Carl Weiss (circumstances of death), the alleged
assassin of Senator Huey Long; the parents of Lizzie Borden
(circumstances of death); and, Butch Cassidy and the Sundance
Kid (question of identity).

51. The exhumation of Lee Harvey Oswald is perhaps most
pertinent to the instant matter. Author Michael Eddowes, a
British citizen of no relation to Oswald, sought to have Oswald
exhumed and examined based on his theory that the man killed
by Jack Ruby was not Oswald but, instead, a Soviet agent who had
taken his place. The strength of his evidence lay in height
discrepancies and the failure of the original autopsy reports to
include the existence of certain known scars. Eddowes was
eventually successful and the body was exhumed in 1981. Upon
examination the body was identified as that of Lee Harvey
Oswald and a very controversial theory was finally put to rest
forever.

52. The evidence presented that led to the aforementioned
historical exhumations falls far short of the physical and
documentary evidence proffered herein to support the exhumation
of the alleged remains of John Wilkes Booth.

VII. HISTORlCAL BACKGROUND

53. On the night of April 14, 1865 the sixteenth President of
the United States of America, Abraham Lincoln, was fatally shot
while attending a performance at Ford's Theater in Washington,
D.C. By the time President Lincoln died the following morning,
his assassin had already been identified. John Wilkes Booth,
twenty-six years of age and a celebrated and well- known actor,
became the subject of the largest manhunt in American history
at the time.

54. On April 26, 1865, the 16th New York Cavalry cornered
Booth at Richard Garrett's farm in Bowling Green, Virginia.
Trapped within the Garretts' barn, Booth refused to surrender
to the detachment of armed federal troops that surrounded him.
Forced out by fire, Booth was struck down by a single shot to
the neck. Within a matter of hours, the assassin was dead.

55. After being brought back to Washington, D.C. the body was
buried under the floor of the Old Penitentiary at the Washington
Arsenal (where the trial and hanging of the conspirators would
later take place) until 1867, when it was exhumed and then
stored in the Arsenal Warehouse. On February 15, 1869, due to
rampant rumors concerning the possibility of Booth having
escaped, President Johnson ordered the body turned over to the
Booth family and it was shortly thereafter interred in
Baltimore's Green Mount Cemetery where it has remained ever
since.

56. It is there that the official historical record of Booth's
last days ends and the dispute at hand begins.

57. Many stories concerning the fate of John Wilkes Booth have
been reported throughout the years since the events described
above. At times Booth was reported to have been living in
Ceylon, India, Mexico and locations across the American
Southwest. But only one story, supported by both physical and
eyewitness evidence, has survived through the years with its
credibility and persuasiveness still intact.

58. It was in 1872 when a young lawyer practicing in Granbury,
Texas named Finis L. Bates first met John St. Helen. Bates
described him as having "splendid Grecian features, sparkling,
deep-set black eyes, wavy, inky black hair and a fine
complexion....His voice was soft and pleasant in conversation
and in his recitations of passages from Shakespeare's plays,
especially Richard III, with which he often entertained small
groups in private." Finis Bates, The Escape and Suicide of John
Wilkes Booth (1907)(hereinafter "Bates, Escape).

59. Shortly after it was ascertained that legal troubles faced
by one of Bates' clients were actually the responsibility of St.
Helen, an agreement was arranged between the gentlemen to
resolve the problem. But in doing so, St. Helen made one demand:
he could not make a public appearance in court or before the
district attorney for fear of being recognized. The nature of
this fear went unexplained but the matter was resolved
nonetheless.

60. Then, in early 1877, St. Helen thought himself near death.
Requesting the presence of Bates at his side, St. Helen informed
him: "I am dying. My name is John Wilkes Booth, and I am the
assassin of President Lincoln. Get the picture of myself from
under this pillow. I leave it with you for my further
identification. Notify my brother Edwin Booth, of New York
City." St. Helen recovered from his illness, and several weeks
later reconfirmed the veracity of his previous remarks. Bates,
Escape at 30.

61. "I have told you that my name is not St. Helen", he said to
Bates, "and, in fact, my name is John Wilkes Booth, a son of the
late Junius Brutus Booth, Sr., the actor, and a brother of
Junius Brutus Booth the second and Edwin Booth the actor." It
was then, to a disbelieving Bates, that St. Helen recounted his
story of escaping the federal troops at Garrett's farm and how,
instead of he, it was, in actuality, a young man named Ruddy or
Robey who had been killed and identified as Booth due to the
fact he was in possession of some of Booth's intimate
belongings, including a diary. Id. at 33.

62. By 1878, the two men had gone their separate ways. But as
the years passed Bates continued to investigate the incredible
story he had been told, including corresponding with high
officials in the War Department during the 1890s.

63. Finally, in 1903, without warning, Bates received word that
a man named David E. George had apparently committed suicide
in Enid, Oklahoma. Personal papers of the man bore Bates' name
and the word was spreading that the deceased had admitted to
being John Wilkes Booth. (See Exhibit XX). After viewing the
body Bates declared it to be his old friend St. Helen and
instructed the mortician to mummify the remains.

64. This mummy uas later exhibited throughout the United
States during the early decades of the twentieth century bearing
the monocle of John Wilkes Booth, assassin of a President.
Bates, by now a prominent attorney in Tennessee, published his
account of the story in his 1907 book The Escape and Suicide of
John Wilkes Booth. Bates' allegations have been subsequently
chronicled over the years in such publications, for example, as
Startling Detective Adventures, a popular magazine of the early
1930s. (See Exhibit XXI).

VIII. EVIDENCE IN SUPPORT OF PETITIONERS' CONTENTION

65. It is the contention of the Petitioners that the historical
record presents conflicting evidence as to the identity of the
body presently interred in the Booth family plot in Green Mount
Cemetery as John Wilkes Booth.

A. Hair Color Discrepancy

66. A glaring inconsistency exists regarding the hair color of
the person killed at Garrett's farm and that of John Wilkes
Booth. At least three witnesses have indicated that the person
identified as Booth had, in fact, red or reddish-brown hair
while Booth himself had very dark, black hair.

67. Sgt. Wilson D. Kenzie, who asserted he was present at the
shooting on Garrett's farm, stated in a sworn affidavit that the
individual killed had sandy hair. "I seized him up as being an
ordinary Virginia farmer. What I do know and positively state
is that it was not the body of John Wilkes Booth. By that time
the officers came up and ordered me ... to keep still and not
say that it wasn't Booth saying the least you say about it, you
are better off." (See Exhibit XXII).

68. Basil Moxley, who asserted he was one of the pallbearers at
the Green Mount Cemetery interment, told the Baltimore News
American, in an article that appeared on June 3, 1903, that the
1869 burial was a "mock funeral". He further stated that he had
"known Booth all of my life and was very close to the family",
that "there were never any two things in the world which
resembled each other less than that body did John Wilkes Booth",
and that specifically he had seen "the body several times and
examined it and I don't hesitate to say that the hair on the
dead body was of a reddish brown color, while Booth's was as
black as a raven's wing." (See Exhibit XXIII).

69. Another witness was Lt. William C. Allen of the United
States Secret Service. His widow reportedly informed a
journalist that the Booth corpse Allen saw had auburn or
chestnut colored hair. (See Exhibit XXIII).

70. Descendants of the Robey family (the name St. Helen used
to identify the individual who might have been killed at
Garrett's farm) have been traced and interviewed by Petitioner
Nathaniel Orlowek. They have indicated that according to their
family history one of their ancestors disappeared and was never
seen again following April 26, 1865. The Robey family has a
history of reddish-brown hair.

B. Statements Concerning Booth's Escape

71. Other witnesses, including relatives of Booth, have stated
they encountered him long after he was thought to have been
killed or that they were aware that he had escaped.

72. Blanche Booth, a niece of John Wilkes Booth, swore out an
affidavit that her uncle attempted to visit her during a
performance in Enid, Oklahoma in December,1902. Ms. Booth also
identified the photograph and mummy, both of which are
described in further detail herein, as that of John Wilkes
Booth. (See Exhibit XXIV).

73. Fannie Bell, who identified herself as a first cousin of
John Wilkes Booth, was told by family members that he had
escaped. Ms. Bell believed that John St. Helen was her cousin,
John Wilkes Booth. (See Exhibit XXV).

74. Nathaniel Charles Newman, who also identified himself as a
first cousin of John Wilkes Booth, executed a sworn affidavit
that Booth visited his home several times after April, 1865.
Newman also identified the mummy of David E. George as John
Wilkes Booth. (See Exhibit XXVI).

75. John P. Simonton, Esq., a former custodian of the War
Department's files on John Wilkes from 1877-1920, executed an
affidavit stating that no definitive proof existed that Booth
was ever captured. (See Exhibit XXVII).

C. Identification of St. Helen's Photograph as Booth

76. Bates maintained possession of the tintype photograph that
St. Helen had given to him in 1877 and went to great lengths to
show it to friends, colleagues and relatives of Booth, St. Helen
and George.

77. The publishers and editors of both the El Rerlo Republican
and El Reno Daily Democrat, both of whom knew George, identified
the photograph as being that of David E. George. An officer of
the El Reno State Bank also stated that the St. Helen photograph
was of George in his younger years. Bates, Escape at 284-86.

78. The City Editor of the Daily Democrat did not know George
but, upon being shown the photograph, indicated he felt the
picture was of John Wilkes Booth. When asked as to why he
thought this to be so, he indicated that he knew Booth well
"personally and on the stage. I regarded him as the greatest
actor of his day on the American stage, and never missed an
opportunity to see him. I saw him and heard him in Baltimore
and New York often, and in Washington also, where I was
connected with the Federal Army, and saw him as a personal
acquaintance. I remember that I saw him for the last time only
a short time before the assassination. I also know other members
of the Booth family and could not be mistaken about this
picture." L. at 286-87.

79. Bates showed the photograph to an old friend of Booth who
also stated that the picture was of Booth although at an age
older than when he last saw him shortly before the
assassination. L. at 299-303.

80. In a sworn statement, Junius Brutus Booth, III, a nephew of
John Wilkes Booth, stated: "I, Junius Brutus Booth, of the city
of Boston, Massachusetts, recognize the likeness of John Wilkes
Booth [in the St. Helen tintype] not only in comparison with
other photographs and pictures of said John Wilkes Booth, but I
can also trace a strong family resemblance and a likeness to
different members of my family in the said tintype." Id. at 304
-09.

81. The tintype photograph and the original affidavits quoted
herein are in the possession of Georgetown University Library's
Special Collections Division where they are part of the E.H.
Swaim Collection. Swaim, an attorney, Lincoln historian and
supporter of the Booth escape theory, purchased Bates' papers in
furtherance of his own research.

D. Statements of David E. George

82. Mrs. E.C. Harper was an acquaintance of David E. George
while he lived in Oklahoma. In a statement given after George's
death, Mrs. Harper wrote:

"Mr. George ... had always been well supplied with money, the
origin or source of which no one knew, for from some mysterious
source he received a regular remittance ... though he claimed to
be a painter of houses, yet he did not work ... Generally he was
gloomy, though at times he would brighten up, sing snatches of
stage songs and repeat Shakespeare's plays in an admirable
manner. He was so well versed in these plays and other writings
that he would often answer questions with a quotation. At one
time the young people of El Reno [Oklahoma] had a play of some
kind. One of the actors became ill and Mr. George filled the
place to the great admiration and entertainment of those who saw
him. When surprise was expressed at his ability as an actor he
replied that he had acted some when he was a young man. Never do
I remember his mentioning the history of his past life or that
he was other than David E. George until he thought he was going
to die -- that was about the middle of April, 1902.

[He said] I feel as if I am going to be sick.' He was Iying on
his bed and he asked me to get him a mirror. [He said] This
messenger of death is my quest, and I desire to see the curtain
of death fall upon the last tragic act of mine. I have something
to tell you. I am going to die in a few minutes, and I don't
believe you would do anything to injure me. Did it ever occur to
you that I am anything but an ordinary painter? I killed the
best man that ever lived.' I asked him who it was and he
answered: Abraham Lincoln.' [H]e seemed to be perfectly rational
while talking to me. He knew me and knew where he was, and I
believe he really thought in fact that he was dying, and asked
me to keep his secret until he was dead, adding that if anyone
should find out that he was J. Wilkes Booth they would take him
out and hang him, and the people who loved him so well now would
despise him. He told me that people high in official life hated
Lincoln and were implicated in his assassination. He said that
the suspense of possibly being detected preyed on his mind all
the time and was something awful, and that his life was
miserable ... He said that he was devoted to acting, but had to
give it up because of his crime, and the fact that he must remain
away from the stage, when he loved the life and profession of
acting so well, made him restless and ill tempered." Bates,
Escape, at 231-37.

83. George died a few months later, apparently by his own
hand, on January 13, 1903. The proprietor and a clerk of the
hotel where George died both signed sworn statements that upon
hearing George's cries and rushing to his aid, he gasped, "I am
-- am John Wilkes Booth. I killed -- killed -- Abraham Lincoln
Bernice Babcock, Booth and the Spirit of Lincoln 306-09 (1924).
Among George's effects was a letter addressed to F. L. Bates.

E. The Mummy

84. The body of "David E. George" was mummified at the request
of Finis L. Bates, who had been called upon to examine the body
after his name had been found on George's correspondence.
Following Bates' death in 1923, the mummy was sold to a
sideshow carnival where it proceeded to tour the country.

85. In December, 1931 the mummy was examined by six Chicago
physicians. It was measured, weighed, photographed, x-rayed and
even opened. As reported in the April 1932 issue of Startling
Detective Adventures, these physicians "had accepted the
invitation to make this final examination in the belief that
they could prove the falsity of the claims made for the corpse.
Definite physical malformations known to have existed in the
body of John Wilkes Booth could be easily recognized . .. if
this were Booth's body. " Id. at 41.

86. The results, as stated in the final report of the
physicians. was that unless the mummy is the body of Booth, "we
have run into a most amazing and unbelievable set of
coincidences". Id. at 56. (See Exhibit XXVIII).

87. Among the findings from the examination of the mummy was:

1) An injury over the right eye socket;

2) Injury to the right thumb;

3) Injury to the left fibula.

88. Booth was known to have suffered the following injuries:

1) An injury over the right eye incurred during sword-play;

2) A malformed thumb said to have been caused when Booth caught
his hand in a curtain windlass;

3) An injury to his left leg caused by his leap from the
presidential box to the stage in Ford's theater.

89. If the mummy had been missing any one of these injuries, it
could have been conclusively disproved to be that of John Wilkes
Booth. As it now stands, the physical evidence continues to lend
credence to the theory that Booth survived thirty-eight years
after the assassination.

90. The mummy was allegedly last seen in the Philadelphia area
in the 1970s. Efforts to locate it have been unsuccessful.

F. The Autopsy of "John Wilkes Booth"

91. The autopsy performed on the suspected assassin several
hours after his death is partly responsible for many of the
reasons why suspicions still exist concerning the identity of
the body. For the same reasons the assassination and autopsy of
President John F. Kennedy would lead to allegations of cover-up
nearly one hundred years later, the autopsy of Lincoln's alleged
assassin was considered to be incomplete, fraught with errors
and far too secretive.

92. For example, Dr. John Frederick May, a local Washington
practitioner, was summoned by the government to the Washington
Navy Yard where the monitor Montauk was docked with the remains
of the alleged assassin onboard. Although May eventually reached
the conclusion that the body was that of John Wilkes Booth his
comments and reports have contributed to the history of
confusion surrounding the body's identification.

93. Writing in a detailed 1887 account, Dr. May described the
moment in which he was shown the body. "By his [Surgeon General
J.K. Barnes] order the cover was removed, and to my great
astonishment revealed a body in whose lineaments there was to
me no resemblance to the man I had known in life! My surprise
was so great that I at once said to General Barnes, There is no
resemblance in that corpse to Booth, nor can I believe it to be
that of him."' May, J.F., Mark of the Scalpel, Manuscript
Division, Library of Congress, Washington, D.C.

94. Not only did Dr. May describe the body during his April
27, 1865 testimony before Brigadier-General Joseph Holt, the
Judge Advocate General of the United States Army, as being
freckled -- although Booth was not -- but he also later
identified the corpse as having a broken right leg although it
was the left leg that Booth supposedly broke upon his leap to
the stage. Although this was attributed to a simple error of
description, soon after the 1869 burial of the body in Green
Mount Cemetery, the Baltimore Gazette reported that one of its
reporters had been present at the exhumation and had noted that
the body did, in fact, have a broken right leg. Lloyd Lewis,
Myths After Lincoln 239 (1940).

95. Despite the fact that onboard the Montauk were some of
Booth's co-conspirators in the plot and that close friends and
relatives were nearby in Washington, none of them were called
upon to identify the body. Instead, approximately ten
individuals who were only casually acquainted with Booth were
brought onboard to view the body. Government testimony elicited
comments of the nature that the body was identified as Booth
only by its "general appearance", far less a standard of
identification that would have been accepted by a court of law
even in that day.

96. Perhaps the one piece of evidence that would lead to
clarification of the identity of the body examined onboard the
Montauk is a photograph taken by Alexander Gardner, a colleague
of famed Civil War photographer Matthew Brady. Unfortunately,
both the photographic plate and the single photograph printed
were immediately confiscated by an official of the United
States government and have never surfaced since.

97. A complete, non-secretive autopsy and the subsequent written
report should have been able to withstand and dispel any rumors
whatsoever of Booth's survival that could be raised. Instead,
the accounts and reports have only led to more questions.

98. The failure of the autopsy to produce satisfactory answers
became quite evident not long after the event. A debate on the
matter was held before the United States Senate in July of 1866.

SENATOR GARRET DAVIS (KY): I have never seen myself any
satisfactory evidence that Booth was killed.

SENATOR REVERDY JOHNSON (MD): I submit to my friend from
Kentucky that there are some things that we must take judicial
notice of, just as well as that Julius Caesar is dead.

SENATOR DAVIS: I would rather have better testimony of the fact.
I want it proved that Booth was in that barn....I have never
seen anybody, or the evidence of anybody, that identified Booth
after he is said to have been killed.

Why so much secrecy about it?...There is a mystery and a most
inexplicable mystery to my mind about the whole
affair....[Booth] could have been captured just as well alive as
dead. It would have been much more satisfactory to have brought
him up here alive and to have inquired of him to reveal the
whole transaction...[or bring his body up here...let all who had
seen him playing, all who associated with him on the stage or
in the green room or at the taverns and other public places,
have had access to his body to have identified it. Congressional
Globe, 28 July 1866, p. 4292.

99. The January-February 1993 issue of Navy Medicine, the
official publication of the Navy Medical Department, published
an article entitled "Identification and Autopsy of John Wilkes
Booth: Reexamining the Evidence". (See Exhibit XXIX). In
preparation for the article a team of forensic pathologists and
anthropologists from the National Museum of Health and Medicine
examined the cervical vertebrae that was removed from the body
at the time of autopsy and which is now on display in the
Museum. As a result, the magazine's editor commented that "[a]
forensic study of the long bones and skull augmented by the use
of video superimposition could establish once and for all
whether the body of John Wilkes Booth reposes in Baltimore's
Green Mount Cemetery." L. at 26.

IX. PLANNED EXAMINATION OF THE REMAINS OF "JOHN WILKES BOOTH"

100. Upon obtaining permission to proceed with the exhumation,
scientific teams from the Smithsonian Institution's National
Museum of Natural History and the Armed Forces Institute of
Pathology's National Museum of Health & Medicine, and other
qualified persons as may be deemed necessary, will undertake
preliminary testing of the burial site. The purpose of such
testing will be to ascertain the condition of the remains within
the burial vault.

101. Unfortunately, there exists no telltale criteria that can
be applied that will lead us to a determination with any degree
of certainty, short of exhumation, of the condition of the
remains after 129 years.

102. Factors of significance include, but are not limited to,
the type of coffin that was used, the acidity of the soil and the
manner in which the body was handled during 1865-1869, when it
was in the custody of the government.

103. The taking of soil core samples to determine the acidity of
the surrounding area and the application of ground-penetrating
radar to ascertain the type of coffin and to verify, after
consulting the records of Green Mount Cemetery, the specific
location of the unmarked grave are two tests that may be applied
prior to the actual exhumation.

104. After the exhumation the remains will be transferred to the
Smithsonian Institution's Museum of Natural History. There, an
examination will be conducted to determine age, sex, race,
stature, body build and the presence of any skeletal injuries
(e.g., fractured leg bone sustained during assassination and
verification of the missing three cervical vertebrae that are
labeled as being taken from John Wilkes Booth and presently on
display in the National Museum of Health & Medicine/AFIP in
Washington).

105. Depending upon the condition of the remains other
procedures will also be performed, including video and
photographic superimposition, such as was used to identify the
remains of Nazi Doctor Josef Mengele, radiography, toxicological
studies, hair analysis, a forensic odontology examination,
clothing inspection and DNA testing and comparison.

106. Following the examination of the remains, if the question
of the identity remains inconclusive or it is determined to be
John Wilkes Booth, the body will be reinterred in Green Mount
Cemetery. Should a finding be reached that the remains are not
those of John Wilkes Booth, the body will, of course, need to be
reinterred in an appropriate location. This location be
determined by a consensus of the interested parties.

X. CONCLUSION

107. Nearly 130 years after the assassination what does it
matter? The response of one historian nearly 30 years ago
remains just as valid an answer as it would today. "Aside from
normal curiosity about any murder mystery and particularly about
one involving a man of Lincoln's stature, it matters deeply
because the assassination undoubtedly changed the course of
American history." Robert Fowler, The Assassination of Abraham
Lincoln 48 (1965).

108. Whether Booth survived past 1865 remains a hotly contested
topic that appears to have no resolution in sight, except by
granting the relief requested herein by the Petitioners. The
issue presented here is not whether the theory that Booth
escaped capture has been proven by the contents of this Petition
nor even if it should be believed. The legal issue is the
standing of the Petitioners. This has been amply demonstrated
herein. The historical issue is whether this matter has risen to
a level of significance so as to merit the granting of the
relief requested. The answer to this question is more than
evident.

109. On these issues there can be no disagreement. For over one
hundred years this subject has been debated by historians,
politicians, authors and the general public at large. It has
been the center of attention of congressional debate, books,
newspaper articles, magazines and television programs and will
likely continue to be for decades to come. 110. Indeed, one
author wrote over 50 years ago that "[t]he question of whether
or not the man who died at Garrett's farm was John Wilkes Booth
is one that doubtless will never be settled." Stem, Philip Van
Doren, The Man Who Killed Lincoln 402 (1939).

111. The evidence of Booth's escape now only exists in
documentary form. We cannot ascertain the credibility of the
people who provided the testimony or affidavits that originally
spurred this debate. The technology now exists to close the
books on this controversy forever, and ensure that history has
been taught correctly or is corrected. There remains, therefore,
but just one proper remedy available to resolve this historical
debate.

WHEREFORE, Petitioners respectfully request:

(I) That this Court issue an Order authorizing the disinterment
and examination of the alleged remains of John Wilkes Booth from
The Green Mount Cemetery;

(2) Any further and additional relief which the Court deems just
and proper.

Dated: November 21, 1994

Jeremy S. Friedberg

Leitess & Associates, P.A.
201 Pomona Square
1700 Reisterstown Road
Baltimore, Maryland 21208
(410) 486-2603

COUNSEL FOR PETITIONERS

Mark S. Zaid~
D.C. Bar # 440532
1225 Eye Street, N.W.
Suite 500
Washington, D.C. 20005
(202) 682-4753

COUNSEL FOR PETITIONERS
