<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<P>In this May 1, 1995 agreement, the daughter of Malcolm X agreed to undergo psychiatric and substance abuse counseling in order to avoid a trial on charges she conspired to murder Nation of Islam leader Louis Farrakhan. Qubilah Shabazz said she accepts responsibility for her involvement in the plan.</P>
<HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT>
<PRE>
UNITED STATES DISTRICT COURT
DISTRICT OF MINNESOTA
FOURTH DIVISION
CRIMINAL No. 4-95-3


UNITED STATES OF AMERICA,        )
          Plaintiff,             )
                                 )
v.                               ) PRETRIAL DIVERSION AGREEMENT
                                 )
QUBILAH BAHIYAH SHABAZZ,         )
          Defendant.             )


The parties in this case do hereby agree to resolve this matter
in the interest of justice pursuant to Pretrial Diversion. The
United States is represented by United States Attorney David L.
Lillehaug and Assistant United States Attorneys Jeanne J. Graham
and Margaret H. Chutich. The defendant, Qubilah Bahiyah
Shabazz, is represented by Federal Public Defender Daniel Scott,
Larry Leventhal, Esq., William Kunstler, Esq., and Percy Sutton,
Esq.

1. This Agreement addresses the federal Indictment against
defendant, charging her with nine counts in violation of Title
18, United States Code, Section 1958(a).

2. Defendant has accepted responsibility for her actions by
execution of an Affidavit (attached hereto), by her statement of
December 20, 1994 (written and typed copies attached hereto),
and by her signature on this agreement. Defendant agrees to
abide by all conditions set forth in paragraph 4. In turn,
prosecution in this District for the offenses contained in the
Indictment shall be stayed for two years from the date of this
Agreement, provided defendant abides fully by the conditions and
requirements of this Agreement.

3. Defendant shall be supervised during the effective term of
this Agreement by the Minnesota office of the U.S. Pretrial
Services.

4. By defendant's signature on this Agreement, defendant agrees
to abide by the following conditions:

 A. Defendant agrees to a change in her Conditions of Release
 and for no less than three months shall reside and undergo a
 program of treatment approved by Pretrial Services at a
 facility in Texas which has been identified to the Court and
 Pretrial Services. Thereafter:

 B. Defendant shall abide by the terms of an after-care
 psychiatric and drug/alcohol program (including testing) to
 be established by Pretrial Services.

 C. Defendant shall report to her Pretrial Services officer (in
 this District or as otherwise agreed) as directed and shall keep
 the officer informed of her whereabouts as directed.

 D. Defendant shall not violate any federal, state, or local law
 which provides for a term of imprisonment of more than one year
 and will immediately contact her Pretrial Services officer if
 arrested.

 E. Defendant shall attend school or work regularly at a lawful
 occupation or otherwise comply with the terms of a work program
 established by Pretrial Services.

5. Defendant understands that if she materially violates any of
the above-stated conditions the United States may revoke or
modify any conditions of this pretrial diversion program and is
entitled to have the stay of the Indictment lifted and proceed
with prosecution of the offenses set forth therein. In the case
of an alleged violation, the United States will furnish defendant
notice specifying the condition of the Agreement defendant
materially violated.

6. If defendant successfully completes the diversion program
and fulfills all the terms and conditions of this Agreement,
prosecution for the offenses set forth in the Indictment shall
not be continued and the Indictment will be dismissed with
prejudice.

7. This Pretrial Diversion Agreement and the stay of prosecution
must be approved by the U.S. District Court. This Agreement
and the attached Affidavit will be filed and made available to
the public, and both defendant and the United States may
introduce, publicly file, and publicly comment on such documents
and any other evidence as deems relevant to the issue of whether
the Agreement should be approved and prosecution stayed. Both
parties may comment publicly on why the Pretrial Diversion
Agreement was entered into.

WAIVER OF SPEEDY TRIAL

I assert and certify that I am aware of the fact that the Sixth
Amendment to the Constitution of the United States provides that
in all criminal prosecutions the accused shall enjoy the right
to a speedy and public trial. A also am aware that Rule 48(b)
of the Federal Rules of Criminal Procedure provides that the
Court may dismiss an indictment, information, or complaint for
unnecessary delay in presenting a charge to the Grand Jury,
filing an information or bringing a defendant to trial. I
hereby request the United States Attorney and the U.S. District
Court for the District of Minnesota to defer and stay such
prosecution. I agree and consent that any delay from the date
of this Agreement to the date of initiation or continuation of
prosecution, as provided for in the terms expressed herein,
shall be deemed to be a necessary delay at my request, and I
waive any defense to such prosecution on the ground that such
delay operated to deny my rights under Rule 48(b) of the Federal
Rules of Criminal Procedure and the Sixth Amendment to the
Constitution of the United States to a speedy trial or to bar
the prosecution by reason of the running of the statute of
limitations for a period of months equal to the period of this
Agreement.

I hereby state the above has been read and explained to me. I
understand the conditions of my pretrial diversion program and
agree that I will comply with them.


/s/Qubilah Bahiyah Shabazz                04-30-95
                                          Date



            AFFIDAVIT OF QUBILAH BAHIYAH SHABAZZ

Qubilah Bahiyah Shabazz, being duly sworn, on oath and deposes
as follows:

1. My name is Qubilah Bahiyah Shabazz.  I am fully competent to
make this affidavit and I do so freely and voluntarily.

2. On December 20, 1994, I was interviewed at my apartment by
Special Agents of the Federal Bureau of Investigation.  During
that interview, I voluntarily signed a statement prepared for my
review.  The statement, although incomplete and inaccurate in
some details, is substantially true and substantially reflects
what I said.

3. I accept responsibility for my involvement in the plan
referenced in my statement.  While I am maintaining my plea of
Not Guilty, I accept the FBI and the U.S. Attorney's Office
acted in good faith in pursuing the investigation and
prosecution.

4. Today I have knowingly and voluntarily entered into a
Pretrial Diversion Agreement with the U.S. Attorney's Office,
which has made available to me this opportunity.  I am doing
so to provide a just resolution of events, and I believe that
during the term of diversion and thereafter I will be a law-
abiding person and not become involved in the types of actions
referenced in my statement.
</PRE>
