<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Court TV Library</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A HREF="/map/library.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/library.gif" ISMAP ALT="Court TV Library" BORDER="0"></A>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<P>This is the ruling by a surrogate court ordering the removal of two co-executors of Doris Duke's $1.2 billion estate. The court found that Duke's former butler Bernard Lafferty was squandering her estate to support his "profligate life style" and that United States Trust Company failed to slow down Lafferty's spending.</P>
<HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT>
<PRE>
SURROGATE'S COURT : NEW YORK COUNTY

-----------------------------X
Probate Proceeding,
Will of DORIS DUKE,                File No. 4440/93
Deceased.
-----------------------------X

PREMINGER, S.

 Doris Duke ("Duke") died in October of 1993 leaving an estate
of over one billion dollars. During her last decade, there were
several changes in her family relationships, confidants and
estate plan. She never wavered, however, in her desire to use
her vast fortune to benefit the public upon her death.

 For at least the last six months of Duke's life control of her
affairs was held by her former butler, then personal assistant
and constant companion, Bernard Lafferty ("Lafferty"). In March
of 1993 Duke lay ill and heavily medicated in a Los Angeles
hospital. Lafferty was instrumental in effecting various changes
in Duke's financial arrangements and estate plan. He brought a
new team of lawyers, recommended by her plastic surgeon, Dr.
Harry Glassman, to her hospital bed. Four days after her initial
meeting with the lawyers, Duke's signature was obtained on a
variety of documents.

 First was a March 8, 1993 codicil to her November 4, 1991 will.
The only substantial changes in the codicil were for Lafferty's
benefit: his annuity was increased by several hundred thousand
dollars annually; his executor's commission was raised from
$250,000 to $5,000,000; he was given authority to designate (and
remove at any time) a corporate co-executor; and a $250,000
ceiling on his aggregate trustee's commissions was deleted,
giving him the potential for more than $1,000,000 in trustee's
commissions every year. Duke also executed powers of attorney in
favor of Lafferty, giving him complete control of her finances.

 The generous provisions for Lafferty in the March 8 codicil (and
another codicil dated March 14, 1993) were retained in an April
5, 1993 will -- the instrument offered for probate. Duke died on
October 28, 1993. Lafferty and the bank designated by him, U.S.
Trust Company of New York ("U.S. Trust"), were appointed
preliminary executors on November 1, 1993.

 Objections to the propounded instrument were filed by Duke's
adopted daughter, Chandi Heffner, who has entered into a
tentative settlement agreement which awaits court approval. The
executors under two prior instruments conducted depositions of
the attesting witnesses and draftsmen in the hope of persuading
the Court to grant them leave to file objections. In the course
of those examinations and litigation over discovery, a number of
serious and startling allegations were raised concerning the
conduct of the preliminary executors before and after Duke's
death.

 On January 20, 1995, the Court appointed Richard H. Kuh, Esq. as
limited temporary administrator (SCPA 702 [8],[9] and [10]) to
examine the allegations of misconduct of the preliminary co
-executors, examine the affairs of the estate, conduct interviews
to the extent deemed necessary, and report to the Court as to
the need, if any, for further action. The Court directed that
Mr. Kuh be accorded unrestricted access to all documents, books
and records relating to the estate and requested the parties and
their counsel to cooperate with him to the fullest extent.

 Mr. Kuh has now filed and served his thorough and extensive
report (the "Report") and the preliminary executors have filed
cartons of documents in response. The Report addresses the
propriety of the actions of both Lafferty and U.S. Trust. At
issue is whether their actions warrant removing them as
preliminary co-executors (SCPA 707, 711, 719).

 The disclosures in the Report can be divided into two
categories. First are the disclosures that rely upon factual
allegations that are disputed by the preliminary executors, but
which, if proved, could constitute grounds for removal. These
include: possible dishonesty on the part of Lafferty, U.S. Trust
and/or their counsel; transfers of Duke's funds shortly before
her death that may not have been made with her knowledge or
consent [FN1]; evidence that Duke's medical condition made it
unlikely that she had the capacity to execute the propounded
will; undisputed evidence that Dr. Glassman removed (and later
replaced) Duke's hospital records; evidence concerning
circumstances surrounding Duke's death that could support an
inference that her death was hastened; and the possible misuse
of funds by the preliminary executors for unnecessary expenses.
These disputed issues will inevitably be explored in depth in
subsequent proceedings, and need not be evaluated here.

 Of more immediate concern is the second category of disclosures
in the Report, based upon facts which are essentially
undisputed.

 Lafferty

 As to Lafferty, these undisputed facts invoke several of the
classic grounds for removal of a fiduciary: (1) commingling of
estate and personal assets; (2) waste of estate assets; (3)
improvidence and want of understanding; and (4) substance abuse.

 1. Commingling of Estate and Personal Assets (EPTL 11-1.6; SCPA
719[7]; Self-Dealing

 Using his authority as preliminary executor Lafferty has
expended and continues to expend estate funds to establish a
profligate lifestyle. He uses Duke's residences as his homes,
living in her California and New Jersey bedroom suites. He
authorized renovations to his California living quarters, at
estate expense, including enlarging the area of glass bedroom
doors facing on a private garden, making improvements to the
garden statuary, and installing in the private bath a spa
bathtub and marble flooring. He admits that the expenditures
inured to his personal benefit and comfort.

 Lafferty lives largely at estate expense. He receives meals
prepared by estate staff. His medical and dental services are
paid for by the estate. He is accompanied by personal security
guards. He is transported at estate expense, in a chauffeured
Cadillac and in the Duke private Boeing 737 before its sale. He
now flies first class on commercial planes, attended by one or
more bodyguard/companions also flying first class.

 Lafferty had access to Duke's credit cards during her lifetime.
He has continued to use the estate's corporate credit cards for
his own personal expenditures. He so thoroughly commingles the
use of personal and estate funds that estate personnel and
outside accountants regularly attempt to reconcile the billings.

 Though the propounded instrument makes generous provision for
Lafferty (through an annuity and fiduciary commissions), it does
not provide him with a residence or authorize continuation of
his lifestyle. This is in contrast to the fact that the will
directs that a residence be provided for three other named
employees.

 2. Waste of Estate Assets (SCPA 711[2]; 719[10]); Self-Dealing

 Lafferty does not have a valid driver's license, yet he was
driving Duke's Cadillac after her death and demolished it in an
accident. The car was replaced at estate expense (partially from
recoupment of insurance proceeds) with a new Cadillac for
Lafferty's personal (chauffeured) use. The justification offered
by the preliminary co-executors for this expenditure is that
Lafferty, designated under the will to be a trustee of major
charitable foundations, will need to travel "in style" when in
California in connection with foundation matters.

 Lafferty continues to draw the $100,000 annual salary [FN2] he
had received as "executive assistant" to Duke, despite her
demise. This salary is in addition to the annuity provided for
Lafferty under the will. It is also in addition to fiduciary
commissions to which he may be entitled, although the will fixes
a maximum commission for his services as executor. The
preliminary co-executors seek to justify this salary with the
claim that Lafferty is performing extraordinary services beyond
those traditionally required of a fiduciary. Yet, while the
preliminary co-executors recognize the questionable and self-
dealing nature of the payments, no application has been made to
this Court for a determination of their propriety (SCPA
2107[2]).

 3. Improvidence and Want of Understanding (SCPA 711[2],[8];
719[10])

 While issues of alleged fiduciary impropriety can sometimes be
deferred to an accounting and remedied through surcharge, it is
unclear that Lafferty could ever answer for losses to this
estate. Lafferty admits that, but for his expectancies from the
estate, he is insolvent. Not only does he have no personal
assets, but since Duke's death he has undertaken massive debt.
His checking account at U.S. Trust has, at times, been
overdrawn. He had unpaid credit card bills in excess of $89,000
and has borrowed $825,000 from U.S. Trust (as discussed below).
The monies have been expended on luxury purchases such as
jewelry and antiques.

 Lafferty's personal financial situation evidences not only a
lack of appreciation of the most basic financial matters, but a
cavalier attitude towards money in general. The Report indicates
numerous instances where Lafferty's responses to financial
queries were inaccurate by orders of magnitude. He estimated the
value of antiques that he had purchased in 1994 at $60,000 -
$70,000, whereas the actual value is approximately $650,000. He
responded to an inquiry about the legal fees of the estate's
primary counsel with an estimate of $30 million, without
comprehending the significance of that sum or the fact that
legal fees paid or payable to that firm as reported on the
Federal estate tax return (that he signed) are approximately $13
million. It is admitted that Lafferty is limited in his
abilities and basically illiterate. An examination of the
exhibits displaying his occasional attempts to communicate in
writing clearly demonstrate his disability.

 4. Substance Abuse (SCPA 711[2],[8]; 719[10])

 Lafferty is an admitted alcoholic and has gone on documented
binges subsequent to his appointment as preliminary co-executor,
including at least one instance where he became combative and
violent and had to have restraints applied. He is also dependent
on substantial doses of a number of anti- depressant and anti
-psychotic medications for mood disorders, sleep disorders and
transient thinking (delusional) disorder [FN3]. Counsel for the
estate and/or personnel of U.S. Trust have been called upon to
rescue Lafferty and assist him in obtaining emergency medical
attention. They have transported him to hospitals (admitting him
under an assumed name) and back to the Duke residences, by Duke
plane and otherwise. The expenses related to such incidents have
been borne by the estate.

 U.S. Trust

 The Report's findings with respect to U.S. Trust are equally
troubling. There can be no question that a fiduciary is
accountable for his acquiescence in the misconduct of his co-
fiduciary (Matter of Rothko, 43 NY2d 305; Matter of Horowitz,
297 NY 252; Matter of Durston, 297 NY 64; Matter of Marks, 137
AD2d 756, appeal denied, 71 NY2d 807; Matter of Rubin, 147 Misc
2d 981). If ever there was a need for a corporate fiduciary to
rein in the excesses of an unsophisticated and unknowledgeable
individual co-fiduciary, it exists in this estate. U.S. Trust
has failed to discharge this duty to the estate and the
charitable beneficiaries.

 U.S. Trust enjoys a reputation as one of the foremost banking
and trust institutions, specializing in the administration of
large and complex estates and trusts. Although it is premature
to assess U.S. Trust's performance prior to the submission of a
formal accounting, the responsive papers seek to demonstrate
that the bank has utilized its sophisticated talents in the
administration of the estate. Teams of its specialists managed
decedent's palatial residential properties in five states,
supervised business assets, appraised and safeguarded extensive
collections of art, antiques, jewelry and other valuable
tangible personal property, and made investment decisions with
respect to financial portfolios [FN4].

 Notwithstanding U.S. Trust's recognized technical expertise, the
Report documents numerous instances where bank officers at the
highest levels sought to appease their powerful co-fiduciary
rather than exercise independent professional judgment. Lafferty
and U.S. Trust were aware that under the propounded instrument
Lafferty has sole authority to appoint the corporate co
-executor, determine its compensation, and remove it at any time.
Indeed, in an affidavit prepared for his signature, Lafferty
admits that at times he made threats to fire U.S. Trust, but
avers that he never intended to act upon them.

 According to U.S. Trust, upon its appointment as preliminary co
-executor it "immediately determined it was necessary to deal
with Mr. Lafferty's need for funds." The bank's president
suggested that a loan be offered to Lafferty to provide him with
"sufficient cash flow beyond his annual salary." No satisfactory
explanation is offered for Lafferty's "need" for a large cash
infusion, particularly in light of the bank's questionable
decision to continue his salary and provide living expenses
through estate funds.

 A November 22, 1993 internal U.S. Trust memorandum indicates
that at least some lower-level bank employees recognized the
improprieties involved in a loan to Lafferty:

 At 2:30 this afternoon, Tony Marshall [a Senior Vice President
and Manager of the U.S. Trust Estate Planning Department] called
me [the loan officer assigned to the matter] to ask if we would
provide Bernard Lafferty with a loan of approximately $300,000,
plus interest to accrue until repayment. Tony needs an answer by
8:30 AM when he has a conference call with Lafferty's Chicago
lawyers. Lafferty may also be amenable to pay interest monthly,
but in that case, would ask for a higher loan, to cover the
interest payments. The interest rate itself was not discussed.

 The purpose of the loan, which would be structured as a non
-revolving line of credit, which would pay Lafferty $30,000 per
month over a 10 month period, would be for living expenses.

 Lafferty earned a salary as a butler, of $100,000 p.a. He used
Miss Duke's credit card to pay for her expenses as well as his
own. Now that she is dead he no longer can use her card. Tony is
trying to figure out how much Lafferty charged on the card for
his own personal expenses.

 Lafferty is both co-executor of the Estate, with U.S.Trust (and
has the right to fire us) and will inherit $500,000 p.a. for the
remainder of his life once the estate is settled.

 The only way out of this loan would be from the payment of
executor commissions. Tony explained that he files a IRS 706
Estate Tax forms, 9 months after death. After that, (in
August/Sept 1994), the executor will apply to the Surrogate
Court for payment on the account of the executor commission.
[FN5] At that time, Lafferty is expected to be given $1,000,000,
which would be payable by the end of 1994. In total, Lafferty is
entitled to $5,000,000. Tony said that even if probate is
denied, Lafferty should get his $1MM commission. Tony gives this
a 99% probability. [FN6]

 Lafferty has no assets in his own right. Tony said that the
estate can not lend him the money. He did not give me the
reason.

 I explained our conference call and that you felt that lending
on an unsecured basis to a co-executor, with no financials of
his own, with terms which would be much more favorable than to a
regular client, appeared to be a conflict of interest. Tony
disagreed, saying that we would be lending on the basis of
expected income, and we could structure the loan so that
Lafferty would pay interest monthly if we lent him the interest
amount.

 Tony indicated that the loan was Jeff Maurer's [President of
U.S. Trust] idea and that Dick Covey [outside counsel to U.S.
Trust] had ok'ed it, as no conflict of interest existed. Tony
indicated that he has to inform the Chicago lawyers in a
conference call at 8:30 AM Tuesday Nov. 23 if we will do this
loan for Lafferty. We have no financial statement from Lafferty,
no 100% first way out, no second way out, no hypothecation of
the estate's assets (which I requested).

 By the next day U.S. Trust had abandoned its concerns as to
conflict of interest and repayment. Lafferty received a $300,000
unsecured line of credit. He quickly depleted these funds, and
further lines of credit to cover his personal expenses were
provided during the next 13 months for a total of $825,000 (an
additional $200,000 on April 11, 1994; $200,000 on September 16,
1994, $30,000 on October 31, 1994; and $95,000 on January 4,
1995). Even after such enormous borrowings, Lafferty was
permitted to continue to draw a salary and live at estate
expense.

 At the time of each loan, the bank was fully cognizant of the
fact that Lafferty had no assets of his own and that repayment
was possible only from his expectancies from the estate, either
in terms of his legacies under the propounded will or from
fiduciary commissions. A fiduciary may not take a position where
his personal interest might be in conflict with his duty; where
a proposed action involves even a technical conflict of
interest, the fiduciary must not proceed without prior authority
from the Court (Matter of Tannenbaum, 30 Misc 2d 743, mod 20
AD2d 808, affd 15 NY2d 829). Nonetheless, court approval
(pursuant to SCPA 2107[2]) for U.S. Trust's loans to Lafferty
was not sought.

 U.S. Trust now seeks to assure the Court that in the future it
will place its fiduciary obligations ahead of its self- interest
in assuring repayment. It denies the existence of any
possibility of loss to the estate, since the loans were not made
from estate assets and only the bank bears the risk of
nonpayment. This ignores the essence of the conflict: U.S.
Trust, which has an affirmative duty to supervise its co-
fiduciary and report on any wrongdoing, has voluntarily placed
itself in the position of suffering a substantial financial loss
if Lafferty does not continue as fiduciary. It is not without
relevance that the large loans were continued after serious
questions about Lafferty's capacity to serve had been raised in
court.

 The potential for harm to the estate is not merely theoretical.
The estate has already borne, without challenge by the
professional corporate fiduciary, the substantial expense of
Lafferty's living arrangements, the continuation of his
questionable salary, the expenses of needless renovations [FN7],
the replacement of a luxury car destroyed through his
recklessness, the expense of reconciling commingled accounts,
and the expense and embarrassment of his public alcoholic
binges. No discovery proceedings have been brought to determine
the validity of the deathbed transfers to Lafferty or others.

 U.S. Trust owes a duty of undivided and undiluted loyalty to the
beneficiaries of this estate (Birnbaum v Birnbaum, 73 NY2d 461;
Matter of Rothko, supra; Wendt v Fischer, 243 NY 439). This is
an inflexible rule of fidelity which requires that U.S. Trust
avoid any situation where its own interests possibly conflict
with the interests of those owed a fiduciary duty (Birnbaum v
Birnbaum, supra at 466; Matter of Durston, supra; Matter of
Ryan, 291 NY 376). The foregoing facts compel the conclusion
that U.S. Trust has violated its fiduciary obligations by its
self- interested concern for continuing as preliminary executor
and attempting to ensure repayment of its loans.

 In addition, U.S. Trust is responsible for its own acts of
waste. The bank permitted the estate to retain the services of
non-resident alien employees, who are paid in cash. No Social
Security or unemployment taxes have been paid on their salaries,
in violation of Federal law. U.S. Trust concedes that these
violations will subject the estate to interest and penalties.

 The tenor of the preliminary executors' response to the Report
is not reassuring. Answering criticism of "off the books" cash
payments to illegal alien employees, U.S. Trust contends that it
was merely continuing Duke's unlawful practice. Answering
allegations of ethical lapses and waste of estate assets, U.S.
Trust argues that administration of the estate is nearly
complete and removal of the fiduciaries at this late date will
cause substantial harm [FN8]. Answering charges that he is unfit
to serve as trustee of the charitable trusts to be funded from
this billion dollar estate, Lafferty declares that he will not
exercise the control he has been given under the propounded
will. Instead, he states that he will assign his "broad powers"
to a star-studded (and presumably busy) panel of celebrities.
These responses evidence a failure to appreciate the proper role
of a fiduciary.

 It should not need repeating that the hallmark of a fiduciary is
not technical expertise, specialized knowledge or professional
reputation. It is integrity and attention to ethical
considerations that sets a fiduciary apart. "Not honesty alone,
but the punctilio of an honor the most sensitive, is then the
standard of behavior" (Meinhard v Salmon, 249 NY 458, 464).

 The courts of this state have been steadfast in enforcing
Cardozo's maxim. No one could read this sorry record and
conclude that the Duke estate has been provided with the loyal
and honorable service that the law demands.

 Any one of the actions of either fiduciary standing alone might
constitute sufficient grounds for his or its removal (see,
Birnbaum v Birnbaum, supra [conflict of interest/ divided
loyalty]; Matter of Cady, 36 Hun 122, affd 103 NY 678
[improvidence/ substance abuse]; DePicabia v Chester Nat. Bank,
50 AD2d 812 [commingling of estate and personal assets]; Matter
of Israel, 64 Misc 2d 1035 [conflict of interest/ divided
loyalty]; Matter of Dolansky, 196 Misc 802 [alcoholism/
substance abuse]; Matter of Grossman, 157 Misc 164, affd 250 App
Div 503, lv denied, 275 NY 650 [commingling]; Matter of Phyfe,
115 Misc 699 [improvidence/ want of understanding]; Matter of
Leopold, NYLJ, May 3, 1995, at 35, col 6 [conflict of interest/
divided loyalty]; Matter of Brandon, NYLJ, Nov. 18, 1993, at 35,
col 1 [waste]; Matter of Metakes, NYLJ, Aug. 13, 1993, at 22,
col 2 [improvidence]; Matter of Diamond, NYLJ, Nov. 8, 1991, at
25, col 2 [improvidence]; Matter of Forte, NYLJ, Aug. 6, 1991,
at 22, col [waste]).

 The Court finds that the full panoply of undisputed actions
demonstrates such a serious lack of understanding of appropriate
fiduciary responsibility that immediate removal of both
fiduciaries is warranted as a matter of law (see, Matter of
Rothko, supra; Meinhard v Salmon, supra). There being no
disputed issues of fact as to the grounds upon which this
decision to remove is based, no evidentiary hearing is required
(SCPA 719; Matter of Birnbaum, 191 AD2d 227; DePicabia v Chester
Nat. Bank, supra; Matter of Iolas, NYLJ, Mar. 23, 1993, at 23,
col 2).

 Accordingly, Lafferty and U.S. Trust are removed as preliminary
executors effective immediately. They are directed to file their
account within sixty (60) days of the date of this order.

 The propounded will does not designate successor executors.
[FN9] While in the ordinary estate it would not be necessary to
appoint both an individual and a corporate temporary
administrator, there is nothing ordinary about this estate. Ms.
Duke intended that her assets create one of the largest vehicles
for dispensing charity in the world. The Court has the
responsibility to assure that decedent's determination tobenefit
the public be fulfilled and that the estate is
administered without waste or mismanagement. This task requires
the resources and the investment and management expertise of a
corporate fiduciary. It also requires an individual with the
intelligence, imagination and integrity to supervise the
transfer to the charitable beneficiaries in a manner that will
achieve Ms. Duke's goals.

 Alexander D. Forger, Esq. is uniquely qualified to perform that
role. He is appointed as the individual temporary administrator
upon duly qualifying in accordance with law. Morgan Guaranty
Trust Company of New York is appointed corporate temporary
administrator upon duly qualifying in accordance with law.

 This decision constitutes the order and decree of the Court.

 S U R R O G A T E

 Dated: May 22, 1995

 END NOTES

 1 In September and October, 1993, at a time when her medical
prognosis was grim and her mental capacity questionable, Duke
purportedly authorized gifts in excess of $16,000,000 to various
individuals and charities. The gifts included $500,000 to Dr.
Glassman and approximately $56,000 to Lafferty.

 2 Lafferty's salary was increased from $40,000 to $100,000 in
mid-1993.

 3 Lafferty's doctor prescribed a number of mind-altering drugs,
including anti-depressants (Prozac, Effexor, Paxil, Imipramine,
Pamelor, Desyrel and Lithium), anti-psychotics (Tegretol,
Risperdal and Haldol), anti-anxiety medications (Klonopin,
Xanax, Valium, Depakote, Phenobarbital and Ativan) and sleeping
pills (Halcion, Restoril and Ambien). On a single day (August
26, 1994) Lafferty filled the following prescriptions: 100
Lithium carbonate 300 mg; 100 Trazodyne 150 mg; 100 Ambien 5 mg;
100 Effexor 75 mg; 30 Klonopin 2 mg; 100 Toprol 100 mg.

 His doctor asserts that the drugs enabled Lafferty to become
"more functional," made his emotions "manageable," and allowed
him to feel more "'in balance' and in touch with himself and his
world."

 4 The Court notes the Report's criticism of U.S. Trust's
decision to invest all of the estate's liquid assets in short-
term fixed-yield investments (without any equity component).
Questions regarding the propriety of the bank's investment
strategy must await the accounting.

 5 No such application was made.

 6 This sanguine prediction disregards the fact that a fiduciary
appointment is not simply an honorific, with automatic
entitlement to compensation (Matter of Goldstick, 177 AD2d 225,
mod on other grounds, 183 AD2d 684). Where a fiduciary's
wrongdoing is sufficiently egregious, commissions may be denied
(Matter of Donner, 82 NY2d 574).

 7 The President of U.S. Trust admits that he stated to Mr. Kuh
that with estate assets of over one billion dollars, he was not
"overly concerned with some reupholstering and some furniture"
but states that his remark was "taken out of context".

 8 No support is given for this prediction, which the Court
rejects. If, as U.S. Trust claims, administration is all but
concluded there should be minimal duplication of effort.

 9 The Court will therefore issue letters of temporary
administration (SCPA 901). The Court has discretion in the
choice of temporary administrators (Matter of Pearson, 228 App
Div 418). 
