STATE OF NEW YORK
SURROGATE'S COURT: COUNTY OF NEW YORK
------------------------------------X
                                      File No. 4440/93
Probate Proceeding, Will of         
                                      E. Preminger, Surrogate
         DORIS DUKE,
                                      REPORT OF RICHARD H. KUH,
               Deceased.              LIMITED TEMPORARY ADMINISTRATOR
------------------------------------X

                        Introduction

          This Report is made pursuant to Your Honor's Order
of January 20, 1995 ("the Order"), designating me limited
temporary administrator for the Estate of Doris Duke ("the
Estate") and directing that I report within forty-five days
(by March 6, 1995).  On March 6, 1995, Your Honor orally
extended that time for an additional forty-five days (until
April 20, 1995) at a conference among the Surrogate and
counsel.

          The Order directed that I "examine the allegations
of misconduct, examine the affairs of the estate, [and]
conduct interviews to the extent deemed necessary . . . ." It
specified that I was named pursuant to the Surrogate's Court
Procedure Act Section 702(8), (9) and (10) (hereinafter,
references to that Act are abbreviated, "SCPA"), and provided
that I was to "be accorded unrestricted access to all documents,
books and records relating to the estate."  "The parties and
their counsel," the Order further said, "are directed to
cooperate with [me] to the fullest extent."
          The Order had taken note of the "serious and
sensational allegations . . . with respect to both the
qualifications of Bernard Lafferty to serve as a fiduciary
and the conduct of Mr. Lafferty and his counsel during the
period preceding and subsequent to Ms. Duke's death," and
further that "[o]ther charges [had been] made with regard to
the co-preliminary executor, U.S. Trust Co."
          Pursuant to the Order, this Report considers the
conduct of the co-fiduciaries and of their counsel,
principally Katten Muchin & Zavis ("KMZ"), concerning the
affairs of the Estate as authorized by Article 7 of the
Surrogate's Court Procedure Act:

       SCPA Section 702(8) deals with conflicts of interest of
         acting fiduciaries.
       SCPA Section 702(9) deals with a fiduciary's failure to
         bring an appropriate proceeding.
       SCPA Section 702(10) broadly authorizes letters for "any
         other purpose or act deemed by the court to be
         appropriate or necessary in respect of the
         affairs of the estate . . . or the proper
         administration thereof."
       SCPA Section 707(1)(e) specifies that a person is
         ineligible to serve as a fiduciary "who does not
         possess the qualifications required of a
         fiduciary by reason of substance abuse,
         dishonesty, improvidence, want of understanding,
         or who is otherwise unfit for the execution of
         the office."
       SCPA Section 707(2) provides that "The court may declare
         ineligible to act as a fiduciary a person unable
         to read and write the English language."
       SCPA Section 711(2) provides, inter alia, for
         disqualification of a fiduciary "by reason of his
         having wasted or improperly applied the assets of
         the estate . . . or otherwise improvidently
         managed or injured the property committed to his
         charge or by reason of . . . dishonesty,
         drunkenness, improvidence or want of
         understanding [such that] he is unfit for the
         execution of his office."
       SCPA Section 711(8) provides, inter alia, for
         disqualification where the person "does not
         possess the qualifications required of a
         fiduciary by reason of substance abuse,
         dishonesty, improvidence, want of understanding,
         or who is otherwise unfit for the execution of
         the office."

       The preliminary co-executors of the Estate, Bernard
Lafferty ("Lafferty") and the United States Trust Company of
New York ("U.S. Trust"), through counsel, have previously
questioned the scope of my inquiry.  I have sought to explore
-- within the span of ninety days (relatively brief, in light
of the multiple allegations of misconduct and the fact that
the Petition for Probate herein was filed just short of a
year and a half ago) -- "the allegations of misconduct" that
have been made, and to "examine the affairs of the estate"
including the propriety of Lafferty, U.S. Trust, and their
counsel, to continue to serve in this matter.

       It is my understanding of my role as limited
temporary administrator that I am not to be judgmental or to
draw conclusions from the facts that I have learned; I am
to report such facts as my inquiry has revealed which the
Surrogate, applying the law, may or may not deem call for
further action pursuant to the relevant SCPA provisions.  I
stress that facts are specified herein either because I see
some potential for the Surrogate deeming each such fact
relevant, or because the fact specified -- although quite
possibly, were it to be viewed alone, falling below the legal
threshold that calls for court action pursuant to the SCPA --
may, along with all other facts, be deemed by Your Honor to
suggest that the preliminary executors (or their counsel) are
"otherwise unfit to serve," as provided by the SCPA.

       I do not suggest that every fact included in this
Report must be relevant, or that each fact -- or even the
totality of all of the facts -- should trigger action by the
Surrogate.  But not to have exposed each fact set forth in
this Report for consideration by Your Honor would, I believe,
have been inappropriate judgmental editing on my behalf.
       I have categorized my fact findings under eight
headings (A through H, which follow), relying upon the
relevant provisions of the SCPA.  In doing so, I have placed
each fact under one major heading only.  I have not cross-
referenced facts under other headings, but obviously some
facts logically belong under more than one heading.

A.   Concerning Possible Improvidence on the Part
  of Bernard Lafferty (SCPA Sections 707(1)(e), 711(2)
  and (8); see also SCPA Section 711(10))           

       (1)  Massive Debt. -- Lafferty was a person with
essentially no assets (Exhibit 5) until -- at the earliest --
Doris Duke's last months.  His annual income had been
approximately $40,000 a year until the summer of 1993 when it
was raised to $100,000 annually.  He has made no visible
effort to live within his means until, at best, quite
recently.  During the near year and a half since Duke's death
he continues to live, at absolutely no expense to himself,
using the various Duke residences as his homes, his meals,
cleaning, laundry and such services being furnished by
domestics employed by the Duke Business Office ("DBO"), he
has chauffeured transportation, free telephone, free medical
services, accounting services supplied by the DBO and
attorney services provided by and through KMZ; there are
minimal charges for pharmaceuticals.

       Between November 26, 1993 and January 4, 1995, a
period of just over thirteen months, Lafferty borrowed a
total of $825,000 from his co-fiduciary, U.S. Trust.
(Exhibit 6).  Additionally, in the eighteen months since
Duke's death on October 28, 1993 -- through the end of this
month of April 1995 -- he will have received approximately
$150,000 in salary as "Executive Assistant to Miss Duke" (at
$100,000 a year), which salary has continued despite her
demise.  During the same period, he incurred unpaid American
Express charges which, as of February 1995, exceeded $89,000.
(Exhibit 7), and which remain unpaid.  At one point --
apparently early May 1994 -- his checking account at U.S.
Trust was overdrawn. (Exhibit 8).  Hence, quite apart from
his living expenses having been provided at virtually no cost
to Lafferty, his total expenditures during this eighteen
month period appear to well exceed $1 million.

       (2)  Substantial Luxury Expenditures. -- Lafferty's
expenditures during the period of December 1993 through
November 1994, as reflected on his American Express charge
card, at seven major retailers -- Cartier, Giorgio Armani,
Louis Vuitton, Neiman Marcus, Yves St. Laurent, Barney's and
Jonathan Kent -- totalled in excess of $155,000. (Exhibit 9).
The Cartier charge included his purchase for almost $35,000
of a second gold and diamond watch for himself. (Exhibit 10).
(By affidavit of May 2, 1994 -- previously filed in this
Court -- Lafferty had stated that Duke, for his birthday in
April 1993, had given him a watch so described.)

       (3)  Haphazard Credit Card Use. -- Lafferty appears
to charge items to his personal and corporate credit cards
without great care as to whether the purchase is for personal
use or is a proper Estate charge. (Exhibit 11).  The DBO
reviews these charges and reallocates them -- after
discussion with Lafferty -- either to him as personal
charges, or to the DBO.  Apart from his own possible
inability to differentiate personal and Estate charges, the
delays inherent in this process have effectively provided
Lafferty with short term DBO loans.  (DBO personnel state
that Lafferty is now, more than a year after becoming a
fiduciary, improving in this regard, for the most part
charging personal items on his personal credit card and
business items on DBO cards.)

       (4)  Insolvency. -- Lafferty was, and remains,
insolvent.  However, if the April 5, 1993 Will is admitted to
probate, Lafferty is to receive a bequest of $500,000
annually for life (Article Five (C)(2) and (C)(6)(a)), as
well as several million dollars in executor's commissions and
trustees' fees.  Moreover, even were the April 5, 1993 Will
not to be admitted to probate, Lafferty -- having already
served as preliminary executor for approximately eighteen
months -- has an expectancy of quite significant fiduciary
commissions.

B.   Concerning Possible Substance Abuse or Drunkenness
  on the Part of Bernard Lafferty (SCPA Sections 707(1)(e),
  711(2) and (8))                                  

       (1)  Alcoholism. -- In his May 6, 1987 application
for employment with Duke, Lafferty responded to the question
"Have you ever or do you presently need professional help for
alcohol or drug abuse?", by checking the "Yes" line; by way
of explanation, he added, "Alcohol I am a member of A.A."
(Exhibit 12).  Duke was aware of Lafferty's problems with
alcohol at the time she employed him and thereafter, and
apparently was pleased that -- for the most part -- while
employed by her he did not abuse alcohol.

       Anthony Marshall, Senior Vice President of U.S.
Trust ("Marshall"), who as such works with Lafferty in
connection with the Estate, has, by affidavit herein of
January 18, 1995, indicated his awareness that Lafferty "is a
recovering alcoholic for which he . . . receives treatment."

       In one of Lafferty's own handwritten notes,
Lafferty wrote "MY DRINKIG IS NOT THE PROPLMEN.  IT IS
HEFFNER." (Exhibit 13)

       (2)  Medical Care. -- From February 1994 to the
present, Lafferty has been under the care primarily of
Dr. Michael Horwitz ("Dr. Horwitz"), a Los Angeles internist
and the Director of the Division of Substance Abuse at
Cedars-Sinai.  (Dr. Horwitz was brought in on the
recommendation of Dr. Charles Kivowitz ("Dr. Kivowitz"),
Duke's primary physician who also has treated Lafferty;
they share a medical suite with Dr. Joshua Trabulus -- who,
ultimately, was to sign the Duke death certificate -- and
others.)  Dr. Horwitz's records include a page dated August
1994 -- about six months after Lafferty became his patient --
reflecting the Lafferty diagnosis as "alcoholic."
(Exhibit 14).  Interviewed, Dr. Horwitz stated that he does
not currently view Lafferty as an alcoholic, but as a person
who on sporadic occasions reacts to depression, tensions and
other problems by alcoholic binges.

       Dr. Horwitz has been heavily medicating Lafferty
for his depressions, stress reactions, tremors, alcohol
problems, etc., and now reports favorably concerning
Lafferty's abilities to function with the assistance of the
prescribed medications.  Counsel for the preliminary
executors, and personnel of the co-preliminary executor, U.S.
Trust, also report that Lafferty functions effectively as
preliminary executor within the parameters of his skills and
abilities.

       (3)  Post-Duke Binges. -- Although Lafferty has
gone on widely-spaced alcoholic binges during his employment
by Duke and the eighteen months since her death, his profile
is not that of a current alcoholic, a person with quite
regular alcohol consumption.  Quite apart from rare
interludes of very heavy drinking while Duke was alive,
particularly during and immediately following a trip in May
1993 with Duke to her Hawaii residence, I am aware that
Lafferty has engaged in the following alcoholic binges since
Duke's death:

       February 1994, at the Breakers Hotel in Palm Beach.
       This binge is well documented.  (Exhibit 15
       consists of several pages culled from the records
       of the West Palm Beach Good Samaritan Medical
       Center to which Lafferty -- using the name Brian
       O'Conner -- was taken by William Doyle, Esq.
       ("Doyle") of KMZ on February 11, 1994.)  The record
       reflects that Lafferty was transported unconscious
       (by Fire Rescue) from the Breakers to the hospital.
       There his combativeness, abusiveness and violence
       led to his having restraints applied.  The Fire
       Rescue Medical Incident Report notes as patient's
       history, "Rehab 1 yr. ago; several relapses since."
       (Exhibit 16).  Doyle, his attorney, then stated to
       Good Samaritan, he "does require detoxification and
       alcohol rehabilitation in spite of the patient's
       protestations to the contrary" (Bates numbered page
       K0000694).  He was discharged and then transported
       to New Jersey (with Doyle and others), and then by
       the Duke plane to Los Angeles (via Chicago) with
       Dr. Harry Glassman ("Dr. Glassman") aboard
       administering medical care.  He was immediately
       hospitalized at Cedars-Sinai and remained there for
       several days, attended by Dr. Horwitz.

       July 1994, when the Heffner litigations were
       apparently settled, Lafferty appeared intoxicated
       at a fine New York City restaurant.  He and the
       attorneys were there celebrating the settlement.
       He was transported to the Duke home in Sommerville,
       New Jersey.

       October 1994, while at the Duke home in
       Sommerville, New Jersey, Lafferty was reported to
       have had another significant alcoholic episode of
       several days duration.

       December 1994, during the Christmas holiday season,
       Lafferty was reported to have experienced another
       significant alcoholic episode, drinking "rum and
       whiskey" for two or three days running at Falcon's
       Lair, requiring house calls by Dr. Horwitz and the
       administration of intravenous medications.

       The above episodes notwithstanding, it was reported
to me that both during Duke's lifetime, and since her death,
Lafferty is generally able to function effectively within the
parameters of his skills.

       (4)  Pharmacological Evaluation. -- Dr. Ralph N.
Wharton, a psychopharmacologist and psychiatrist at Columbia
University's College of Physicians and Surgeons, whose
curriculum vitae and report are appended (Exhibit 3), has
reviewed Lafferty's medical and pharmaceutical records, as
well as records of Lafferty's hospitalization at Cedars-Sinai
in 1993 and 1994.  His report notes, inter alia, that
Lafferty received at least three sleep medications, seven
anti-depressants, three anti-psychotics and six anti-anxiety
medicines, many simultaneously.  Critically, Dr. Wharton
notes that further episodes of alcohol abuse in the future
are likely, that a full psychiatric and neurological
examination is required and that Lafferty should not be
managing complex financial matters for an appreciable time.

C.   Concerning Possible Want of Understanding, Including
  Ability to Read and Write the English Language, on the
  Part of Bernard Lafferty (SCPA Sections 707(1)(e), 707(2),
  711(2) and (8))                                     

       (1)  Writing English. -- The extent of Lafferty's
ability to write English is illustrated by the documents
appended hereto as Exhibit 17.  These were written as notes
to himself, with no intention of being seen by others.

       (2)  Reading and Comprehension. -- Lafferty's
ability to read and comprehend the English language was
explored when he was questioned by me on March 2, 1995 and
April 13, 1995.  Asked on March 2, 1995 to read aloud
section 7 of the California Statutory Form Durable Power of
Attorney for Health Care (Exhibit 18), which Duke had
executed in his favor on April 16, 1993, and which he and
Doyle utilized in making arrangements with the Los Angeles
mortuary following Duke's death, he read slowly, tripping but
once during the reading and then correcting his own error.
When questioned concerning content -- specifically, pursuant
to which provision he authorized the cremation of Duke's
remains -- Lafferty re-read the indicated section slowly to
himself, then responding incorrectly that it was pursuant to
"paragraph 4", a paragraph elsewhere in the document.  On
April 13, 1995 he misread several words of the January 19,
1993 Durable Medical Power Attorney (Exhibit 19) that Duke
had executed in his favor (the first numbered paragraph of
which I asked him to read), but his counsel's interjection
prevented any evaluation of his comprehension of what he
read.

       (3)  Reading and Being Read To. -- Nurse Tammy
Payette reported that Lafferty often asked Duke's private
duty nurses to read to him the names of medications on bottle
labels.  Duke's former chef, Colin Shanley, and Nuku
Makasiale ("Nuku"), the Falcon's Lair housekeeper, each
stated that, on occasion, Lafferty had asked each of them to
read to him.  Nuku stated, however, that she had seen
Lafferty reading "business papers" by himself without
assistance, and KMZ and U.S. Trust personnel indicated
Lafferty showed familiarity with business papers.

       (4)  General Understanding. -- Several of
Lafferty's responses during my March 2, 1995 questioning also
indicated his questionable understanding, not of English but
of the extent of his own property and of the Estate's
obligations.  For example, when questioned concerning the
heavy debt he has acquired since becoming preliminary
executor, and how he may repay this debt (other than
ultimately paying out of funds that he may realize for his
services as preliminary executor and/or pursuant to the
April 5, 1993 Will), he stated he might sell some of the
antiques that he had purchased, essentially during 1994.
Asked about the value of those antiques, he estimated that
value at $60,000 or $70,000.  This was corrected by KMZ's Lee
Ann Watson and Doyle who suggested that the proper value was
about $650,000.

       Similarly, when asked if he knew the extent of the
legal fees of the KMZ law firm, as reported in the U.S.
Estate Tax return (the Form 706, which he had executed along
with U.S. Trust), he stated $30 million.  The previous day,
March 1, 1995, during my conference with Doyle, it had been
pointed out that the Form 706 reflected some $13 million in
legal fees to KMZ.  Lafferty had not then been present, but
possibly this information had been relayed to him in the
course of KMZ's preparation of him, and he may well have
misheard the figure of $13 million as $30 million, and did
not realize how extremely far out of line it would have been.

       On April 13, 1995, I questioned Lafferty as to his
general understanding of the nature of investments yielding
fixed income, and equity investments.  His responses were
simply that fixed income was a safe, stable method of
investment -- oil and gold being types of fixed income
investments (although he said that the Estate has not
invested in these things) -- and equity was a "fast way of
making money" but "not a good way when you're holding money
for a foundation."  He identified the stock market as a means
of investing in equities.  He further said that U.S. Trust
has "investment people" working on the investments, and that
he has periodic meetings with them to discuss the
investments.

       (5)  Fiduciary Services. -- The KMZ and other
attorneys for the preliminary executors, and U.S. Trust
personnel state -- not directly referring to his reading
comprehension -- that Lafferty is extremely helpful as a co-
fiduciary by virtue of his knowledge of Duke's desires and
practices and his knowledge of her various properties and of
the personnel employed on them.

D.   Concerning Possibly "Wasted or Improperly Applied . . .
  or Otherwise Improvidently Managed" Assets of the
  Estate, Attributable to Bernard Lafferty, U.S. Trust
  and Katten Muchin & Zavis (SCPA Section 711(2))             

       (1)  Improving Yield. -- A memorandum apparently
prepared by KMZ has posited that while the assets of the Duke
Estate are virtually entirely invested to yield fixed
incomes, a conservative asset allocation for a foundation
would consist of approximately fifty percent fixed income and
fifty percent equity. (Exhibit 20).  Premised on this,
the suggestion is posed that were the Estate admitted to
probate, and were it thereby to make distribution to the
foundations pursuant to the terms of the April 5, 1993 Will,
the projected return would be approximately 8.3%, while
currently the Estate is receiving approximately a 5% return.
As the Estate assets exceed one billion dollars, annualizing
this difference in projected return of 3.3% suggests to KMZ
an annual "loss" of approximately thirty-three million
dollars during the Estate's temporary administration.

       Since at least the start of my own involvement with
the Estate (as of January 20, 1995), the preliminary
executors, through counsel, have not been shy in addressing
letters and motions to the Surrogate.  As, essentially,
Duke's testamentary scheme has remained substantially
unchanged despite the number of executed testamentary
documents during the last years of her life, putting aside
changes in executors, I am aware of no reason why the
preliminary executors could not have made application to the
Court (if, acting conservatively, the Court's permission were
deemed necessary) for authority to invest in part in
equities, and to utilize long-term investment strategies
rather than the apparent short-term strategy to which the
undated KMZ memorandum refers.  Had this been done shortly
after U.S. Trust became co-preliminary executor, or even were
it to be done now, it would appear from the memorandum that
the return to the Estate could soundly be increased by
approximately $30 million annually.

       (2)  Post-Duke Rising Expenses. -- The records of
the DBO show quite significant increases following Duke's
death in previously relatively stable expenses, of several
natures, incurred in connection with the various Duke
residences ("Rough Point" in Newport, R.I., the apartment in
New York City, "Duke Farms" in Sommerville, New Jersey,
"Falcon's Lair" in Beverly Hills, California, and "Shangri-
La" in Honolulu, Hawaii).  Standing alone and without
detailed analysis, increased overall expenditures after the
death of Duke -- for whose use, enjoyment and comfort these
homes were maintained and adequately staffed, and these homes
not yet having been devoted to charitable purposes --
suggests waste.

       The salaries of employees at the managerial level,
which had historically been increased effective as of October
of each year (which increases in 1993 were apparently made,
retroactively, after Duke's death), were far more markedly
increased after Duke's death than they had been before.
(Exhibit 21).  As to such employee raises, Marshall explained
that Duke generally underpaid her staff, and that it was a
business decision of the preliminary executors as to what an
appropriate level of compensation was.

       Also the numbers of Duke employees increased
significantly after Duke's death. (Exhibit 22).  Counsel, the
preliminary executors and DBO personnel indicate that these
increases were justified by mounting security needs after
Duke's death.  Doyle stated that at a June 1993 meeting with
Duke, she stated she wished security increased and that
security upgrading began to be implemented while Duke was
still alive.  U.S. Trust, moreover, justifies the increased
security at Duke Farms and Falcon's Lair on the basis that,
despite Duke's lesser security concerns, as fiduciaries the
preliminary executors had greater responsibility than Duke
for maintaining and preserving the Estate assets before
turning them over to any trustee of a charitable foundation.

       Although Duke is gone, Lafferty has the services of
a security guard who travels with him locally, and flies with
him between the Duke homes.  The preliminary executors
continued the employment of Colin Shanley, previously Duke's
chef, after Duke's death as combination chef, houseman, and
chauffeur, essentially for Lafferty, until Shanley quit or
was terminated in mid-June 1994.  (Shanley's role did not
involve physical maintenance of the Duke properties.)  The
justification for keeping him on -- at least at some expense
to the Estate -- does not appear except as for his performing
personal chores for Lafferty.

       (3)  Specific "Home-Making" Expenses. --
Appreciable construction and refurbishing took place at the
various Duke homes, particularly at Duke Farms and Falcon's
Lair, both of which I visited.  Although cautious maintenance
certainly justified at least a portion of these expenditures,
the need for some of them -- those of a nature having nothing
to do with preventing further deterioration, but only with
making the Duke homes more comfortable during the period of
temporary administration when they are being used by Lafferty
-- appears to be at least questionable.

       In connection with these expenditures, I have in
mind that Jeffrey Maurer, President of U.S. Trust, stated
that with Estate assets of over one billion dollars, U.S.
Trust was not "overly concerned with some reupholstering and
some furniture," and other maintenance or remodeling charges.
But whether the massiveness of the Estate is a proper
yardstick for considering possible waste is not a decision
for me to make.

       Over $60,000 was spent at Falcon's Lair for
draperies, furniture reupholstering, and the like, paid to
Ellison Draperies & Interiors. (Exhibit 23).  (I was unable
to determine the precise need for such work as the principal
of Ellison was unable to meet with me.)  I am informed that
Lafferty had authorized at least some appreciable portion of
this work, which was paid for in February-April 1994 (five or
six months after Duke's death), without clearing with U.S.
Trust.  When Doyle became aware that Lafferty was
reupholstering furniture at Falcon's Lair, he advised
Lafferty and U.S. Trust that this should be deferred, the
decision ultimately to be made by the Trustees of the Doris
Duke Charitable Foundation.

       Although Lafferty stated that Duke had knowingly
neglected Falcon's Lair for years, and that his
reupholstering and other changes were part of his charge from
Duke, Eleanor Lawson ("Lawson") (one of the very few who was
permitted to visit Duke until her death and to whom Duke
bequeathed $3 million) noted that the house and furnishing
seemed to be in fair shape while Duke remained alive, noting
further that some months before Duke died a decorator had
refurnished and redecorated Duke's Falcon's Lair bedroom.
Fay and Virginia Wright of the Self-Realization Fellowship
(to which Duke made annual six figure gifts and bequeathed
one half million dollars in her Will) also were permitted to
visit Duke throughout 1993 despite her serious illness.  They
noted that Falcon's Lair had not appeared shabby or run down.

       Approximately $260,000 was spent at Falcon's Lair
on repairs and renovations paid to Campolong Construction Co.
(Exhibit 23).  Certainly, a substantial portion of this was
necessitated by January 1994 California earthquake damage.
However, U.S. Trust officials who visited Falcon's Lair after
the earthquake had found only "minor earthquake damage."
(Exhibit 24), and Falcon's Lair security personnel said the
same.  Moreover, the $260,000 included approximately $60,000
on such items as the remodeling of Duke's bedroom, used since
her death by Lafferty, including enlarging the area of glass
bedroom doors facing on a private garden, new pedestals for
statuary in this private garden, installation in Duke's
private bathroom of a spa bathtub and marble flooring.
Lafferty, who said he made these changes out of respect for
the house and Duke, concedes that the reconstruction of the
bedroom glass doors, leading to the private garden outside
the master bedroom at Falcon's Lair, made his life more
pleasant.  Similarly, his purchase of a new bed canopy
(ultimately, I am informed, charged to Lafferty personally),
improved the room's appearance, making it more attractive,
Lafferty noted, for any prospective purchaser.

       According to Robert Toretta, house manager at
Falcon's Lair since October 1994 -- interviewed in the
presence of KMZ -- some of the repairs/reconstruction at
Falcon's Lair would have been less necessary were it not that
people were living there.  Occupancy, for example, affected
the septic system, the need to upgrade the telephone system,
etc.

       (4)  New Cadillac Purchase. -- In June 1994,
Lafferty -- not an experienced driver and lacking a driver's
license -- recklessly drove and totalled a Duke Cadillac in
Los Angeles.  I was informed that some $50,000 was recovered
from the insurer, and in January 1995 a new Cadillac was
purchased in Los Angeles for approximately this amount.  The
justification for this purchase offered by Lafferty and U.S.
Trust was that Lafferty, designated to be trustee of major
foundations, would have to travel in style when in California
in connection with foundation matters.  Lafferty does not
drive but is chauffeured when in Los Angeles.  The actual use
of the Cadillac discussed by Lafferty when questioned by me
-- apart from its use for him and for U.S. Trust personnel
when in Los Angeles -- has so far been to escort Victoria
Principal, well known and apparently involved in charitable
enterprises benefitting children, to Falcon's Lair.
Ms. Principal is married to Dr. Glassman, one of Duke
physicians considered hereinafter.

       (5)  Legal Fees. -- Quite significant legal fees,
totalling just under $10,000,000, billed by a number of
different law firms, have been paid by the Estate.
(Exhibit 25).  In excess of $9,000,000 has been paid to KMZ
through February 1995.  The Estate's Form 706 reveals total
legal fees, either paid or to be paid to KMZ, of just under
$13,500,000, of which a fixed amount of $8,000,000 is
described as for administration.  A breakdown of this
$13,500,000, reflecting figures as set out in the Estate's
Form 706, is appended. (Exhibit 26).  KMZ's January 20, 1994
letter retainer agreement is also appended. (Exhibit 27).
Litigation (the Will contest, the 1917 Trust, the Heffner New
Jersey action, etc.) and other matters were to be -- and have
been -- billed separately from the $8,000,000 administration
charge.  Marshall negotiated the retainer with KMZ -- which
law firm had, advising Lafferty, brought U.S. Trust into the
picture -- and believes it to be reasonable, and states it is
certainly not so high as to be improper.

       When Duke retained KMZ in the Spring of 1993, that
firm's agreement with her called for billing (during her
lifetime) to be essentially on a time basis. (Exhibit 28).

       (6)  Miscellaneous Expenses. -- Miscellaneous
expenses have been incurred during the preliminary
administration that do not appear to be appropriately
classified as necessary maintenance items, to be expended by
those now charged only with the temporary administration of
the Estate's assets.  For example, a pistol firing range was
"reactivated" at Duke Farms in order that security personnel
there could appropriately hone their firearm skills.
Expense: $1,769.  Duke had had two camels at Duke Farms, one
of which died;  two miniature horses were purchased to
provide companionship for the remaining camel.  Expense:
$2,600.  Although Duke was an ardent conservationist, I am
informed that security needs after her death required that
trees on the Falcon's Lair property be cut down and cleared
away, and a new lighting system installed there at
considerable expense.

       Appended is a listing of some 90 work orders,
culled from records of many more, that were approved between
November 1993 and February 1995. (Exhibit 29).  A casual
reading of the list reflects, among other items, the apparent
approval of the purchase of eight further vehicles,
apparently for Duke Farms (items 3, 14, 15, 19, 39, 59, 76,
78), as well as a number of other items, approved by the
Estate's provisional administrators, the need for which may
be questioned.

E.   Concerning Honesty or Possible Dishonesty on the Part
  of Bernard Lafferty, U.S. Trust and Katten Muchin &
  Zavis (SCPA Section 707(i)(e), 711(2) and (8))           

       (1)  Sizable Pre-Death Gifts. -- A number of gifts
of Duke's funds were made in September-October 1993, at a
time when Duke admittedly was in poor physical condition and
in at least questionable mental shape.

       Duke's hospital chart (utilizing for Duke the name
"Norma Jane") reflects that on March 16, 1993 Lafferty signed
a bone marrow consent, stating as a reason "patient has
difficulty signing." (Exhibit 30).  An April 20, 1993 pre-
operative note states that Lafferty "will sign consent as
legal guardian" (Exhibit 31), possibly suggesting Duke's
diminished mental status at that point.  During September
1993, Duke had a series of physical therapy sessions with a
therapist who had worked with her months earlier; the
therapist stated that although Duke was "alert" in September
1993 there was "no comparison" with the level of her
alertness then with what it had been earlier.  This therapist
also noted at least two instances, in the course of four
therapy sessions, in which Duke was not clear; in one of
these instances, she was disoriented as to place, not knowing
that she was in California.  A number of therapeutic sessions
with Duke were canceled, apparently because of either her
physical condition or respiratory difficulties which
prevented the physical exertions involved in physical
therapy.  A respiratory therapist who treated Duke in
September-October 1993, both at Cedars-Sinai and at home,
stated that while at Cedars-Sinai, even before returning
home, Duke was approximately halfway between being fully
alert and comatose.

       Under date of September 27, 1993, in response to
interrogatories propounded by Heffner in her New Jersey suit,
the Duke verification was physically signed by Lafferty,
purportedly at the express request and direction of Duke and
in her presence; apparently, she was unable to sign, or even
to put her mark on the verification. (Exhibit 32).  As
Dr. Kivowitz, Duke's primary physician, testified at
deposition, on October 7, 1993 he viewed Duke as terminal, as
a hospice case, although he had not written this down.
(Exhibit 33).  Pearl Rosenstein, a nurse who had been with
Duke continuously from February of 1993 until the time of her
death, has stated that Duke was in and out of awareness from
late in her hospital stay, in September 1993; Duke was not
alert, did not communicate, generally her eyes were shut and
she may have been asleep.  Nurse Rosenstein further stated
that Duke was occasionally disoriented as to time and place
both at the hospital and after going home on September 20,
1993.  Prior to early October 1993 Duke's physical and mental
condition had apparently deteriorated significantly.  (See
appended Report of Dr. Macris, Exhibit 2, pp.7-8.)  The
medical reports of both Dr. Macris and Dr. Stephen Hyman
(Exhibits 2 and 4) indicate that as early as March 1993 --
seven months before a $500,000 gift was made to Dr. Glassman
-- the amounts and kinds of medication Duke was receiving
were such as to have affected her cognition.

       A February 23, 1995 letter from KMZ to me,
explaining unopened Duke mail from Summer into Fall 1993,
refers to the period "from July to October 1993 when she was
very ill." (Exhibit 34).

       Duke died October 28, 1993.

       Against this background, it is appropriate to
consider the significant gifts of her funds that were made in
September-October 1993, and whether in fact these were
actually gifts authorized by Duke, or whether they suggest
misapplication of her assets.

       In September 1993, a "loan" of $900,000 was made to
Dr. Rolando Atiga ("Dr. Atiga"), as reflected in Schedule C
of the U.S. Estate Tax Return, Form 706.  At the time,
Dr. Atiga's then prior quite substantial Duke loans (in
excess of $400,000) remained -- and remain -- unpaid.  By
check dated October 4, 1993, a $500,000 gift was made to
Dr. Glassman (Exhibit 35), also reflected in the U.S. Gift
Tax Return for 1993 (Exhibit 36).  As to this gift, Lafferty
states that Duke said "Dr. Glassman has always been good to
us all, I'm going to give him a gift."  On March 2, 1995,
Lafferty said that when he had spoken to George Reed ("Reed")
at the DBO, and instructed him to send a $500,000 check
payable to Dr. Glassman, Duke was listening on a
speakerphone.  When again interviewed by me a month later, on
April 13, 1995, Lafferty was told that the previous day
(April 12, 1995) Reed, who had kept contemporaneous notes
(Exhibit 37), had said he had not been told that Duke was on
a speakerphone, and knew nothing of such first-hand Duke
knowledge -- all his dealings having been with Lafferty and
Doyle -- Lafferty said maybe nothing had been said to Reed
about it.

       My inspection of Duke's U.S. Gift Tax Returns
(Forms 709) for calendar years 1990-92, reflects not a single
reported gift to any individual (non-charitable gift) during
any of those years.  The gift to Dr. Glassman, obviously, is
not in keeping with any Duke tradition.

       Under date of September 21, 1993, Dr. Kivowitz --
whose medical bills to Duke during the last months of her
life came to $50,000 monthly -- had received a $10,000 gift,
drawn on the DBO account. (Exhibit 38).

       Besides the non-charitable gifts to Dr. Glassman
and Dr. Kivowitz, the Estate's U.S. Gift Tax Return for
Calendar Year 1993, Form 709 (Exhibit 36), shows that a
number of charitable gifts were made in early October 1993
including $2,000,000 to Duke University, $1,000,000 to an
Elizabeth Taylor AIDS foundation, and $1,000,000 to People
for the Ethical Treatment of Animals, as well as in excess of
$10,700,000 to the pre-existing Doris Duke Foundation.  As to
these early October charitable gifts, Lafferty and Doyle
instructed Reed to cut the checks, purportedly on Duke's
instructions. (Exhibits 37 and 39).  On March 2, 1995,
Lafferty told me that letters had been prepared for Duke's
signature and transmitted by the DBO with the checks to Duke
for her to execute and forward.  A month later, when
interviewed on April 12, 1995, Reed said his files showed no
such letters.  The following day, on April 13, 1995, Lafferty
said he -- not Duke -- may have signed such letters, and his
earlier statement "may have been a mistake I made."  Covering
letters in fact were sent by Lafferty. (Exhibit 40).

       No documentation establishes that these various
gifts -- non-charitable and charitable -- were, in fact,
approved by Duke.  As noted, it is likely she was in such
condition in September-October 1993 that she well may have
been incapable of understandingly approving.  Lafferty had
extremely broad Duke Powers of Attorney under the laws of
California and New Jersey. (Exhibit 41).  But none of these
Powers specifically provided authority to make gifts, and
Lafferty did not claim to have acted pursuant to such powers
of attorney.

       Doyle stated he had not researched whether the
California Uniform Form Durable Power of Attorney Duke had
executed in Lafferty's favor implicitly included the power to
give gifts.  Research suggests it does not.

       Although Doyle and Lafferty stated the gifts to
Drs. Glassman and Kivowitz and to the various charities in
early October 1993 were pursuant to decisions made by Duke,
Reed (who signed each of the checks) stated unequivocally --
and his contemporaneously made early October 1993 notes
provide corroboration -- that he dealt only with Doyle and
Lafferty and had no reason to believe (other than what Doyle
or Lafferty may then have said) that Duke had requested or
authorized that these gifts be made.

       As to the $900,000 September loan to Dr. Atiga,
Doyle recognized the at best slight likelihood that it would
ever be repaid, but stated it had been discussed with Duke
and it was her desire that the "loan" be made.  Here, too,
Reed's recollection and notes, analogous to their early
October 1993 counterparts, reflect only Doyle's and
Lafferty's -- not Duke's -- directions. (Exhibit 42).

       (2)  Dr. Glassman's $500,000 Gift. -- As noted, the
U.S. Gift Tax Return for 1993 reflects an October 4, 1993
gift of $500,000 to Dr. Glassman.

       Dr. Glassman (according to the KMZ attorneys,
Lafferty, and apparently Dr. Kivowitz) introduced KMZ,
through its Los Angeles partner, Alan Croll, to Duke.  KMZ's
fees, as noted (item D-5 hereinabove), according to the
Form 706, are estimated to exceed $13,000,000 in this matter.
Lafferty, on the recommendation of KMZ, brought U.S. Trust in
as his co-fiduciary.  Its fees are anticipated to exceed
$5,000,000.

       Apart from introducing KMZ and Duke to each other,
it is undisputed that Dr. Glassman took Duke's hospital chart
from its place of safekeeping at Cedars-Sinai in or about
August 1993.  Shanley apparently overheard a reference to
Dr. Glassman's action, and Lafferty and Doyle confirm that
they became aware of it.  After Shanley reported it,
purportedly Dr. Glassman returned the chart intact, but there
is no way of verifying whether or not any items had been
removed from it. (It is speculated that it was taken to
remove items reflecting negatively on Duke's testamentary
capacity in March-April 1993.)

       (3)  Duke's Cremation. -- The death certificate
states that Duke died at 5:48 a.m. on October 28, 1993.
(Exhibit 43).  At the time of Duke's death, Doyle was present
at Falcon's Lair, as were Lafferty, nurses Rosenstein and
Payette, the Falcon's Lair staff and Nuku's sister.  Doyle
said that he had learned from Dr. Kivowitz that, on
October 7, 1993, he (Dr. Kivowitz) had discussed with Duke
that she was not recovering, and that he could do nothing for
her but keep her comfortable.  (No medical records -- nurses'
notes, etc. -- confirm such conversation with Duke on that
date or any other date.)  Dr. Kivowitz that day altered his
course of treatment, focusing on keeping Duke pain free and
comfortable.

       I am informed by the personnel of Pierce Brothers,
the mortuary establishment in Los Angeles that handled the
arrangements following Duke's death, that customarily
cremation follows death by four or five days; I am further
informed that Duke's cremation took place commencing at
4:17 a.m. on October 29, 1993 -- less than twenty-four hours
after death -- quite unusual, but not entirely unique,
swiftness.

       Because of realistic fears, including that Heffner
might, in some fashion, have interfered with Duke's desire to
have her Estate probated in New York County, arrangements
were made, through KMZ, to obtain the death certificate
promptly, on the day of death, Thursday, October 28th.  This
facilitated the quick cremation early Friday morning.

       This swift cremation precluded any possibility of
an autopsy or exhumation.

       The rush to cremation was also in part purportedly
occasioned by concern that Heffner may have wanted Duke's
body; Duke had not wanted Heffner anywhere near her body.
(My research suggests there may be some ambiguity, under
California law, whether Heffner, as Duke's daughter, would
have had a claim to the body, even though the Durable Power
of Attorney for Health Care, executed by Duke on April 16,
1993, gave Lafferty authority to make decisions concerning
the remains.)

       Doyle conceded that once the death certificate had
been secured (Thursday afternoon), the probate proceedings
could have moved ahead even though the body had not yet been
disposed of.  A proceeding was in fact instituted by the
Heffner attorneys in New Jersey, brought on by Order to Show
Cause of November 1, 1993, seeking to restrain KMZ and others
from seeking probate elsewhere than in the State of New
Jersey. (Exhibit 44).  By the time, however, that the New
Jersey Show Cause Order was served, preliminary letters had
issued in New York.

       The April 5, 1993 Will, drafted by KMZ, specified
Duke's desire that there be no funeral or memorial service,
and that she "be buried at sea."  This provision was
virtually identical to those contained in her earlier
November 4, 1991 and July 28, 1987 Wills, and had not been
changed by any of the intervening Codicils.  I have not been
informed of any contrary side letters or other contrary
written instructions.

       Doyle stated that in conference with Duke (at
Falcon's Lair in April 1993) Doyle informed Duke that
California law required cremation if human remains were to be
placed into the sea; that an uncremated body could not be
deposited into the sea under California law.  Having so
informed Duke, Doyle states that Duke expressed willingness
that her remains be cremated. (Doyle had had Michael
McCarthy, then a KMZ attorney, research California law
concerning "burial at sea" after Duke was admitted to the
Cedars-Sinai Intensive Care Unit on March 19, 1993.  Doyle
stated he did not think it necessary to research Hawaiian law
concerning burial at sea, and did not think it necessary to
advise Duke that California law would not apply to burial off
Hawaii.)

       Lafferty states that in conversations he had with
Duke she stated her desire to be cremated, these
conversations having taken place after Lafferty had learned
of his raise to $100,000 annually, during the summer of 1993.
Lafferty stated that Duke had further instructed him that she
wished her remains carried to each of her houses (Falcon's
Lair, Duke Farms, Rough Point, and Shangri-La), to spend one
night in each of these residences before the remains were
disposed of.  There appears to be accord that Duke wished her
remains brought to each of her homes, other than New York
City.  (Without judging the logic of this, and insofar as
this may make any sense at all, would it have made more sense
if the remains meant her body -- via the Duke 737 airplane --
rather than her ashes, so that domestics or neighboring
friends might, there being no funeral, pay respects?)  In
fact, the remains were not taken to Hawaii until November 14,
and disposed of there on November 17, 1993, after having been
taken to the various homes -- as indicated -- for one or more
nights.

       Others have informed me that Duke told them that,
after death, she wished to be "fed to the sharks," in no
fashion indicating any desire for cremation.

       As KMZ was continuing to prepare various further
documents for Duke's execution in both April 1993 and June
1993 (Exhibit 45), a writing might then have been readily
presented to Duke for execution specifying cremation.  This,
apparently, was not done.

       My inquiry suggests that Doyle misinformed Duke, in
that he focused attention solely on California burial law.
This, in fact, interprets "burial at sea" to include
cremation and does not speak of depositing a body into the
sea.  California Health and Safety Code Section 7117.  However,
there is agreement among Doyle, Lafferty, and others that
Duke wanted her remains -- whatever form they were in --
deposited in the sea across from Shangri-La, her home at
Diamond Head in Hawaii, not off the California coast.
Hawaiian law does not define "burial at sea," and my inquiry
of personnel of the Hawaii Department of Health confirmed
that either a body or cremated remains can be deposited in
the sea off Hawaii, outside the three nautical mile limit.
(Indeed, 40 C.F.R. Section 229 (1994) would permit the deposit
of a body, or cremated remains, three nautical miles off the
United States coast, off California or wherever.)  And so
cremation was not required to meet Duke's "burial at sea"
desire, and assuming the Doyle-Duke conversation took place
as Doyle told me of it, Doyle misled Duke.

       Apart from the oral statements of Doyle and
Lafferty, some uncertain support for the purported Duke
request for cremation was offered by two persons whom I
interviewed.  Eleanor Lawson -- who received a bequest of
$3,000,000 pursuant to the April 5, 1993 Will (a like bequest
having been provided for her by the March 13, 1991 Codicil to
the July 28, 1987 Will) -- equivocated concerning cremation.
When she met with me she was accompanied not only by her own
attorney, but by two KMZ partners as well, all three of whom
entered the conference room, in which I had been waiting,
together with Lawson.  Lawson stated that she had discussed
cremation with Duke over the years, that Duke believed in
cremation, and that she assumed that Duke's Will had
expressly provided for cremation.  Dr. Atiga, as already
noted a person very deeply in debt to Duke who had received a
$900,000 "loan" of Duke funds in September 1993 (after he had
received earlier substantial loans that remained unpaid), was
accompanied to the conference with me by two KMZ partners,
one of whom, during the conference, said he also served as
Dr. Atiga's lawyer.  Dr. Atiga stated that Duke would say
interchangeably she "wants to be tossed in the ocean" and
"wants my ashes tossed in the ocean."

       In contrast with the Lawson and Atiga somewhat
tentative approaches to suggesting Duke may have wished
cremation, in conference with Fay and Virginia Wright, Duke's
two spiritual advisors -- sisters so close to Duke that they
were among the very few permitted to visit Duke both at
Cedars-Sinai and at Falcon's Lair shortly prior to her death,
and persons whose religious mission received annual gifts as
well as a sizable bequest under the April 5, 1993 Will --
they stated that they had not discussed cremation or burial
arrangements at any time with Duke, although they personally
believed in cremation.

       There had been extensive Duke discussions with
William Zabel of Schulte Roth & Zabel that led to the
drafting and execution of Duke's November 4, 1991 Will.  Duke
never discussed cremation with Zabel, and I am informed that
had she his practice would have been to document this request
in writing.

       (4)  Awareness of the April 16, 1992 Codicil. --
The May 2, 1994 Doyle affidavit -- executed more than a year
after the facts to which it referred -- in describing Doyle's
March 1993 contacts with Duke that led to the two KMZ
Codicils and then the April 5, 1993 Will, states (at para. 4)
that at KMZ's first meeting with Duke, on March 4, 1993 at
Cedars-Sinai, Duke gave Doyle "copies of her then current
Will [that of November 1991] and Codicil [that of April 16,
1992]," and further states that "she wished to make some
minor changes."  Thereafter, this 1994 affidavit refers again
to the "existing Will and Codicil."  This May 1994 reference
both to Duke's and Doyle's purported awareness, in March-
April 1993, of the April 16, 1992 Codicil appears to conflict
with documents prepared by Doyle and his KMZ colleagues in
March and April 1993.

       The March 8, 1993 Codicil, the first Codicil
prepared by KMZ, makes no express reference to the April 16,
1992 Codicil (which had been prepared by a partner of Samuel
Greenspoon, Esq., who had long served as Duke's legal
advisor) ("the Greenspoon Codicil"), or to expressly revoking
that particular Codicil.  This first KMZ Codicil simply
states that it (the March 8, 1993 testamentary instrument) is
a Codicil to the November 4, 1991 Will, further providing
generally for the revocation of "any other Will made by me
and any codicil made to my Will."  A memorandum, under date
of March 9, 1993, dictated by Alan Croll and Doyle concerning
execution of the March 8, 1993 Codicil and events leading up
to it (Exhibit 46), makes no reference to the Greenspoon
Codicil.  (For security's sake, KMZ used the name "Mary
Newport" for Duke.)  The memorandum refers to Doyle's showing
Duke the provisions in the November 1991 Will (as if this was
all the first KMZ Codicil was changing).  It contrasts the
fees to be given Lafferty pursuant to the first KMZ Codicil
with those given Irwin Bloom under the November 4, 1991 Will,
failing to note any discussion of the much lesser fees given
to Walker Inman and Lafferty, named as executors pursuant to
the April 1992 Codicil, which it ignores.

       A partial summary (2 pages only) was begun by
Doyle, under date of March 15, 1993, which refers to the
execution on March 14, 1993 of the second KMZ Codicil.
(Exhibit 47).  This also makes no reference to the Greenspoon
Codicil, and it denominates the March 14, 1993 KMZ document
as "a Second Codicil," referring to the earlier KMZ
testamentary document as "my `First Codicil'" to the 1991
Will.

       Under date of April 4, 1993, Doyle wrote a
memorandum to Duke analyzing how the new Will would
incorporate the November 4, 1991 Will and the two KMZ
Codicils. (Exhibit 48).  Once again, no mention is made
reflecting any knowledge of the Greenspoon Codicil.  A chart
appended to that memorandum contrasts the compensation
Lafferty would receive under the new Will with that of Irwin
Bloom under the November 1991 Will, again failing to take any
note of the Greenspoon Codicil and its relatively minimal
compensation provisions for Messrs. Lafferty and Inman as
Executors and Trustees.

       Thereafter, under date of April 5, 1993, a Doyle
memorandum (Exhibit 49) concerning the execution of the
April 5, 1993 Will states (at the top of its second page)
that he explained to Duke that the new Will "simply
incorporated all the provisions of her current Will [that of
November 4, 1991] and the March 8, 1993 and March 14, 1993
Codicils [both KMZ documents] into a single document."  Once
again, no mention is made of the Greenspoon Codicil.  Also
omitted is the fact that under the April 5, 1993 Will -- as
considered hereinafter at E 5 -- the trustees' prospective
fees may be massive compared to the limited commissions to
Inman and Lafferty, for performing duties as trustees, under
the April 16, 1992 Greenspoon Codicil.

       This history strongly suggests that in March-April
1993 Doyle -- and quite likely Duke -- were unaware of, or
did not call to mind, the April 16, 1992 Greenspoon Codicil,
despite Doyle's contrary affidavit of more than a year later,
May 2, 1994.

       When questioned concerning the absence of any
reference in these March-April 1993 documents to the
Greenspoon Codicil -- contrasted with the references in
Doyle's May 1994 affidavit -- Doyle insisted that he had in
fact received an unexecuted copy of the Greenspoon Codicil
from Duke at the hospital on March 4, 1993, and that he was
fully aware of its content when he prepared the various
Codicils and memoranda above referred to, but that he was
uncertain whether it was a valid instrument.  Moreover, he
stated that as the first KMZ Codicil revoked the prior
Greenspoon Codicil, there was no need to refer to it
thereafter.  Moreover, Doyle stated that the $250,000 limit
on the fees to be paid to the individual executors (pursuant
to the Greenspoon Codicil) was "outrageous," that he
discussed this with Duke, and that she agreed.

       No further explanation was proffered for the fact
that the KMZ documents overall rewarded Lafferty as
Executor/Trustee far more handsomely than had the Greenspoon
Codicil rewarded Lafferty and Inman, and why KMZ contrasted
the Lafferty fees as provided in the March-April 1993 KMZ
documents with those of Bloom as provided in the November 4,
1991 Will which fees had been rendered nugatory by the
Greenspoon Codicil.

       (5)  Trustees' Statutory Compensation. -- As noted,
in memoranda reporting information given to Duke in March-
April 1993, Doyle stressed changes from the November 4, 1991
Will, not contrasting the new testamentary documents with the
April 16, 1992 Greenspoon Codicil.  Further, pursuant to the
Greenspoon Codicil the maximum compensation of each Lafferty
and Inman, as trustees, was fixed at $250,000.  The
November 4, 1991 Will had provided that the charitable
foundations to be created under that Will were to be "in the
form of corporations or trusts, or a combination thereof"
(Article 9, para. A), further providing that each director or
trustee of such foundation was to "receive reasonable
compensation" (Article 9, para. C).

       The April 5, 1993 KMZ Will allows trustees'
compensation, not limited to $250,000 (as in the Greenspoon
Codicil) and not specified to be "reasonable compensation"
(as in the Zabel November 4, 1991 Will).  Rather, it allows
trustees' of the Doris Duke Charitable Foundation, which it
creates as a trust (see Article 8), compensation in the
amount of one-half of the commissions provided by law.  As
SCPA 2309(5)(a) provides commissions of 6% annually, under
the April 5, 1993 Will the trustees would be entitled to 3%.
If the Doris Duke Charitable Foundation is -- as is
anticipated -- to be in the billion dollar range, and to earn
income of at least 5% or $50,000,000 annually, 3% of this
could be something well in seven figures; moreover, two
trustees' commissions, not simply one, are allowable under
the statute.  The April 5, 1993 Will allows Lafferty to
apportion these commissions among the five (or more)
trustees, at least three of whom Lafferty is to designate.
(Article Eleven, para. B(5)).

       This suggests that contrasting the trustees'
commissions under the April 5, 1993 Will with the "reasonable
compensation" of the "directors or trustees" under the
November 4, 1991 Will demonstrates that far more than a
"minor change" has been made by KMZ.  But, the Doyle May 2,
1994 affidavit (at para. 4) spoke of "minor changes."
Furthermore, the Doyle memorandum of April 5, 1993, at pages
2-3, describes Doyle's explanation to Duke of fees and
commissions pursuant to the April 5, 1993 Will; it does not
contrast them, however, with the "reasonable compensation"
provision under the November 4, 1991 Will or the very
stringent limitation under the Greenspoon Codicil.

       (6)  Non-Reported Cash Salaries. -- While Duke was
alive, and continuing into the present, the DBO has paid
salaries -- which now come to approximately $40,000 to each
annually -- in cash, to two Duke employees, Cupie and Digi
Singh.  Indeed, within the last year an additional employee
has been taken on (at Duke's New York City apartment) also
paid in cash, off the books.  The immigration status of all
three employees appears to be illegal.  Immigration counsel
have now been employed by the preliminary executors, through
KMZ, to regularize the status of these employees, but in the
meanwhile they continue to be paid in cash, off the books.

       Query: Regardless of Duke's having herself ignored
this Zo Baird problem, what is the propriety of fiduciaries,
particularly in an estate of this size, having continued for
about a year and a half to pay salaries in cash off the
books?  This avoided withholding taxes and Social Security
payments and any report on income on which the employees
would be required to pay income taxes.  Despite their
irregular immigration status, the Singhs (and the new
employee) could have been paid on the books, with appropriate
fringe benefits, including Social Security, tax deductions,
etc.  The Internal Revenue Code Sections 3102(a), 3301(a) and
3402(a), and Reg. Section 31.6051-2, require employers to withhold
taxes and file W-2s.  That this would have made a record of
the employees' illegal immigration status -- which is now (I
am informed) being dealt with through counsel -- does not
excuse an employer's failure to pay Social Security, to
withhold taxes and to report the employees' tax obligation.

F.   Concerning Possible Conflicts of Interest on
  the Part of Bernard Lafferty, U.S. Trust and
  Katten Muchin & Zavis (SCPA Section 702(8))     

       (1)  Bank's Loan to Its Designating Fiduciary. --
As noted (A 1), between November 26, 1993 (less than a month
after Duke's death) and early January 1995, U.S. Trust
extended unsecured loans to Lafferty totalling $825,000.
(Exhibits 50).  Although Lafferty's personal financial
statement, filed with the bank, had shown a complete absence
of assets, he had an immense expectancy if either the
April 5, 1993 Will were to be admitted to probate or were he
to be allowed a commission, as preliminary executor, for his
services.  He is also given income of $500,000 annually under
the April 5, 1993 Will. (The earlier November 4, 1991 Will
had provided him with an annuity of approximately $100,000
annually for life.)

       Article Eleven, paragraph A(4) of the April 5, 1993
Will provided Lafferty with "absolute discretion to remove
the corporate Executor at any time," and to appoint a
different bank or trust company in its place.

       Lafferty states that no one raised with him the
issue of a possible conflict of interest in his borrowing so
substantially from his co-fiduciary, U.S. Trust.

       U.S. Trust's agreement with Lafferty (who had
designated it) for the bank to serve as co-fiduciary, assures
the bank of fees and commissions of in excess of five million
dollars (Exhibit 51), if the proffered Will is admitted to
probate.  Doyle had made the suggestion to Duke to include
U.S. Trust in the Will, and had suggested transferring Duke
assets and accounts to U.S. Trust.  Doyle states he had not
previously met Marshall, but had had telephone discussions
with him concerning matters having nothing to do with
Duke.

       In extending the first portion of the Lafferty
loan, namely a loan of $300,000, high U.S. Trust personnel
questioned whether this loan, "on an unsecured basis to a co-
executor, with no financials of his own, with terms which
would be much more favorable than to a regular client," would
be a conflict of interest. (Exhibit 52).  Ranking bank
personnel disagreed, and an oral opinion from outside counsel
was sought which, I was informed, expressed the view that
this would not constitute a conflict. (Exhibit 53).  As the
amount lent grew -- with an additional $200,000 on April 13,
1994, a further $200,000 on September 16, 1994, an additional
$95,000 on January 8, 1995 and a final $30,000 on October 31,
or January 11, 1995 -- U.S. Trust appeared not to have
sought to enforce (prior to January 1995) any restraints on
Lafferty's continued spending.

       Jeffrey Maurer, President of U.S. Trust, who
apparently personally approved of the loans to Lafferty, is
unaware of any concrete controls placed on Lafferty's
spending.  While recognizing that the Lafferty loan was given
the bank's lowest grade, he stated that traveling and living
with Duke, Lafferty had "acquired certain tastes which
altered the lifestyle to which he previously had been
accustomed," and it is customary for the bank to lend money
to people to enable them to maintain lifestyles when, as
fiduciaries, they will be able to repay these lent funds.  In
Lafferty's case, Maurer is satisfied the loans were not
unreasonable when viewed in comparison with Lafferty's
expected fees.  U.S. Trust believes that, on a quantum meruit
basis, Lafferty had earned at least one-third of his
executor's commission, or $1.65 million.  This being so, the
loan totalling half of that amount -- mainly $825,000 -- the
bank believes is fully secured.

       Query: Does the conjuncture of these facts --
Lafferty's power of life or death over U.S. Trust with regard
to the Estate, the bank's fee expectancy in this matter of in
excess of $5,000,000 and the bank's acts of lending Lafferty
money from time to time, ultimately totalling $825,000 in
just over thirteen months -- put both Lafferty and U.S.
Trust, as fiduciaries, in conflicted positions?

       (2)  Double Dipping? -- Following Duke's death,
Lafferty has continued to live -- essentially expense free --
in Duke's homes, a somewhat unusual bonus for an estate's
fiduciary.  If the April 5, 1993 Will is admitted to probate
he will be entitled to a lifetime annuity, executor's
commissions and trustee's fees.  The DBO, advised by KMZ and
U.S. Trust, continues to pay Lafferty a salary of $100,000 a
year, the amount to which Duke had -- at the time of
consultations with KMZ attorneys in mid-1993 -- raised his
compensation as her Executive Assistant.  Recognizing that
ultimately this payment might be found to be vulnerable, it
is being continued with the understanding that upon an
accounting by the fiduciaries, it would be repaid were the
Surrogate to so require.

       (3)  Bank's Reporting a Duke-Lafferty Death-bed
Gift. -- The United States Gift Tax Return for Calendar Year
1993, Form 709, prepared and executed by U.S. Trust -- apart
from the Glassman and charitable gifts already considered
(item E-1, supra) -- reflects a $56,582.92 gift to Lafferty
under date of October 27, 1993, the day before Duke's death.
(Exhibit 36).  I am informed that this is the amount of
Lafferty's personal credit card charges incurred before
Duke's death that had remained unpaid at the time of her
death.  As Duke had, apparently, paid Lafferty's personal
credit card charges while she was alive and functioning --
his charges, apparently, having, until her last weeks, been
quite chary -- (and I am informed had done the same for
Heffner during their active relationship), U.S. Trust
determined to record this open item as a Duke gift, and it
was paid by the DBO.  (I failed to inquire, and was not
informed, how this past Duke generosity had been handled, or
reported, tax-wise.)

       (4)  Complete Control Over Duke Assets. -- Between
March and June of 1993, KMZ prepared and supervised Duke's
execution of at least two dozen documents (Exhibit 45) at a
time during and immediately following her hospitalization at
Cedars-Sinai, when she was in an at least questionable mental
state (item H-2, infra).  Several of these documents,
including the March 8, 1993 Codicil, were executed only four
days after KMZ's initial contact with Duke.  The documents
prepared by KMZ during this period include Powers of Attorney
exercisable in California and in New Jersey (Exhibit 41),
Durable Powers of Attorneys for Health Care and other health
care proxies (Exhibits 18 and 54), and instructions
(unsigned) to all Duke managers to take direction from
Lafferty (Exhibit 55).  The totality of these documents
delegated to Lafferty essentially unfettered control over
Duke's assets, homes, staff and medical treatment during her
life and, ultimately, over her remains and her Estate.

       The broad control granted to Lafferty contrasts
with the more limited powers enjoyed by designees pursuant to
Duke's prior instruments, instruments prepared by her
previous attorneys each of whom had enjoyed a more extensive
relationship with Duke than had KMZ in the early Spring of
1993.  For example, Duke had had numerous meetings and
correspondence with William Zabel, Esq., concerning her
estate planning since July 1991, culminating in the execution
of her November 4, 1991 Will.  Yet she explicitly instructed
him not to release the Powers of Attorney she had executed on
November 4, 1991 in favor of Irwin Bloom, her long-time
accountant. (Exhibit 56).  Similarly, the Durable Medical
Powers of Attorney in favor of Lafferty prepared by Susan
Walker, Esq. -- who had then represented Duke for over a year
-- were not exercisable unless Duke could not communicate her
desires, or was mentally incapacitated. (Exhibit 19).
Indeed, the April 6, 1992 Power required Lafferty to consult
with Dr. Atiga "in all matters pertinent to [Duke's] medical
care, including [her] mental competency and judgment," the
January 19, 1993 Power similarly requiring Lafferty to
consult with both Drs. Atiga and Kivowitz.  No such
restrictions were placed on Lafferty's ability to immediately
exercise the powers granted under the instruments prepared by
KMZ.

       The breadth of the powers given Lafferty under
these documents -- particularly when contrasted with earlier,
far more limited delegations -- suggest that KMZ, which was
to receive sizable legal fees, used its position (and
possibly Duke's illnesses) to utilize that massive power that
it had, through Duke, placed under the control of Lafferty.
Given Lafferty's dependence on persons -- including KMZ's
Doyle and others -- more sophisticated than he, KMZ thus
effectively delegated to itself much control over Duke's
affairs.

G.   Concerning Possible Failures by the Fiduciaries,
  Bernard Lafferty and U.S. Trust, and their Counsel,
  Katten Muchin & Zavis, to Bring Appropriate
  Proceedings (SCPA Section 702(9))                     

       (1)  Reclaiming Gifts. -- As noted, the 1993 U.S.
Gift Tax Return (Form 709) reflects a gift to Dr. Glassman,
on October 4, 1993, of $500,000. (Exhibit 36).  The Form 706
reflects a "loan" of $900,000 to Dr. Atiga, dated
September 10, 1993, which loan (history shows) has virtually
no likelihood of repayment.  Form 709 also reflects
charitable gifts: on October 3, 1993 of $1,000,000 to the
Elizabeth Taylor AIDS Foundation, on October 5, 1993 of
$10,724,000 to the Doris Duke Foundation (a foundation
created by Duke during her life), on October 5, 1993 of
$1,000,000 to People for Ethical Treatment of Animals, and on
October 5, 1993 of $2,000,000 to Duke University.

       These gifts were made, as noted, at a time when
Duke's own ability to consciously and intentionally authorize
them was at least dubious. (Item E-1, supra).  I have seen no
documentation demonstrating Duke's knowledgeable
authorization of these gifts.  And, as Reed's notes and
recollection reflect, his instructions in each instance as
the maker of each of the checks were from Doyle and Lafferty,
not from Duke.  As the residuary beneficiary of the Estate is
a new foundation, the Doris Duke Charitable Foundation, if
these death-bed gifts were not properly authorized, possibly
the preliminary executors should have instituted proceedings
to recover these amounts.

       (I recognize that it is unrealistic to have
expected the preliminary executors to have brought such
actions, but SCPA Section 702(8) and (9) provide a mechanism for
such suits.)

H.   Considering Whether Bernard Lafferty, U.S. Trust and
  Katten Muchin & Zavis May Be Otherwise Unfit for the
  Execution of their Office (SCPA Section 707(1)(e), 711(8);
  SCPA Section 702(10))                                   

       Questions of undue influence and lack of
testamentary capacity are issues to be explored if and when
formal objections are filed to the probate of the April 5,
1993 Will.  However, at the January 20, 1995 conference at
which I was designated, and at conferences thereafter
attended by all counsel, Your Honor noted not only that you
had not intended to restrict my authority, but when specific
inquiry was made (on January 20, 1995) as to my role in
inquiring concerning the so-called "murder allegations,"
according to a Lee Ann Watson memorandum, "Preminger noted
that although it may be out of her province to prosecute a
murder allegation to the extent there is any evidence of a
murder that might be `euphemistically speaking, proof of
undue influence'" (January 21, 1995, Watson memorandum,
appended to her March 13, 1995 Affidavit).

       Therefore, in terms of reporting whether Lafferty,
U.S. Trust or KMZ might be "otherwise unfit for the execution
of the office" that they are now (in preliminary fashion)
filling, some fact report of what I learned -- in the course
of my broader inquiry -- concerning Duke's death, and
concerning the execution of the April 5, 1993 Will, seems
appropriate.

       (1)  Duke's Death. -- With the Court's permission
to employ such investigators or others as I deemed necessary,
I retained the services of Dr. Nicholas T. Macris, whose
report of April 11, 1995 and curriculum vitae, are appended
hereto. (Exhibit 2).  As that report notes, I supplied
Dr. Macris with all the medical information, including
hospital records and nurses' notes, that I obtained through
KMZ; I informed Dr. Macris of the nature of my assignment and
my lack of any preconception, and requested that he
objectively evaluate the information with which I supplied
him, and that he prepare a written report reflecting his
analysis.  He has done so.  The report speaks for itself.

       Although Dr. Macris notes that by September-October
1993 it was clear that Duke's illness was terminal, he
further notes that Dr. Kivowitz' actions in "increasing the
morphine to a dosage level" was such that it would "stop Ms.
Duke's breathing and cause her death."  Further, he states
that the cause of death as reflected in the death certificate
executed by Dr. Trabulus remains unsupported by the medical
documentation.

       On October 25, 1993, following a meeting between
Lafferty and Dr. Kivowitz, Dr. Kivowitz told Duke's
respiratory therapist -- who was then in the midst of
administering treatment -- to stop treatment, explaining that
Duke had a urinary tract infection (apparently not uncommon
among seriously ill elderly persons), and that further
respiratory treatments would be discontinued.

       Colm Kennedy, who was in charge of Duke's
private 737 airplane, made a diary entry on October 25, 1993
that Lafferty called and asked if the plane would be ready,
although Duke was then bedridden, heavily sedated and being
administered hospice care.

       Duke's death was clearly anticipated by Wednesday
evening October 27, 1993.  On that day, as reflected in a
note in Pierce Brothers' (mortuary) file, Dr. Glassman had
contacted the mortuary (Exhibit 58).  And the afternoon
nurses (3:00 p.m. to 11:00 p.m.), I am told, had been asked
by Dr. Kivowitz to be prepared to stay on, and were told to
cancel the night nurses, who ordinarily came on duty at
Falcon's Lair form 11:00 p.m. to 7:00 a.m.  Moreover, in his
deposition transcript, at page 911 (Exhibit 59), Dr. Kivowitz
stated:

       I increased the morphine so that she would not
       linger, that she would not suffer, and
       ultimately that she would die perhaps shortly
       or sooner than she would have otherwise died
       from her medical conditions, which I judged
       within a 48-hour period were of a terminal
       nature.

       Reviewing the nurses' notes from October 23 through
October 28, 1993, nurse Rosenstein could find no indication
that Duke was in any pain, was agitated or restless.  She had
no explanation of why Duke had been given morphine or why the
morphine dosage was increased (Exhibit 60), and why there was
a morphine push (Exhibit 61).  At the time Duke had a bad
heart and poor respiration; the increased morphine dosages
would -- and did -- decrease respiration.  Duke expired, as
noted, at 5:48 a.m. on Thursday, October 28, 1993.

       Following Duke's death, KMZ personnel and Lafferty
flew east over the weekend of October 30-31, 1993, finalized
and executed necessary documentation, and filed the Petition
for Probate in this Court on Monday morning, November 1,
1993.  Had Duke not expired when she did, the advantage of
the intervening weekend -- and the time it afforded to
complete all documentation -- might have been lost, and with
it possibly the ability for a Monday morning filing before
Heffner could interfere.

       (2)  Duke's Mental Clarity. -- In considering undue
influence or possible lack of testamentary capacity in March-
April 1993, I respectfully refer the Court to the April 11,
1995 report of Dr. Macris (Exhibit 2), which states that the
medications that Duke was taking at Cedars-Sinai from the
date of her admission in February 1993 through and subsequent
to the execution of the April 5, 1993 Will, were such that
they "may effect mental acuity," as could her "ongoing
chronic illness."  I also refer to the report, received by me
under date of February 24, 1995, from Dr. Steven E. Hyman,
Professor at the Harvard Medical School, which is appended
along with his covering letter and his curriculum vitae.
(Exhibit 4).  (In this connection, I note that initially Dr.
Hyman had been retained by Alan Fuchsberg, Esq. and Marie
Lambert, Esq., then counsel for Irwin Bloom.  Without
denigrating Dr. Hyman, I further note that, unlike
Dr. Macris, he did not initially come into this matter as a
neutral expert.  A preliminary report of Dr. Hyman was among
the documents, submitted on behalf of Irwin Bloom, which I
received soon after my designation.  I contacted Dr. Hyman
who informed me that his report had been updated and, at no
fee, he was kind enough to send me a copy of the updated
report.)

       As noted in the execution memorandum concerning the
March 8, 1993 Codicil (Exhibit 46), Doyle stated that Duke --
in the presence of the codicil's witnesses -- did nothing
other than nod her head and/or say "yes" to questions posed.
Although he thought it desirable to bring in Susan Walker,
Esq., from Hawaii, and other witnesses who knew Duke, he did
not see the need to encourage some conversation on her part,
in the presence of the witnesses, to demonstrate fully her
alertness and awareness.

       Nurse Rosenstein first met Duke in April 1992 after
Duke broke her hip.  From Duke's Cedars-Sinai hospitalization
in late February 1993, through Duke's death on October 28,
1993, nurse Rosenstein continuously served the afternoon
shift, without days off.  She states that in the Spring of
1993, although Duke was in poor medical condition,
malnourished, anemic, dehydrated, fragile and weak (unable to
turn in bed by herself or walk), she was alert and oriented,
and that she was also alert and mentally capable of doing
business at Duke Farms, New Jersey, in June 1993.

       Nurse Rose Mary Souza worked for Duke for several
months after Duke's discharge from Cedars-Sinai in April
1993.  She noted that, even that early, Duke suffered
intermittent bouts of confusion.  At times this confusion
would persist, at other times, it was short-lived.

       In June 1993, Duke met at Falcon's Lair with
personnel of Chemical Bank who had requested the meeting to
discuss that bank's having been, essentially, discharged,
U.S. Trust being substituted for it on most of Duke's funds
and assets.  It is undisputed that Nuku and other domestics
dressed Duke for that meeting, physically carried her
upstairs from her bedroom to the living room, and essentially
during the meeting -- which lasted no more than fifteen
minutes and was attended by Lafferty, Doyle and Chemical Bank
personnel -- Duke said nothing other than "yes" and "no" and,
at one point "corroborated."  Bank personnel, who did not
draw her into conversation, stated that she appeared to be
normal.

       I have been in contact with Susan P. Walker, Esq.,
who had done some legal work in Hawaii for Duke.  Walker made
available to me three file memoranda, two of March 19, 1992
and one of April 3, 1992 (Exhibit 62), as well as other
consistent documents.  These documents clearly reflect
directions that Ms. Walker told me she had received orally
from Duke on March 17, 1992: to prepare a new testamentary
instrument in which Lafferty was to be named executor and
trustee of the various Duke trusts.  Walker further stated
that although these instructions were unequivocal, she
informed Duke that her firm was not highly sophisticated in
the trusts and estates area and recommended that Duke employ
such attorneys.  Ultimately Walker did not prepare a
testamentary document that was executed.

       It is virtually undisputed, premised on the
statements of persons with knowledge whom I interviewed, that
as of 1993 the Duke-Lafferty relationship appeared to be a
loving one on the part of both, akin to a tender and devoted
mother-son relationship.

Miscellaneous Observations

       Since my designation on January 20, 1995, I have
read through a number of linear feet of documents, including
testamentary documents, litigation papers, medical reports
(including nurses' notes), memoranda and correspondence.  I
have also conducted face-to-face interviews with more than
fifty persons, both in the New York area (including New
Jersey) and the Los Angeles area, such persons essentially
being those who dealt with Duke toward the end of her life,
as well as attorneys both for the preliminary executors and
for those who may seek to contest admission to probate of the
April 5, 1993 Will, or who have some other professional
interest in this Estate.  Further, I have interviewed an
additional half dozen less critical persons by telephone.

       I must express my disappointment that my efforts,
through their counsel, to arrange face-to-face interviews
with Drs. Kivowitz and Glassman, either in Los Angeles or New
York, have proven unsuccessful.  KMZ personnel, acting for
the preliminary executors in refusing to waive
confidentiality agreements, blocked me from access to either
Chandi Heffner or her attorneys, and from two former
security persons at Duke Farms (Peter Wilczek and Frank
Senerchio), each of whom I was led to believe may have had
pertinent information.  A few relatively minor players were
also unavailable.

       The interviews I conducted were informal, not under
oath, and -- for the most part -- the persons interviewed
were not accompanied by counsel.  Personnel of the
preliminary executors and of the DBO and other Duke employees
were accompanied by KMZ counsel, and several of them by other
counsel as well, also employed by the preliminary executors.
Of Duke's three nurses whom I interviewed, counsel for two
were retained by the Estate; counsel for the third was
retained by Dr. Harry Demopoulos.  Lawson and Dr. Atiga, as
noted, were interviewed in the presence of KMZ attorneys,
with Lawson also having her own attorney present.  Walker
Inman and Dr. Demopoulos each were attended by their own
attorneys.

       Although I make no apologies for this Report, I
note that the time pressures of conducting the interviews,
absorbing all the information that I have learned, and
writing the Report have been considerable.  While I hope that
I have not missed critical information, this Report might
have been more complete had time permitted visits to the two
Duke homes I did not visit, Rough Point (Newport, Rhode
Island) and Shangri-La (Honolulu, Hawaii), and had there been
interviews there with further Duke employees and Duke
friends.  Still other persons in the New York and Los Angeles
areas, too, might have been interviewed.

       The Court has honored me through this designation
as limited temporary administrator, and I deeply appreciate
the Surrogate's confidence inherent in that appointment.


Dated: April 20, 1995              Respectfully submitted,

                               ________________________
                                    RICHARD H. KUH

</PRE>
