<HEAD>
<TITLE>Court TV Library</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A HREF="/map/library.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/library.gif" ISMAP ALT="Court TV Library" BORDER="0"></A>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<P>The following is the full text of a letter by John Grisham's attorney responding to attorney Patricia Douglass's claim letter concerning the alleged misappropriation by Grisham of a book by author Polly Nelson.</P>
<HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT>
<PRE>
Doubleday

Katherine J. Trager Vice President Deputy General Counsel

January 17, 1995 VIA FACSIMILE and AIRBORNE EXPRESS

Patricia D. Douglas, Esq. 1029 31st Street N.W. Washington, D.C. 20007

Re: Claim by Polly Nelson

Dear Ms. Douglas:

Your letter of December 30 has been referred to me for response and I
have reviewed it with John Grisham. While I understand you have
undertaken a very careful analysis of both your client's nonfiction
work, Defending the Devil: My Story as Ted Bundy's Last Lawyer (the
"Devil") and The Chamber by Mr. Grisham ("The Chamber"), there is no
factual or legal basis for the claims asserted in your letter.

First and most importantly, Mr. Grisham has never read the Devil.
Indeed, it would have been impossible for him to have read it before
writing The Chamber. The Devil was published on July 21, 1994. The
Chamber was on sale on May 25, 1994. Copies of The Chamber were in
production even earlier. Obviously, Mr. Grisham could not have copied
from a book which was not published until well after his book was
completed and on sale. At the end of your lengthy claim letter, you
appear to assert that Doubleday had an eighty page version of the
Devil and that "editors" met with Ms. Nelson and her agent at
Doubleday's offices on October 15, 1990. No one here at Doubleday
recalls such a meeting or proposal; if you wish, I will look into this
further, provided you can identify the editor and agent involved,
inform me as to whether or not the eighty page proposal was retained
at Doubleday or returned to your client and provide the proposal with
proof that it was written in 1990. In any event, there is not a shred
of evidence to support a claim that somehow Mr. Grisham obtained this
eighty page proposal and used this as the basis for The Chamber. Nor,
of course, does it in any way support the other forty pages of your
claim in which you cite alleged similarities between The Chamber and
the Devil. Thus, a claim based on the proposal could only be asserted
if you could establish that (i) Mr. Grisham had access to the proposal
and (ii) that there are substantial similarities of copyrightable
material between the proposal and The Chamber.

We, of course, have not seen the proposal and your letter does not
say, nor could it say, that the similarities you identify are all
present in the proposal as well as the finished version of the Devil.
Even aside from the logical problem with your claim, the comparisons
you identify between he Devil and The Chamber are not actionable under
basic fundamentals of copyright law.

First, facts and ideas within a work are not protected by copyright.
Harper & Row Publishers v. Nation Enterprises, 471 U.S. 539, 54748
(1985); Gardner v. Nizer, 391 F.Supp. 940 (S.D.N.Y. 1975). The Devil
is a work of nonfiction. As described in the claim letter, it recounts
facts concerning the author's life and her experiences in representing
Ted Bundy. The fact that the author was a young lawyer when she took
the case, a graduate from a midwestern law school, that she went to
work for a major law firm, that she came from a poor background, etc.,
are all unprotectable facts. Anyone could write about those facts,
and, contrary to the assertion contained on page 1 of your letter, it
is perfectly permissible for someone to sit down and write a biography
of Polly Nelson and a description of the efforts she made to defend
Ted Bundy, using her book as its only source. See e.g. Walker v. Time
Life Films, Inc.. 784 F.2d 44 (2d Cir. 1986) affirming 615 F. Supp.
430 (S.D.N.Y. 1985), cert. denied, 476 U.S. 1159 (1986), Hoehling v.
Universal City Studios, Inc., 618 F.2d 972 (2d Cir. 1980); Miller v.
Universal City Studios, Inc. 650 F.2d 1365 (5th Cir. 1981). Even if
your client's work were fictional, the claim asserted here would still
fail. It is well established that scenes a faire, ("sequences of
events which necessarily follow from a common theme,") are not
protectable. Reyher v. Children's Television Workshop, 533 F.2d 87, 91
(2d Cir.), cert. denied, 429 U.S. 980 (1976); Walker v. Time Life
Films. Inc,. supra 784 F.2d, at 48 (incidents, characters, or settings
that are indispensable or standard in the treatment of a given topic
are not copyrightable.) The many alleged similarities you cite are
common to lawyers and death penalty cases.

Without addressing all of these alleged similarities, it is sufficient
to just note a few, which establish that there is no basis for any
claim of copyright infringement here:

Both books involve young lawyers. Many young lawyers do pro-bono work
and many death penalty cases are done on a pro-bono basis. Frequently
the young lawyers who do these cases are employed by large law firms,
because those are the firms that can afford to have a lawyer spend the
unbillable hours involved in a pro-bono death penalty case.

Major law firms try to hire the best and the brightest law students
they can find. Therefore, it commonly follows that young lawyers
handling death penalty cases at major law firms would also tend to be
among the brighter students and members of law review. It is, of
course, well known that law review members often do get offers from
many law firms.

We can go on and on here. Many lawyers who do pro-bono work do
complain that others in the firm are not sympathetic to their work.
Often, the partner who is supervising an associate is cold and distant
and puts pressure on the young associate. These general similarities,
of course, apply to law firm practice in general and cannot possibly
be considered as protectable material of the plaintiff.

The comments concerning the other characters' similarities are
similarly generic and to the extent there is any resemblance between
such characters, it is a necessary consequence of the fact that such
characters and situations arise in death penalty cases and stories
about death penalty cases. It is well known, for example, that many
judges are impatient with the appeals made on behalf of death penalty
inmates. It is well known that some judges revel in press attention,
that law clerks let it be known that they do not appreciate
defendants' motions, and that death penalty counsel, like other
lawyers, do tell "war stories" to each other.

You make the somewhat disjointed infringement claim that Mr. Grisham's
fictional characters are composites of real people portrayed in your
client's book. For example, it is asserted that Hez Kerry "has his
genesis" in three real people, Mike Mellow, Mark Olive, and Jeff
Robinson. Even if it were true that Mr. Grisham based his character on
these three living people, there could hardly be any claim of
"copying" based upon a fictional character who coincidentally has one
or two characteristics which are common to each of three different
people.

The common developments in the "plot" of the Devil and The Chamber
also do not support any claim. Again, your client does not have any
protectable interest in facts and none of the facts concerning her
representation of Ted Bundy is protectable. Moreover, any similarity
in events in the Devil and The Chamber are common to many death
penalty cases. It is well known that death penalty cases receive lurid
press coverage; that lawyers become exhausted and resentful of the
extraordinary pace of the criminal justice system; that lawyers who
represent convicted murderers do have doubts about what they're doing;
that young lawyers do enjoy the luxury of a car paid for by the firm
and that lawyers do need to sometimes get up and leave their desks
when they are nervously awaiting a decision. Also, it is true that
news people do gather at executions without embarrassment and that
often, as a threatened execution approaches, inmates do make
confessions, and do exhibit vulnerability.

Aside from the similarities in "plot," you also make much of the
allegedly similar descriptions and word usages. But, the similarities
are so general, and involve such commonplace examples, that any claim
of copying must fall. That both characters stare at blank computer
screens; that a breeze chases away humidity, that the words
"typically" and "interminable" appear in both books, is of absolutely
no consequence. I could continue. I have examined the similarities
alleged in your tables. Again, such similarities, to the extent that
they even are similarities, must be coincidental; and even if they
were not, they simply do not support a claim of copyright infringement
because they are not substantially similar: see e.g. Narell v.
Freeman, 872 F.2d at 907, 16 Media Law Reporter 1579 (9th Cir. 1989);
Hoehling, 618 F.2d at 979 (random duplications of phrases not
infringement). (See, for example, this comparison from "Table K": The
Chamber, p. 433: "With his black hair, black beard, black glasses, and
black suit, [Dr. Swinn] indeed gave the appearance of an ominously
brilliant master of his field." The Devil, p. 208: "[O]nce on the
stand, Dr. Dorothy Lewis was brilliant- clear, convincing, articulate.
Resplendent in a deep purple suit, she illuminated the courtroom" Or,
because, again, they are so common: such as the claim in Table I that
both prisons had signs which identified them as respectively,
"Mississippi State Penitentiary" and "Florida State Prison."

Obviously, I could show that the foregoing is applicable to all the
claimed "infringements." But I believe this is sufficient to apprise
you of the facts that: 1) Mr. Grisham could not possibly have copied
your client's book because his book was finished and published long
before your client's was published; 2) to the extent that the claims
are based on facts in your client's book, such facts are not
protectable as a matter of law and 3) even if your client's work was
fictional, the alleged similarities between the two works either do
not exist or are so commonplace that they are not subject to copyright
protection.

I hope that you and your client will carefully analyze this response
before you take any further action in this matter. If this is pursued,
in view of the impossibility of the claim and its legal deficiencies,
I must advise you that Mr. Grisham and Doubleday will vigorously
defend the suit and will, of course, file a motion for attorney's fees
under 17 U.S.C. 505 and also under Rule 11 of the Federal Rules of
Civil Procedure. Since your client is a lawyer, she should be aware of
these provisions, particularly the sanctions under Rule 11 against a
party who files a pleading that is frivolous.

In conclusion, I must also remind you and your client that Mr. Grisham
is a lawyer who has tried many cases, both criminal and civil. As
demonstrated by his books, Mr. Grisham has a sophisticated and broad
knowledge of the law, the judicial system, lawyers and law firms. As
stated in the Acknowledgments section of The Chamber, Mr. Grisham
spent many hours with lawyers involved on both sides of death penalty
cases and with prison personnel. Together with his creative mind, they
are the sources for The Chamber. This best-selling author hardly
needed to rely on your client's four-year old proposal to write a book
about the death penalty.

Very truly yours,

Katherine J. Trager
</PRE>
