<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Court TV Library</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A HREF="/map/library.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/library.gif" ISMAP ALT="Court TV Library" BORDER="0"></A>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<P>The following is the full text of the letter from Patricia Douglass, the lawyer representing an author who claims John Grisham misappropriated her book in writing The Chamber, to Grisham and his publisher.</P>
<HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT>
<PRE>
PATRICIA D. DOUGLASS
ATTORNEY AT LAW
1029 31ST STREET N.W.
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20007
(202) 965-3300
FAX (202) 337-0454

December 30, 1994

Bantam, Doubleday, Dell
        Publishing Group, Inc.
1540 Broadway
New York, New York 10036
        ATTN: General Counsel

Mr. John Grisham
c/o Bantam, Doubleday, Dell
        Publishing Group, Inc.
1540 Broadway
New York, New York 10036

Re: The Chamber/Defending the Devil

Dear Sirs:

        I have been retained by Polly Nelson to prosecute
a claim for infringement of copyright and related claims
arising from publication of Mr. Grisham's novel The Chamber.
In The Chamber, Mr. Grisham has unlawfully appropriated the plot,
characters, descriptions, and personal introspection found in Ms.
Nelson's non-fiction book Defending the Devil: My Story as Ted
Bundy's Last Lawyer (Morrow, 1994; the "Devil"). By so doing,
Mr. Grisham has also wrongfully appropriated Ms. Nelson's
life story, which she was privileged to market for her
economic benefit.

It is immediately obvious on reading the two works that each
tells exactly the same story--the tale of a new lawyer in an
establishment law firm who, to meet her or his own personal
needs, volunteers to take on the representation of the
most notorious killer on death row. The inmate faces execution
within a few weeks. The young lawyer immediately becomes heavily
invested in the case, and struggles against the legal system
determined that the condemned inmate should die at the
scheduled hour. She and he must also contend with state politics;
the
politics of her/his law firm; a restless, marginally cooperative
client unwilling or unable to inspire a sympathetic response;
and relentless press efforts to sensationalize the story.
In the end, the client is executed, the politicians rejoice, and
the shattered lawyer immediately leaves the firm.

Below we set out at some length our preliminary analysis of some
of the striking similarities between the two books. As
attachments we include a side-by-side comparison of a number of
very similar passages. We have cited to specific page numbers of
each book to facilitate your review of our conclusions, except
when the bases for our observations are obvious. We have shared
our analysis in this depth in the hope that you will devote the
serious attention to our claim that will permit it to be
resolved short of litigation. Careful study of the points we
raise, which are certainly not all of those we would expect to
raise at trial, can lead to no other conclusion than that Mr.
Grisham in fact based his work on Ms. Nelson's book, blatantly
appropriating both grand themes and small details, and that his
attempts to disguise this appropriation will be readily exposed.

CHARACTERS

Most of the characters appearing in The Chamber, major and minor,
have direct counterparts in the Devil. In many other cases,
either traits of one character in the Devil are split between
two characters in The Chamber, or one character in The Chamber
takes on traits of two or more characters in the Devil. Several
examples follow:

The Young Lawyer Protagonist. In The Chamber, Adam Hall is a
newly graduated lawyer, the editor of his Midwestern law
school's law review, who has been working for nine months at a
prosperous, business-oriented, metropolitan law firm. In the
Devil,
Polly Nelson is a newly graduated lawyer, the editor of her
Midwestern law school's law review, who has been working for
three months at a prosperous, business-oriented, metropolitan
law firm. Each protagonist earns a healthy professional salary
but chooses, from inertia or emotional vacuum, to live in
surroundings unequal to her/his status in life (a converted
warehouse/skin care salon), too paralyzed by the demands of
their work at the high-pressure law firm to look for a new place
to live. FN 1 Neither has a sex life, or any personal life at
all. Both
plan to work at the law firm for only a couple of years and then
move on to do what they really want to do. FN 2
Both take on--as the first case for which they take primary
responsibility--the cause of defending an inmate sentenced to
death in a Southern state.

Each is simultaneously naive and dedicated. Both come from modest
backgrounds and are openly awed at the travel and fringe
benefits provided by their law firms. FN 3 Both grew up feeling
overly responsible, due to dependent and "unhappy" parents; both
were "born" to represent this particular inmate. FN 4 Each
confesses to being excited/intoxicated by the life-and death
nature of the case. FN 5 Neither can believe that her/his law
firm is not wholly supportive of all necessary efforts to halt
the execution. FN 6

Both young lawyers struggle to regard their clients with sympathy
and to avoid thinking about the crimes for which they face
execution. Despite these efforts, Adam and Polly cannot help but
feel empathy for the ethnic/gender group
the inmate targeted for murder, both suffer intermittent bouts of
internal rage directed at the inmate and wonder if they should
be representing him. FN 7 Neither feels he/she can give up on
the case. Both fight through a haze of exhaustion to save
the inmate's life, and both lose. Neither attends the execution.
Both become disillusioned about the law; the relationship
between each and his/her law firm deteriorates badly. Both
unhappily leave their firms promptly after the execution. FN 8

Both Adam and Polly feel a moral calling--even a compulsion--to
represent the condemned inmate, a calling they only
superficially understand at the outset, a calling that appears,
at least at first, to conflict with their best interests. FN 9
The gradual illumination of this calling provides a plot running
parallel to the prisoner's steady march towards execution.
Polly has other dimensions, however, that Mr. Grisham has
displaced onto the character of Lee Cayhall Booth. Both Lee and
Pol-lee are alcoholics who are at risk of relapse under the
emotional burden of the pending execution. FN 10 Both are also
compulsive social workers, seeking gratification from the belief
that others need them. FN 11

The Prosperous Law Firm Employing the Protagonist. Kravitz & Bane
and Wilmer
Cutler & Pickering both advertise a commitment to pro bono work,
which is one reason the protagonists, with many offers to choose
from, landed at those firms. FN 12 It turns out that this
commitment is sorely tested when the pro bono case taken on by
a young associate becomes an all-consuming, very expensive,
very public crusade to halt the execution of the nation's most
despised villain. FN 13 Most partners at the firm are late in
learning that the firm in fact has taken on this notorious case;
when they learn of it, they see it as an unpalatable burden
about which nothing can be done. FN 14 In both firms, those
partners who direct associates in pro bono projects apparently
have limited ability or desire to protect them from the
resentment and retaliation of other, less generous partners. FN 15
For example, Daniel Rosen plays the same role in The Chamber as
do the insurance partner who is angry at Polly for neglecting his
work and the
unnamed managing partner who ultimately fires her. FN 16 All
three of these partners come to believe that the protagonist has
come to the firm only to exploit its support for pro bono work.
FN 17
Both firms reluctantly expend grand sums (in excess of $2 million
in The Chamber and $1.5 million in the Devil) on this one case.
FN 18

The Partner Supervising the Protagonist. Each protagonist is
nominally supervised and supported by a partner with pro bono
and death penalty experience. Both Garner Goodman and Jim
Coleman are cool, wise and dependable, managing to stay aloof
and detached from the emotional fray attendant on an impending
execution. Each also seems to stand somewhat apart from his
partners at the firm, limiting his practice to pro bono matters,
or at least supervising more such cases than other partners. FN 19
Each stays in the background of the inmate's case as much as
possible and actively participates only as an execution date
draws near. FN 20 Neither takes the pressure off the young
protagonist to
any significant extent, and spends time being chummy with the
death penalty community. FN 21 This partner and the young lawyer
have a formal, distant, respectful relationship, free of
disagreements but also free of any real emotional connection.
FN 22

The Condemned Inmate. Both Sam and Ted are the most famous and
notorious inmates on death row, the perpetrators of several
unmitigated and grisly murders, convicted after more than one
well-publicized trial. Both have murdered multiple, innocent
victims. Neither is expected to escape execution.

Each inmate has represented himself and fired his lawyers. Each
has and has had great difficulty ceding control of his case to
his counsel. Each is clever enough to write long, overblown
legal papers and condescendingly quizzes his lawyers by throwing
out the names of precedent-setting death penalty cases. FN 23
Although both Sam and Ted know that their new lawyers are
inexperienced, they also know that they were very successful law
students and come with the backing and resources of a
prestigious,
large law firm. FN 24 Both young lawyers conclude that the
inmate is in fact not as clever as he thinks he is and that, on
the contrary, each inmate has been and remains potentially a
danger to his own cause. FN 25 In both cases the lawyer presses
an incompetency claim that the inmate thinks is nonsense. FN 26

In the midst of the countdown toward execution, each inmate is
stubborn about minor details of prison procedures and is adamant
about his exercise privileges. FN 27 For example, on a rare
excursion off death row, each, although facing imminent execution,
is angry and obsessed about the comfort/safety conditions
in the van in which he is riding. FN 28

Each inmate is largely ignored by family and friends. FN 29 Each
goes into a ``trance'' when the lawyer asks the hard questions
about his crimes. FN 30
Toward the end, each inmate plans to make a complete confession,
but warns that it will take a long time because there is so much
to confess and it is so deeply buried. FN 31 Each ultimately
admits there were additional victims, previously unknown.
FN 32 Each urges the lawyer to believe he is not the sort of
person to hurt anyone. FN 33 It is difficult, despite twinges of
sympathy, not to conclude that both Ted and Sam are profoundly
evil men.

Sam and Ted, although of different generations, are described in
remarkably similar physical terms, as seen in Table A, attached.

The Judges. Both Adam and Polly are resigned to the fact that the
state courts will reject any claims they might bring. Both
naively place their faith in the federal district courts, and
are severely disappointed. FN 34 District Court Judge Slattery/
Zloch is a recent Reagan appointee who is facing his first death
case. FN 35 Judge Slattery/Sharp works all hours to prepare for
the case, impatiently calling the lawyers to demand filings in
advance. FN 36 He denies all claims, taking care to avoid
grounds for reversal by a pro forma review of the record. FN 37

The judges/their law clerks informally make known their
displeasure with defense claims, even in advance of their
filing. FN 38 The judges revel in press attention, FN 39 and seem
to be cozy
with the prosecutors in a manner that does not signal success
for the inmate's case. FN 40 The judges set hearings with so
little notice that the lawyers must rush across the state to get
to a suddenly scheduled hearing. FN 41 Yet the judges also feel
free to protect their leisure activities from interference
from this case. FN 42 In both books, the judges let the lawyers
put on extensive testimony about the inmate's mental competency
only out of fear of being reversed on appeal. FN 43

Allied Counsel. In both books, the protagonist receives a modicum
of support by lawyers specializing in defeating imposition of
the death penalty. In The Chamber that support comes from Hez
Kerry, a young black lawyer who has renounced big firm life
and who now heads a Southern anti-death-penalty group. FN 44
Kerry has his genesis in several of Nelson's characters--Mike
Mello, a lawyer with an anti-death-penalty group in Florida;
Mark Olive, the chief litigator for the same group; and Jeff
Robinson, a young black Wilmer associate who has successfully
taken
on a previous death penalty case, who gets Polly into the case,
and who leaves the firm soon thereafter for public service. FN
45

Opposing Counsel. Both Adam and Polly face lawyers for the state
who are far more experienced and are death zealots. They also
seem to appear in droves. FN 46

Supporting Characters. The following characters appear in both
books:

The calm, laid-back guard, specializing in handling the
condemned, who is solicitous of the inmate and the lawyer. FN 47

The corrections officials and personnel who will be disappointed
if a stay is granted. FN 48

Governors and attorneys general seeking political benefit from
the inmate's death, e.g., posturing on TV to show how hard they
will work to make sure the inmate is put to death. FN 49

A pathetic and insane white inmate who corresponds with Sam/Ted.
FN 50

The experienced and rough-talking former investigator who
alternatively despises and understands the inmate, and who
thinks the young lawyer is naive about the extent of his evil.
FN 51

A young secretary (Dara or Darlene), not the young lawyer's
regular secretary, described as working long hours, excited by
her role in this notorious case, and very competent. FN 52

The evangelical preacher who gains the inmate's respect. FN 53

The eccentric psychiatrists testifying for the defense. FN 54

Family members who have withdrawn from the inmate. Neither Ted's
wife Carole Boone nor Sam's daughter Lee Cayhall Booth comes to
see the inmate before the execution, but both Ted and Sam
pretend to understand this. FN 55 Both inmates have a younger
brother who never comes to visit and does his best to withdraw
from the inmate and the execution. FN 56 In both books the
inmates have an elderly aunt who calls him her "favorite nephew"
yet does not visit. FN 57

Family members of the young lawyer who keep their distance from
the case. Both protagonists have mothers who live in a distant
state, with whom they talk on the telephone. FN 58 Each
protagonist has a sibling who flies in for a visit during the
case. FN 59

In sum, each of the important people in Ms. Nelson's book has a
counterpart in Mr. Grisham's--from the lawyer and inmate, right
on through the judges, other lawyers, relatives, correctional
officials, secretaries and politicians.

PLOT

Each book is the story of an unsuccessful attempt by an
inexperienced young lawyer to save a notorious condemned
murderer from the death penalty. In each, the execution
approaches at a steady, relentless pace, despite frantic legal
efforts by the protagonist to avoid it. In each, the inmate moves
from stoicism,
to manic activity, to fear, to a sort of dignified acceptance.
In each, the protagonist moves from naive idealism, to
awkwardness, to hope, to doubt, to introspection, to
overwhelming fatigue and frustration, to disgust at the passion of
the public,
press and judicial establishment to see the inmate executed, to
aggravation at the inmate himself, to a last-minute glimmer of
intimacy with the inmate and to numb disorientation following
his death. For example, both books share the following
subplots and themes:

The young lawyer explores his or her personal reasons for taking
on this case for this client, and gains a measure of self-
knowledge by the end of the book. FN 60

Both lawyers are exhausted by and resentful of the extraordinary
pace at which the criminal justice system requires counsel to
conduct post-conviction death penalty litigation. Each is
convinced that the courts to which they are appealing for relief
simply want to ensure that the execution goes ahead as
scheduled, without any stays. FN 61

Both cases receive lurid press coverage, including constant re-
caps of old news about the inmate and his crimes. The reporters,
both local and national, aggressively seek interviews with the
lawyer and with the inmate. The lawyer vacillates at times,
but ultimately learns how to handle aggressive press
attention. FN 62

Both Sam and Ted are depicted as mentally tortured by the
uncertainty of the death penalty appeal process. FN 63

In both books the inmate has two things he wants to accomplish at
the end of his life: (1) publicly to denounce one of the causal
factors of his crimes (the Klan/violent pornography), and (2)
to confess to all his crimes, even those not charged. Sam
springs the Klan letter on Adam while they are awaiting a
decision by the Fifth Circuit Court of Appeals, following their
only evidentiary hearing, which dealt with Sam's competency to
be executed. Ted springs the confession scheme on Polly while
they are awaiting a decision by
the Eleventh Circuit Court of Appeals, following their only
evidentiary hearing, which dealt with Ted's competency to be
tried. In both books, the inmate's plans threaten the pending
appeal, and the lawyer attempts to control the inmate in his
public statements. In neither case is the lawyer wholly
successful. FN 64

The following events are among those that advance the plot and
these sub-plots in both books:

The protagonist's experiences and feelings:

On first receiving a call from/entering the prison, Polly and
Adam both wonder if the operator/guard is having any reaction
upon hearing the famous inmate's name. FN 65

On the occasion of her/his first contact with the prison, Polly
and Adam encounter a prison official who checks up on her/his
identity and informs her/him that more lawyer access than usual
is permitted in the case of an inmate facing imminent execution.
At the same time, the lawyer is told of/notes the
conflicting emotions experienced by prison personnel who must
deal with inmates on a daily basis and then execute them. FN 66

Both young lawyers need to hear the inmate himself describe the
crimes to them. FN 67

Upon viewing a realistic artistic portrayal (sculpture/movie),
the lawyer struggles with her/his sympathy for and strong
identification with the victims, and sudden overwhelming hate
for the client. The lawyer feels guilt and disgust at
her/himself
for representing this evil man. FN 68

Both are abruptly confronted by partners in the home office while
an execution is imminent, warning them that their jobs are in
jeopardy because of their singleminded pursuit of the inmate's
case. Both are astounded that the partners are not instead
offering assistance and support. Neither has any sympathy for
the law firm's point of view. FN 69

Both are suddenly forced to fly back to the home office of the
law firm while the clock is ticking toward execution. Both
immediately return the next day. FN 70

The lawyer is shown to be as vulnerable as anyone else to the
type of violence suffered by the inmate's victims, as the lawyer
is/imagines being stalked by a killer. Neither incident affects
the relentless forward march of the story line, and neither
lawyer is ever confronted by any real personal danger. FN 71

The paralyzed young lawyer, still at the office at 8 p.m., gazes
out of the office windows into darkness. FN 72

Unwelcome words become soothing when spoken with a southern
drawl. FN 73

Both young lawyers avoid reviewing evidence of the inmate's
crimes as long as they can. FN 74

Both Polly and Adam delight in the luxury of a car paid for by
the firm. FN 75 In each book an experienced, empathetic lawyer
walks the young lawyer to and admires that car. FN 76

Polly and Adam, in a vacation environment, feel sad that the
inmate will never enjoy such experiences. FN 77

Goodman/Coleman & Polly stay in a small, quaint lodging house
offering a taste of luxury and refinement during their down-and-
dirty fight in the last days before the execution. FN 78

Both Adam and Polly need to break out of the stifling atmosphere
of their offices as the tension mounts waiting for the ruling of
the Circuit Court of Appeals. See Table B.

Both Adam and Polly wistfully envy ordinary people unencumbered
by the great burden of saving a man from execution. See Table C.
They are struck by the carefree demeanor of well-dressed locals
on the street and in restaurants going on with their ordinary
lives. FN 79 See Table C.

People get little sleep, people and briefs are rushed to the
airport, meals are gulped or postponed, and lawyers check into
hotels or board airplanes without clean clothes. FN 80 But every
once in a while the lawyer gets a respite, a quiet meal in a
nice restaurant, where there is no talk of the inmate's case.
FN 81

In the last days before a scheduled execution, Goodman/Polly go
shopping for a respite from the pressure, and become giddy with
a frivolous purchase/thought of a purchase. FN 82

Both Adam and Polly get a sudden break in the demands on them on
the Sunday two days before a scheduled execution. They get a
full night's sleep and get to flip through newspapers
(assiduously avoiding stories about their own case) and drink
coffee
at leisure, but the peace is subject to disruption at any
moment. FN 83

Adam and Polly are assaulted and repelled by the excitement of
the citizens at the imminence of the execution. FN 84 They are
disgusted as crowds outside the prison jeer and chant. FN 85
The young lawyer is shocked by photographs/news footage of people
gathered to celebrate a lynching/the execution, without
embarrassment. FN 86

Neither young lawyer lets her/himself believe that the execution
will in fact take place. FN 87

Both lawyers experience the aftermath of the execution as time
playing games or not moving forward. The lawyer is/feels hung
over. See Table D.

Obstacles in the way of the protagonist's efforts:

The state
where the inmate is jailed is competing with other states to be
the one with the most executions. FN 88

Law firm personnel act coolly toward Adam/Polly to express their
displeasure with the firm's representation of this notorious
inmate. FN 89

While staying at a motel, both lawyers are bombarded by
television reports concerning the client's imminent execution,
with accompanying political posturing. See Table E.

Jewish/Women partners of the prosperous law firm object to the
representation because the inmate killed Jews/women. See Table .

Assorted pundits (most often the press or state attorneys) quote
odds on the execution going forward at various points, as if
it's all a game. FN 90

Governor/Judges exhibit southern courtesy, while denying relief.
FN 91

Adam/Polly hurriedly backs away at a restaurant from a persistent
reporter from The New York Times/Life magazine who wants to
interview the inmate. FN 92

Both inmates recognize that the press keeps replaying the "same
old rehash/thing," but feel public excitement growing as the
execution nears. FN 93

In both books, judges disdain psychiatrists who attempt to help
inmates avoid the death penalty. FN 94

The inmate's experiences and feelings:

The inmate eventually comes to enjoy talking about his crimes,
and does so in a chillingly methodical way. After a
pause/hemming and hawing, he goes into a "trance," remembers
every detail, and seems to admire his own skill. The inmate
describes and
analyzes the details fondly, without consideration for how cold-
blooded it makes him look or how it repulses the young lawyer.
FN 95

Both inmates feign paranoia about being doped by prison
authorities to make the execution go smoothly. FN 96

Both inmates stubbornly refuse to make last requests while there
is any hope for a stay. FN 97

Both inmates are aggressively approached to sell their stories.
FN 98

The inmate is unnerved upon hearing prison personnel make
physical preparations for the execution. FN 99

Both inmates balk at describing one particular murder to a
minister. FN 100

Each inmate shows his vulnerability and pleads with his lawyer
only once. Sam pleads with Adam not to file hopeless last-minute
claims, including one asserting that he is incompetent to be
executed, because he wants to die with dignity. Ted pleads with
Polly to file a hopeless last-minute claim that he is
incompetent to be executed, but Polly convinces him to die with
dignity instead. FN 101

Silence signals meaningful communication between the lawyer and
his client near the end. There is nothing appropriate to say.
The inmate has retreated to an unknowable, private place. FN 102

Both lawyers will tell the inmate anything he wants to hear at
the end, when the inmate shows genuine emotion about his
personal relationships. FN 103

Case events:

Both inmates had been identified by a witness who came forward
only after the defendant had been indicted and his face had been
prominently featured in the press. FN 104

The young lawyer is excited when she/he realizes that a witness
who was never called to testify at trial may have evidence that
will exonerate the inmate, or otherwise diminish his
culpability. In each case, the missing witness had supposedly
spotted
the inmate/the victim at a truck stop. In each case the
protagonist wants badly to believe in the worth of this
testimony, but is firmly disabused of his hope by the inmate. FN
105

Unlike the competency claim, the inmate is enthusiastic about the
first major ground for reversal put forth by the lawyer, and
eagerly offers to help with legal research. FN 106

Adam/Polly seeks out a former investigator on the case, hoping he
will provide helpful information. That investigator takes
control of the interview and provides cryptic information both
reinforcing and mitigating the inmate's culpability. FN 107

Law students have a ball working on both cases. FN 108

During the competency hearing, the judge interrupts the testimony
once to ask his own question, apparently out of sheer
curiosity. FN 109

Both Ted and Sam are curious when they see on television a young
black lawyer they have never met, who is part of the defense
team, explaining what the defense team is up to. FN 110

At one point, the state's lawyers and the inmate's lawyers appear
to share the sense that they are being caught up in ridiculous
time limits, and the state's lawyers graciously offer their
facilities to counsel for the inmate. A fancy phone system is
required for the expedited decision from the Circuit Court of
Appeals, which all the lawyers recognize is simply going through
the motions. The inmate's appeal is denied virtually instantly
the same afternoon. FN 111

On the night before the execution, Adam and Polly are both called
out of their last "huddled" meeting with the inmate to take a
telephone call from the supervising partner, who is monitoring
the last possibility for saving the inmate's life. FN 112

Parallel gratuitous details:

Both law firms have Christmas parties, mentioned in passing. FN
113

Lee and Polly focus on the physical details of the victims'
deaths and, at least momentarily, declare legal niceties
superfluous. FN 114

Many other death row residents have been waiting for their
executions longer than have Sam or Ted FN 115, and the
warden/allied counsel is already thinking ahead with dread to
the next execution after Sam/Ted. FN 116

The lawyer's family members get to follow the course of events in
the press due to extensive, nationwide publicity, but do not
actively offer support. FN 117

Professional death penalty lawyers bolster their confidence by
telling war stories with their fellows. FN 118

DESCRIPTIONS

Many descriptive passages in the two books are so strikingly
similar that copying by Mr. Grisham is the only rational
explanation.

One example is when the young lawyer drives toward the prison and
meets the condemned inmate for the first time. Both Adam and
Polly feel not "particularly . . .welcome"/"unwelcome" and
drive cautiously past "ramshackle" buildings, numbed by their
cars' sound systems. See Table G. The lawyer suddenly feels
reluctant to proceed toward the prison after reading a sign
indicating that the prison is five/six miles ahead. FN 119 Each
lawyer's shoes become a focal point as she/he awaits clearance
through
prison security procedures. FN 120 The young lawyer is surprised
at the large size of the room in which he/she first meets the
inmate. FN 121 In both cases the lawyer is nervous, but reminds
him/herself that he/she is up to the job at hand given the
"formidable" resources of the large law firm. FN 122 Each lawyer
has
great difficulty looking her/his new client in the eye, and each
is surprised at how short, thin and pale the prisoner is. See
Table H.

The following are some additional examples:

The young lawyer and the supervising partner sit together in
silence in a rare shared moment after receiving bad news and
realizing the struggle ahead. FN 123

Both inmates are described as stubbornly keeping secret the truth
about their crimes because of an oath or vow made to others as
well as to themselves. FN 124

The prison entrance is announced by an arched sign. See Table I.
Both young lawyers are blinded by the brilliant midday sun
outside the prison. FN 125

In both books, barbed wire is described as "razor wire," and
particularly as "gleaming" razor wire. FN 126

The protagonist looks out another lawyer's window to see the
rooftops of nearby buildings. FN 127

Lee and Polly sink low into sofas. FN 128

"Bulky" legal files are maintained by the inmate. FN 129

The physical description of Todd Marks copies that of Mark Olive.
See Table J.

Conversation between the lawyer and the investigator/psychiatrist
with insight into the inmate's criminal nature is made
impossible by the roar of a motor. FN 130

A breeze chases away humidity. FN 131

Both Adam and Polly "stare" at a "blank computer screen." FN 132

The primary defense psychiatrist is described as completely
incapable of/bypassing small talk. FN 133

Expert psychiatrists gain credibility from talking
differently/having an accent, traveling great distances, and
illuminating the courtroom by the color of their clothes. See
Table K.

WORD USAGE

Mr. Grisham must have seen and studied Ms. Nelson's manuscript of
the Devil before completing The Chamber. There is no other
rational explanation for the striking similarities in plot,
character, and description that we have set out above. As
additional evidence, however, we have discovered Polly Nelson's
"literary fingerprints" throughout The Chamber in Mr. Grisham's
use of her distinctive words and phrases.

First, many distinctive word combinations or phrases appear in
both The Chamber and Defending the Devil, but cannot be found
anywhere in the four novels published previously by Mr. Grisham.
We've listed a few of them in Table L. We continue to find
more examples.

In addition, certain individual words used in the Devil also
appear in The Chamber but apparently not in any other Grisham
novel. There appear to be scores if not hundreds of examples of
this phenomenon. Some are very telling, common words, the
repetitive use of which constitutes an integral stylistic habit
that
signals a particular authorship. For example, the word
"typically" appears seven times in the Devil and nine times in
The Chamber. The word has never been used by Mr. Grisham in any
of his other published novels.

Other words are so uncommon as to preclude the likelihood that
their appearance for the first time in this, Mr. Grisham's fifth
novel is coincidental. Among these are "pesky, "chirpy,''
"scruffy," "ruckus", "slinky", "interminable," "inundate,"
"quipped", "steely," "reverberate," "glint," "forsaken,"
"pristine," and
"wistfully." All of these (and many others) appear in both the
Devil and The Chamber, and apparently not in any prior Grisham
novel.

IMMATERIALITY OF DISTINCTIVE ELEMENTS

We are mindful, of course, that The Chamber employs certain story
lines not present in Defending the Devil. None of these
distinctive elements, however, is an integral part of Mr.
Grisham's book and most, on closer analysis, turn out not to be
"distinctive" at all.

For example, Rollie Wedge stalks Lee and Adam, and comes to
threaten Sam. Yet
nothing becomes of this subplot--Wedge simply vanishes, and the
protagonist Adam never even knows that he may have been in
danger. Wedge's return and his menacing actions thus have no
effect whatsoever on Mr. Grisham's story. It turns out that the
explanation for this narrative lapse is a simple one--Mr. Grisham
is copying an incident where Polly Nelson imagines that she is
being stalked at the death penalty conference. FN 134 Since
Polly's stalker is an imaginary one (and, thus, can have no
impact on the events of her nonfiction account), Mr. Grisham's
copycat stalker plot line likewise can have no impact on his
novel. So too with other diversionary parts of Mr. Grisham's
story such as Lee. Booth's relentless social work, her alcoholic
relapse, and her retreat into a recovery program. These events in
no way advance Mr. Grisham's story, and in fact distract from it
and lead nowhere. They are, of course, simply a thinly disguised
version of the real life story of Polly Nelson.

Finally, the fact that Adam is Sam's grandson--what might be
urged as the most striking difference between the two books--is
in fact another, central parallel. Just as Adam is called to
understand and defend his grandfather (and thus understand his
family, his upbringing and himself), Polly too is irresistibly
driven by her unhappy family relationships to undertake the
career-destroying and hopeless task of defending a "worm" such
as Ted Bundy. Adam's defense of his grandfather Sam is surely
derived from the central theme of Polly's book "I was born to
represent Ted Bundy."

THE CHAMBER IS WHOLLY UNLIKE ANY PREVIOUSLY PUBLISHED GRISHAM
NOVEL

That Mr. Grisham copied Ms. Nelson's book is further established
by a comparison of The Chamber with the other published works of
Mr. Grisham. As the reviewers have recognized, and as we are
prepared to demonstrate by expert testimony, The Chamber is
a very different book than any previously associated with Mr.
Grisham.

ACCESS

After receiving an 80-page version of the Devil (then named
peace, ted), Doubleday editors met with Ms. Nelson and her agent
at Doubleday's offices on October 15, 1990, to discuss her book
proposal in expansive detail. Of course Ms. Nelson submitted
her proposal and participated in such a meeting only on the
premise that Doubleday would not publish her story without
compensation and credit to her.

RESOLUTION

We have written this letter only after careful analysis of the
facts and the available legal remedies. We will, of course,
carefully consider any evidence that you may wish to submit that
points to conclusions other that those set out above.
This letter's purpose is to avoid litigation, if that is
possible. We have addressed it to Doubleday and Mr. Grisham, but
we urge you to share it with other potentially affected parties
such as the purchasers of the movie rights, foreign rights, etc.
We are informed by press accounts that The Chamber was sold to
Universal Studios in the summer of 1993 for a substantial sum.
We are unaware of the current status of any motion picture based
on Mr. Grisham's book but feel constrained to state that
release of a motion picture based on The Chamber without
concomitant compensation and credit to Ms. Nelson is
unacceptable.

This letter notifies you of our claim and demands that you desist
from all infringing activities. Please be advised that we
require you to retain any and all potentially relevant evidence.
We will take the position that the loss or destruction of any
potentially relevant evidence after receipt of this notice is
evidence of liability, evidence of bad faith, and an act
designed to obstruct justice.

I look forward to discussing with you, or your representatives,
the terms under which we might compromise this claim. We will be
required to seek judicial redress if we do not hear from you
within the next two weeks.

Sincerely,



Patricia D. Douglass


cc: Polly Nelson

