<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Court TV Library</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A HREF="/map/library.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/library.gif" ISMAP ALT="Court TV Library" BORDER="0"></A>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<P>Restaurateur Tomasso Buti, who owns the Fashion Cafe in affiliation with models Claudia Schiffer, Naomi Campbell and Elle Macpherson, filed this complaint against the corporation that owns a restaurant with the same name in Milan, Italy. The two parties are fighting over the trademark rights of the name "Fashion Cafe."</P>
<HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT>
<PRE>
UNITED STATES DISTRICT COURT
SOUTHERN DISTRICT OF NEW YORK

_ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _   x

TOMMASO BUTI and FASHION WORLD
COMPANY,

Plaintiffs,

- against -

IMPRESSA PEROSA, S.R.L.,

Defendant.



Civil Action,No.
95 Civ. 3525 (AGS)

COMPLAINT FOR DECLARATORY JUDGMENT

Plaintiffs, Tommaso Buti and Fashion World Company, by
and through their attorneys, requesting an adjudication regarding
their rights and those of Defendant, allege as follows:

THE PARTIES

1. Plaintiff, Tommaso Buti, is an individual who is a
citizen of Italy, having an office and place of business in New
York, New York.

2. Plaintiff, Fashion World Company is a limited
partnership organized and existing under the laws of the State of
New York, located at 16 East 53rd Street, New York, New York,
10022.

3. Upon information and belief, Defendant Impressa
Perosa, S.R.L., is a corporation organized and existing under the
laws of Italy, having a place of business in Milan, Italy.

JURISDICTION AND VENUE

4. This Court has subject matter jurisdiction over
this controversy pursuant to 15 U.S.C.  1121 and 28 U.S.C.
Sects. 1331 and 1338, there being a substantial federal question
arising under a law of the United States and act of Congress
relating to asserted claims of unfair competition and trademark
infringement.

5. Personal jurisdiction over Defendant is based upon
information and belief that Defendant is contracting to franchise
a restaurant in the State of New York, and the commission of
tortious acts by Defendant within the State and outside of the
State causing injury within the State of New York, pursuant to
N.Y. Civ. Prac. Law  302(a)(1)-(3).

6. Venue is proper in this district pursuant to 15
U.S.C.  1391(b), (c) and (d), in that the controversy arose in
this district.

CONTROVERSY

7. This action is for a declaratory judgment pursuant
to 28 U.S.C.  2201, there being a substantial actual controversy
within the jurisdiction of this court now existing between the
parties. Plaintiffs are interested parties and require deter-
minations and declarations by this Court of their rights with
respect to said controversy.

A. Plaintiffs' FASHION CAFE Restaurant And Trademark Rights

8. Plaintiff Tommaso Buti is a restauranteur who, in
1993, through a corporation owned by him, adopted and used the
name and service mark FASHION CAFE in connection with an Italian
restaurant and restaurant services in the South Beach area of
Miami Beach, Florida. The name FASHION CAFE was chosen by
Plaintiff Buti in order to identify the restaurant with South
Beach is flourishing modeling industry and to capitalize on
Plaintiffs' associations with the fashion industry. The FASHION
CAFE restaurant in Florida has an Italian theme and became popular
and received considerable press. Annexed hereto as Exhibit 1 is
a copy of the menu for the Florida FASHION CAFE restaurant.
Annexed hereto as Exhibit 2 are copies of articles from 1993 and
1994 reporting on the Florida FASHION CAFE restaurant.

9. In June of 1994, Plaintiff Buti commenced plans to
open a franchise of theme restaurants based on the fashion and
modeling industry which would include fashion related motifs and
displays of fashion memorabilia, under the name and service mark
FASHION CAFE. From its inception, the concept of the FASHION CAFE
theme restaurant was to offer American cuisine in each restaurant
and to also offer for sale souvenir merchandise bearing the
FASHION CAFE logo. The premier FASHION CAFE restaurant opened in
New York City on April 7, 1995.

10. From September 1994 to the present, Plaintiffs
Tommaso Buti and Fashion World Company embarked upon a promotional
campaign for the opening of a restaurant under the service mark
and trade name FASHION CAFE. The campaign announcing the opening
of Plaintiffs' New York FASHION CAFE restaurant has received
worldwide press coverage. The promotional campaign has been lead
by the internationally famous fashion supermodels Claudia
Schiffer, Elle Macpherson and Naomi Campbell, each of whom have an
interest in the franchising of FASHION CAFE restaurants.
Publicity concerning the April opening of the restaurant has
appeared in articles directed to the general public in newspapers
and magazines including the Boston Herald, Women's Wear Daily, New
York's Daily News, Vogue, The Detroit Free Press, The Star,
Italy's La Republica and London's Evening Standard. Copies of
press clippings from various newspapers and magazines regarding
Plaintiffs' FASHION CAFE are annexed hereto as Exhibit 3.

11. Part of the campaign included an official ground
breaking ceremony in early December 1994, featuring the three
famous supermodels that was aired on television news and talk
shows, on every major network as well as on cable networks
including but not limited to WNBC's "Live At Five" news program,
the evening news on the WNBC, WABC, WCBS, WPIX and WNYW (Fox)
networks, "Prime News" on Cable News Network and "Week in Review"
on E! Entertainment TV.

12. The premier New York City FASHION CAFE is located
in Rockefeller Center Plaza. Future sites for franchises of the
FASHION CAFE restaurant are being planned for the Far East
including Japan and Hong Kong, London and South America. Negoti-
ations concerning franchises are current and ongoing. Plaintiffs
have invested over $5,000,000 dollars in the opening.

13. In order to assure that Plaintiff Buti would be
able to continue to use the FASHION CAFE trademark for a theme
restaurant in the United States, Plaintiff Buti conducted a
trademark search in August of 1994. The search did not uncover
any use or registration of the mark FASHION CAFE by Defendant nor
any other entity or individual. Based thereon, Plaintiff Buti
filed a United States trademark application which was assigned
Serial No. 74/569,511 in the United States Patent and Trademark
Office, on September 2, 1994, for the service mark/trademark
FASHION CAFE for restaurant services and clothing. A copy of the
official filing receipt for this application is annexed hereto as
Exhibit 4.

14. After the logo was developed for the restaurant,
Plaintiff Buti filed another United States trademark application
which was assigned Serial No. 74/619,500 on January 10, 1995, for
the service mark/trademark FASHION CAFE & Design for restaurant
services and clothing. A copy of the official filing receipt for
this application is annexed hereto as Exhibit 6.

15. The name of the Florida FASHION CAFE restaurant was
changed in December 1994 in order for the FASHION CAFE restau-
rants, to be operated by Plaintiff Fashion World Company, to
maintain a single identity in terms of the theme, decor and food.
The Florida restaurant is now called FASHION ON THE BEACH and
continues to offer Italian cuisine in an Italian bistro setting.

B. Defendant's Actions That
Caused This Controversy

16. In a letter dated January 19, 1995, from
Defendant's attorney, Defendant asserts a claim that Plaintiffs'
use of FASHION CAFE for its New York restaurant is infringing
Defendant's trademark rights and is violating the unfair
competition laws of the "Lanham Act and the Trademark Law Revision
Act", by using the name FASHION CAFE for its restaurant and
allegedly "employ[ing] many of the themes utilized at
[Defendant's] original 'Fashion Cafe'" in Milan, Italy. The
particular themes are not identified in the letter. Defendant
further alleges that its "Fashion Cafe" in Milan is "world-
renowned", that Defendant was "contacted concerning a license of
its trademark for a New York franchise of [Defendant's]
restaurant" and that Defendant would suffer "irreparable harm and
consumer confusion" if Plaintiffs were to use the mark FASHION
CAFE for its restaurant. Defendant further demands that
Plaintiffs discontinue use of the mark FASHION CAFE and indicates
that Defendant would take "all necessary legal actions to protect
[Defendant's] rights, including seeking injunctive relief,
compensatory and punitive damages and attorney's fees." A copy of
Defendant's January 19, 1995 letter is annexed hereto as
Exhibit 6.

17. After corresponding with counsel for Defendant in
an attempt to settle the claims asserted by Defendant, Plaintiffs'
counsel received a letter from Defendant's counsel dated February
21, 1995, indicating that Defendant's counsel was "working with
[his] client to set forth his understanding of the [settlement]
proposal." Nevertheless, Plaintiffs were to "remain on notice to
cease and desist from infringing the rights of and unfairly
competing with [Defendant]." Annexed hereto as Exhibit 7 is a
copy of the February 21, 1995 letter.

18. Plaintiffs' FASHION CAFE restaurant opened on April
7, 1995, as scheduled. Thereafter, in the April 27, 1995 issue of
the Italian magazine Panorama, Defendant, through its owner, again
asserted that it had plans to sue Plaintiffs. Annexed hereto as
Exhibit 8 is a copy of the article that was published in the April
27, 1995 issue of Panorama.

C. Harm To Plaintiffs From Defendant's Threatened Action

19. Plaintiffs have expended enormous time, effort and
money in advertising, promoting and designing its new FASHION CAFE
restaurant which opened with great fanfare in Rockefeller Plaza
Center less than two months ago. Also, merchandise including
jackets and other clothing bearing the FASHION CAFE logo have been
manufactured and are being sold in the New York FASHION CAFE
restaurant.

20. Contrary to the assertions of Defendant, Defendant
has established no rights to the FASHION CAFE mark in the United
States under federal or common law, that would entitle Defendant
to assert trademark infringement or unfair competition claims in
the United States. Defendant has not filed an application nor
registered the trademark in the United States, nor has Defendant
opened a restaurant or rendered restaurant services in the United
States. Plaintiffs believe that Defendant's "Fashion Cafe" bar in
Milan, Italy, is not famous or well-known to the consuming public
in the United States. Accordingly, Defendant cannot prove any
likelihood of confusion on the part of the consuming public, thus
rendering Plaintiffs free from any liability.

21. Plaintiffs are offering to franchise third parties
in locations outside of New York and have used the New York
opening of FASHION CAFE in April as a launching pad for their
franchise of FASHION CAFE restaurants. Accordingly, Plaintiffs
have begun to negotiate with third parties to open additional
restaurants and will be severely damaged and otherwise irreparably
harmed should Defendants continue to assert that Plaintiffs' usage
of the FASHION CAFE mark for its restaurant and other merchandise
violate its rights.

22. Defendant has threatened to seek an injunction and
refuses to withdraw its claims of infringement and unfair
competition. For this reason, a substantial justiciable
controversy now exists because Plaintiffs and Defendant have real,
immediate and adverse interests based on Defendant's direct threat
of imminent litigation including Defendant's threat that it shall
seek injunctive relief.

23. The claims of trademark infringement and unfair
competition by Defendant against Plaintiffs will cause
considerable injury to Plaintiffs because of the substantial
investment by Plaintiffs in the FASHION CAFE restaurant and shall
interfere with Plaintiffs' business including plans for fran-
chising the FASHION CAFE restaurants which are presently in
negotiation. For all of the reasons set forth above, Plaintiffs
will suffer immediate irreparable harm if Plaintiffs are unable to
establish that Defendant has no right to assert claims of
infringement and unfair competition based on the FASHION CAFE
mark.

24. Plaintiffs have no other adequate remedy at law and
will be irreparably harmed unless this Court grants the relief
prayed for herein.

WHEREFORE, Plaintiffs pray for judgment and an
adjudication;

A. That Defendant does not have rights in the
trademark "Fashion Cafe" for restaurant services or clothing in
the United States;

B. That Plaintiffs do not infringe trademark rights of
Defendant, if such rights exist, based on its use, advertisement,
promotion, rendering of restaurant services and sale of
merchandise under the name and mark FASHION CAFE:

C. That Plaintiffs do not unfairly compete with
Defendant by use, advertisement, promotion, rendering of
restaurant services and sale of merchandise under the name and
mark FASHION CAFE;

D. That Plaintiffs do not misrepresent the origin of
their FASHION CAFE restaurant services or suggest that these
services originate with or are sponsored by Defendant;

E. That Plaintiffs do not injure the business
reputation of Defendant;

F. That Defendant, its officers, agents, servants,
employees and attorneys and those in active concert or
participation with them, be preliminarily and permanently enjoined
from asserting, contending, claiming, alleging or threatening to
assert that Plaintiffs, their partners, associates, related
companies or potential franchises, have infringed its rights, or
unfairly competed therewith, from bringing suit or threatening to
do so, against Plaintiffs, and from advising the public or press
of any alleged infringement or unfair competition by Plaintiffs;

G. That Defendant, its officers, agents, servants,
employees and attorneys and those in active concert or
participation with them, be preliminarily and permanently enjoined
from publicizing Defendant's claims of infringement and/or unfair
competition against Plaintiffs, and from suing or threatening to
sue Plaintiffs, their partners, associates, related companies or
potential franchisees;

H. Awarding Plaintiffs damages sustained by Plaintiffs
due to the actions of Defendant;

I. Awarding Plaintiffs punitive damages in the amount
of $1,000,000 as a result of Defendant's willful, intentional and
malicious interference with Plaintiffs' business;

J. Awarding Plaintiffs their costs in this action and
their reasonable attorneys' fees; and

K. Such other and further relief as this Court may
deem just and proper.

Dated: New York, New York
May 17, 1995

Respectfully submitted,

STROOCK & STROOCK & LAVAN
Attorneys for Plaintiffs
TOMMASO BUTI and
FASHION WORLD COMPANY
Seven Hanover Square
New York, New York 10004-2696
Tel: (212) 806-5400

By:
Steven B. Pokotilow (SBP-2215)
Michele P. Schwartz (MPS-4174)
</PRE>
