<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Staff Bios - Jane Okrasinski</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A HREF="/map/ontheair.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/ontheair.gif" ISMAP ALT="Court TV On the Air" BORDER="0"></A>

<H2>Jane Okrasinski</H2>
<IMG HSPACE=5 ALIGN=LEFT SRC="/graphics/ctv/anchors/jane.gif">Jane Okrasinski graduated from Emory law and became a Georgia lawyer in 1980. She practiced in Atlanta for four years, doing securities and corporate litigation work, then was appointed by a federal judge to be a monitor in the Texas prisons. After a year in the prisons, Okrasinski came back to Atlanta and went to work in a homeless shelter, where she made soup and such and had nothing much to do with lawyers for a year and a half. In February 1987, she began writing for The Daily Report, the Atlanta newspaper owned by American Lawyer Media, and won several journalism awards there before joining Court TV about a year before it went on air.
<P>Since then, she's covered more than 30 Georgia trials, incuding Mosely v. General Motors -- the pick-up truck gas tanks case -- and two murder cases against police officers -- Georgia v. Cassotta and Georgia v. Chapel. Okrasinski also recently covered the Black Crowes civil case -- Is a pie chart a contract? -- and the Mickler wrongful death trial, where the family of a gospel singer killed by a semi was awarded $5 million.
<HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT>
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/rights2.gif" ALT="Copyright 1996 by American Lawyer Media, L.P. All Rights Reserved.">
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/frontpage/spacer.gif" ALT="No parts of this site may be reproduced without permission of American Lawyer Media." BORDER="0">
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/frontpage/spacer.gif" ALT="Nothing in this site is intended to constitute legal advice." BORDER="0">
