<HEAD>
<TITLE>Court TV On The Air</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A HREF="/map/ontheair.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/ontheair.gif" ISMAP ALT="Court TV On the Air" BORDER="0"></A>
<H3>Court TV Study Guide For September 1996 Class Action Program:<BR>
National High School Mock Trial Championship</H3>

<P>CLASS ACTION AIRS ON COURT TV EVERY SATURDAY AT 4AM ET</P>

<b>Description</B><BR>
Get an inside look at how a top team prepares for the final championship and experiences the ups and downs of  competition. Then watch the highlights of the final round between the two best mock trial teams in the nation. Students act as both the attorneys and the witnesses while arguing this year's case, Cambria Iron Company v. The South Fork Fishing and Hunting Club (The Johnstown Flood).<P>

<B>Purpose</B><BR>
This program can be used in two ways:<br>
@ As an example of high school students using their public speaking ability and their knowledge of the law to compete in a mock trial competition.<br>
@As a springboard for discussion on liability and negligence. <br>
After watching the competition students will have heard arguments on both sides of the case.<p>

<B>The Case</b><br>
The Cambria Iron Company alleges that the South Fork Club did not properly maintain its dam and when the worst flood in 100 years hit, the dam collapsed and destroyed the entire town. The Iron company says the resulting damage was preventable and entirely the fault of the Club. The Club argues that no man is nature's master, the dam was properly maintained and that no dam could have withstood the flood.<p>


<B>The Competition</B><BR>
In the championship round each team must be prepared to argue either side, the plaintiff or the defense. In this competition the Michigan team argued the plaintiff's case and Arizona the defense. Each side presented opening and closing statements and three witnesses. Everyone in the competition is a high school student.<P>

<B>Breakdown</B><BR>
Segment 1:<BR>
Meet the Delaware team and watch them start to strategize for the competition and enjoy their time off in Pittsburgh.<P>

Segment 2<BR>
Round one of the competition. Watch as Delaware meets Michigan. Both of these teams are very strong and only one will advance to the finals.<P>

Segments 3, 4 and 5<BR>
The final round of competition, Michigan vs. Arizona.<P>

Segment 6<BR>
The announcement of the winners and the awards banquet.    <P>

<B>Discussion Before Viewing</B><BR>
Discuss how a trial works. Start with opening statements, talk about how attorneys question a witness and then discuss closing statements.<P>

What is the difference between a civil trial and a criminal trial?<P>

In this case the plaintiff had to prove negligence on the part of the defense. What does that entail?<P>

How are liability laws different today than they were 100 years ago?<P>

Do you believe clubs and companies have an obligation to create safe environments and products or is it the consumer's responsibility (or in this case the town's), to make sure the environment/product is safe? Should the town have built its own dam or should it have forced the South  Fork Club to fix its dam?<P>

<B>Discussing After Viewing</B><BR>
Did watching the trial change your original opinion of the case?<P>

If this case happened today instead of 100 years ago, what do you think the outcome would be?<P>

Do you think the South Fork Club  members' status in the community affected the verdict? Do you think it would today? Think of current trials where celebrities or wealthy people went on trial. Do you think their celebrity status affected the outcome of the trial?<P>
<HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT>
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/rights2.gif" ALT="Copyright 1996 by American Lawyer Media, L.P. All Rights Reserved.">
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/frontpage/spacer.gif" ALT="No parts of this site may be reproduced without permission of American Lawyer Media." BORDER="0">
