<HEAD>
<TITLE>Court TV On The Air</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A HREF="/map/ontheair.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/ontheair.gif" ISMAP ALT="Court TV On the Air" BORDER="0"></A>
<H3>Court TV Study Guide For October 1996 Class Action Program:<BR>
AIDS: Its Side Effects on America </H3>

<P>CLASS ACTION AIRS ON COURT TV EVERY SATURDAY AT 4AM ET</P>

<b>Purpose</b><br>
A chance to get an inside look at how people in our society have been challenged by and have faced AIDS and HIV. To examine how this disease has changed the way we look at our laws, our society, and our responsibility both as a society and as individuals.<p>

<b>Discussion Before Viewing</b><br>
Discuss the difference between AIDS and HIV: AIDS is the disease, and HIV is the virus that causes AIDS. People who are HIV positive can appear to be perfectly healthy for up to ten years before showing any signs of AIDS. Who do you have to tell? Who should you tell? Do you have to tell your employer? Do you have to tell your doctor? Is there a difference between who legally needs to know and who should know?  How would being HIV positive affect your behavior?	<p>

<b>Segment 1: The Diagnosis</b><br>
Vernelle Lowder was diagnosed with AIDS. The health center told her she had AIDS, not just that she was HIV positive. Two years after the diagnosis, after making major changes to her life, she discovered she did not have the disease nor did she test HIV positive. So, she sued the clinic and the lab for the misdiagnosis. <p>

<b>Discussion:</b> Legally the clinic is not required to tell a patient, who tests positive, to get a retest. However, the standard practice for HIV testing labs is to recommend a retest when the results are positive. Who was responsible for the misdiagnosis? Should Lowder have asked for a retest or should the health center have suggested it? Should the Health Center be held responsible in a court of law for a misdiagnosis? <p>

<b>Segment 2: A Real Life "Philadelphia"</b><br>
In this segment you meet Scott Doe. When Scott filed the lawsuit he used the pseudonym John Doe to remain anonymous. Then, his lawyer recommended he use his given first name, instead of the pseudonym, so that the jury would relate to him on a more personal level.<p>

Scott Doe sued his law firm for discrimination under the Americans with Disabilities Act. He said the firm found out he was HIV positive and fired him. They said it had nothing to do with his disease, rather that his work was unsatisfactory. In this segment, Scott Doe takes the stand and tells his side of the story.<p>

<b>Discussion:</b> The Americans with Disabilities Act protects disabled workers from discrimination by their employers. But it had never been used to protect a person with the AIDS virus. Scott Doe challenged the definition of this law when he brought this lawsuit. The judge ruled in his favor. He said people who are HIV positive are disabled even when they do not have AIDS. Do you think this was a fair ruling? Can you think of other instances when this law could be used? Does your state have additional laws protecting the disabled?<p>

<b>Segment 3: A Real Life "Philadelphia" (continued)</b><br>
Scott Doe is cross examined by the defense. Next, his boss Steven Asher takes the stand and tells the law firm's side of the story. He claims Scott Doe's work was unsatisfactory, therefore he was fired. <p>

<b>Discussion:</b> Who do you believe? Essentially, this lawsuit pits Scott Doe's word against his boss' word. How will the jury decide? Discuss the affects of HIV on Scott's professional life.   <p>

<b>Segment 4: "Who Can You Trust?" and "Helping or Harming?"</b><br>
Two different cases are explored in this segment. Alberto Gonzalez was charged with attempted murder. He allegedly knew he was HIV positive, had unprotected sex with a woman, and infected her with HIV.<p>

Next we meet a man who was giving out clean needles and syringes to injection drug users. Joseph McGrath says it was necessary for him to break the law in order to save people from spreading HIV and AIDS through dirty needles.<p>

<b>Discussion:</b> Both societal and individual responsibilities are questioned in each of these cases. Ask your class who should have taken responsibility in these two situations. Ask your students to think about how each of them can be affected by people who don't take precautions. <p>

<b>Segment 5</b><br>
Finally, we meet police officers, a doctor, and a managing partner in a gym who tell us how HIV and AIDS have changed their daily jobs. Through these professionals, with help from Scott Doe, Court TV takes you into their lives to talk about the issues surrounding HIV and AIDS in the workplace. <p>

<b>Discussion:</b> Ask your students if they have noticed any changes within their lives. What about teachers within the school? Have teachers and students learned about universal precautions? What are universal precautions?<p>

<b>Segment 6</b><br>
A wrap-up of everything we have seen and the outcome of each of these four cases.<p>

<b>Discussion After Viewing</b><br>
In each of these cases, the question of individual and societal responsibility is addressed. Explore these notions. Ask your students to look at each case to decide who was responsible and how the law should have handled it. You can debate both sides of the issue by dividing your class into teams. <p>

AIDS/HIV is an epidemic in our society. How does this disease fit into history? Think about other epidemics and diseases that have forced us to change the way we live. For example: TB and the bubonic plague. Compare these diseases to AIDS and look at their history.  <p>

<b>Suggested Activity</b><br>
Invite a professional from your community into your class to talk about their experience with HIV and AIDS. Has it changed their daily lives? If so, in what ways? Call a local AIDS organization in your community and invite the Executive Director to your school to explain universal precautions and the reasons for implementing them.<p.

Research Project: Have your students call the state prosecutor's office, the district attorney or the county attorney, and ask them if any AIDS/HIV-related cases have gone through their system. Use the people just seen as example cases. Has anyone ever been tried for attempted murder for spreading the virus, like Alberto Gonzalez? What are the laws about distributing clean needles? Can you buy hypodermic needles over the counter?  <p>

<HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT>
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/rights2.gif" ALT="Copyright 1996 by American Lawyer Media, L.P. All Rights Reserved.">
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/frontpage/spacer.gif" ALT="No parts of this site may be reproduced without permission of American Lawyer Media." BORDER="0">
