<HEAD>
<TITLE>Court TV On The Air</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A HREF="/map/ontheair.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/ontheair.gif" ISMAP ALT="Court TV On the Air" BORDER="0"></A>
<H3>Court TV Study Guide For November 1996 Class Action Program:<BR>
Getting Physical: How Relationship Abuse is Affecting Teenagers</H3>

<P>CLASS ACTION AIRS ON COURT TV EVERY SATURDAY AT 4AM ET</P>

<b>Purpose</b><br>
To provoke discussion in the classroom and possibly outside of the classroom regarding relationship abuse. Can this be happening to your students  and how can you get them to talk about it if it is?<p>

<b>Brief Discussion Before Viewing</b><br>
Discuss the concept of relationship abuse and how it may escalate into violence. Talk to your students about what they have seen in their relationships or in the relationships of their friends, and what they think is acceptable behavior. Then compare what they said before the show to their thoughts after the show. Did their views change?<p>

<b>Legal Issues For Discussion After Viewing</b><br>
In the case of MA vs. Fuller, Jamie Fuller killed his 14 -year -old girlfriend, Amy Carnivale. Mark DeMeule, one of Jamie's friends, was present at the time of Carnivale's murder. He was not charged with accessory to a crime in exchange for his testimony against Jamie Fuller. Do you agree with that? Do you believe he should be punished in some other way?<p>

Do you think there should be stricter laws pertaining to relationship abuse? What is the difference between a boyfriend and girlfriend hitting each other and two strangers hitting each other? What is assault?<p>

As you know, the O.J. Simpson double murder trial has brought the issue of domestic violence to the forefront of the case. Do the students realize that relationship abuse can turn into domestic violence? Do they believe the laws regarding domestic abuse cases should be more stringent?<p>

<b>Social Issues For Discussion After Viewing</b><br>
What do you think about teenage dating? Do you think teenagers are becoming more abusive in their relationships? If so, why? What has brought about the change in teenage dating? Do you think alcohol plays a role?<p>

What did the students think about the excerpts from the play, "Hitting Home?"   Discuss the messages they got from the show. Do you think they understood the message of the play? Did they seem to want to see the play performed at their school?<p>

How did they react to the characters? Did they relate to their problems and anxieties? Do you think males and females react differently to the show?<p>

What is and isn't acceptable behavior between boyfriends and girlfriends? And what are the responsibilities of each one when the behavior is not acceptable?<p>

<b>Suggested Activity</b><br>
If the program seemed to have an effect on the students, maybe you can expand the issue. Try bringing in a counselor from a local shelter to personalize the problem and show them that relationship and domestic abuse are out there.<p>

<HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT>
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/rights2.gif" ALT="Copyright 1996 by American Lawyer Media, L.P. All Rights Reserved.">
