<HEAD>
<TITLE>Court TV On The Air</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A HREF="/map/ontheair.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/ontheair.gif" ISMAP ALT="Court TV On the Air" BORDER="0"></A>
<H3>Court TV Study Guide For December 1996 Class Action Program:<BR>
A White Supremacist on Trial: Murder or Self-Defense?</H3>

<P>CLASS ACTION AIRS ON COURT TV EVERY SATURDAY AT 4AM ET</P>

<b>Purpose</b><br>
To familiarize students with the legal issues of self-defense, premeditation and hate crimes, and to provoke discussion on whether a defendant's racial views can affect a jury's decision.<p>

<b>Brief Discussion Before Viewing</b><br>
Outline the basic details of the incident without making references to the race or employment of the two men involved. Do the students think George Loeb could have been acting in self-defense? Add the information that Loeb is white and Harold Mansfield is black. Do their views change? Now add that Loeb is a white supremacist and Mansfield was a Navy veteran just back from the Gulf War. Do these details make a difference? Should they?<p>

Discuss with students what they think premeditation means. How do they think a prosecutor proves a killing was premeditated?<p>

Review the four possible verdicts for this case: First Degree Murder (a premeditated killing); Second Degree Murder (intentional killing, but without premeditation); Manslaughter (killing with reckless disregard for human life); and Not Guilty (acted in self-defense). Review again after watching all the testimony and hearing the judge's definition of premeditation, but before the verdict is announced. How would the students vote if they were the jury? After the verdict discuss ways in which their views compare with those of the jury.<p>

<b>Legal Issues For Discussion After Viewing</b><br>
The judge determined before the trial started that he would allow evidence concerning Loeb's racial views to be admitted at the trial under the condition that they not become the focus of the trial. Why would some judges determine this evidence to be too "prejudicial" and not allow it? What does "prejudicial" mean? If the judge had not allowed Loeb's racial views as evidence in court, would the verdict have been different? If so, was it fair to allow it?<p>

The defense attorney had to make the decision on whether or not Loeb should take the stand in his own defense. Discuss the balance between the jury wanting to hear what happened directly from the defendant versus "opening the door" for the prosecution to bring in evidence concerning Loeb's background and asking him difficult questions on cross examination. Do you think Loeb helped or hindered his case by testifying?<p>

Some jury members stated after the verdict that they were not influenced by Loeb's racial views, but convicted him based on the eyewitnesses' testimony. Compare the eyewitnesses for the prosecution and the defense. Why did the jury consider the former to be more persuasive?<p>

How does a "premeditated" killing differ from a "planned" killing? In the judge's instructions to the jury, he states: "Killing with premeditation is killing after consciously deciding to do so. The decision must be present in the mind at the time of the killing. The law does not fix the exact period of time that must pass between the formation of the premeditated intent to kill and the killing."  How did the prosecution convince the jury that the killing was premeditated? What does it mean to say that George Loeb's motivation was premeditated?<p>

Loeb testified that he fled from Jacksonville after the shooting because he had no confidence in the criminal justice system. Does that affect your opinion about whether he is guilty or not?<p>

<b>Social Issues For Discussion</b><br>
What are "hate crimes?"  What are some examples of crimes that would fall under this category? Have there been incidents at your school that could be considered to be motivated by hate? How does your school treat such incidents? Why do you think these types of crimes are on the rise?<p>

How close to Loeb do you think Mansfield would have to be in order to feel Loeb was justified in shooting him? Are there any other actions Loeb could have taken instead of shooting Mansfield if he felt his life was threatened? Or do you think, as Loeb claims, he "had no other choice?"<p>

Did the fact that Mansfield returned to the parking lot with a friend after the first argument contribute to his own death? Is there such a thing as "he asked for it?"  Is that a justification for killing someone?<p>

Loeb's attorney admits that he does not share his client's racial views. How can he then represent him in this trial? Do attorneys have to "like" their clients? Should they believe they are not guilty?<p>

<b>Suggested Activity</b><br>
Many states have hate crime statutes. Find out if your state does, and what types of crimes fall into that category and how the penalties differ. Contact the nearest local office of the Anti-Defamation League (ADL) and the NAACP for information. (Most cities will have a local office; if not, contact the ADL in New York City -- they will send information and let you know if there is an office near you.) If so, invite a representative to come and speak to the class about the growing incidence of hate crimes, and how the courts in your state treats them.<p>

<HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT>
