<html><head><title>Seminars - Welcome to the Seminar</title>
</head> <BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#FF0005">
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/smb.gif" BORDER=0>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<h2>Welcome to the Seminar</h2>
<!--- full_start: 631--->
<H2>Corporate Compliance: Standards For The 21st Century</h2>







<H3>Seminar Discussion Thread</h3>











Over the next few weeks, lawyers on <A HREF="http://www.counsel.com/about.htm">LEXIS&#174  Counsel Connect<font size=-2><tt>(tm)</tt></font></A>, 







the largest online communications network for lawyers are participating in a special seminar devoted to a discussion of  "corporate compliance."







You are invited to "listen in" on the discussion here, and <a href=../../../../download/seminars/form1.html>submit proposed questions</a> to the participants. Here







is the introduction to the seminar as posted online for the lawyers on Lexis Counsel Connect.















<H3>Corporate Compliance Standards Project</h3>















The <A HREF="http://www.pacificrim.net/~ncpl/">National Center for Preventive Law (NCPL)</a> 







has begun a project that will produce a set of published "standards" for







corporate compliance programs.  The need for such standards stems







from the promulgation of the <EM>Federal Sentencing Guidelines for







Organizations</em> in 1991. Those Guidelines established that the







existence of an "effective compliance program" within an organization







would be an important factor in mitigating the consequences to the







organization for violations of criminal laws. The Guidelines,







however, offer little concrete direction as to what constitutes an







"effective compliance program." Organizations cannot look to decided







cases in search of guidance, since experience under the Guidelines







will develop slowly. And in any case, judicial descriptions of







compliance programs will of necessity focus on companies that in some







sense failed to prevent the offense in question.<p>















The Guidelines also create an unusual mixture of civil and criminal







legal concepts.  The standard of guilt for criminal acts is precise







and specific, but sentencing standards and the assessment of a







compliance program's adequacy takes the form of a "due diligence"







analysis, something akin to the amorphous civil law concept of







"reasonableness."  Thus, under the official Guidelines, adequate







compliance efforts are not precisely described in advance.<p> 















In 1994, the NCPL assembled a working group to address this problem.







The group is comprised of legal and compliance professionals from







corporations, law firms, consulting firms and universities. Its goal







is to create a set of "standards" that can be applied by







organizations of all types and sizes.  The NCPL Working Group is







cognizant of the widely-differing needs, circumstances and







capabilities of organizations, and alert to the message that a set of







"standards" might communicate to enforcement agencies and the







judiciary. The Group's purpose is therefore to create not minimum







requirements, but concrete interpretations and suggestions for the







design and operation of compliance programs.<p>















While the official Guidelines are directed at avoiding criminal







liability, the NCPL Working Group intends its standards to be of







benefit for both the prevention of criminal liability and for the







prevention of civil law consequences.  This is for two reasons. 







First, the overwhelming majority of legal problems experienced by







organizations occur in the civil law context. Second, it is a goal of







the U.S. Sentencing Commission, in promulgating its Guidelines, to







encourage the actions of organizations to prevent wrongdoing, not







merely to measure their sentences.<p>















<H3>Goals of the Seminar</h3>















The NCPL Working Group has two objectives in offering this seminar.







One is to make available to involved persons the results of the







substantial work it has done thus far.  The second objective is to







gather from seminar participants additional concrete examples and







illustrations of steps the business and legal communities have taken







in designing and operating systems for corporate compliance. 







Participants are therefore invited to contribute two things --







critique and implementation examples.  The end product -- a published







set of standards that are relevant and meaningful to corporate







clients -- will be in the form of detailed and concrete suggestions







to create practical corporate compliance programs.<p>















The Working Group's product, as it now stands, is a set of <EM>Twenty







Principles</em> with accompanying <EM>"Considerations."</em> The 







Considerations articulate in detail the Principles.  The Working Group 







is now collecting implementation examples, which will further articulate each







Consideration.<p>















This is how seminar participants can contribute to the project.  Each







day of this seminar one or more of the Principles and their







Considerations will be posted.  A commentary will also be appended







explaining the aspect of the Guidelines which the Principles and







Considerations address. We would appreciate your review,







consideration and response to any of the Principles or







Considerations.<p>  















You can also participate by sharing your company's own implementation







examples. 







Examples contributed should be as concrete and practical as possible,







providing real-life compliance program features. (Drafting







suggestions and a model example will follows this introduction.)<p>















In addition to the model and list of NCPL Principles posted below, we







also set out today an <EM>excerpt from the United States Sentencing 







Commission's Federal Sentencing Guidelines for Organizations</em>. This







excerpt  sets out the factors to consider and the due diligence steps







relating to an "effective compliance program." <p>















Members of the NCPL will be online to react to questions and







comments. A short biographical sketch of each moderator is posted







separately.<p>















<h4>None of these materials may be reproduced without the permission of the NCPL, Lexis Counsel Connect, and Court TV.</h4>















The NCPL seeks as broad an exposure as possible to this work. You are







encouraged to involve your non-lawyer colleagues and relate their







reactions as well as your own. Any non-LCC persons can contact the







<A HREF="http://www.pacificrim.net/~ncpl/">NCPL</a> office by telephone 







at 303-871-6099, by mail at 1900 Olive Street, Denver, CO  80220 or by







Internet e-mail to <A HREF="mailto:msalazar@counsel.com">msalazar@counsel.com</a>.



<hr><p>



