<html><head><title>Seminars - NCPL Model Implementation Example</title>
</head> <BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#FF0005">
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/smb.gif" BORDER=0>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<h2>NCPL Model Implementation Example</h2>
<!--- full_start: 652--->
<H2>Corporate Compliance: Standards For The 21st Century</h2><p>







<H3>Seminar Discussion Thread</h3><p>







<H3>Drafting Company Implementation Examples</h3><p>











<A HREF="http://www.pacificrim.net/~ncpl/">NCPL</a> is following the 







format below for examples it is including in







its final publication.  While those commenting are encouraged to use







this format, examples in any format are welcome.  The main objective







is to create the maximum response.  NCPL reserves the right to alter







examples submitted to achieve the desired format.<p>















<H4>These materials may not be reproduced without the permission of the



NCPL.</h4><p>















DRAFTING FORMAT SUGGESTIONS (AN ACTUAL MODEL FOLLOWS):<p> 







1.  Each example should be 3-4 sentences in length;<p> 















2.  The first sentence in each should identify the design decision or







factor within the prior consideration that the example relates to;<p> 















3.  The second sentence in each should explain what approach to that







design decision or factor the example will illustrate;<p> 















4.  The third and fourth sentence should describe a specific







compliance system design choice or implementation that illustrates







one resolution of the issue that is the overall subject of the







example.<p> 















<H3>Model Implementation Example for Principle 9, Consideration (a)</h3>















<H4>Principle #9<p>







An effective compliance program has the support of the senior







management of the organization. Each officer, manager and employee is







responsible for supporting and complying with the compliance







program's standards and procedures.</h4><p> 















Factors to Consider:<p> 















<H4>Consideration (a)<p>







Having participation in and support for the program throughout







the organization and not limited to the compliance officer.</h4>















<H3>Example 1</h3>







<H4>Participation throughout an organization means attention







to compliance in operational practices at every management level.  In







the midst of other performance pressures that are typical of middle







management environments, corporate managers at low levels in







corporate hierarchies may only address compliance concerns and







translate them into operational directions to their superiors if







those managers know that these activities will be monitored by higher







management. Thus, to encourage company-wide compliance, one large







corporation conducts audits of management performance in which each







manager is specifically asked to produce his or her copy of basic







company policies and to explain how the manager informs employees of







the policies.</h4>



<hr><p>



