<html><head><title>Seminars - Taxpayer Compliance Measurement Program</title>
</head> <BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#FF0005">
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/smb.gif" BORDER=0>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<h2>Taxpayer Compliance Measurement Program</h2>
<!--- full_start: 649--->
<H2>Corporate Compliance: Standards For The 21st Century</h2><p>



<H3>Seminar Discussion Thread</h3><p>





From: Bernard Wolfman -- Harvard Law School - Cambridge<br>



Date:  Tue Oct 24 08:50<br>



Subject:  TCMP IRS Audits<p>



Taxpayer Compliance Measurement Program (TCMP) audits fingered



particular taxpayers for a special type of audit, one that



required the [taxpayer] to document every single item on its return.

Most observers concluded that these audits provided the Government

with extraordinarily useful statistical data on compliance.

Although not used for the past several years, the IRS had planned



to resume TCMP audits on December 1, covering 150,000 taxpayers

for the year 1994.  But yesterday the IRS announced it was



"indefinitely postponing" the program resumption in order to save



the $1.5 billion it would cost, this in light of Congressional

budget cutting.  Most people in the know, although not all,



believe that by killing TCMP audits the Government's ultimate loss



in compliance, particularly corporate compliance, will cost it



far more than the $1.5 billion it will save.<p>



<hr><p>



Appended by: John Voorhees -- Isaacson Rosenbaum - Denver<br>



Date: Tue Oct 24 10:38:21 1995<br>





Subject: TCMP IRS Audits<p>



I am  not in a position to know whether the TCMP audit program



should or should not be either eliminated or even postponed. I am

interested in the type of information contained in tax returns



that could be used by the government  against a corporate taxpayer 

to demonstrate non-compliance in regulatory proceedings.  For



example, can the government use information collected from a tax



return to obtain proof of an environmental violation. I thought



there was a prohibition against that type of activity. What should



companies do in creating compliance programs that insure the

filing of accurate tax returns?<p>



<hr><p>

Appended by: Bernard Wolfman -- Harvard Law School - Cambridge<br>





Date: Tue Oct 24 16:04:05 1995<br>



Subject: Tax Return Information<p>





It is generally prohibited for tax return information to be





divulged by IRS personnel to other branches of Government for any





purpose.  There is a narrow exception band, and it requires





approval at the highest level, rarely applicable.<p>

Among other things, a corporation's employee incentives, for those





in the tax department, must not be gauged on how little tax is





declared but on how accurate the return ends up.  Many of the





largest corporations, year after year, pay additional tax on





audit, just waiting to see if the revenue agent picks up the





dubious item.  The interest paid, along with the tax principal





when the agent finds an item, is usually less than the corporation





is able to earn on the principal, and so it pays to wait and see.





And it is also often an intra-corporate brownie point if a dubious





item claimed on a return escapes notice.  That culture would need





to be changed to meet what Mr. Vorhees seeks.<p>



<hr><p>



Appended by: Susan Kohn Ross -- Ross & Associates - Los Angeles<br>

Date: Fri Oct 27 12:19:50 1995<br>

Subject: Access to Tax Returns<p>



You should be aware that there is a provision in the law which

allows the I.R.S. to make copies of returns available to U.S.

Customs under strict provisions in order that Customs may carry

out its audit functions and for the purposes of determining

whether or not violations of law have occurred.<p>



For more details, e-mail me <A HREF="mailto:skohnxro@counsel.com">skohnxro@counsel.com</a>.

<hr><p>



