<html><head><title>Seminars - What is a Compliance Program?</title>
</head> <BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#FF0005">
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/smb.gif" BORDER=0>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<h2>What is a Compliance Program?</h2>
<!--- full_start: 648--->
<H2>Corporate Compliance: Standards For The 21st Century</h2><p>







<H3>Seminar Discussion Thread</h3><p>











From: Rick Bulman -- FL Counsel Connect - Miami<BR>







Date:  Mon Oct 23 17:10<BR>







Subject:  What is a Compliance Program?<P>







OK, I confess. I get this uncomfortable feeling with the term







"corporate compliance". In one way I feel it's sort of a new wave







psycho babble marketing pitch for lawyers trying to sell services







to corporations. (Like corporate "wellness" programs which are







simply ways to sell people on expanded insurance programs that







"save" money in the long run. "Uh right, I went broke while







getting well...".) I also get this overtone of "time-motion







studies" - standardized principles that enable all corporations to







do X with Y for Z. Except no company ever fits into X, Y or Z and







the solutions proposed are just more rules and regs that create







layer upon layer upon layer of paper from which to say, "Hey, what







are you, a dope? Try a little common sense." On the other hand it







would be nice to try and head off a few problems at the pass







without having to constantly justify oneself or to refer to a







guidebook the size of the Congressional record for a Mom & Pop







store. So, what really is this stuff? Who uses it? Why is it good?<p>







<hr><p>







Appended by: Edward Dauer -- Denver Law School - Denver<br>







Date: Mon Oct 23 18:55:28 1995<br>







Subject: What's a Compliance Program?<p>







A fundamental question.  Thanks for asking it.<p>







It goes like this.  First, it is usually (but not always) the case







that preventing legal trouble (criminal violations and civil







liability) is more efficient, for the client, than is fixing legal







trouble after it arises.<p>







Second, it is correct that no two business organizations are







alike.  That becomes relevant to the legal-risk-prevention







business in a direct way, since the origin of legal risk usually







lies in the behavior of people.  If organizations are unlike, then







no one-size-fits-all way of addressing risk should be expected to







be very effective anywhere.<p>







Third, reinventing wheels is also inefficient.  If each of us







tried to create for each of our clients a legal risk prevention







(or minimization) program, tailored to each client's needs, we







could not do so at any acceptable cost to the client.<p>







Fourth, and here's the turning point, we believe that while the







gears and gizmos of prevention can't be one-size-fits-all, there







are common denominators -- i.e., principles that can be identified







as having positive effects in reducing legal risk.  The thrust of







the effort is therefore to identify those principles and to offer







them to others.  New applications thus have a place to start.<p>







There is nothing new in this.  It's just good management applied







to legal affairs.  And the idea of principles vs. practices isn't







new either.  For example, everyone knows that an auditor should be







independent of the person being audited.  That's at the level of







principle (though a pretty obvious one).  The elaborate structures







we see in corporations that are created to achieve that







desideratum are just specific applications of the general, and







replicable, principle.  We (at NCPL) believe there are a number of







useful, identifiable principles which can be articulated and







implemented in many particular ways, and which can lead to the







efficient reduction of legal risk.<p>







Years after this process began, the Federal Sentencing Commission







validated the notion by offering substantial mitigations in fines







otherwise assessed for corporate crimes, if the corporation







had put into place a system that was reasonably well designed to







serve as a legal-risk-preventive or compliance system.  The







problem with the FSG's guidelines is, that some people believe







they are too vague; and you won't find out if your efforts







qualify until after the fact.  If that is so, the trick is how to







create more useful and concrete ideas about workable







techniques for compliance -- i.e. legal risk reduction -- without







getting into the errors of the one-size-fits-all approach.<p>







That's why we're here.<p>







E. A. Dauer<br>







National Center for Preventive Law<p>







<hr><p>







Appended by: Scott Lehecka -- Atlantic Richfield - Los Angeles<br>







Date: Tue Oct 24 12:01:16 1995<br>







Subject: What is a Compliance Program?<p>







Good point.  Common sense goes a long way, usually a lot farther







than a fat compliance manual that only one person in a hundred has







read (and what kind of work is he doing??)<p>







It seems to me that all of the compliance programs, training







courses, manuals, memos, etc., are trying to accomplish two







things:<p>







No. 2: to convey information about legal requirements and what to







do to comply.<p>







No. 1: to get across the message (on a gut level, as part of the







organization's culture) that compliance is important, and that







each employee has the responsibility and authority to do something







about it.<p>







Number 1 is the more important, because that's what will make







people alert to use their common sense and the information they







get in training.  And even though this seems simplistic and







obvious, the message seems to get lost.  (Let's face it, "common"







sense often isn't, and if compliance were that easy, everybody







except the deliberate violators would have no trouble with







compliance.)  One training meeting a year doesn't demonstrate to







employees that this is a priority among the thousand other things







they have to do.<p>







It takes repetition and attention to keep sending the message that







compliance matters, but in running the programs, there is a danger







of burying people in more information than they need (message # 2)







and losing sight of the fact that the real point is simple: keep







paying attention.<p>







<hr><p>







Appended by: Chris Lemens -- The Continuum Co. - Austin<br>







Date: Tue Oct 24 12:14:38 1995<br>







Subject: What is a Compliance Program?<p>







The points being made about teaching ethical intuition ("gut level







instincts") is important.  As part of the compliance program that







my company is drafting, we are thinking about including (and thus







legitimizing) a "smell test" that I have shamelessly plagiarized







from Texas Instruments, then renamed.  The formal elements are







listed below, but the concept is intended to guide employees when







the written materials don't cover the problem or cover it







ambiguously and they can't get immediate help.  (E.g. competitor's







salesman says to our salesman at a bar, "We're thinking of revising







our price for Competitor's Product.  What are you guys charging







for Your Product?")  The point of each of the elements is







indicated parenthetically.<p>







1)      Is it legal?  (Refer to the law.  Often they won't know, but







will have a decent idea that it isn't.)<p>







2)      Does it comply with our values?  (Refer to our mission







statement, etc.)<p>







3)      Is it wrong?  (Refer to employee's articulable values.)<p>







4)      If you do it, will you feel bad?  (Refer to employee's







unarticulated values.)<p>







5)      How would it look in the newspaper?  (Refer to society's







values.)<p>







6)      If you're not sure, what did the people you asked say?  (Make







them seek advice.)<p>







Any comments or additions?<p>







Chris Lemens<br>



clemens0@counsel.com<p>







<hr><p>







Appended by: Keith Fisher -- Law Offices - Washington<br>







Date: Tue Oct 24 16:24:35 1995<br>







Subject: What is a Compliance Program?<p>







As I read these comments, two things strike me.<p>







First, mediating between "common sense" and a telephone book-sized



compliance manual that few (if anyone) will read before-the-fact



(obviously reading it after-the-fact rather defeats the purpose,



like shutting the barn door after the horse has bolted) suggests



the need for some kind of training program for each and every



employee whose job description is such that his acts or omissions



may result in substantial noncompliance.   (In other words, it



probably will not be necessary to require compliance training for



mailroom clerks, messengers, or other employees whose



responsibilities give rise to no reasonable risk of



noncompliance).  Whether such a training program is done in-house



by a full-time compliance officer, is outsourced to consultants,



uses fancy video or software programs or other bells and whistles,



is designed for repeat or refresher courses on an annual or other



periodic basis, etc. are all things that are likely to be highly



individualized decisions for each company.<p>







Second, there are undoubtedly different levels of compliance



programs and compliance training that are appropriate for



different industries, depending upon the type of regulation to



which that industry is subject.  For years I have represented



clients in the financial services industries (commercial banks,



investment banks, savings institutions, their holding companies,



etc.), which are highly regulated.  Banks in particular are



inundated with compliance issues and a particularly high



regulatory burden, and the risks of noncompliance are not limited



to possible sentencing consequences in the (relatively rare) event



of criminal misconduct but include a panoply of  civil enforcement



powers that federal regulators have in their arsenal.  



Noncompliance with certain types of regulatory requirements may



produce lesser consequences than noncompliance with others.  In



banking, for example, noncompliance with the Community



Reinvestment Act often will not lead to any particularly harsh



regulatory sanction; in contrast, as the past three years have



shown, any kind of lending discrimination (even unintentional) can



have very serious consequences indeed.  I suspect that, as



virtually all industries are regulated at some level (i.e., by



federal, state, or local agencies or some combination thereof), it



should be possible to design certain basic compliance programs



that are not merely firm-specific but have industrywide



application.  The question then becomes how many people within



each organization need to be familiar with that level of detail,



and what kinds of simplified guidelines can be prepared to give



the requisite collection of mental "red flags" to the rest of the



employees?<p>







<hr><p>







Appended by: John Voorhees -- Isaacson Rosenbaum - Denver<br>







Date: Tue Oct 24 18:28:56 1995<br>







Subject: What is a Compliance Program?<p>







Responding to Chris Lemens' six questions:  Each of these



questions tests the effectiveness of the compliance efforts of the



company. If the employee stops and seeks advice from the right



source the program works. NCPL's principles and considerations are



designed to  assist  the creation of a program that when



implemented operates effectively.  I read these questions as



reminders for employees who need to familiarize themselves with



the compliance program generally and then learn how to gauge their



actions accordingly. If the employee when confronted with  an



ethical  dilemma or compliance problem  stops and asks himself or



herself  one or more of these questions the program is working.

<hr><p>



<CENTER><I><A HREF="http://www.courttv.com/download/seminars/form1.html">

Submit your question or comment to the discussion</i>.</a></center>

