<html><head><title>Seminars - Training [employees in compliance]</title>
</head> <BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#FF0005">
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/smb.gif" BORDER=0>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<h2>Training [employees in compliance]</h2>
<!--- full_start: 647--->
<H2>Corporate Compliance: Standards For The 21st Century</h2><p>











<H3>Seminar Discussion Thread</h3><p>











From: Daniel Bishop -- Western Atlas, Inc. - Beverly Hills<br>











Date:  Mon Oct 23 12:50<br>











Subject:  Training<p>











As the Director of  Compliance for my corporation I have found the











creation and initial implementation of a Compliance Program to be











relatively easy. What has turned out to be difficult has been











keeping awareness of the Program at a sufficiently high level. I











had hoped to accomplish this through  various training courses but











the logistics of providing them in a consistent and meaningful way











at  worldwide locations has proved difficult. What would be most











helpful would be an interactive training program that can be used











by the individual users on their own PCs. A program of this nature











exists in the DOD contractor environment, however the











non-recurring charge plus the need for specialized equipment plus











the fact that a large portion of the training material is unique











to government contractors make it unattractive for the commercial











corporation. Does anyone know of any interactive training











materials relating to business ethics? For those of you with











children, we need the adult equivalent of  "Where in the World is











Carmen SanDiego?"<p>











<hr><p>











Appended by: Edward Dauer -- Denver Law School - Denver<br>











Date: Mon Oct 23 15:52:54 1995<br>











Subject: Interactive Training<p>











Two pieces of information should soon be coming your way.  I have











asked our research department (Department?  It's two people, named











Greg and Michele) to do some bibliographic research for you in our











own resources.  We will share what we find.  By the way, we hope











to make some of this kind of service available throughout the











seminar.  Second, on another wavelength I learned that Kirk Jordan











has actually done just this sort of thing; I have invited Kirk to











stop by here and append something on the subject to your thread.











You should hear from him soon.<p>











E. A. Dauer, NCPL<p>











<hr><p>











Appended by: Kirk Jordan -- Compliance Systems - Warwick<br>











Date: Tue Oct 24 11:21:01 1995<br>











Subject: Interactive Training<p>











Dan --<p>











As Ed mentioned, at Compliance Systems Legal Group we recently











developed a PC based interactive video program for legal











compliance and business ethics training.  We custom developed the











program for a manufacturing company with about 10,000 employees at











dispersed locations.  The program is designed to introduce all of











the company's employees and agents to the company's formal











compliance program, by describing the major components of the











program (i.e., who is the compliance officer, how the company's











"hotline" works),  and by placing employees, through the use of











video scenarios, in "on the job" compliance situations.  In order











to navigate successfully through the scenarios, employees are











required to make the right choices.  If  an employee chooses the











wrong answer,   a reteaching segment  or consequentiality video











follows. The company is reporting great success in implementing











the program.<p>











The entire course is interactive, requiring employee participation











and response throughout.  Like many of the programs developed by











the Defense Industry Initiative companies, our program features











video as the dominant multimedia medium.  In our experience,











employees greatly prefer video over traditional text based CBT.











Because these interactive training programs run on computers,











comprehensive and flexible training records can be easily











generated.<p>











As I mentioned, this program was custom developed.  I am not aware











of any generic interactive training programs for business ethics











and legal compliance (although we have been kicking around the











idea of developing some generic modules, that could be











"customized").  There are, of course, some generic interactive











"compliance" training modules in discrete substantive areas -- for











example, OSHA and sexual harassment.  But I question whether the











government would consider "effective" a training program that











utilized only generic training modules -- particularly for a large











company.<p>











If you (or anybody else) would like more information on the











program, feel free to post another comment, call me ((401)











738-3666), or <A HREF="mailto:kjorda00@counsel.com">e-mail me (kjorda00@counsel.com)</a>.<p>











Also, stay tuned to the corporate compliance seminar: in the











coming days we will discuss many compliance training and











communications issues (see particularly principles/considerations











16-20), and perhaps we'll hear from others on what they have found











to be effective means of communicating compliance standards in











their organizations.<p>











<hr><p>











Appended by: Ira Moskatel -- Atty - Ira Moskatel - Los Angeles<br>





Date: Tue Oct 24 18:47:23 1995<br>





Subject: Reference materials<p>











I've had some success in creating computerized materials for legal





compliance in relatively narrow areas, particularly trade





regulation, and securities regulations. When properly set up,





these have the effect of a training program, even though they





don't attempt to emulate a classroom program.<p>











In one trade regulation system, the delivery vehicle on its





surface was a document assembly/quasi expert system used to





prepare work product. The user interface, however, was structured





to teach the underlying regulatory scheme and was supported by a





"help" system which provided explanations and a research system





which organized and presented the case law illustrating the





particular point. The system is being used in a large law





department and is accessible to non-lawyers as well in a variation





which does not permit the production of legal work product.<p>











When new hires or transfers are first exposed to the area, they





are trained to use the system by being given hypothetical cases





which they work through the process. If the user attempts to





do something which is not permitted by the regulations, the





system will identify the anomaly and, in many cases, propose





an alternative strategy. Each of the steps is presented to them





and a supervisor goes over the work product. The result is that





the compliance program is built into the process for creating the





work product.<p>











The missing element from such a system is *indoctrination*, a key





part of any compliance system. When I put the substantive law





materials together for the system, I focused on underlying





rationales for the regulatory scheme. When I interviewed senior





lawyers responsible for managing the compliance program, however,





I discovered conflicting attitudes toward compliance overall.





Instead of indoctrinating their staff with the underlying concerns





of the regulatory scheme, their approach was "teach them how to





dodge the bullets and get through."<p>











Overall, the system has been successful, but I would





rather have inculcated a set of compliance values. I believe that





the result would be less dissonance when the system explained the





inappropriateness of a particular tactic, and thus a higher level





of compliance and less wasted time.<p>











<hr><p>











Appended by: Aileen R. Leventon -- Atty-Leventon, A. - New York<br>





Date: Wed Oct 25 00:13:41 1995<br>





Subject: On-Line Training<p>











Does using the company's network count as interactive training?





While I was at Equitable Life, I formulated the company's first





insider trading compliance and education program.  The company had





just gone public (in 1992), so we had the opportunity to start





from scratch, but with considerable learning from others.  I was





struck by the typical approach of paper-based communication with





employees to announce and disseminate policies.  I used this





because it was the norm.<p>











But then I added another feature:  I used the company's network





(that housed the e-mail and internal communications system) and





created a bulletin board (like the Discuss menu at Counsel





Connect) called "Equitable stock information."  I provided





information on that bulletin board of interest to employees:





daily stock price, commission free purchase program details,





dividend reinvestment plan data.  But you had to scroll through a





"warning notice" first, that stated that there are special rules





that apply to purchases and sales of the company's stock.  The





next statement referred to the insider trading policy, and then





stated that if you hit a keyboard key, you could immediately





access the policy statement.<p>











This provided immediately available information on the policy,





avoided excuses about the thick manual or loss of paper (which





most employees, don't read anyway) and became very popular,





because the lure was in providing information to employees that





was useful and relevant to them.<p>











We found that employees read this bulletin board more than any





other -- even the job posting board.<p>











<hr><p>











