Appended by: Cloyd Laporte, III -- Counsel Connect - New York<br>

Date: Wed Nov  8 08:58:45 1995<br>

Subject: From Corval, Inc.<p>



[The following comment was submitted from an individual reading

the transcript of this seminar on the Small Business Law Center on

the Court TV Law Center. - Cloyd]<p>



FROM: Tom McQueen C Ph.D.<br>

TITLE: President and CEO<br>

<A HREF="mailto:us013394@interramp.com">EMAIL: us013394@interramp.com</a><br>

COMPANY: CorVal, Inc.<br>

PHONE: 1-800-677-8258<p>



Concerning interactive training for compliance programs, there are

a number of nationwide organizations like ours that provide these

services. However, at a recent seminar entitled "Corporate Crime

in America - Strengthening the 'Good Citizen' Corporation,"

sponsored by the United States Sentencing Commission, I was

impressed by the research conducted by The Council of Ethical

Organizations. In assessing training programs that were effective

vs. ineffective, or harmful, the study concluded that "training

programs delivered primarily by means of video and interactive

technology and in game format were ineffective or harmful. However,

training programs that were 'interactive' over one contact hour in

length, and periodically repeated  were effective." Please see our

upcoming article in the December issue of the <I>Preventive Law

Reporter</i> entitled <STRONG>GAMES TRAINERS PLAY</strong> in which we discuss,

among other things, how to make compliance training interesting,

meaningful, and very practical.<p>



<hr><p>



Appended by: Joe Murphy -- Bell Atlantic - Philadelphia<br>


Date: Mon Nov 13 15:40:33 1995<br>


Subject: From Corval, Inc.<p>





To Tom McQueen,<p>





Corporate Conduct Quarterly, of Rutgers University,  published


the results of the Council's study in Vol. 3, issue 4, along with


a piece by me raising questions about the study.  While I agree


that some training techniques are better than others, and that


games, video, etc, should not be used on a stand-alone basis, I


have some skepticism about the broadness of  Mark Pastin's


conclusions.  For example, it would take some powerful study


techniques to convince me that computer-based training actually


<STRONG>increases</strong> the likelihood of violations.  I think Pastin does not


take into account the effectiveness of such techniques in helping


employees to retain important information on such technical areas


as government contract compliance.   We need more research on what


really works in the compliance area, but we should be very careful


about drawing conclusions from such early studies.<p>





Anyone interested in seeing the CCQ pieces or finding out more


about the Quarterly should call 609 225-6311.<p>





