<html><head><title>Seminars - Principle No. 1 - Establishing a Program</title>
</head> <BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#FF0005">
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/smb.gif" BORDER=0>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<h2>Principle No. 1 - Establishing a Program</h2>
<!--- full_start: 644--->
<H2>Corporate Compliance: Standards For The 21st Century</h2><p>







<H3>Seminar Discussion Thread</h3><p>







From: Christina Cooley -- Counsel Connect - Atlanta<br>





Date:  Mon Oct 23 21:48<br>





Subject:  PR. 1-Establishing a Program<p>







This is how seminar participants can contribute to the





project.  Each day of this seminar one or more of the







Principles and their Considerations will be posted.  A







commentary will also be appended explaining the aspect of















the Guidelines which the Principles and Considerations











address.  We would appreciate your review, consideration











and response to any of the Principles and Considerations.<p>



You can also participate by sharing your company's own







implementation examples.  Examples contributed should be



as concrete and practical as possible, providing real-life



compliance program features.  (Drafting suggestions and a







model example are located in this discussion group.)<p>







<H4>NATIONAL CENTER FOR PREVENTIVE LAW WORKING GROUP DRAFT</h4>







<H3>Establishing Compliance Programs</h3>











<I>Note: Principle 1 and its Considerations are intended to







address the following aspect of the <a href=../../../../download/seminars/fsg1.html>











Federal Sentencing Guidelines:  Sec. 8A1.2(k)(1)</a>:  "The Organization must have











established compliance standards and procedures to be followed







by its employees and other agents that are reasonably capable



of reducing the prospect of criminal conduct."</i><p>







<H4>Principle 1.  Organizations should pursue compliance through



the creation and maintenance of an effective compliance







program.</h4>







Factors to Consider:<p>



(a) Creating a program that is built on pre-existing



organizational values and practices, so that the program reflects,







incorporates and is integrated with an organization's culture,







ethos and corporate objectives.<p>







(b) Designing a program that is tailored in formality and scope







to the size, form and history of an organization.<p>



(c) Identifying the types of legal requirements most commonly







affecting an organization and its operations.<p>







(d) Reviewing the need for special compliance components based on







an organization's history of violations (if any), the legal risks







inherent in the operations of the organization, industry standards







and regulatory regimes, federal sentencing commission standards



and other governmental standards describing desirable components







of compliance systems.<p>



(e) Directing organization members toward compliance through



compliance codes, operating standards, codes of ethics, and other











corporate policy and philosophy statements.<p>







(f) Setting forth program definitions and operating practices in







writing and disseminating program descriptions through manuals and







other appropriate media.<p>







(g) Memorializing specific steps taken in the implementation and







operation of a compliance program so as to create a record of



organizational attention to compliance.<p>







(h) Including systematic record making and document retention







practices in organizational operations that will aid in monitoring







organizational compliance and in demonstrating the completion of







compliance procedures.<p>







We urge you to submit comments and examples about the above



Principle.  To assist you in this, please review the postings



from the first day of the seminar, October 23, on the <a href=../../../../download/seminars/fsg1.html>Federal







Sentencing Guidelines</a>, the <a href=../../../../download/seminars/principle1.html>Full Set of Principles</a> and the <a href=../../../../download/seminars/model1.html>Model







Example</a>. Please note that the Principles and Considerations are







copyrighted by the NCPL and may not be reproduced without



permission of the NCPL.<p>











<hr><p>



Appended by: Thomas Roehlk -- Premark Intl., Inc. - Deerfield<br>







Date: Tue Oct 24 09:08:31 1995<br>







Subject: PR. 1-Establishing a Program<p>



Let me start things off by offering an example of Consideration







(d) to Principle 1:<p>







The food equipment industry has a standard-setting body and







"listing"  agents which address, among other things, the food







adulteration concerns of the Federal Food, Drug and Cosmetics Act.







The standards set by the National Sanitation Foundation have







aspects which are intended to prevent food equipment materials,



components and designs from containing toxic materials as







identified by FDA regulations.  A manufacturer which elects to







have its products "listed" to such standards by organizations like







the National Sanitation Foundation or Underwriters Laboratories







accomplishes two worthwhile outcomes under Considerations 1(d).



First, it manufactures product to an industry standard which has



had careful development with the involvement of the regulatory



authorities.  Second, it agrees in its listing agreement to (i)



submit to the listing agency its specifications and to maintain







the same throughout the manufacturing process, and (ii) subject







itself to periodic compliance audits by the listing agent, which







is an independent, external organization of the type that FDA



enforcement officials have recommended be a part of company



compliance measures.<p>







<hr><p>







Appended by: Mary Rose Pica -- Hobart Corporation - Troy<br>



Date: Tue Oct 24 12:59:49 1995<br>



Subject: Communication<p>







It is important that knowledge of laws applicable to the







particular industry be fully communicated and accepted within the



organization.  For example, one of our subsidiaries manufactures



food equipment to be sold to the consumer market.  The Consumer











Product Safety Act applies to the product line.  The requirements







of the law were reviewed in detail with the key managers of the



subsidiary.  Procedures are now being implemented to assure that



the company continues to be in compliance.<p>



<hr><p>



Appended by: Daniel Bishop -- Western Atlas, Inc. - Beverly Hills<br>







Date: Wed Oct 25 17:22:58 1995<br>



Subject: PR. 1-Establishing a Program<p>







Your NCPL principles are obviously well thought out and well



crafted; however, I would pose a basic question going to the premise



of the project, namely does it  substantially add anything to the







template for a Compliance Program provided by the [FSG]. It would







seem that a careful reading and understanding of the [FSG] followed



by the crafting of a program to meet, in some form, each of the



identified criteria would result in a satisfactory program. Since



the director of the company's program is to be a senior company



official it would seem as though this individual would be well



placed to develop a program that is best suited for that



particular company. In short, I am not sure the creation of a



program is all that difficult; it is the day to day running  of











the program that is hard.<p>







<hr><p>







Appended by: John Voorhees -- Isaacson Rosenbaum - Denver<br>



Date: Wed Oct 25 19:37:11 1995<br>



Subject: PR. 1-Establishing a Program<p>







Dan: speaking for myself as a member of the NCPL Commission that



has been drafting the principles of corporate compliance and not



for the full Commission let me address your comment as follows.



For the last several years since the [Federal Sentencing Guidelines] were promulgated



there has been a compelling need for businesses to create



compliance programs  not only to avoid stiff penalties for



criminal violations but also to prevent  criminal violations from



occurring as well as to minimize civil liability. Many of us have



done what you have suggested and studied the [FSGs] criteria and



used other materials for guidance in creating programs for clients



and for our own companies.   NCPL found that there were persons



quite knowledgeable in this area who could pool their collective



experience and develop common principles and considerations that



could be useful to all companies of whatever size  who were



interested in achieving compliance in a hostile regulatory



environment.   Many companies even with excellent compliance



programs have encountered  problems in implementing their



programs. For  these reasons and more  it was decided to attempt



to draft principles  and considerations that would be helpful to



all companies  who wanted to make a real commitment to achieving



compliance. The [FSGs] only specify the "types of steps" a company



must take "at a minimum" to create an effective compliance



program. The [FSGs] alone do not provide a complete answer how to



achieve compliance nor do they adequately address serious issues



of avoidance of civil liability. The principles and considerations



drafted by the Commission are not intended to set minimum



standards in this regard but they are intended to  provide as much



common experience as possible to aid the development of effective



compliance programs at  minimal cost.<p>



John Voorhees.<p>



<hr><p>



Appended by: Herb Zinn -- AZ Public Service - Phoenix<br>

Date: Sat Oct 28 10:14:39 1995<br>

Subject: PR. 1-Establishing a Program<p>



Dan, I generally agree with your perspective, but the Devil is in

the Details, as they say, and there is not enough detail in the

FSG's to give the newcomer or the unwary enough perspective to

develop a program and run it in the first pass.  Witness the

complexities of the Draft Environmental Guidelines that the USSC

has been considering.<p>



I could type on and on but I will spare you.  Your perspective

was one consideration in the article I authored about 

<A HREF="http://www.courttv.com/legalhelp/business/seminar/634.html">nuclear

weapons systems and compliance programs</a>.  It's in the Library for

this seminar.  I would recommend you look it over.  It relates in

large part to the points you have raised in your note.

