<html><head><title>Seminars - Principle No. 2 - Promote Legal Compliance</title>
</head> <BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#FF0005">
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/smb.gif" BORDER=0>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<h2>Principle No. 2 - Promote Legal Compliance</h2>
<!--- full_start: 656--->
<H2>Corporate Compliance: Standards For The 21st Century</h2><p>



<H3>Seminar Discussion Thread</h3><p>



From: Christina Cooley -- Counsel Connect - Atlanta<br>

Date:  Tue Oct 24 18:08<br>

Subject:  PR. 2-Promote Legal Compliance<p>



<H4>NATIONAL CENTER FOR PREVENTIVE LAW WORKING GROUP DRAFT</h4>



<H3>Establishing Compliance Programs, Continued. . .</h3>



<I>Note:  Principle #2 and its Considerations are intended to

address the following aspect of the <a href=../../../../download/seminars/fsg1.html>

Federal Sentencing Guidelines:  Sec. 8A1.2(k)(1)</a>:  "The Organization must have

established compliance standards and procedures to be followed

by its employees and other agents that are reasonably capable

of reducing the prospect of criminal conduct."</i><p>



<H4>Principle #2:  An effective compliance program is designed to

prevent, detect and respond to legal risks and to promote

compliance with the law.</h4>



Factors to Consider:<p>



(a) Identifying liability-causing conduct based on industry or

organizational experience, as well as the occasions for such

conduct.<p>



(b) Locating non-obvious offenses and incipient misconduct that

tends to promote illegal actions.<p>



(c) Scrutinizing incentive practices that inadvertently promote

immoral, unethical or illegal activities.<p>



(d) Structuring compliance practices to be effective, while

still protecting and enhancing an organization's business,

assets and goodwill and preserving legal privileges and rights

possessed by the organization.<p>



We urge you to submit comments and examples about the above



Principle.  To assist you in this, please review the postings



from the first day of the seminar, October 23, on the <a href=../../../../download/seminars/fsg1.html>Federal



Sentencing Guidelines</a>, the <a href=../../../../download/seminars/principle1.html>Full Set of Principles</a> and the <a href=../../../../download/seminars/model1.html>Model



Example</a>. Please note that the Principles and Considerations are



copyrighted by the NCPL and may not be reproduced without



permission of the NCPL.<p>



<hr><p>



Appended by: Susan Kohn Ross -- Ross & Associates - Los

Angeles<br>

Date: Tue Oct 24 19:58:30 1995<br>

Subject: Need for Compliance Programs<p>



The need for corporate compliance programs is coming from a number

of federal agencies which regulate the way businesses operate. For

example, in the environmental area the use of compliance programs

has exploded over the last three to four years.<p>



In the export licensing area, the existence of corporate

compliance programs is mandatory in order to avoid criminal

problems. The use of corporate compliance programs is now being

urged by U.S. Customs as part of its new philosophy known as the

Mod Act, the second part of the NAFTA legislation. Although no

detailed regulations have yet been published, there are provisions

in the law which lower or eliminate civil penalties  if the

company has in place a compliance program which the agency

approves. Criminal penalties can be avoided or lessened on the

same basis.<p>



This discussion group has brought up compliance programs regarding

the Federal Sentencing Guidelines and FDA issues. The ABA recently

advertised a program in the environmental area. I was a speaker at

a program a couple of weeks ago in Chicago where four speakers

dealt with issues all from the perspective of how compliance

programs avoid problems: anti-trust, Foreign Corrupt Practices

Act, export licensing and trade.<p>



It seems to me the question is not whether or not  compliance

programs are a good idea. Rather the issue is if companies do not

implement them, they will be at a serious disadvantage when the

agencies which audit or otherwise influence how they do business

"visit" them.<p>



If anyone is interested in more details, feel free to contact me

at <A HREF="mailto:skohnxro@counsel.com">skohnxro@counsel.com</a>.

<hr><p>



<CENTER><I><A HREF="http://www.courttv.com/download/seminars/form1.html">

Submit your question or comment to the discussion</i>.</a></center>

<!--- full_end--->

</BLOCKQUOTE>
