<html><head><title>Seminars - Principle No. 3 - A Dynamic Process</title>
</head> <BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#FF0005">
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/smb.gif" BORDER=0>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<h2>Principle No. 3 - A Dynamic Process</h2>
<!--- full_start: 657--->
<H2>Corporate Compliance: Standards For The 21st Century</h2><p>



<H3>Seminar Discussion Thread</h3><p>



From: Christina Cooley -- Counsel Connect - Atlanta<br>

Date:  Tue Oct 24 18:08<br>

Subject:  PR. 3-A Dynamic Process<p>



<H3>NATIONAL CENTER FOR PREVENTIVE LAW WORKING GROUP DRAFT</h3><p>



<H4>Establishing Compliance Programs, Continued. . .</h4>



<I>Note:  Principle #3 and its Considerations are intended to

address the following aspects of the <a href=../../../../download/seminars/fsg1.html>

Federal Sentencing Guidelines:  Sec. 8A1.2(k)(1)</a>:  " The Organization must have

established compliance standards and procedures to be followed

by its employees and other agents that are reasonably capable

of reducing the prospect of criminal conduct"  and

Sec. 8A1.2(k)(i): "Size of the organization -- The requisite degree

of formality of a program to prevent and detect violations of

law will vary with the size of the organization: The larger the

organization, the more formal the program typically should be.

occur because of the nature of its business . . ." and

Sec. 8A1.2(k)(iii):  "Prior history of the organization -- An

organization's prior history may indicate types of offenses

that it should have taken actions to prevent. . ."</i><p>



<H4>Principle #3: An effective compliance program is a dynamic

process that is designed to be flexible and modified, when

appropriate, to reflect changing conditions.</h4>



Factors to Consider:<p>



(a) Considering the differing compliance problems and needs of

dissimilar operating units.<p>



(b) Providing for continuous operation of a compliance program

and incorporating it into the daily activities of the

organization.<p>



(c) Including mechanisms within a compliance program that

promote changes in the program in response to new business

activities or other organizational changes.<p>



(d) Recognizing that organization members or other firms may

develop new methods to achieve compliance and providing

mechanisms for identifying and testing those new methods.<p>



(e) Designing a compliance program to promote and reward

compliance program improvements and other positive changes in

an organization's culture.<p>



We urge you to submit comments and examples about the above



Principle.  To assist you in this, please review the postings



from the first day of the seminar, October 23, on the <a href=../../../../download/seminars/fsg1.html>Federal



Sentencing Guidelines</a>, the <a href=../../../../download/seminars/principle1.html>Full Set of Principles</a> and the <a href=../../../../download/seminars/model1.html>Model



Example</a>. Please note that the Principles and Considerations are



copyrighted by the NCPL and may not be reproduced without



permission of the NCPL.



<hr><p>



<CENTER><I><A HREF="http://www.courttv.com/download/seminars/form1.html">

Submit your question or comment to the discussion</i>.</a></center>

