<html><head><title>Seminars - Pitfalls [of Implementing a Compliance Program]</title>
</head> <BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#FF0005">
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/smb.gif" BORDER=0>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<h2>Pitfalls [of Implementing a Compliance Program]</h2>
<!--- full_start: 658--->
<H2>Corporate Compliance: Standards For The 21st Century</h2><p>

<H3>Seminar Discussion Thread</h3><p>

From: Mark Rasch -- SAIC - McClean<br>



Date:  Tue Oct 24 19:54<br>



Subject:  Pitfalls (or why not to...)<p>



Here is the problem I see with Corporate Compliance programs.



Inevitably, someone within the company will engage in some



misconduct, which, hopefully, the company will detect.  If so, the



compliance program must determine whether or not to report the

criminal misconduct engaged in on behalf of the company.  If the

company chooses not to report, the compliance program will be



deemed ineffective at best and obstructionist at worst.  If a



report is made to law enforcement, the company becomes a first



time offender -- decreasing the sanction for the first offense,

but dramatically increasing the sanctions for any subsequent

offense.  All told, it is better to evaluate on a case by case

basis whether or not to voluntarily disclose misconduct, rather



than to have a knee-jerk "policy" on this...<p>



Mark Rasch<br>



Science Applications International Corporation<br>

(703) 917-5430<p>

<hr><p>

Appended by: Kirk Jordan -- Compliance Systems - Warwick<br>







Date: Tue Oct 24 22:13:23 1995<br>

Subject: Incentives (or why to ..)<p>



You make a valid point Mark:  Under the Organizational Sentencing

Guidelines, a company will not receive credit for its compliance



program if, after becoming aware of a criminal offense, the

company unreasonably delays reporting the offense to the

government.<p>



However, if the company's compliance program is functioning



effectively, there's a good chance that the company will discover



the misconduct earlier rather than later.  I would take the issue



you raised and consider it this way:  Is it better for the company



to discover incipient misconduct, investigate it, impose







discipline, make appropriate modifications to its compliance







program, and then (if it so chooses) go to the government,  or







first hear of the illegal activity when the government comes







knocking at the door?  In the former posture, the company is in a



much better position to argue that the government should pursue

the responsible individuals only, and not the company.<p>

My point is this -- an effective compliance program will often put



the company in the driver's seat with respect to internal



misconduct.  After catching a violation in the early stages, and

with appropriate time for investigation and reflection, the

company may decide reporting is the way to go. On the other hand,

assuming there is no independent duty to report, the company may

determine, after a violation, simply to take appropriate internal



action and bear the risk of a nondisclosure.<p>



Finally, there are existing programs -- such as the Antitrust



Amnesty Program -- that provide significant incentives to



organizations to be the first to disclose misconduct.   Under the



Antitrust program, the second to disclose can expect no benefit,



and is likely to be prosecuted.  An effective compliance program,



with robust auditing and monitoring mechanisms --  will help



ensure that your company is the first through the door.<p>



Stay tuned to the seminar -- principles 12-15 will dig into these



issues in more detail.<p>



<hr><p>



Appended by: Joe Murphy -- Bell Atlantic - Philadelphia<br>



Date: Wed Oct 25 15:34:08 1995<br>



Subject: Pitfalls(or why not to...)<p>

Mark - I endorse Kirk's reply, but would like to add a technical



point.  I do not think it is completely correct to say that one



gets "no credit" for a compliance program if one fails to



self-disclose.  The mitigation credit is lost, but compliance



programs still count in determining where within the sentencing



range you fall, once the formula of mitigating and aggravating



factors is used to determine what range applies.  That is, after

you find the culpability score, there is a minimum and a maximum







multiplier that applies.  Where you fall between the minimum and







maximum can be affected by the existence of a compliance







program.<p>

Secondly, existence of a program is taken into account in the



decision to impose probation.  If you have no program, one will



likely be imposed (and a God-awful one it will be!).  If you have



a program, even if you did not voluntarily self-disclose, you can







avoid a government-imposed program.<p>



Of course, there are other benefits from having a good program,



including the ability to convince a prosecutor not to prosecute,





and the ability to prevent many violations in the first place.<p>



Joe Murphy<p>



<hr><p>



Appended by: Robert Sanger -- Sanger & Associates - Santa Barbara<br>



Date: Wed Oct 25 21:20:44 1995<br>



Subject: Pitfalls<p>







We all are waiting to see how these things shake out in the real



world of government agents, prosecutors and judges.  However, I



think that the last remark of Mr. Murphy bears reflection.<p>







As a criminal defense lawyer, I do tend to see the bleaker



picture. If we are brought in post-indictment, the government



starts any discussion with mechanical applications of the



Sentencing Guidelines, whether for individuals or organizations,



and we embark on an uphill journey.  If we have the opportunity to



come in pre-indictment, our main focus is to avoid the filing of



the indictment or to limit its scope in terms of number and



seriousness of charges or who the defendants will be.<p>



Historically, government agencies become aware of and even



investigate far more cases than they take to the United States



Attorney's office for filing.  And [Assistant U.S. Attorney's]



do not file a good



number of the cases presented to them.  We have all had



considerable success in persuading the government no to indict



even if it means a civil consent decree or some other approach



which keeps the FSG's from being invoked.  In other words,



appealing to the discretion of the law enforcement agency and the



AUSA pre-indictment can make all of the difference in the world.<p>







What is antithetical to our way of thinking as Americans is to be



required to turn ourselves in in order to avoid more Draconian



punishment.  The Organizational Sentencing Guidelines fail to take



into account that the human beings who are required to do this



have been raised with the correct understanding that they, as



individuals, do not have to incriminate themselves.  And, while we



may understand the reasoning for voluntary organizational



disclosure, it is still intuitively repugnant.<p>







However, given the present state of prosecutorial affairs, a



company with a good compliance program, which catches illegal



activity early and deals with it has a chance to avoid indictment. 



That chance, historically (before the Organizational Sentencing



Guidelines), has been rather significant.  Therefore, there is a



good pragmatic reason (as we see things now) to favor disclosure.



Of course, as said above, each case has to be evaluated on its



facts.<p>







What we will have to find out is whether or not voluntary



disclosures will significantly increase the filings.  In other



words, will the agencies and the U.S. Attorney's office be more



likely to seek indictment.  It may seem easier for an agent to



persuade an AUSA to indict if the corporation has laid out all of



the evidence, there does not seem to be any resistance to



prosecution and evidence collection Fourth and Fifth Amendment



concerns have been obviated by the private organization doing law



enforcement's work.  Hopefully, the government will see the



benefit to early disclosure and reward it appropriately rather



than taking unfair advantage.<p>







Time will tell,<p>







Bob Sanger<p>



<hr><p>



Appended by: Herb Zinn -- AZ Public Service - Phoenix<br>

Date: Sat Oct 28 10:06:59 1995<br>

Subject: Pitfalls(or why not to...)<p>



Respectfully, I submit that the discussion may be too focused on

the prosecutorial end of the issue, and not enough on the

practical side.  What I mean is this.  Aside from the implicit

issues of self monitoring and reporting, is the preventative

aspects of the program.  Good training and communication enhances

the opportunity to create an awareness and understanding in the

organization that contributes significantly to a reduction of

ignorance -- which, in my opinion, is one of the major reasons why

people (and hence organizations) do things wrong in the first

place. <p>



Without a program (at least the type defined by the FSG's), there

is little chance that an organization will stop to take the time

(and devote the resources) to give employees and agents focused,

quality training and communications on what it is they need to

know to stay out of trouble, and hence keep the organization out

of trouble, too.<p>



Now, I don't believe for a moment that everyone will leave their

pew after the sermon and sin no more, but it has been my

experience that the greater majority do, and they then become

aware of missteps by others in their midst, enhancing both the

deterrent and detective value of the program.<p>



Herb.<p>



<hr><p>



Appended by: John Voorhees -- Isaacson Rosenbaum - Denver<br>

Date: Sat Oct 28 13:49:53 1995<br>

Subject: Pitfalls(or why not to...)<p>



Mark Rasch: There are several problems with your "case-by-case"

approach. You say "inevitably" someone will engage in misconduct

that "hopefully" the company will detect. Compliance programs are

designed to prevent misconduct from occurring in the first

instance. A key component of any compliance program is training.

Stay tuned to the seminar because Principles 12-15 address how to

create and implement training programs that are helpful in

preventing violations. No compliance program that I have drafted

or that I have seen has a "knee-jerk" policy on reporting

violations. To the contrary, effective compliance programs have

built in mechanisms to detect circumstances that may be present

that make  misconduct possible. The idea is to avoid violations by

identifying liability-causing conduct and training management and

employees before the violation can occur. If a violation does

occur despite the best efforts of management and employees, an

organizational response is essential. Principles 16-20 address how

to respond to violations to minimize the company and employees'

exposure and maximize the ability of the company to prevent future

misconduct. Case-by-case evaluations are important  but they need

to be conducted subject to internal controls  and an

organizational structure, Principles 8-11. All of us who have

worked on compliance problems share your concern that disclosure

of violations can make matters worse for everyone. To solve this

problem, a company must have a program that is designed to be fair

to all employees and at the same time prevent and deter future

misconduct. A  case-by-case approach  without  internal controls

is prone to post hoc rationalizations that inevitably make matters

worse for everyone, particularly when the second offense occurs.<p>



John Voorhees<p>



<hr><p>



Appended by: Robert Sanger -- Sanger & Associates - Santa Barbara<br>

Date: Sat Oct 28 13:53:29 1995<br>

Subject: Pitfalls<p>



Mr. Zinn is not in disagreement with the others in this thread.  I

think we all agree that corporate compliance programs which

promote awareness and understanding are intrinsically good.<p>



The issues addressed first by Mr. Rasch, and subject to comment

thereafter in the thread, are the pitfalls associated with (as

some have called it) the privatization of law enforcement,

voluntary disclosure, or self-policing.  These are cases where the

corporate compliance officers hand a potential criminal case over

to the government on a silver platter.  The FSG's provide for

mitigation of sentence if you voluntarily disclose possible

criminal behavior but there is no provision for immunity, nor can

there be in the FSG's since they are by nature post-conviction

remedies.  Historically in criminal investigations, the U.S.

Attorney will offer immunity to certain participants in a scheme.

It is roughly founded on the proposition that the first on board

gets the deal to testify against the others.  Mr. Jordan notes

that there is an Antitrust Amnesty program based on the same

concept but there is no policy covering most of what may be

voluntarily disclosed.  And there is no policy guiding the

government in these cases to simply prosecute no one in light of a

voluntary disclosure.<p>



In the real world today we still do not know how this

self-policing is going to work out.  And those of us who have seen

what happens to the lives of people who are indicted, even if they

are eventually acquitted, know how critical the filing decision

is.  As indicated here and in another thread, several

practitioners voice strong desires to see some kind of

codification establishing clear restrictions on prosecution where

corporations turn themselves and their employees in.<p>



In essence, if the self-policing aspect of the guidelines catches

on, the government will hear about all sorts of criminal behavior

which never would have come to its attention.  Even more

significantly, it will receive on a silver platter detailed

information, perhaps sufficient to present to an AUSA for

indictment, which it would have had to spend hundreds or thousands

of agent hours investigating.  In fact, in a nation of snitches,

law enforcement agents will have more than enough to do processing

"voluntary disclosures" without ever following up on their own

leads.<p>



The harsh reality is that when the U.S. Attorney's office really

files on a silver platter case, there is a good chance that there

will be substantial prison time for one or more individuals and

substantial fines for the organization.  This may not be too hard

to accept if there were one or two bad actors who deserve to be

punished in some greater sense, however, wait until you have one

of those strict liability offenses or some other situation where

good people are going to be felons.  For instance, a corporation's

staff person fails to make a full disclosure in a routine SEC

filing; the compliance officer is contacted and not only directs

that an amended filing be made immediately but that a further

voluntary disclosure be made to the enforcement division; the CEO,

CFO and the other top officers of the corporation have been

involved in fund raising during this period and the company

continues to sell securities through its brokers.  As a part of

the silver platter, the compliance officer turns over to the

government information it would have never found or asked for

laying out in detail who was responsible for what with a lot of

internal fingerpointing memos by which everyone is trying to cover

themselves while implicating others.<p>



The compliance program has worked.  It corrected an error.  It

also got information to the government regarding possible criminal

behavior before it was discovered by the government.  Everyone

should get a gold star, right?  Wrong!  The CEO, CFO and top executives

will all be indicted for securities fraud.  With any kind of

significant "intended loss," the CEO, CFO and top executives are

looking roughly at 51 to 63 months in the federal Bureau of

Prisons (explain that to their husbands, wives and children at the

next company picnic if there is one and you still let them come).

Not only that, but the company is indicted for a series of

felonies and faces disgorgement, fines and probation along with

civil penalties and debarment.  The company gets a break on the

criminal fines, but it may not matter.<p>



Even if we win the criminal trial for some or all of the

participants, everyone's life is changed forever.<p>



Now, this doesn't mean that I advocate corporate ignorance (quite

to the contrary) or that I advocate conspiracies to coverup crime.

However, I do think that "knee-jerk" disclosure, as first posted

for discussion by Mr. Rasch, should not replace careful evaluation

on a case by case basis.  I also think that "self-policing,"

"voluntary disclosure," "privatization of law enforcement," "Good

Citizen" corporations, "snitching on your fellow humans at work"

or whatever you want to call it is both dangerous and distasteful.<p>





There are a lot of other issues (which I think are coming up in

this seminar) but one serious issue is whether or not we will

restrain the government from indicting as a result of voluntary

disclosure, silver platter cases.  If so, how and to what extent?<p>



Bob Sanger<P>

<hr><p>



Appended by: Herb Zinn -- AZ Public Service - Phoenix<br>

Date: Sat Oct 28 10:06:59 1995<br>

Subject: Pitfalls(or why not to...)<p>



Respectfully, I submit that the discussion may be too focused on

