Even if we win the criminal trial for some or all of the

participants, everyone's life is changed forever.<p>



Now, this doesn't mean that I advocate corporate ignorance (quite

to the contrary) or that I advocate conspiracies to coverup crime.

However, I do think that "knee-jerk" disclosure, as first posted

for discussion by Mr. Rasch, should not replace careful evaluation

on a case by case basis.  I also think that "self-policing,"

"voluntary disclosure," "privatization of law enforcement," "Good

Citizen" corporations, "snitching on your fellow humans at work"

or whatever you want to call it is both dangerous and distasteful.<p>





There are a lot of other issues (which I think are coming up in

this seminar) but one serious issue is whether or not we will

restrain the government from indicting as a result of voluntary

disclosure, silver platter cases.  If so, how and to what extent?<p>



Bob Sanger<p>



<hr><p>



Appended by: Michele Salazar -- NCPL - Denver<br>

Date: Mon Oct 30 16:01:23 1995<br>

Subject: Incentives (or why to ..)<p>



Louis Brown wrote an editorial in the Winter 1994 Preventive Law

Reporter.  This editorial addresses some of the issues discussed

above and Louis suggested we reprint it within this thread.<p>



THOUGHTS ABOUT COMPLIANCE REVIEW UNDER THE FEDERAL SENTENCING

GUIDELINES<p>



Organizations operate under an extremely diverse set of rules,

regulations and laws.  Traditionally, the initial enforcement of

the criminal process is the sole responsibility of the executive

branch of government.  With the vast increase in the scope and

complexity of these rules, regulations and laws, the growth and

diversity of organizations and the general prevailing view for

reduction of taxes, it is virtually impossible for government to

police and enforce all these laws.<p>



We have reached the time when law enforcement is to become

partially privatized.  Privatization in this sense means that the

very organizations that must abide by the laws are the

organizations that must police the laws.  Self-policing has become

a course of conduct; that is, a socially needed function.  For

self-enforcing procedures to work and for organizations to pursue

them, they need as much encouragement as can be offered.<p>



What is needed is a reward theory to affirmatively encourage the

compliance review process.  This important idea was set forth in

Sigler and Murphy, Interactive Corporate Compliance: An

Alternative to Regulatory Compulsion (Quorum Books, 1988).<p>



The Federal Sentencing Guidelines include a provision for reducing

criminal sentences where the guilty organization has an

appropriate compliance review process.  Under the present

Guidelines, the compliance review process is effective only after

conviction.<p>



I can suggest three means by which this socially desirable

objective of self-policing under effective compliance review can

be furthered:<OL><p>



<LI>PERMIT EVIDENCE OF COMPLIANCE REVIEW IN THE CASE IN CHIEF.<br>

Evidence of a defendant organization's review process is

admissible under present procedures only after conviction.  Could

the compliance review process be taken into account earlier in the

criminal prosecution under the case in chief?  Should the jury (or

judge), in effect, be permitted to evaluate whether there should

have been a prosecution?<p>



<LI>ALLOW DUE DILIGENCE/ADVISE OF COUNSEL AS A DEFENSE.<br>

This is an established concept that should be considered.  It is

permitted as a defense in connection with a fraud penalty in

federal income tax and malicious prosecution cases.  Should it be

allowed as a defense in cases that come under the Sentencing

Guidelines.  Due Diligence/Advise of Counsel can be shown where a

corporation adheres to appropriate standards, such as those being

developed in the current NCPL project.<p>



<LI>DEVELOP PROSECUTORIAL GUIDELINES.<br>

A related approach might be to use compliance standards to assist

in establishing a set of U.S. prosecutorial guidelines.  As far as

I am aware, prosecution is a unilateral discretionary

determination by the prosecuting authority.  I do not know (does

anyone know?) what goes into this determination.  Would it be

socially desirable to establish principles, standards or rules so

that the decision to prosecute tends toward uniformity?  More

important than uniformity, compliance standards might be used to

encourage further self-policing.  Perhaps provisions might be made

for cooperative policing instead of prosecution.<p></ol>



I am confident that once appropriate compliance review standards

are established and further rewards are made available for

enacting effective processes, self-policing will increase and

enhanced compliance will result.<p>



Louis M. Brown<br>

Chairman Emeritus, National Center for Preventive Law

<p>



<hr><p>



Appended by: Gregory J Wallance -- Kaye Scholer - New York<br>

Date: Mon Oct 30 19:49:31 1995<br>

Subject: Pitfalls(or why not to...)<p>



In reading these comments, I can't help but wonder why there is

not more vigorous criticism of the government for failing to offer

more concrete incentives to companies to voluntarily disclose

violations of law by their employees.  In promulgating the

organizational sentencing guidelines the government encourages

companies to self-police and disclose violations of law.  At the

same time, the government (except the Antitrust Division) reserves

the right to harshly punish the disclosing company to the extent

permitted by the Guidelines, leaving every lawyer in a quandary

about whether to recommend disclosure.  In other words, if you

don't self-police and disclose you will be punished and when you

do, you still may be punished. The government can't have it both

ways but so far, other than the Antitrust Division, its trying to.<p>



The bar and business community, in my opinion, have not been

sufficiently outspoken about the government's inconsistent

approach.<p>



<hr><p>



Appended by: Joe Murphy -- Bell Atlantic - Philadelphia<br>

Date: Tue Oct 31 13:32:11 1995<br>

Subject: Pitfalls(or why not to...)<p>



Greg - I agree with that criticism of the government.  In fact,

much of our legal system seems designed to discourage effective

compliance programs and voluntary self-disclosure.  Although

there are exceptions like the Sentencing Commission, government in

general is often timid about recognizing  and rewarding compliance

programs.<p>



In addition to the Antitrust Division's leniency policy, another

example of government giving a commitment to those who self-police

is the recent state legislation granting immunity for voluntary

disclosures of environmental violations (in the Texas legislation

this also includes workplace safety violations).  There is a

similar proposal pending before Congress.<p>



Before we heap too much praise on the Antitrust Division, though,

it should be noted that they are in  the Stone Age when it comes

to dealing with company compliance programs.  The Division's

spokespeople have said such programs are essentially irrelevant in

the prosecution decision, and with respect to issues of liability.<p>



On that point other agencies are far ahead of the Division.<p>



Joe Murphy

