<html><head><title>Seminars - Insider Trading Policy Issues</title>
</head> <BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#FF0005">
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/smb.gif" BORDER=0>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<h2>Insider Trading Policy Issues</h2>
<!--- full_start: 659--->
<H2>Corporate Compliance: Standards For The 21st Century</h2><p>

<H3>Seminar Discussion Thread</h3><p>



From: Jeffrey Davis -- Moore & Van Allen - Charlotte<br>



Date:  Wed Oct 25 11:46<br>



Subject:  Insider Trading<p>

One of my partners has a client which is a rapidly growing company



that conducted an initial public offering within the last 12 months 



and whose stock is thinly traded on NASDAQ.  The executive officers 



of the Company would like to have as long a window as possible after 



making their quarterly and year-end announcements and filings within



which to trade their stock.  They would like their Company's insider 



trading policy to provide for a trading window which opens



when they make their quarterly or annual announcements and filings



and remains open until the end of the current quarter.  They understand 



that at all times they are subject to restrictions on



trading due to their possession of other material inside



information and they also understand the consequences on a Company's 



stock price if the executives of the Company sell stock.  The



Company has a number of divisions and the senior executives state



that until they gather information after the end of the quarter, 



that they do not know as a general matter how the



current quarter or year will look.  They acknowledge that they



might have knowledge in a particular quarter that earnings would be 



high or low due to an unique event or series of events



and would not trade with that knowledge.  My partner would like to



know:<p>







A.  How long a trading window have smaller, publicly held clients



in the technology or health care area adopted?<p>







B.  In all events do you advise your clients that the trading



window should close at the end of a quarter or calendar year 



or do you recommend that the window close within two weeks or more



prior to the end of a quarter or calendar year?<p>







C.  Are you aware of any resource materials specifically dealing



with or including proposed insider trading policies for companies



like this?<p>







D.  Sample insider trading policies would be appreciated.<p>







Thanks in advance for any help.<p>



<hr><p>



Appended by: Jeffrey Bernfeld -- Spire Corporation - Bedford<br>

Date: Thu Oct 26 15:54:30 1995<br>

Subject: No window at all<p>



A window open as widely as [you] describe is no window at all.<p>



On the "tweaking" side, the window should not open on release of

earnings, but anywhere from 24 to 72 [hours] after that time,

depending on your confidence level re: the distribution of your

earnings announcements (e.g. a widely traded stock followed by

several analysts tends to get almost immediate attention).<p>



On the larger side, a "window" that is open for something like 45

or more days (depending on when [you] release earnings) is the same as

simply relying on [executives] not to trade on inside information.  Maybe that's

adequate in a given company, but the "window" is not giving [you] any

greater protection.  Sure, [executives] may not "know" how the quarter

will come out, but they certainly have a good idea, and the purpose

of the window should be to take the [question] of when a "good idea"

becomes "knowledge" out of their hands, for everyone's benefit.<p>



An alternative, which we use here at a small thinly traded

technology [company], is to require all [executives] subject to insider trading

rules to clear trades [with me, the general counsel] first.  The number of

people involved is small, the [amount] of trading is small, and it works

fine.<p>



Another alternative, if appropriate, is to encourage the [executives] to

establish a regular program of selling not dependent on any

external event - [for example] "I want to sell 1000 shares on the last day of

every quarter, and I won't change that plan [without] at least [one quarter's]

notice to (an internal compliance person or the [corporate secretary])".<p>



On your specific [questions], I don't have specific [statistics], but my sense is

that a 20 or 30 day window is more common than the [approximately] 45 or 60

days [you] propose.  I think Prentice Hall's Sec. 16 Guide has sample

policies.

<hr><p>



