<html><head><title>Seminars - Principle No. 5 - Endorsement by Highest Authority</title>
</head> <BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#FF0005">
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/smb.gif" BORDER=0>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<h2>Principle No. 5 - Endorsement by Highest Authority</h2>
<!--- full_start: 669--->
<H2>Corporate Compliance: Standards For The 21st Century</h2><p>



<H3>Seminar Discussion Thread</h3><p>



From: Christina Cooley -- Counsel Connect - Atlanta<br>

Date:  Thu Oct 26 12:05<br>

Subject:  PR. 5-Highest Endorsement<p>



<H3>NATIONAL CENTER FOR PREVENTIVE LAW WORKING GROUP DRAFT</h3><p>



<H4>Establishing Compliance Programs, Continued. . .</h4><p>



<I>Note:  Principle #5 and its Considerations are intended to

address the following aspect of the <a href=../../../../download/seminars/fsg1.html>

Federal Sentencing Guidelines:  Sec. 8A1.2(k)(2)</a>:  "Specific individual(s) within

high-level personnel of the organization must have been

assigned overall responsibility to oversee compliance with such

standards and procedures."</i><p>



<H4>Principle #5: The highest governing authority within the

organization endorses the compliance program.</h4>



Factors to Consider:<p>



(a) Choosing carefully the mode or modes by which a governing

body expresses its endorsement of the organization's compliance

policies and compliance program.<p>



(b) Providing for continuing, active participation of the

organization's executive authorities in promoting and

overseeing a compliance program.<p>





We urge you to submit comments and examples about the above

Principle.  To assist you in this, please review the postings

from the first day of the seminar, October 23, on the <a href=../../../../download/seminars/fsg1.html>Federal

Sentencing Guidelines</a>, the <a href=../../../../download/seminars/principle1.html>Full Set of Principles</a> and the <a href=../../../../download/seminars/model1.html>Model

Example</a>. Please note that the Principles and Considerations are

copyrighted by the NCPL and may not be reproduced without

permission of the NCPL.

