<html><head><title>Seminars - Implications of Due Diligence</title>
</head> <BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#FF0005">
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/smb.gif" BORDER=0>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<h2>Implications of Due Diligence</h2>
<!--- full_start: 670--->
<H2>Corporate Compliance: Standards For The 21st Century</h2><p>



<H3>Seminar Discussion Thread</h3><p>

From: Richard S. Gruner -- Whittier Law School<br>



Date:  Thu Oct 26 15:52<br>



Subject:  Implications of Due Diligence<p>

While the focal point of the discussions in this seminar will be



the implications of corporate law compliance programs in



preventing corporate criminal liability and in reducing related



sentences, participants in the seminar should be aware that



corporate law compliance efforts have growing significance in a



number of other legal areas.  Compliance programs that satisfy the



compliance program standards now being developed by the NCPL will



stand a good chance of gaining benefits for firms in these other



legal areas.<p>







The ways that government standards and practices should be



reshaped to reward companies with strong compliance efforts was



the topic of a symposium recently hosted by the United States



Sentencing Commission.  This symposium, entitled "Corporate Crime



in America: Strengthening the 'Good Citizen' Corporation" included



discussions of a number of ways that rewards for firms with



substantial compliance programs are being incorporated into



liability standards and regulatory practices.<p>







The following is an excerpt from remarks I presented at this



symposium in order to summarize some of the developing trends



towards greater legal rewards for companies with substantial



compliance programs:<p>







<I>"The defining feature of this symposium has been the idea around



which this whole conference revolves -- the need to develop



distinctive, favorable legal treatment for the 'good citizen



corporation.'<p>







I submit that the concept of the good citizen corporation as



a feature of our legal landscape is not only new, but



fundamentally important.  By a good citizen corporation I mean the



type of corporation that has been the subject of our discussions



here -- a corporation that has undertaken due diligence to prevent



offenses in its business operations.  We are moving from a legal



regime in which the concept of the good citizen corporation was



irrelevant to a legal system in which this concept may be a



central consideration in evaluating corporate liability.



Currently, corporate criminal liability usually depends on



</i>respondeat superior<I> 



principles[legal doctrine whereby a master



may be held liable in certain circumstances for the wrongful acts



of his servant, or a company for the wrongful acts of its employees].



These principles effectively



equate an employee offender with the offender's corporation.  If



an employee commits an offense within his or her scope of



employment and for corporate benefit, then the corporation is



liable for the offense as well as



the employee.  We are moving from these principles for measuring



corporate liability towards a view that a corporation's



responsibility for an offense should be evaluated separately.



Under this new approach, the good citizen corporation that can



show due diligence concerning law compliance may avoid liability



for an occasional, aberrational employee offense.  In short, the



law is shifting towards a system in which the culpability of the



organization matters.<p>







This is a significant change that has broad implications.  I



want to sketch a few of the legal developments that may implement



this new approach in the next few years.  You have seen hints of



some of these developments here at this symposium.  My comments



are aimed at suggesting how the good citizen corporation may



figure in additional legal standards.<p>







One type of change that seems likely is an expansion of the



range of legal contexts in which good citizen corporations are



exempted from liability.  We have heard suggestions at this



symposium of corporate criminal liability standards that would



turn on whether a company undertook due diligence to prevent



offenses before a particular employee committed an offense.  Such



standards would shift the assessment of the quality of a



corporation's law compliance efforts from the sentencing stage --



where they reside under the Sentencing Commission's Organizational



Sentencing Guidelines -- to the liability determination phase of



the criminal case.<p>







There are several ways that this sort of change may be



implemented.  Standards may be changed so that the absence of



corporate due diligence needs to be shown to establish corporate



criminal liability.  More plausibly, corporate due diligence of



this sort may be recognized as a basis for an affirmative defense



to corporate criminal liability.  These sorts of changes need not



be limited to criminal offenses.  I think that we will see



equivalent developments in regulatory settings in which



definitions of regulatory violations are revised to turn on



whether or not a corporation has undertaken diligent efforts to



prevent violations.<p>







This is still not a broad enough perspective, however.  I



think that we are going to see greater reliance on the good



citizen corporation concept in law enforcement activities.  In



particular, the targeting of government investigations and



regulatory oversight will increasingly depend on prior assessments



of how extensively particular corporations are policing



themselves.  Experimental programs now being tried by the EPA



illustrate how the good citizen corporation might be treated in



this context.  Under these



programs, companies that submit to an intensive review of their



compliance systems can qualify for later relaxation of



governmental oversight.  Once the internal policing within these



companies is shown to be sound, the need for external reviews is



correspondingly diminished.  This sort of targeting of regulatory



oversight makes sense not only as a means for allocating scare



regulatory resources, but also as a means to recognize and reward



corporations that have pursued socially beneficial efforts to



prevent offenses.<p>







The status of a firm as a good citizen corporation may also



have growing significance in other legal contexts.  For example,



it was suggested in Joe Murphy's presentation that punitive



damages should not be assessed against a corporate defendant in a



tort action if the corporation is found to have taken diligent



steps to prevent the misconduct at stake.  Withholding punitive



damages on this basis would be a logical means to reserve such



damages for the worst cases of irresponsible corporate conduct.



In addition, standards diminishing punitive damages for good



citizen corporations would strongly encourage diligent law



compliance and harm prevention efforts in areas where tort actions



and damages are real threats, but criminal sanctions are not.<p>



Finally, a firm's status as a good citizen corporation may



figure in day to day contracting and commerce.  Perhaps the most



significant activity discussed at this conference was the



development of ISO 14000, a standard for measuring the sufficiency



of environmental law compliance systems.  Once issued, this



standard is intended to figure in a system of privately enforced



compliance system obligations in which one contracting party will



insist that its contracting partners certify their compliance with



ISO 14000.  Maintaining an adequate compliance program -- and



being a good citizen corporation, at least in the respects



addressed in ISO 14000 -- will be a matter of contract obligations



and incentives.  Hence, a system of private contracting and



rewards may ultimately drive the development of better compliance



practices."</i><p>



<hr><p>



Appended by: Robert Sanger -- Sanger & Associates - Santa Barbara<br>

Date: Fri Oct 27 04:19:08 1995<br>

Subject: What is happening?<p>



Not to rain on anyone's parade but, as a criminal defense lawyer

for a couple decades, I have seen the disasters which ensue in the

wake of a criminal indictments.  I am also very suspicious of

depending on the government's good will vis a vis its citizens,

individual and corporate.  And, for some reason, terms like "Good

Citizen Corporation" make me nervous.<p>



There is something to be said for the proposition that we

shouldn't have to turn each other in under the fear of substantial

punishment if we don't and less substantial punishment if we do.

And I can't help saying again that we, as individuals, grow up

with the comfort that in this country we did not have to spy on

each other and snitch each other off.  Not so anymore.<p>



In any event, the above post raises interesting issues, for

instance, whether the substantive laws could be amended to allow

for a defense based on due diligence.  That is something we have

not seen yet and would be the kind of codified limit on government

power that is critical. Is there anything in the works?<p>



I would also like to know more specifically whether or not the

Department of Justice has or will amend the United States

Attorney's Manual to include specific guidelines on not seeking an

indictment in deference to due diligence.  I believe section

9-27.110 presently describes filing discretion in general.<p>



I do not mean to take away from the other issues discussed, such

as limits in civil liability, freedom from intensive audits,

exemption from punitive damages and, even, reduction in fines and

other criminal penalties.  However, IMHO there needs to be much

more emphasis on concrete rules regarding whether or not there

will be a criminal indictment sought in the first place.  The

[Federal] Sentencing Guidelines [("FSGs") for Organizations ] have 

turned the law enforcement

system upside down.  They do not provide for not prosecuting, they

simply say that consideration will be given for compliance systems

and voluntary disclosures in terms of the criminal sentence.  This

also does not take into consideration the Draconian application of

the FSGs to the individuals who will be offered up in the course

of all this.  Believe me, the government has always had tremendous

power when it chooses to investigate and more when it indicts; the

individual FSGs gave it more power (and Judges less discretion)

at sentencing; now the Organizational FSGs have given the

government the benefit of a nationwide posse without any mandatory

reduction in the power to indict and with only vague promises at

sentencing.<p>



In any event, is there any movement at the legislative, agency, or

prosecutorial stage to <I>codify</i> a commitment not to prosecute

corporations and "good citizen" officers in return for snitching

off fellow corporate employees?  Is there any serious effort from

the business community to support reductions in mandatory minimum

sentences and the individual FSGs so that technically guilty

fellow employees are not confined forever by the federal Bureau of

Prisons?  Is there any concern from corporate officers that

voluntary disclosure may result in mandatory prison for almost

randomly selected corporate officers on offenses which have no

requisite criminal intent?<p>



I know that the FSGs for Organizations has created a cottage

industry of compliance experts, compliance audits, and compliance

publications.  But what about the companies which are fined and

"disgorged" out of business and what about all those human beings

who will become felons and go to prison as a result of this?  I

respectfully submit that we need to strongly challenge the

underlying assumptions and not surrender what is left of our

autonomy to the government while discussing the details of

implementing the brave new world of compliance.<p>



It is just my opinion,<p>



Bob Sanger<p>



<hr><p>



Appended by: Louis Brown -- Sanders Barnet - Los Angeles<br>

Date: Fri Oct 27 13:48:17 1995<br>

Subject: Three ideas<p>



In an editorial I wrote for Preventive Law Reporter VOL. 13 #4,

winter 1994, I expressed three ideas that seem to be coming to the

surface in these discussions:<p><OL>



<LI><H4>Develop prosecutorial guidelines.</h4> So far as I know (and I

really know very little about this subject) there is great

variation in the kinds of situations where there will be a

prosecution. The suggestion is that there should be standards or

guidelines directed to prosecutors giving as much detail as is

practical, concerning the kinds of situations where there should

be prosecution. That is, prosecutorial discretion should be

predictable. Etc.<p>



<LI><H4>Permit evidence of compliance review in the case in chief.</h4> As

of now, there are two steps in a prosecution and sentence. Where

the defendant is found guilty, a second proceeding allows

introduction of compliance review process. The suggestion is to

permit compliance to be introduced in the case in chief. That

would be a way of allowing the jury or judge to test whether there

should have been a prosecution at all. It would also further

encourage corporations to establish and maintain compliance

review.<p>



<LI><H4>Allow due diligence and advice of counsel as a defense.</h4> This is

a bit stretching but we do allow the defense where there is a

penalty (for example, tax fraud and other situations). Further

encouragement to corporation to go forward with compliance. One

aspect of this is to recognize that our laws and regulations are

so numerous and often so complex that we need to do what we can to

encourage compliance.</OL><p>



Some of this seems to me needed because we seem to be developing

into the privatization of enforcement. The government cannot be

expected to enforce all of these laws/regulations (certainly not

when we are so obsessed with tax reduction). So we are leading

into an era of privatization of enforcement where each enterprise

is to be its own police. Or something like that.

I probably did a better job of saying this in the editorial which

you are encouraged to read....<p>



Louis M. Brown<p>



<hr><p>



Appended by: Richard S. Gruner -- Whittier Law School - Los Angeles<br>

Date: Fri Oct 27 14:10:07 1995<br>

Subject: Implications of Due Diligence<p>



Just a response to a few of the points raised in the prior

message:<p><OL>



<LI> Regarding DOJ standards on withholding indictments in cases of

due diligence towards law compliance, these sorts of standards do

exist in some areas.  For an example, see Department of Justice,

Factors in Decisions on Criminal Prosecutions for Environmental

Violations in the Context of Significant Voluntary Compliance of

Disclosure Efforts By the Violator (July 1, 1991) (reprinted in R.

Gruner, Corporate Crime and Sentencing Appendix E. (1994)).<p>



<LI> The federal sentencing guidelines for organizational offenders

did not address the issue of whether firms that engage in due

diligence should be immune from liability because this questions

was beyond the jurisdiction of the Sentencing Commission.  The

Commission was authorized to set sentencing standards.  The

sentencing standards which the Commission has promulgated

necessarily assume that any party brought under those standards

has already been convicted of an offense.  Hence, the application

of other standards for determining which parties are or are not

prosecuted or convicted was not something that the Commission was

authorized to address.  Nor would the implementation of a due

diligence defense or a set of prosecutorial discretion standards

turning on due diligence be inconsistent with the Commission's

guidelines.<p>



<LI> While there is no magic in the term "Good Citizen

Corporation", there is an underlying notion that I think is now

gaining growing acceptance.  This notion is that an organizational

actor (particularly a large corporation) has a positive duty to

engage in self-policing of activities carried out on its behalf

and, perhaps, a duty to aid public law enforcement when violations

are detected.  This responsibility comes as a condition of being

offered the privilege of acting in a corporate form.  Those

entities that fulfill these responsibilities may have an

opportunity to reduce their liability when their affairs are

conducted through illegal conduct, provided that the sort of due

diligence defense or prosecutorial discretion standards discussed

in my earlier message are observed.    This is a better state of

affairs than would prevail under the standard federal rule of

corporate criminal liability that would simply hold corporations

liable under respondeat superior standards for the acts of

corporate employees.<p>



<LI> To the extent that these pressures and rewards cause more

firms to surface illegal conduct in their operations, more

responsible individuals will be prosecuted.  This will both

improve the administration of justice by increasing the

correlation between crime and punishment and increase deterrents

against misconduct within corporate organizations.  Of course, due

process should not be sacrificed in carrying out these processes.

However, objections to the evolving system  of corporate

self-policing and related increases in prosecutions should be

aimed at including due process protections within the new system,

not at doing away this system as a whole.</ol><p>



Richard Gruner<p>



<hr><p>



Appended by: Joe Murphy -- Bell Atlantic - Philadelphia<br>

Date: Fri Oct 27 15:48:42 1995<br>

Subject: What is happening?<p>



Bob - For many of us who have been working in this area for awhile

(2 decades, in my case) the points you raise have been central

ones.  There is clearly a need to recognize positively those

companies that have made a serious effort to prevent misconduct.

Unfortunately, much of the legal system actually works to deter

and even punish effective compliance efforts.<p>



Regarding the due diligence defense, there has been a fair amount

written about that.  Harvey Pitt and Karl Groskaufmanis did a

major piece on this in the Georgetown Law Journal.  As Richard

Gruner indicated, this view has found acceptance in some places.

For example, I know there have been some antitrust cases where

evidence of a compliance program was admitted in the defense of

liability.  And in the civil area, the Supreme Court has said this

is a defense in hostile work environment sexual harassment cases.<p>



Your point about standards to control prosecutors is a good one.

The sources Richard refers to (e.g., DOJ's July 1, 1991 statement)

still leave it up to the prosecutor's discretion.  This same point

also applies to offering immunity for those who voluntarily

self-disclose.  The Antitrust Division does, in fact, offer a

binding commitment not to prosecute a company or its employees, if

it is the first one to turn itself in, and it helps the government

get the goods on other potential defendants (e.g., in a

pricefixing case).  Recently a number of states have passed laws

in the environmental area giving immunity to those who voluntarily

disclose violations.  This is a step in the right direction, but

we need much more in this area.<p>



So I do not see your comments as "raining on anyone's parade";

just a reminder that we need to carry umbrellas with us when we do

any compliance work.   Joe Murphy



<P><hr><p>



