<html><head><title>Seminars - Principle No. 6 - Accountability for Compliance</title>
</head> <BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#FF0005">
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/smb.gif" BORDER=0>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<h2>Principle No. 6 - Accountability for Compliance</h2>
<!--- full_start: 682--->
<H2>Corporate Compliance: Standards For The 21st Century</h2><p>



<H3>Seminar Discussion Thread</h3><p>



From: Christina Cooley -- Counsel Connect - Atlanta<br>

Date:  Fri Oct 27 09:30<br>

Subject:  PR. 6-Accountability<p>



<H4>NATIONAL CENTER FOR PREVENTIVE LAW WORKING GROUP DRAFT</h4><p>



<H3>Establishing Compliance Programs, Continued. . .</h3><p>



<I>Note:  Principle #6 and its Considerations are intended to

address the following aspects of the <a href=../../../../download/seminars/fsg1.html>

Federal Sentencing Guidelines: Sec. 8A1.2(k)</a>(1):  "The organization must have

established compliance standards and procedures to be followed

by its employees and other agents that are reasonably capable

of reducing the prospect of criminal conduct" and Sec.

8A1.2(k)(5): "The organization must have taken reasonable steps to

achieve compliance with its standards, e.g., by utilizing

monitoring and auditing systems . . . "</i><p>



<H4>Principle #6:  An effective compliance program establishes

accountability for compliance throughout the organization.</h4><p>



Factors to Consider:<p>



(a) Creating mechanisms that hold all organizational directors,

officers, employees and agents accountable for compliance in

the course of activities that they initiate or oversee.<p>



(b) Designing a program with input from knowledgeable

individuals about likely risks of noncompliance with applicable

laws and related gaps in compliance accountability.<p>



We urge you to submit comments and examples about the above

Principle.  To assist you in this, please review the postings

from the first day of the seminar, October 23, on the 

<a href=../../../../download/seminars/fsg1.html>Federal Sentencing 

Guidelines</a>, the <a href=../../../../download/seminars/principle1.html>Full Set of 

Principles</a> and the <a href=../../../../download/seminars/model1.html>

Model Example</a>. Please note that the Principles and Considerations are

copyrighted by the NCPL and may not be reproduced without

permission of the NCPL.

