<html><head><title>Seminars - Principle No. 7 - Operate Fairly and Equitably</title>
</head> <BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#FF0005">
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/smb.gif" BORDER=0>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<h2>Principle No. 7 - Operate Fairly and Equitably</h2>
<!--- full_start: 683--->
<H2>Corporate Compliance: Standards For The 21st Century</h2><p>



<H3>Seminar Discussion Thread</h3><p>







From: Christina Cooley -- Counsel Connect - Atlanta<br>

Date:  Fri Oct 27 09:32<br>

Subject:  PR. 7-Fair and Equitable<p>



<H4>NATIONAL CENTER FOR PREVENTIVE LAW WORKING GROUP DRAFT</h4><p>



<H3>Establishing Compliance Programs, Continued. . .</h3><p>



<I>Note:  Principle #7 and its Considerations are intended to

address the following aspect of the 

<a href=../../../../download/seminars/fsg1.html>

Federal Sentencing Guidelines:  Sec. 8A1.2(k)</a>(1)"The organization 

must have established compliance standards and procedures to be followed

by its employees and other agents that are reasonably capable

of reducing the prospect of criminal conduct."</i><p>



<H4>Principle #7:  An effective compliance program is designed to

operate fairly and equitably.</h4>



Factors to Consider:<p>



(a) Incorporating practices in a compliance program that treat

all employees fairly and consistently.<p>



(b) Providing mechanisms for guarding against retaliation and

thereby reducing risks to employees from complying with the

provisions of a compliance program.<p>



(c) Providing means for responses to incidents involving

violations of legal requirements or failure to comply with law

compliance program standards.<p>



If you'd like to submit comments and examples about this

principle but wish to remain anonymous, just e-mail me or call

me at 404-521-1227. Also, please note that the Principles and

Considerations are copyrighted by the NCPL and may not be

reproduced without permission of the NCPL.

