<html><head><title>Seminars - Developing a Program... What to Address?</title>
</head> <BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#FF0005">
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/smb.gif" BORDER=0>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<h2>Developing a Program... What to Address?</h2>
<!--- full_start: 685--->
<H2>Corporate Compliance: Standards For The 21st Century</h2><p>



<H3>Seminar Discussion Thread</h3><p>



From: Anonymous<br>

Date:  Fri Oct 27 09:40<br>

Subject:  Corporate Compliance<p>





Our company is developing a corporate compliance program.  Of

course, it is our intent to comply with all applicable laws.  What

areas of the law are most important for a manufacturing company to

specifically include in its program?  What areas do your companies

specifically address in your programs?<p>



<hr><p>



Appended by: Susan Kohn Ross -- Ross & Associates - Los Angeles<br>

Date: Fri Oct 27 12:29:32 1995<br>

Subject: Compliance Considerations<p>



You do not mention whether or not your company imports or exports.

If it does, you will want to include the substantive areas covered

by the applicable agencies. Whether or not you do, we have a

number of clients who differentiate their ISO compliance from

their corporate compliance. They do so with two separate manuals.

They start by establishing the issues of most importance to them

in determining compliance. Those general principles are approved

at the Board level by resolution. The next step is setting out how

compliance will be obtained and then who will enforce it.<p>



Does the compliance group within the company have full access to

and the complete support of management? Are there benefits and

incentives to being part of the compliance group, etc?<p>



It is also important to have "teeth" in the program so that when

violations occur, as they inevitably do because we are all human,

discipline is set out in the personnel manual and it is evenly

enforced.<p>



We have found with our clients that the substantive areas are

generally determined by the number and nature of the agencies with

which our clients deal, federal, state and local. With more

information about the products you manufacture,  I could make more

suggestions.<p>



For more details, <A

HREF="mailto:skohnxro@counsel.com">skohnxro@counsel.com</a>.<p>



<hr><p>



Appended by: Joe Murphy -- Bell Atlantic - Philadelphia<br>

Date: Fri Oct 27 15:22:27 1995<br>

Subject: Corporate Compliance<p>



I understand you are looking for a kind of compliance inventory

list, of subject areas to address in a compliance program.  To

give a good answer I'd need to know much more about your business.

However, I'll try to list some possible areas here.  I would not

limit this to federal crimes, but would consider a broad range of

legal and ethical risk areas.  There is a more comprehensive list

in 2 Corporate Conduct Quarterly 35 (Winter 1992).<p>



Possible areas:  Workplace safety, environment, product safety,

antitrust, EEO/labor law (e.g., FLSA), international (e.g., FCPA,

export control, Antiboycott, etc.)(if you do international work),

PAC's/lobbying, securities law/insider trading, government

contract requirements (if you do any work for the government),

intellectual property, taxes, consumer protection,

documents/records management, consent decrees (if you have ever

had any scrapes with the government before), and conflicts of

interest.<p>



Hope this is helpful.   Joe<p>



<hr><p>



Appended by: Herb Zinn -- AZ Public Service - Phoenix<br>

Date: Sat Oct 28 09:43:05 1995<br>

Subject: Corporate Compliance<p>



When we set up our program, we started by doing a basic inventory

of the legal areas set out in Chapter 2 of the [Federal Sentencing Guidelines].

That outlines the crimes that are subject to the FSG's.  It's a good

starting point to get your orientation.  Our frame of reference

was conceptualizing any infraction that "a corporate

organization," not necessarily mine -- could commit, understanding

the nature of the infraction.<p>



Then, using that, we broadened it out to all civil, as well as

criminal matters, including regulatory programs.<p>



We then made sure to consider state and local counterparts as well.<p>



Then, we dropped into the netherworld of ethics to fill in gaps.<p>



I agree with the others who answered your question.  A complete

response depends upon a knowledge of your business and its risks.

But, generically, this is a good way to start.  Joe Murphy's list,

I might add, is a very complete one.<p>



We have some written materials on this.  If they would be of help

to you, let me know.  I'd be glad to fax them to you.  Just give

me your number.<p>



Herb Zinn.

