<BLOCKQUOTE>
<h2>Call for Concrete Examples</h2>
<!--- full_start: 686--->
<H2>Corporate Compliance: Standards For The 21st Century</h2><p>    

<H3>Seminar Discussion Thread</h3><p>    

From: Edward Dauer -- Denver Law School - Denver<br>  

Date:  Sun Oct 29 22:45<br>  

Subject:  Compliance Examples -- NCPL<p>    

The contributions made to the seminar this past week have been  

sterling; on behalf of the National Center for Preventive Law  

(NCPL) I want to thank all who took part.  As we post the balance  

of our compliance guidelines this week and next, I hope they  

and the discussion they generate provide as much that is useful to  

all as the commentary has been to our group.<p>    

There is one special opportunity in which we hope all will  

participate to the extent they are able.  We have been trying to  

collect concrete, practical "examples" of what companies are  

actually doing, to illustrate the  

<A HREF="http://www.courttv.com/legalhelp/business/seminar/654.html">  

twenty principles</a> and their associated considerations.  

(Very much like the "Illustrations"  

that appear in the ALI's Restatements.)  A  

<A HREF="http://www.courttv.com/legalhelp/business/seminar/652.html">model</a>  

or two were  

appended to the seminar at the outset, and are still available.  

(If you can't access or find them easily, leave an append here and  

we will get one out again.)  We would again invite anyone who  

wishes to do so, to offer an illustration draw from their own or  

their clients' experiences.  Even if it contradicts our stated  

Considerations!  So much the better in that case.<p>    

I thank you again for your participation; I hope our work is of  

use to you; and I look forward to hearing about your own methods  

and experiences, posted during the seminar for all to share.<p>    

Enjoy.<p>    

Edward A. Dauer. President<br>  

National Center for Preventive Law    

<p>    

<hr><p>    

Appended by: Theodore Banks -- Kraft Foods, Inc. - Northfield<br>  

Date: Mon Oct 30 20:29:23 1995<br>  

Subject: Compliance Examples<p>    

Here are some compliance ideas (in no particular order) that I  

like:<p><UL>    

<LI>Include a compliance message with new employee orientation  

materials.<p>    

<LI>Train the internal audit staff to look for legal violations in  

addition to accounting mistakes.<p>    

<LI>Work with the corporate training department to incorporate  

compliance messages in every training program administered by the  

company.<p>    

<LI>Attach a compliance training requirement to each job  

description, and track attendance at compliance programs in  

personnel records.<p>    

<LI>Make certain that a "hotline" service is available for the  

reporting of wrongdoing when the normal chain of command is  

inappropriate.<p>    

<LI>Review all compliance presentations and publications to make  

sure they cover two basic points a) what should I do/not do, and  

b) where do I go when I have a question (and there is no such  

thing as a stupid question).    

<LI>Train attorneys to be better teachers (i.e., presentation  

skills).<p>    

<LI>Use feedback to improve the communications of compliance  

messages.<p>    

<LI>Put compliance messages in simple, concrete terms (e.g., use  

examples from the business).<p>    

<LI>Get the chairman/president to record a 90-second video message  

emphasizing the importance of legal compliance in terms of the  

employee's future with the company and play it before  

presentations.<p></ul>    

<HR><p>    

Appended by: anonymous<br>  

Date: Tue Oct 31 10:57:15 1995<br>  

Subject: comments from an in-houser<p>    

[These comments are from a corporate counsel who prefers to remain  

anonymous.]<p><OL>    

<LI>Is this really anything more than "Don't lie, cheat or steal,  

and obey all applicable laws.  If in doubt, call this number."  

Those are pretty simple rules.  Everything else is education and  

procedure.  Only difficult questions are (a) whether to  

self-report and (b) how to punish the offender(s).<p>    

<LI>In-house attorneys deal with this from a different  

perspective.  As the contributors have already noted, The Game  

(congrats to the Braves, btw) is to avoid indictment.  The  

government contracting history is certainly instructive, as they  

are seven years ahead of the rest of the pack, at least.<p>    

<LI>If an employee has violated a policy of compliance with all  

applicable laws ("CWAALs"), and that was done without knowledge,  

the in-housers need to be prepared to bear part of the blame.  

Otherwise, fry the puppy, and do it publicly.<p>    

<LI>Many of the companies that have such policies have had some  

problems in the past.  Is there a message there?  This isn't all  

the terms of the consent decree.<p>    

<LI>Hopefully, these are more than attempts to insulate senior  

management from jail terms, as the front line folks are prone to  

think.  The front line has fairly sensitive bullshitometers, and  

will respond with a cya barrage if they are forced to get close to  

the line by senior management inaction.  That will raise even  

worse problems for an organization.  But you get what you expect  

from people, I guess.<p>    

<LI>I think that five years from now, after a little shakeout  

cruise, most publicly traded companies will have gotten the  

message that the preparation that you need to do to implement and  

maintain one of these programs, and to truly enforce it, saves big  

problems and headaches.  More importantly, it probably (although  

maybe not demonstrably) saves money.  It does, however, force the  

in-housers to engage in much more training and a lot less "pure  

lawyering."  That may get left for the outsides.  This aspect is  

not as much fun for some.  [Ted] Banks was right in his comments about  

the compliance examples, re[garding] the need for more education.  The  

self-reporting thing will, one hopes, be mandated by the  

shareholders, who will start to hold seniors accountable for the  

actions of those for whom they have "responsibility."  Isn't that  

called leadership?<p>    

<LI>Biggest problem is not self-reporting, it's avoiding number 5.  

If you win on number 5, you win.  Collect one brass ring.<p>    

<LI>Does success in these respects factor in to the seniors'  (or  

anyone else's) bonus rights/appraisal?  If not, both positively  

and negatively, it isn't going to happen.<p></ol>    

<hr><p>    

Appended by: Edward Dauer -- Denver Law School - Denver<br>  

Date: Tue Oct 31 13:45:38 1995<br>  

Subject: Hillel's Dictum<p>    

This is in response to the anonymous counsel who suggested that an  

adequate compliance system would be the admonition, "Don't lie,  

cheat or steal.  Any questions, call this number."<p>    

Many years ago (a couple of centuries c.e., if I recall rightly)  

Hillel the Elder was challenged to teach all of the Judaic law  

while standing on one leg.  He said, while standing on one leg,  

"Treat others as you would have them treat you.  All the rest is  

commentary.  Go study."<p>    

I quite agree that finding the essence of a complex matter is  

critical, and efficient.  But I suspect it cannot be done in every  

setting at every moment while standing on one leg.  Still, I defer  

to experience.  Would the counsel do us the favor of sharing the  

actual experiences he has seen with the core admonition approach?  

Many thanks.<p>    

<hr><p>    

Appended by: Richard S. Gruner -- Whittier Law School - Los Angeles<br>  

Date: Tue Oct 31 15:03:46 1995<br>  

Subject: Compliance Examples -- NCPL<p>    

This is a further response to the suggestion that an effective law  

compliance program is little more than an elaborate admonition  

along the lines of "Don't lie.  Don't steal....."<p>    

There are several reasons to think more broadly about compliance  

programs and related corporate management programs.  Here are a  

few:<p><OL>    

<LI>While some corporate crimes (e.g., fraud) are morally obvious  

(as was suggested by the prior "Don't steal..." comment), many  

newer offenses are not.  For example, would it be clear to the  

uninitiated that the failure to report certain cash transactions  

of over $10,000 is a federal offense?  The world of corporate  

crime is increasingly the world of the technical <i>malum prohibitum</i>  

offense [an act which is not inherently immoral, but becomes so because its commission is  

expressly forbidden by law].  One can argue whether such offenses should be imposed,  

but the current reality is that many corporate employees need a  

lot of information about laws (criminal and civil) that apply to  

their jobs.  Furthermore, they often need help to understand how  

bare legal requirements should be transformed into operational  

instructions about what to do on a day to day basis.  These  

matters are necessary targets of both training and follow up  

studies and audits to see if the employees are getting the  

message.<p>    

<LI>Liability rules such as the collective knowledge doctrine  

applied by some courts to impose corporate criminal liability can  

cause individual employees to have even less notice of when their  

actions will produce corporate liability.  Under that doctrine,  

information throughout an organization is aggregated to assess  

whether corporate actions were undertaken knowingly or willingly.  

For example, in <I>United States v. Bank of New England, 821 F.2d  

844 (1st Cir. 1987)</i>, knowledge of federal cash transaction  

reporting requirements held by one bank employee was combined with  

the conduct of bank tellers in failing to report certain  

transactions to find that the bank engaged in a knowing and  

willful violation of federal reporting standards.  Under these  

sorts of tests, firms will need to take a careful look at who  

within their organizations have related information and duties and  

then establish coordination procedures linking those employees to  

insure that inadvertent conduct by an uninformed individual does  

not lead to corporate liability.  These sorts of coordination  

arrangements are additional desirable features of compliance  

programs.<p>    

<LI>Even if law compliance programs were as simple as instructing  

employees "Don't steal, etc.....,"  

firms would still need to adopt audit programs and other  

investigative practices to insure that these instructions were  

carried out.  At least some periodic self-evaluation is probably  

necessary to cause employees to take a compliance instructions  

seriously and to determine if the instructions are complete and  

framed in effective terms.  Such monitoring is also critical if a  

firm hopes to convince prosecutors or courts that it operated a  

generally effective compliance program at the time of a violation.<p>    

<LI>Finally, although we are generally discussing programs to  

prevent criminal offenses in this seminar, the goals of a law  

compliance program should not be so narrowly framed.  The general  

purpose of such programs should be to enhance the legal position  

of the corporation in a systematic fashion.  Granted, part of the  

achievement of this goal will be the prevention of offenses and  

resulting corporate penalties and reputational impairment.  

However, the avoidance of civil liability will be another key  

element.  Additionally, strengthening the corporation's legal  

position relative to others can also be furthered by systematic  

efforts to understand and revise corporate practices with legal  

implications.  When these broader goals of compliance programs are  

considered, the need in compliance program designs for more  

elaborate direction of employee actions and monitoring of results  

is clearer.<p></ol>    

Richard Gruner<p>    

<p>    

<hr><p>    

Appended by: anonymous<br>  

Date: Wed Nov  1 09:51:15 1995<br>  

Subject: response from anon1<p>    

[<I>This comment is from the anonymous corporate counsel who posted  

yesterday:</i>]<p>    

In response, first:  what makes you think I am a he?  We are  

offended.<p>    

Second, following the example of Prof. Janet Spragens, a Tax Prof  

from yesteryear:  Read on.  My comment said not only don't lie  

cheat or steal.  But also obey all applicable laws.<p>    

The inside's job is to identify and to educate -- perhaps more  

than to lawyer in whatever passes in these troubled times for  

"lawyering."  Find what applies and explain it to the non-lawyers.  

Shake the bushes.  Look under rocks.  Talk with people who have  

to apply Your Great teachings.  Walk amongst the hoi polloi.  

If the system fails and someone doesn't know what The Law is that  

applies to The Business, who's to blame?<p>    

OTOH, if they know, and fail to obey, where's the problem?  And  

the solution?<p>    

<I>When folks are taught<br>    

What to do<br>    

And do they not<br>    

What they ought<br>    

Time to start<br>    

With employees new.<p>    

Burma Shave.</i><p>    

Were one to (subjunctive, condition contrary to fact) consider  

what purpose a compliance with all laws or whatever policy  

fulfills, beyond being but one arrow in the inhousers' educational  

quiver, one would be hard pressed to fill the blank.  It is but a  

yellow flag along the road, a mere indicator of when it is  

advisable to talk with One AllKnowing.<p>    

My call:  Spend the time educating and explaining and spreading  

the message far and wide.  That's what we're here for, brothers  

and sisters of the inhouse stripe.  Leave the policy  

pronouncements for the windbags.  All else is windows dressing,  

and poor theater at that.<p>    

Anon.<p>    

<hr><p>    

Appended by: Richard S. Gruner -- Whittier Law School - Los Angeles<br>  

Date: Wed Nov  1 12:46:42 1995<br>  

Subject: Compliance Examples -- NCPL<p>    

In the spirit of evaluating what really works, I would respond to  

our anonymous insider that education is necessary, but not  

sufficient.  The test of the pudding is whether law compliance is  

treated with the same seriousness as other important management  

concerns.  What important management concern (e.g., product  

quality, cost reduction, etc.) is addressed only with education?  

Even with the best law compliance education program, management  

(including inside counsel) needs to follow up with periodic  

monitoring of compliance levels and more intensive investigations  

of revealed compliance failures.  Furthermore, persons found to  

have failed to maintain compliance should receive discipline and  

publicity should be given to the administration of such discipline  

(although perhaps not to the identify of the disciplined parties  

to the extent that this can be concealed).  Absent these types of  

steps, it is likely that a program will not be effective.  

Employees will not take it seriously (they know what steps  

management takes towards matters that management really thinks are  

important) and misconduct that could have been detected and  

prevented will go on unabated.<p>    

Pretend that law compliance is a performance quality control  

problem.  What would your concern do to insure quality?  Consider  

the same sorts of practices regarding law compliance.<p>    

Richard Gruner<p>    

<hr><p>    

Appended by: Susan Macaulay -- Caremark Inc. - Northbrook<br>  

Date: Wed Nov  1 15:39:22 1995<br>  

Subject: Compliance Examples -- NCPL<p>    

For what it's worth, and to state the utterly obvious....An  

effective compliance program is not simply a matter of "If you  

build it, they will come."  You can write all of the manuals you  

want to, hold all of the training programs you have time for,  

audit the heck out of your operations, and fire any employee who  

even has a bad thought.  You can write 50-page documents  

accompanied by glitzy videotapes, or you can hand out 3X5 cards  

that say "Don't do anything illegal, immoral, or fattening."  In  

the end, the form and content aren't really that important  

(ignoring, of course, the FSG's, which do require a certain amount  

of tangible evidence).  All you've created is an elaborate  

corporate police force, which, speaking personally, I find an  

utterly distasteful way to practice in-house law.<p>    

I'm a relative newcomer to Caremark (only here since April), so I  

arrived just in time for our $161 million settlement/guilty pleas  

with the U.S. government, fortunately missing most of the 4-year  

OIG-investigation experience most of my Caremark Law Group  

colleagues so bravely and painfully endured. But as the  

in-house attorney who is now part of the Corporate Integrity Team  

and an active participant in the development and implementation of  

our Corporate Integrity Program, I can tell you that although the  

existence of the tangibles of compliance are important (and, in  

our case, mandated as a result of our settlement with the  

government), they don't mean a damn thing if a commitment to  

integrity and fair dealing isn't part of the corporate culture,  

the way people think about and act and do their jobs.   Teach it  

all you want.  If someone's out to beat the system, they will.<p>    

And that's the really hard part of an effective compliance  

program.  Integrity is really tough to teach.  Integrity is  

sometimes even tougher to exercise when you're competing in an  

industry where not everyone else does.  People within the  

organization have to feel it, and those who don't have to be  

"supported" and "encouraged" and "guided" by those who do.  Those  

who don't ultimately "get it" have suffer the consequences, no  

matter how much they contribute to the bottom line.<p>    

Enough of the sermon. <p>    

Although I've been following this discussion since it's inception,  

I've not commented until now because, as one who is deep in the  

midst of a government-mandated and unbelievably far-reaching  

compliance program, anytime I've tried to attach a specific  

comment, it seemed utterly inadequate (as does the one I've just  

created).  So I will make the following offer:  If anyone has  

specific questions about what we're doing, what we're required to  

do, how we're getting it done, etc., I'd be happy to talk, either  

through this discussion group or, if you'd prefer, by phone, at  

708-559-5459.  I may not be able to talk to you at the time you  

call, but I'd be happy to set up a time that works for us both.<p>    

Just one final caveat:  Get a compliance program in place that  

works - if you don't, the government will solve the problem for  

you, and you won't like their solution one bit!<p>    

<p>    

<hr><p>    

Appended by: anonymous<br>  

Date: Thu Nov  2 09:29:38 1995<br>  

Subject: Another response from Anon1<p>    

[<I>This is a third comment from the anonymous corporate counsel participating  

in the discussion.</i>]<p>    

Re[garding] Mr. Gruner's comment that education is not everything there is  

about corporate compliance.<p>    

We agree.<p>    

But what is the lawyer's role in such a program (or, better,  

process)?<p>    

One difference between a product quality program and a compliance  

with all laws policy is that the business people feel they know  

what product quality means (whether they do or not is a different  

panel).  They will do surveys of what customers feel is important,  

and apply their own business sense.<p>    

In the law area, though, the Guild has kept the keys to the  

Kingdom of Knowledge, or at least the pace and  

complexity/ambiguity of new laws is such that no mortal (or even  

an attorney) can truly master it all.  Business people count on  

the lawyers to identify the laws that might apply and to explain  

them in business terms.<p>    

Having done that, it is perhaps someone else's job to decide what  

to do if someone does a no-no.  The impact of not reacting is,  

perhaps, a matter with legal import; but it is just a matter of  

judgment  (in which the lawyers have no better or worse judgment)  

as to how much to react.<p>    

But we certainly agree that if the organization does not Truly  

Believe that this is important, no amount of training will matter.  

Nor will a policy or a program.  This is as true with product  

quality as it is with law.  We would prefer to be elsewhere when  

the Federal Boot drops.<p>    

OTOH, if the organization Believes, then training and guidance  

might be a big part of having a process that works.<p>   

<hr><p>  

From: Philip Sellinger -- Sills Cummis -- Newark<br> 

Date:  Fri Nov  3 11:11<br> 

Subject:  Compliance Examples<p>  

The anonymous comments about self-reporting raise serious issues. 

In many respects, the decision whether or not to report when not 

mandated by law, and how to report, are among the most troublesome 

and those without general rules of thumb.  To be sure, the 

advantages the FSGs offer in mitigation of sentence are not 

available to those who do not self-report.  Nonetheless, most 

companies make decisions about reporting on a case by case 

basis.<p>  

They may decide that in certain circumstances, the benefits the 

FSGs offer do not justify the risk occasioned by involvement with 

regulators that might  otherwise be avoided.<p>  

I am not sure that shareholders, as you suggest, are oftentime in 

a position to encourage disclosure except that if management 

erroneously decides not to report and a serious investigation 

nonetheless results, management will probably lose their jobs. 

Independent directors, on the other hand, are more likely to be in 

a position to demand self-reporting.  Further, their likely 

independence from the wrongdoing or wrongdoers and their 

disinclination to incur risk makes them likely candidates to 

demand disclosure even when such disclosure is not required. 

Thus, in public companies with independent directors, disclosure 

is practically more likely than it might otherwise be.<p>  

<hr><p>  

Appended by: Theodore Banks -- Kraft Foods, Inc. - Northfield<br> 

Date: Sat Nov  4 16:09:04 1995<br> 

Subject: Wear the Halo.<p>  

"Obey the law & call if you have a question" should be 

considered the starting point of a compliance program.  Obviously, 

there is lots more.  In corporations, one of the most common ways 

to ensure compliance is to establish procedures that do not allow 

any flexibility to break various laws.  For example, a salesman in 

my company would have a difficult time fixing prices, since he 

would not have authority to set the price.  OTOH, it is precisely 

these kind of rigid policies or procedures that can result in 

excessively bureaucratic, static, unimaginative corporations, that 

end up going down the drain.   So, the goal of the corporation is 

to establish minimum level of procedures necessary to ensure 

financial controls and legal compliance, while giving the 

employees room to do their jobs creatively.  The lawyer must work 

with all of the assets of the corporation (training department, 

internal audit, executives) to make sure that the compliance 

message comes through in an environment where the employee has some 

freedom to make choices.<p>  

