<html><head><title>Seminars - Principle No. 8 - Structure and Control</title>
</head> <BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#FF0005">
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/smb.gif" BORDER=0>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<h2>Principle No. 8 - Structure and Control</h2>
<!--- full_start: 702--->
<H2>Corporate Compliance: Standards For The 21st Century</h2><p>



<H3>Seminar Discussion Thread</h3><p>



From: Christina Cooley -- Counsel Connect - Atlanta<br>

Date:  Mon Oct 30 08:50<br>

Subject:  PR. 8-Structure and Control<p>



<H4>NATIONAL CENTER FOR PREVENTIVE LAW WORKING GROUP DRAFT</h4>



<H3>Establishing Compliance Programs, Continued. . .</h3>



<I>Note:  Principle #8 and its Considerations are intended to

address the following aspect of the <a href=../../../../download/seminars/fsg1.html>

Federal Sentencing Guidelines: Sec. 8A1.2(k)</a>(2):  "Specific individual(s) within high-level

personnel of the organization must have been assigned overall

responsibility to oversee compliance with such standards and

procedures."</i><p>



<H4>Principle #8: Specific high-level personnel in an organization

are responsible for the administration and oversight of the

compliance program.</h4><p>



Factors to Consider:<p>



(a) Having an organizational compliance officer take "ownership"

of the compliance function in the sense of having overall

responsibility for initiating, coordinating and reviewing

organizational compliance efforts.<p>



(b) Insuring that the top organizational executive with

responsibility for a compliance program has the degree of clout

necessary to make the program effective.<p>



(c) Making the types of expertise available to a compliance

officer that are needed to help operate a compliance program

effectively.<p>



(d) Selecting a compliance officer with personal characteristics

that will make the individual effective in leading and promoting

organizational compliance efforts.<p>



(e) Determining what functions, if any, the compliance officer

should perform besides management and oversight of compliance

activities.<p>



(f) Considering whether the designation of one person with

primary responsibility for management of compliance practices will

lead others in the organization to conclude that compliance is

only the compliance officer's job.<p>



(g) Identifying resources, support and infrastructure needed by

the compliance officer and others to pursue compliance

effectively.<p>



(h) Determining the compliance officer's proper level of authority

and access to the organization's governance authorities in order

to insure both that the officer is able to exert effective control

over compliance-related matters and that compliance management is

perceived as an important activity by other organization

members.<p>



We urge you to submit comments and examples about the above

Principle.  To assist you in this, please review the postings

from the first day of the seminar, October 23, on the <a href=../../../../download/seminars/fsg1.html>Federal

Sentencing Guidelines</a>, the <a href=../../../../download/seminars/principle1.html>Full Set of Principles</a> and the <a href=../../../../download/seminars/model1.html>Model

Example</a>. Please note that the Principles and Considerations are

copyrighted by the NCPL and may not be reproduced without

permission of the NCPL.

<P><hr><p>



<CENTER><I><A HREF="http://www.courttv.com/download/seminars/form1.html">

Submit your question or comment to the discussion</i>.</a></center><!--- full_end--->

</BLOCKQUOTE>
