<html><head><title>Seminars - Principle No. 9 - Support of Senior Management</title>
</head> <BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#FF0005">
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/smb.gif" BORDER=0>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<h2>Principle No. 9 - Support of Senior Management</h2>
<!--- full_start: 703--->
<H2>Corporate Compliance: Standards For The 21st Century</h2><p>



<H3>Seminar Discussion Thread</h3><p>



From: Christina Cooley -- Counsel Connect - Atlanta<br>

Date:  Mon Oct 30 08:52<br>

Subject:  PR. 9-Sr. Management Support<p>



<H4>NATIONAL CENTER FOR PREVENTIVE LAW WORKING GROUP DRAFT</h4><p>



<H3>Establishing Compliance Programs, Continued. . .</h3><p>



<I>Note:  Principle #9 and its Considerations are intended to

address the following aspects of the <a href=../../../../download/seminars/fsg1.html>

Federal Sentencing Guidelines: Sec. 8A1.2(k</a> (1): "The organization must have

established compliance standards and procedures to be followed

by its employees and other agents that are reasonably capable

of reducing the prospect of criminal conduct," and Sec. 8A1.2(k):

"The hallmark of an effective program to prevent and detect

violations of law is that the organization exercised due

diligence in seeking to prevent and detect criminal conduct by

its employees and other agents."</i><p>



<H4>Principle #9:  A compliance program has the support of senior

management of the organization.  Each officer, manager and

employee is responsible for supporting and complying with the

compliance program's standards and procedures.</h4><p>



Factors to Consider:<p>



(a) Having participation in and support for the program

throughout the organization rather than limiting visible

support for compliance to a compliance officer.<p>



(b) Considering the consistency of the incentive, appraisal and

recognition systems used within the organization, with the idea

that compliance is a widespread responsibility and should be

reflected in those systems.<p>



(c) Examining the variety of ways senior management can send

the message that it considers a specific compliance behavior or

objective to be high priority.<p>



(d) Determining the degree to which the management of

compliance or ethical practices by subordinates is part of day-

to-day responsibility.<p>



(e) Determining the compliance roles of organizational agents

and further participants in the organization's business

activities other than employees.<p>



(f) Examining the express and implied messages that managers

give to employees about meeting the organization's compliance

goals.<p>



We urge you to submit comments and examples about the above

Principle.  To assist you in this, please review the postings

from the first day of the seminar, October 23, on the <a href=../../../../download/seminars/fsg1.html>Federal

Sentencing Guidelines</a>, the <a href=../../../../download/seminars/principle1.html>Full Set of Principles</a> and the <a href=../../../../download/seminars/model1.html>Model

Example</a>. Please note that the Principles and Considerations are

copyrighted by the NCPL and may not be reproduced without

permission of the NCPL.

