<html><head><title>Seminars - Principle No. 11 - Reasonable Steps to Achieve Compliance</title>
</head> <BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#FF0005">
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/smb.gif" BORDER=0>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<h2>Principle No. 11 - Reasonable Steps to Achieve Compliance</h2>
<!--- full_start: 726--->
<H2>Corporate Compliance: Standards For The 21st Century</h2><p>



<H3>Seminar Discussion Thread</h3><p>



From: Christina Cooley -- Counsel Connect - Atlanta<br>

Date:  Wed Nov  1 09:20<br>

Subject:  PR. 11-Reasonable Steps<p>



<H4>NATIONAL CENTER FOR PREVENTIVE LAW WORKING GROUP DRAFT</h4>



<H3>Establishing Compliance Programs, Continued. . .</h3>



<I>Note:  Principle #11 and its Considerations are intended to

address the following aspects of the <a href=../../../../download/seminars/fsg1.html>

Federal Sentencing Guidelines: Sec. 8A1.2(k)</a>(5): The organization must have taken

reasonable steps to achieve compliance with its standards .

.</i><p>



<H4>Principle #11: The organization takes reasonable steps to

achieve compliance with its standards and the law.</h4>



Factors to Consider:<p>



(a) Using evaluative and reporting systems to determine the

effectiveness of compliance efforts and to deter and detect

violations.<p>



(b) Reviewing and auditing employee conduct and corporate

operations to provide measures of how the company is doing in

its efforts to comply with the law and its own standards.<p>



(c) Using different compliance review methods for different

purposes and in different business environments.<p>



(d) Pursuing self-monitoring and regular reporting in key

aspects of business performance related to compliance.<p>



(e) Using evaluative techniques to measure both the degree of

substantive compliance, and how well compliance processes are

being implemented.<p>



(f) Evaluating the desirable frequency and scope of such

reviews.<p>



(g) Assessing the independence and reliability of persons who

perform compliance evaluations.<p>



(h) Determining whether compliance reviews should be done by

persons inside or outside an organization or organizational

unit.<p>



(i) Devising channels of communication between those who are

performing compliance studies or audits and those who need the

results to act on the findings.<p>



(j) Establishing systems to assure follow-ups to negative

investigation or audit findings.<p>



(k) Adopting real-time monitoring of conduct as a technique for

promoting compliance.<p>



(l) Having a means for employees and agents to report

violations of legal requirements and compliance program

standards.<p>



(m) Providing protection against retaliation for those who

report misconduct.<p>



(n) Taking steps to assure that employees and agents know how

to reach systems for reporting offenses and other misconduct.<p>



(o) Including compliance issues in due diligence studies

preceding mergers and acquisitions and in planning for new

business activities.<p>



(p) Defining the degree of confidentiality and legal privilege

protection that are appropriate for self-evaluative compliance

activities.<p>



We urge you to submit comments and examples about the above

Principle.  To assist you in this, please review the postings

from the first day of the seminar, October 23, on the <a href=../../../../download/seminars/fsg1.html>Federal

Sentencing Guidelines</a>, the <a href=../../../../download/seminars/principle1.html>Full Set of Principles</a> and the <a href=../../../../download/seminars/model1.html>Model

Example</a>. Please note that the Principles and Considerations are

copyrighted by the NCPL and may not be reproduced without

permission of the NCPL.

