<html><head><title>Seminars - Containing the Costs of Compliance</title>
</head> <BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#FF0005">
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/smb.gif" BORDER=0>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<h2>Containing the Costs of Compliance</h2>
<!--- full_start: 727--->
<H2>Corporate Compliance: Standards For The 21st Century</h2><p>



<H3>Seminar Discussion Thread</h3><p>



From: Cloyd Laporte, III -- Counsel Connect - New York<br>

Date:  Wed Nov  1 10:28<br>

Subject:  Costs of Compliance<p>



Today's Wall Street Journal reports that the Small Business

Administration (SBA) has presented a study to Congress showing

that small businesses spent a total of $265 Billion complying with

federal regulations in 1992, or about $5,400 per employee for

companies with fewer than 500 workers. In contrast, larger

companies (>500 employees) spent $130 Billion or $3,000 per

employee.<p>



The Journal quotes Jere Glover, SBA's chief counsel for advocacy,

"[O]ne conclusion is beyond dispute. Small businesses bear a

disproportionate share of this nation's annual regulatory bill[,].

11/2/95 at B2.<p>



Can an effective compliance program reduce these costs? Should

compliance efficiency, as well as efficacy, be a goal of a

compliance program? The 

<a href=../../../../download/seminars/principle1.html>

NCPL's Twenty Principles</a> seem equally

applicable to small and large businesses, but can a small company

afford to implement them?<p>



[By the way, I checked the <A HREF="http://www.sbaonline.sba.gov/">

SBA home page</a> on the Web, and the study isn't available

there as of this morning. I did post a request there, and will

check again later this week].<p>



- Cloyd<p>



<hr><p>



Appended by: Richard S. Gruner -- Whittier Law School - Los Angeles<br>

Date: Wed Nov  1 12:30:29 1995<br>

Subject:<p>



A systematic effort to pursue law compliance should aid small

business in the following ways:<p><OL>



<LI>Efforts that are undertaken can be limited to those with a

high likelihood of success.  By thinking through law compliance

programs in advance, small firms can avoid throwing away their

highly limited resources on ineffective compliance efforts.<p>



<LI>Systematic law compliance efforts can achieve levels of

efficiency that isolated, haphazard efforts will not.  To some

extent, this probably explains why the study described in the

previous message found that larger concerns were spending less per

employee on compliance.  The larger concerns may simply be

pursuing compliance more efficiently because they are able to get

more mileage out of some of their compliance efforts.  Small

businesses can do the same in some areas.  Where a small firm will

engage in a particular activity repeatedly, it will be worthwhile

to work out related law compliance measures on a systematic

basis.<p>



<LI>While small concerns can not justify the same scope and

formality of programs as larger firms, the small companies should

undertake some compliance efforts in the areas addressed by the

NCPL standards.  This issue is addressed in proposed standards for

environmental compliance programs now being considered by the U.S.

Sentencing Commission.  While these proposed standards discuss

compliance efforts regarding environmental law compliance, most of

the comments are relevant to compliance efforts in broader areas.

In discussing the need for compliance efforts in small concerns,

the proposed standards noted:<p>



<I>"It should be emphasized that in assessing the extent of an

organization's commitment [to environmental law compliance], both

the size and the nature of the organization are very important.

Ordinarily, organizations with larger numbers of operating

facilities or pollution control activities and obligations should

have more extensive and sophisticated environmental management

systems, programs and resources of the nature described in the

[proposed standards] than would be expected of similar, but

smaller organizations.  Similarly, organizations whose business

activities may pose significant risks of harm to human health or

the environment from non-compliance with environmental

requirements (e.g., manufacture, use or management of hazardous

products, materials or wastes) should have more extensive and

sophisticated systems, programs and resources than would be

expected of comparably sized organizations in less risky types of

business.<p>



"Small organizations should demonstrate the same degree of

commitment to environmental compliance as larger ones, although

generally with less formality and less dedicated resources (if

any) than would be expected of larger organizations.  While each

of the functions and objectives described in [proposed standards]

should be substantially satisfied by all organizations, the small

organization typically will rely on management personnel,

operations personnel or others to assume compliance support

responsibilities in addition to their routine duties, and will

have less sophisticated systems for establishing compliance

procedures, auditing and tracking compliance issues, training

employees and carrying out the other programmatic components of

their compliance effort.  For example, in a very small business,

the manager or proprietor, as opposed to independent compliance

personnel, might perform routine audits with a simple checklist,

train employees through informal staff meetings, and perform

compliance monitoring through daily "walk-arounds" or continuous

observation while managing the business.  In appropriate

circumstances, this reliance on existing resources and simple

systems can demonstrate the same degree of commitment that, for a

much larger organization, would require, for example, a full-time

audit department, a training staff, an active compliance

monitoring staff, and computer systems for tracking the resolution

of compliance issues.<p>



"The essential requirement is that each organization must

demonstrate, through appropriate documentation, that the resources

and management processes it utilized were reasonably determined to

be sufficient to perform the basic functions described in Part D.

If, prior to the conviction, the organization had a reasonable

basis to believe that its commitment of resources and processes

would be sufficient, given its size and the nature of its

business, then an appropriate mitigation value should be applied

even though that commitment proved insufficient to prevent the

offense of conviction."</i></ol><p>



Advisory Group on Environmental Sanctions, Final Report to the

Sentencing Commission &szlig; 9D1.1 (Nov. 16, 1993) (Comment 3).  The

full text of this proposal was reprinted in the BNA Environmental

Reporter, Nov. 26, 1993, at 1378 and is also available in the

BNAENV file on Lexis.  A copy of the proposal is available by

request from the Sentencing Commission by contacting Michael

Courlander, Public Information Specialist, at

(202) 273-4590.



<p>



<hr><p>



Appended by: Joe Murphy -- Bell Atlantic - Philadelphia<br>

Date: Thu Nov  2 08:31:11 1995<br>

Subject: Costs of Compliance<p>



Cloyd,<p>

In addition to Richard's points about scaling the compliance

efforts to match the risk and resources of the company, there are

other sides to the cost issue.<p>



First, I would not describe the effort as a "law" compliance

program.  It is really a form of  exercising control;  the subject

need not be limited to the company's compliance with law.  The

fact is that a good system for controlling the business' conduct

from a legal and ethical point of view can result in the entity

being more efficient as well.<p>



Second, I think smaller businesses are overlooking the

opportunities to pool costs with other businesses.  For example,

small businesses could work through trade associations and other

groups to arrange group training, operate a hotline, and share

other resources.<p>



A third point is that a good compliance program will detect

instances where the company itself is the victim or potential

victim of costly wrongdoing, such as employee theft.  In smaller

and start-up businesses where controls are notoriously lax, having

an effective compliance program, with the awareness of risk that

this can create, can more than pay for the cost of the effort just

in this area of self-protection.<p>



Of course, there is also the value of preventing company

violations of law and the resultant harm and costs associated with

that.    Joe Murphy<p>



