<html><head><title>Seminars - Principle No. 13 - Importance of Investigatory Resources</title>
</head> <BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#FF0005">
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/smb.gif" BORDER=0>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<h2>Principle No. 13 - Importance of Investigatory Resources</h2>
<!--- full_start: 738--->
<H2>Corporate Compliance: Standards For The 21st Century</h2><p>



<H3>Seminar Discussion Thread</h3><p>



From: Christina Cooley -- Counsel Connect - Atlanta<br>

Date:  Fri Nov  3 09:32<br>

Subject:  PR. 13-Investigatory Resource<p>



<H4>NATIONAL CENTER FOR PREVENTIVE LAW WORKING GROUP DRAFT</h4>



<H3>Response to Violations and Incidents, Continued. . .</h3>



<I>Note:  Principle #13 and its Considerations are intended to

address the following aspects of the <a href=../../../../download/seminars/fsg1.html>

Federal Sentencing Guidelines:  Sec. 8A1.2(k)</a>(6): "The standards must have been

consistently enforced through appropriate disciplinary

mechanisms, including, as appropriate, discipline of

individuals responsible for the failure to detect an offense,"

AND Sec. 8A1.2(k)(7):  "After an offense has been detected, the

organization must have taken all reasonable steps to respond

appropriately to the offense and to prevent similar offenses --

including any necessary modifications to its programs to

prevent and detect violations of law."</i>



<H4>Principle #13: An effective compliance program possesses or has

access to investigatory, valuative and reporting resources.</h4>



Factors to Consider:<p>



(a) Determining who will conduct compliance investigations in

advance of occasions for such investigations.<p>



(b) Assuring that compliance investigations are undertaken by

persons with adequate expertise to identify breaches of legal

requirements and compliance program standards.<p>



(c) Making certain the investigative and response programs are

identifiable.<p>



(d) Making certain that further investigations and responses

are undertaken following the detection of possible misconduct.<p>



(e) Assuring the adequacy of resources available to compliance

fact finders.<p>



(f) Insuring the independence of compliance fact finders from

line managers whose activities or organizations are being

scrutinized.<p>



(g) Developing record-keeping capabilities and resources to aid

in identifying compliance problems and in monitoring responses.<p>



(h) Assuring preparedness for compliance investigations and

responses.<p>



(i) Assuring appropriate scope and methodologies in the

completion of compliance investigations and responses.<p>



(j) Defining internal reporting systems that will provide

indications that compliance investigations are needed.<p>



(k) Assuring accuracy and reliability of information gathered

in compliance investigations.<p>



We urge you to submit comments and examples about the above

Principle.  To assist you in this, please review the postings

from the first day of the seminar, October 23, on the <a href=../../../../download/seminars/fsg1.html>Federal

Sentencing Guidelines</a>, the <a href=../../../../download/seminars/principle1.html>Full Set of Principles</a> and the <a href=../../../../download/seminars/model1.html>Model

Example</a>. Please note that the Principles and Considerations are

copyrighted by the NCPL and may not be reproduced without

permission of the NCPL.<p>



