<html><head><title>Seminars - Principle No. 14 - External Reporting of Legal Violations</title>
</head> <BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#FF0005">
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/smb.gif" BORDER=0>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<h2>Principle No. 14 - External Reporting of Legal Violations</h2>
<!--- full_start: 742--->
<H2>Corporate Compliance: Standards For The 21st Century</h2>



<H3>Seminar Discussion Thread</h3><p>



From: Christina Cooley -- Counsel Connect - Atlanta<br>

Date:  Sun Nov  5 22:33<br>

Subject:  PR. 14-External Reporting<p>



<H4>NATIONAL CENTER FOR PREVENTIVE LAW WORKING GROUP DRAFT</h4>



<H3>Response to Violations and Incidents, Continued. . .</h3>



<I>Note:  Principle #14 and its Considerations

are intended to address the following

aspects of the <a href=../../../../download/seminars/fsg1.html>

Federal Sentencing Guidelines:  8A1.2(k)</a>(5): "The

organization must have taken reasonable

steps to achieve compliance with its

standards . . ." and  8A1.2(k)(7):  "After

an offense has been detected, the

organization must have taken all reasonable

steps to respond appropriately to the

offense and to prevent similar offenses --

including any necessary modifications to

its programs to prevent and detect

violations of law."</i><p>



<H4>Principle #14: An effective compliance

program addresses the occasions for

external reporting of violations of the

law.</h4>



Factors to Consider:<p>



(a) Weighing the advantages of self-

reporting of misconduct under federal

sentencing guidelines, government voluntary

disclosure programs and other legal

standards.<p>



(b) Designating decision-making

responsibility and authority for determining

when and how to self-report detected

misconduct.<p>



(c) Assuring that self-reporting by an

organization will at least comply with

mandatory reporting requirements.<p>



(d) Determining the appropriate scope of

disclosures when a decision is made to

self-report detected misconduct.<p>



(e) Addressing potential conflicts between

an organization and its agents and

employees where the organization chooses to

report detected misconduct.<p>



(f) Waiving or preserving legal privileges

in the course of disclosing information to

public officials.<p>



(g) Considering whether self-reporting will

be accompanied by an organizational

acceptance of responsibility in accordance

with provisions of federal sentencing

guidelines.<p>



(h) Deciding whether to cooperate with

external investigations by public

authorities as encouraged by federal

sentencing guidelines.<p>



(i) Remediating harm from detected

misconduct.<p>



(j) Identifying the scope and ramifications

of an organization's vicarious

responsibility for detected misconduct.<p>



We urge you to submit comments and examples about the above

Principle.  To assist you in this, please review the postings

from the first day of the seminar, October 23, on the <a href=../../../../download/seminars/fsg1.html>Federal

Sentencing Guidelines</a>, the <a href=../../../../download/seminars/principle1.html>Full Set of Principles</a> and the <a href=../../../../download/seminars/model1.html>Model

Example</a>. Please note that the Principles and Considerations are

copyrighted by the NCPL and may not be reproduced without

permission of the NCPL.

<p>



<hr><p>



Appended by: Robert Sanger -- Sanger & Associates - Santa Barbara<br>

Date: Wed Nov  8 23:45:08 1995<br>

Subject: External Reporting<p>



This is an area which should give rise to a great deal of thought

and it would be good to see a discussion here.<p>



Earlier, we posed a number tough questions and a bit of hard

reality in a thread entitled "Pitfalls."  Suffice it to say, from

the prospective of a criminal defense lawyer who is often not

called in until after the search warrants are served, the

indictment is returned or folks are arrested, criminal prosecution

is not a pleasant matter.  It can end the life of the corporation

and it can change the life forever of the individual.  Of course,

we fight hard to avoid these dire results but, even in a

successful defense, the toll is great.<p>



The guidelines and Principle #14 highlight certain specific

questions of importance to the criminal defense lawyer (and of

importance to the potential and actual criminal defendants):<p><OL>



<LI>Even though voluntary disclosure may mitigate criminal

punishment, what steps can be taken to try to avoid the decision

to indict in the first place?<p>



<LI>When should corporate counsel advise employees that they have

a right (ought) to have the advice of counsel?<p>



<LI>When can the corporate counsel advise the employees?  When

should corporate counsel arrange for outside counsel?  Should

outside counsel be paid for by the company?<p>



<LI>How can you best preserve the attorney/client privilege and

the work product doctrine for the corporation?  For it's officers

and directors?  For other key employees?  Do you want to?<p>



<LI>Who amongst the corporation itself, the officers, directors

and key employees, if any, are going to throw themselves on their

swords to accept responsibility?   Will it do any good?<p>



<LI>Who is going to be thrown upon someone else's sword

involuntarily?  Will it do any good?<p>



<LI>Will you enter into a joint defense agreement with your

new-found codefendants?  Prior to indictment?  Post-indictment?<p>



<LI>Will corporate counsel assert the attorney/client privilege at

the grand jury?  As to what?  At the trial?  As to what?<p></ol>



Criminal defense lawyers, including myself, have some ideas -- and

a bunch of sea stories -- on each of these questions.  It would be

interesting to hear from corporate counsel as well.  Any thoughts?<p>



Bob Sanger<p>





<hr><p>





Appended by: Joe Murphy -- Bell Atlantic - Philadelphia<br>


Date: Mon Nov 13 16:00:54 1995<br>


Subject: External Reporting<p>





Bob,<p>


You raise quite a list of good questions.  I'd like to answer


them all, but my company keeps insisting that I do work, so I will


just offer a few words.<p>





You ask about avoiding prosecution.  My first goal is to avoid a


violation; if one occurs my goal is then to avoid prosecution.  If


all I am left with is a sentence reduction, then I will have


failed.  You are right to focus on the declination decision.<p>





How do you avoid prosecution?  I would look for several steps:


1)Have in place a compliance program with real teeth;  go light on


the paper and preaching, and heavy on audits, senior management


commitment, discipline, etc; 2)If you find a problem, react to it


quickly and fix it fast;  a company's reaction to a violation is


much more likely to get it into trouble than the violation itself;


3)Remedy the wrong; e.g., if you stole something, give it back;


4)Consider self-reporting; it is a gut-wrenching decision, but


there is no substitute for this from a prosecutor's point of view;


5)If you are going to self-report, use outside counsel who knows


the agency;  know what you are doing before you start on this


process.<p>





Some agencies have good programs for voluntary disclosure (e.g.,


the Antitrust Division; for others you just take your chances.


But a number of prosecutors have been saying the right words about


the value of compliance programs and voluntary disclosure in terms


of avoiding criminal prosecution.<p>





With respect to privilege, you cannot count on it, but I would


not give up the chance to assert it.  In conducting an


investigation, I would follow the path set out in the Upjohn case.<p>





If I was making a voluntary disclosure and decided to waive the


privilege, I would make sure the prosecutor understood how big a


concession we were making. Of course, I would  be very careful in


writing up the investigation, always assuming that others will


somehow see it.  For those who are interested, we've covered this


at some length in Compliance Programs and the Corporate Sentencing


Guidelines, chapter 5, on privileges.<p>





Joe<p>





<hr><p>





<CENTER><I><A HREF="http://www.courttv.com/download/seminars/form1.html">





Submit your question or comment to the discussion</i>.</a></center><!--- full_end--->

</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P ALIGN=CENTER><br>
