<html><head><title>Seminars - Principle No. 15 - Learning from Incidents of Non-compliance</title>
</head> <BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#FF0005">
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/smb.gif" BORDER=0>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<h2>Principle No. 15 - Learning from Incidents of Non-compliance</h2>
<!--- full_start: 744--->
<H2>Corporate Compliance: Standards For The 21st Century</h2><p>



<H3>Seminar Discussion Thread</h3><p>



From: Christina Cooley -- Counsel Connect - Atlanta<br>

Date:  Sun Nov  5 22:34<br>

Subject:  PR. 15-Incidents of Noncompliance<p>



<H4>NATIONAL CENTER FOR PREVENTIVE LAW WORKING GROUP DRAFT</h4>



<H3>Response to Violations and Incidents, Continued. . .</h3>



<I>

Note:  Principle #15 and its Considerations are

intended to address the following aspects of the

<a href=../../../../download/seminars/fsg1.html>

Federal Sentencing Guidelines:  8A1.2(k)</a>(6):

The standards must have been consistently

enforced through appropriate disciplinary

mechanisms, including, as appropriate,

discipline of individuals responsible for the

failure to detect an offense AND  8A1.2(k)(7):

 "After an offense has been detected, the

organization must have taken all reasonable

steps to respond appropriately to the offense

and to prevent similar offenses -- including any

necessary modifications to its programs to

prevent and detect violations of law."</i><p>



<h4>Principle #15: An effective compliance program

utilizes incidents of noncompliance to evaluate

its own effectiveness, to correct deficiencies

and to effect improvements.</h4>



Factors to Consider:<p>



(a) Disciplining and retraining responsible

employees.<p>



(b) Identifying root causes of misconduct,

including weaknesses in detection practices.<p>



(c) Using external reviewers as evaluators of

incidents of misconduct and related compliance

program weaknesses.<p>



We urge you to submit comments and examples about the above

Principle.  To assist you in this, please review the postings

from the first day of the seminar, October 23, on the <a href=../../../../download/seminars/fsg1.html>Federal

Sentencing Guidelines</a>, the <a href=../../../../download/seminars/principle1.html>Full Set of Principles</a> and the <a href=../../../../download/seminars/model1.html>Model

Example</a>. Please note that the Principles and Considerations are

copyrighted by the NCPL and may not be reproduced without

permission of the NCPL.<p>



<hr><p>



Appended by: Marc Chafetz -- Law Office - Washington<br>

Date: Mon Nov  6 10:32:34 1995<br>

Subject: small co. & practicality<p>



This may have been touched upon elsewhere, but to what extent do

the rules change for smaller companies?  Not all companies are

Kraft with huge resources available.  Presumably there is some

rule of reason that allows for a more modest formal program --

maybe where some one says don't lie, cheat or steal -- when the

company is so small that that is the best that they can do.

Stated otherwise, though the substantive aspects of compliance

would not be different, from a procedural prospective, a

necessarily more lax program would exist.<p>



Moreover, I must be terribly naive, but I do not recall being told

in <I>any</i> job that I have ever had not to lie, cheat or steal (I

started working at a young age and have worked in a diverse number

of jobs).  I simply <I>assumed</i> one should not do those things.  Is

this view so unusual?  In Ben Bradlee's recent book, he talks

about the Janet Cooke affair (a reporter simply fabricated a

story, winning a Pulitzer and later disgrace).  My sense is that

it did not occur to him that one of his reporters would commit

that kind of fraud; he trusted them.  Isn't that attitude not too

uncommon?<p>



<hr><p>



Appended by: Joe Murphy -- Bell Atlantic - Philadelphia<br>

Date: Mon Nov  6 17:12:42 1995<br>

Subject: small co. & practicality<p>



Marc,<p>



On your first question, the Sentencing Guidelines do in fact take

size into account;  if the company is small, the program can be

less formal.<p>



Overall I think the Guidelines' definition of an effective

compliance program does offer a good start, even for small

companies. There are some weaknesses, but the standards show a

sensitivity to the need to have management involved in the

process.   I think, however, that sometimes people get off the

track in addressing the compliance question in general.  I am

particularly struck by the idea that the answer is  just telling

people not to do bad things, and then punishing those who disobey.<p>



I would describe this as the "preach and punish" theory.    The

real question to me is a very simple one to ask:  "What Works?"

Which steps really do affect how organizations behave, and which

steps are a waste of time.  Answering that question, however, is

anything but easy.<p>



I do not buy the "preach and punish" approach;  it is too

legalistic and it hasn't worked in organizations.  I believe that

organizations and the people in them act differently from

individuals. If you want to change the way an organization works,

you have to work with the organization's own management processes.

 You need to know the company's culture, you need its senior

management's active support, and you have to employ such

management processes as evaluations and appraisals, discipline,

auditing, management reporting, etc.  You use whatever the

management of that company would use to achieve results.<p>



Also, I do not see great success with the preach and punish model

even  in dealing with individuals outside of organizations.   Most

people are not motivated solely by fear;   incentives and other

positives, and the influence of one's peers, play a very important

role that the legal system and lawyers seem to overlook.<p>



As for the newspaper example, the question for me is whether they

checked the background of the person they hired.  I do not see a

need for rigid restrictions and structures imposed on companies.

But I am not naive about people in organizations.  Corporations,

especially big ones, have an enormous capacity to cause harm.  If

management is aware of a risk area, it is reasonable to expect

management to take the types of preventive steps that are designed

to deal with that risk.  When I buy medicine from a pharmaceutical

company, I do not care what their management style is or whether

the company is large or small.  But I want to be sure they are

checking what comes off the production line, and that their

employees care about the quality of their products.  After all,

while on the surface when we discuss compliance we are just

talking about one more area of the law, in a very real sense we

are addressing a matter that affects the health, safety and well

being of each of us.  That leads me to my original focus:  We need

to ask what works to prevent misconduct in companies.  Some parts

of this pursuit may be easy, but others will require all of our

best efforts to find answers.<p>



<hr><p>



<CENTER><I><A HREF="http://www.courttv.com/download/seminars/form1.html">



Submit your question or comment to the discussion</i>.</a></center>

