<html><head><title>Seminars - Rules and Reason [behind the Federal Guidelines]</title>
</head> <BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#FF0005">
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/smb.gif" BORDER=0>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<h2>Rules and Reason [behind the Federal Guidelines]</h2>
<!--- full_start: 743--->
<H2>Corporate Compliance: Standards For The 21st Century</h2><p>



<H3>Seminar Discussion Thread</h3><p>



From: Edward Dauer -- Denver Law School - Denver<br>

Date:  Sun Nov  5 12:15<br>

Subject:  Rules and Reason<p>



I am, as always, fascinated by the conversations in this

[seminar] -- in this case, on the relative uses of rules (mechanical

compliance things) and reason (education about what's right and

what's wrong).  In my view, as something of an outsider to the

corporate world, the blend of Ted Banks' and Susan Macauley's

ideas makes great good sense.  Neither rules nor reason are

sufficient, to some degree both are necessary, yet each used alone

(or used to excess) can create more problems than it solves.<p>



I wonder, however, whether the use of rules (systems,

contrivances, mechanical things) doesn't have a place beyond the

evidence of law-abidingness that Susan mentions, and as part of

the culture that Ted says is important.  Doesn't the use of a

system (but not a rigid one) act as the reminder and the

reinforcement of the organization's more general commitment?  To

see a supervisor fill out a compliance report italicizes

compliance in the workers' mind.  To see the executives visibly

following some systems and rules reinforces the idea that

lawfulness is high among the corporate values.  So, for example,

having a "hotline" may never disclose an interruptible

crime-in-process.  But having a hotline does say something to the

work force that mere words don't.<p>



If this is true, then what it says is that the "system" ought to

speak at least as well as it works; and that, because what it

expresses is at least as important as what it does, it need never

be so contrived or rigid as to interfere with anything else.<p>



Could that be what the Sentencing Commission was after?<p>



E. A. Dauer<p>



