<html><head><title>Seminars - Principle No. 16 - Communications Objectives</title>
</head> <BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#FF0005">
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/smb.gif" BORDER=0>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<h2>Principle No. 16 - Communications Objectives</h2>
<!--- full_start: 745--->
<H2>Corporate Compliance: Standards For The 21st Century</h2><p>



<H3>Seminar Discussion Thread</h3><p>



From: Christina Cooley -- Counsel Connect - Atlanta<br>

Date:  Tue Nov  7 15:03<br>

Subject:  PR. 16-Communications<p>





<H4>NATIONAL CENTER FOR PREVENTIVE LAW WORKING GROUP DRAFT</h4>



<H3>Training Programs -- Making the System Effective</h3>



<I>Note:  Principle #16 and its Considerations are intended to

address the following aspect of the <a href=../../../../download/seminars/fsg1.html>

Federal Sentencing Guidelines: Sec. 8A1.2(k)</a>(4): "The organization must have taken

steps to communicate effectively its standards  and procedures

to all employees and other agents . . ."</i><p>



<H4>Principle #16: The organization's compliance program has a

communications component, the objectives of which are to make

employees and other agents aware of applicable standards of

conduct and to promote compliance.</h4>



Factors to Consider:<p>



(a)Identifying the communications component of the

organization's compliance program.<p>



(b) Identifying the appropriate organizational personnel to

include in the design and implementation of the communications

program.<p>



(c) Specifying the instructional objectives that should be

included in the communications component of the organization's

compliance program.<p>



(d) Structuring the communications program so that it provides

feedback and evaluative information.<p>



(e) Documenting the steps taken in, and the results of, the

organization's communications program.<p>



We urge you to submit comments and examples about the above

Principle.  To assist you in this, please review the postings

from the first day of the seminar, October 23, on the <a href=../../../../download/seminars/fsg1.html>Federal

Sentencing Guidelines</a>, the <a href=../../../../download/seminars/principle1.html>Full Set of Principles</a> and the <a href=../../../../download/seminars/model1.html>Model

Example</a>. Please note that the Principles and Considerations are

copyrighted by the NCPL and may not be reproduced without

permission of the NCPL.<p>



