<html><head><title>Seminars - Measuring  the Cost of Compliance Programs</title>
</head> <BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#FF0005">
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/smb.gif" BORDER=0>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<h2>Measuring  the Cost of Compliance Programs</h2>
<!--- full_start: 748--->
<H2>Corporate Compliance: Standards For The 21st Century</h2><p>



<H3>Seminar Discussion Thread</h3><p>



From: Aileen R. Leventon -- Atty-Leventon, A. - New York<br>

Date:  Mon Nov  6 21:49<br>

Subject:  Measuring Costs<p>



I am interested in locating studies on the dollar costs of

compliance programs.  For example, how many people are assigned to

compliance functions?  Who defines themselves in the organization as

being a part of the compliance function?  (The compliance

department?  Members of the legal department? Human resources

staff who do training?)  What are the outside counsel and

consultants' expenses for designing, implementing and monitoring

programs? Our discussion thus far has centered on litigation

expense for compliance failures, and compliance with regulation.

What about the costs of an infrastructure for an effective

compliance program?  If anyone is aware of efforts in this area,

including a description of the proactive and laudable work of the

US Sentencing Commission, it would be helpful!  Thanks.<p>



<hr><p>



Appended by: Louis Brown -- Sanders Barnet - Los Angeles<br>

Date: Tue Nov  7 13:33:25 1995<br>

Subject: Budget<p>



This suggestion does not directly answer your fine inquiry. It

may, however, stimulate further discussion.<p>



I early suggested that corporations set up a line <I>budget</i> item for

compliance review. If any corporations have done this, the

experience will help answer the inquiry.

If you have set up a line <I>budget</i> for compliance review (or for

legal audit), what is your experience?<p>



Louis M. Brown<p>



<hr><p>



Appended by: Aileen R. Leventon -- Atty-Leventon, A. - New York<br>

Date: Tue Nov  7 22:20:44 1995<br>

Subject: Budget Components<p>



What are the components of a line budget for compliance review?

Does it cover preventive law assessments?  Does it cover drafting

the policy statements?  Review of applicable law?  Communications

and training?  Do all of those activities necessarily fall within

the ambit of the legal department or compliance department?  Does

it pick up [Human Resources] and Communications departments too? 

I'd love to hear about others' experience!!<p>



<hr><p>



Appended by: Louis Brown -- Sanders Barnet - Los Angeles<br>

Date: Wed Nov  8 14:14:11 1995<br>

Subject: Budget a Law reason<p>



One of my thoughts in suggesting a budget line item concerns

proof, if needed, of the extent of the compliance review process

in an enterprise...The FSGs remind us that a Compliance Review in

place reduces, or might reduce, a criminal sentence.  The problem

then becomes proof of the Compliance Review process. It seems to

me that evidence (if it can be introduced) of the amount expended

for Compliance Review, and its components should help the

defendant...<p>



It is my understanding that when a corporation has a line item in

its budget, the normal practice is to keep a record of the

expenditures within that budget.<p>



All this does not, of course, answer the question of what goes

into the components...For the present, until a standard practice

is established, I assume that each corporation may set its own

components.  Yes, I would include preventive law activities within

that sort of budget. ....(Someday, I hope in the not too distant

future, NCPL will endeavor to arrange a training program for Legal

Audit, - including Compliance Review, and the rest of  Preventive

Law . <STRONG>Big Subject</strong>.)<p>Louis M. Brown<p><hr><p>







Appended by: Herb Zinn -- AZ Public Service - Phoenix<br>


Date: Sat Nov 11 07:38:50 1995<br>


Subject: Measuring Costs<p>





I wish I could offer you detailed numbers but during the


establishment of our program, no one was keeping time.  Let me


say, however, that none of our program was developed through the


use of outside resources -- lawyers or consultants.  We went about


it by setting up a task force of in-house experts under a team of


line managers representative of key areas around our company.


Then, for two months, we conducted reviews with these people along


subcommittee lines focused on each of the seven criteria in the


FSG's.  Our task was to see what the company was already doing or


had in place and to determine what we needed to do to beef it up


-- if anything -- to meet the expectations of the FSG's.<p>





Then recommendations were made to the Manager Committee, which


quality controlled the process.  Once they were happy, it went up


to the officers and then the Board for adoption.<p>





This way, we "reengineered" what we had and redirected it with


the FSG's in mind -- but the FSG's were not our only target.  We


were concerned in compliance at all levels -- criminal, civil,


contractual, ethics, etc.<p>





The groups involved in the compliance team included


representatives from Audit Services, Human resources, Corporate


Security, Law, Risk Management, Environmental Services,  Media


Relations and our nuclear power plant.  On average, these groups


met twice over this period for two to three hours each -- then the


results of the interviews were distributed in draft form for


further review by them.  So, I'd estimate each individual spent


around 10 to 20 hours over the two months on this -- except the


lawyers who were driving the process at the time.<p>





The reason I am going through this detail is to demonstrate to


you the fact that it needn't cost a fortune if you define the


process as being part of the accountabilities of certain groups in


the company and redirect them to include this effort in their


operations.  By reengineering, we were able to rationalize this.<p>





From there, we developed a written code of conduct pamphlet.  Ten


thousand were produced for about $2,000 in our in-house print


facility -- not including the time for graphic design and layout,


which was also done in-house (maybe 5 to 10 hours, tops).  On top


of that, we developed a four-minute video to introduce the program


to all employees (then, about 8,000) throughout the company.  Cost


was $1,400 -- again, using in-house AV resources.  When it was


rolled out, the video and the codes were given to each manager,


who in turn called a staff meeting to present the video, discuss


the program and its objectives (from a predetermined script that


the compliance team wrote, so that the message was consistent


throughout the company), and to align their teams on the issue


through a strategic planning effort that resulted in individual


reports to the compliance team.  There were several management


meetings and training sessions at the outset, but these were


undertaken within the normal work routine, so no added expense was


incurred.<p>





This all happened in three months beginning January, 1994.  By


summer, the departments had each been indoctrinated and our


concerns line and Law Department were regularly receiving calls


and requests for support -- indicating that the effort was being


addressed by the rank and file.  This was buttressed by the


quality of questions we were receiving.<p>





By the way, we had two existing concerns lines and staffs, so


there was no added start up cost there, either, to the program set


up.  Our concerns lines are nothing very fancy.  A staff, phone


lines and message machine.  I don't know what they are costing to


maintain, but again, they are part of existing resources -- not


new additions -- and so it's easy to rationalize them.<p>





I realize this doesn't address you question head on, but we did


not keep logs of cost.  I hope, that by demonstrating how we went


about it, you can see that it doesn't have to cost hundreds of


thousands of dollars to install and operate.    Of course, the


path taken depends on the culture of the organization and its


situation.  If it did not have a compliant culture to begin with,


chances are some of these incremental steps may have to be taken


from ground level.  Or larger, more complex organizations may


necessarily cost more to redirect and manage.<p>





If I can be of further help, please let me know.<p>





Herb Zinn -- Arizona Public Service -- Phoenix.<p>





<hr><p>





Appended by: Joe Murphy -- Bell Atlantic - Philadelphia<br>


Date: Mon Nov 13 16:17:32 1995<br>


Subject: Budget Components<p>





Aileen,<p>





When the Sentencing Commission decided to have studies conducted


on what is being done in compliance, they had a group of advisors


offering suggestions on how to proceed.  I had the opportunity to


participate in that group.  One of the questions we considered was


the one you asked:  "What resources were spent in the compliance


program?"<p>





The advisory group convinced the Commission staff not to ask this


question, because the answers from different companies would not


be comparable.  For example, I could describe my company's program


in very low-cost terms, much in the way that Herb Zinn did.  But I


could just as fairly describe it as a highly resource intensive


program.  I believe that most if not all of the legal department


plays a role in compliance. Companies with internal auditing and


security functions could also include those. Any industrial


hygienists?  Environmental engineers?  Quality control people in


the food and pharmaceuticals industries? Risk management?  They


could all be added in.  We also get time from HR people, corporate


communications, and a group that issues corporate policies. Its a


bit like the story of the blind men and the elephant.  Of course,


the best program is one where managers throughout the business


take ownership and include compliance and ethics in their normal


management oversight.<p>





As for outside resources, most of our work was done in-house, but


incorporated much of what I have learned from networking with


others in compliance for years.  I believe there are a number of


companies that use outside firms to handle hotline calls and to


help in video productions.<p>





I know this response is not specific regarding numbers;  it is


not a question I could answer with one bottom-line figure.  I'll


be interested to see what others have to offer.<p>





Joe Murphy<p>





<hr><p>

