<html><head><title>Seminars - Principle No. 19 - All Management Responsible for Communications</title>
</head> <BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#FF0005">
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/smb.gif" BORDER=0>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<h2>Principle No. 19 - All Management Responsible for Communications</h2>
<!--- full_start: 827--->
<H2>Corporate Compliance: Standards For The 21st Century</h2><p>





<H3>Seminar Discussion Thread</h3><p>





From: Christina Cooley -- Counsel Connect - Atlanta<br>


Date:  Mon Nov 20 14:03<br>


Subject:  PR. 19-All Mgmt Levels<p>





<H4>NATIONAL CENTER FOR PREVENTIVE LAW WORKING GROUP DRAFT</h4>





<H3>Training Programs -- Making the System Effective, Continued. . .</h3>





<I>Note:  Principle #19 and its Considerations are intended to


address the following aspect of the <a href=../../../../download/seminars/fsg1.html>


Federal Sentencing Guidelines:  Sec. 8A1.2(k)</a>(4): "The organization must have taken


steps to communicate effectively its standards and procedures


to all employees and other agents . . ." AND Sec. 8A1.2(k)(2):


"Specific individual(s) within high-level personnel of the


organization must have been assigned overall responsibility to


oversee compliance with such standards and procedures.</i><p>





<H4>Principle #19:  All levels of management are responsible for


the operation of the organization's communications program


concerning compliance.</h4><p>





Factors to Consider:<p>





(a) Determining the role of senior management in an


organization's compliance communications program.<p>





(b) Determining the role of a compliance officer and further


compliance staff members in an organization's compliance


communications program.<p>





(c) Determining the roles of supervisors and middle level


managers in an organization's compliance communications program.<p>





(d) Integrating a compliance communications program with other


communications programs and organizational operations.<p>





We urge you to submit comments and examples about the above


Principle.  To assist you in this, please review the postings


from the first day of the seminar, October 23, on the <a href=../../../../download/seminars/fsg1.html>Federal


Sentencing Guidelines</a>, the <a href=../../../../download/seminars/principle1.html>Full Set of Principles</a> and the <a href=../../../../download/seminars/model1.html>Model


Example</a>. Please note that the Principles and Considerations are


copyrighted by the NCPL and may not be reproduced without


permission of the NCPL.<p>





