<html><head><title>Seminars - Designing and Implementing an Effective Compliance Program</title>
</head> <BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#FF0005">
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/smb.gif" BORDER=0>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<h2>Designing and Implementing an Effective Compliance Program</h2>
<!--- full_start: 643--->
<H2>Corporate Compliance: Standards For The 21st Century</h2>

<H3>Seminar Library File</h3>

<H1>Preventive Law Reporter, Winter 1993</H1>

<h5>Copyright&#169;1993 Preventive Law Reporter</h5>

<H4>By HERBERT I. ZINN, Esq.</h4><EM>EDITOR'S NOTE: This article is excerpted from the Arizona 

Compliance Manual, published by Maricopa County Bar Association, 

Phoenix, Arizona. The excerpted portion focuses solely on the 

steps necessary in developing and preparing a compliance program 

and has been modified to some extent due to space limitations.<P>HERBERT I. ZINN has been a Senior Attorney with Arizona

Public Service for fourteen years.</em><p><H3>INTRODUCTION</h3>A thorough understanding of the Guidelines is a necessary

tool in the implementation of a compliance program, but there

is an even more important ingredient -- and that is having a

thorough understanding of the organization for which you are

designing the program. Without a sensitivity for the organization's

culture, the program, no matter how well it meets the criteria set

out in the Guidelines, will miss the mark in terms of effectiveness. 

The perspectives presented in this article are meant to

focus the implementation effort in such a way to allow program

designers to tailor the perspecaves to meet the strengths and

weaknesses of the organization. Needless to say, the considerations 

expressed in the discussion which follows need to be

thoroughly evaluated by the designers as they set about to build

the program for the organization.<p>



<H3>GETTING STARTED</h3>



<Strong><EM>Strategic Planning: Blueprint the Plan</strong></EM><p>



Assuming you have gained management's support for the

implementation of a compliance program, the next step is

strategic planning. A blueprint for implementation must be

drawn up, premised on management's vision, came frames, and

contingencies for unforeseen events that may impede the

smooth flow of the project.<p>



<Strong><EM>The Business Case Approach</strong></EM><p>



It is both fundamental and useful to develop a program

document at this point. For the purposes of this discussion, we

call it a Business Case. A Business Case is simply a detailed plan

of action that outlines the process. The Business Case will serve

as a valuable checklist for the implementation process, and is

also a good way to communicate roles and responsibilities

among the individuals assigned to develop the plan. But more

importantly, it will help flesh out latent issues that, if not

recognized up-front, may slow or even defeat the process.<p>



Who should be involved in the development of the Business

Case? Clearly, legal counsel plays an important role. Additionally, 

the development team should include an individual with

extensive knowledge of the organization, and, where applicable, 

a member of the audit staff to ferret out issues and develop

recommendations for their handling. Other professionals and

disciplines to consider are representatives from Human Resources, 

Security, and Risk Management.<p>



<Strong><EM>Scope and Objectives</strong></EM><p>



The Business Case should start with a concise statement of

management's vision -- its scope and objectives, i.e., what is the

desired outcome? The vision statement should be consistent

with the direction taken by the organization's governing body,

and be clear and understandable to each employee and agent

of the organization. The vision statement should be written in

terms that can be verbally tracked in the program document

itself. How should the vision be stated? It can be as simple as

this:<p>



<H5>It is the policy of ABC Company to comply with all

laws which apply to its business and activities, and to

conduct its affairs in a way that is both ethical and

responsible. Employees and agents of the Company

are expected to at all times discharge their dues in

full compliance with this policy.</h5>



The drafters of the statement may wish to elaborate upon the

meaning management imparts to these words, to help guide

those responsible for bringing the program into existence. The

organization should also consider how the program applies to

any of the organization's subsidiaries. Will the subsidiaries be

required to abide by the organization's program or develop their

own?<p>



Those responsible for developing the organization's vision

statement, should keep this consideration in mind: is the

organization developing the program so it will merely gain a

three point reduction in its culpability score under the Guidelines? 

Or does the organization want a program capable of

deterring criminal conduct before it occurs -- a program capable

of convincing a prosecutor that there is no purpose in initiating

criminal proceedings against the organization? At this point in

the discussion, there should be little doubt which path the

drafter wants the organization to follow.<p>



<Strong><EM>Resources</strong></EM><p>



Next, the Business Case should address the resources needed to

develop the program and bring it into operation. It is appropriate

here to describe the program in terms of its component parts

with reference to the Guidelines' requirements. The organization

may decide to surpass the Guidelines' requirements in all or

certain aspects of the program, depending upon the character and

needs of the organization and the risks it confronts.<p>



Among the resources the organization should address are the

skills and talent needed to make the program work (e.g., legal,

security, auditing, training); the existence of these skills and

talents in-house; the degree to which they will have to be

obtained through outside support (e.g., legal counsel, consultants, 

and vendors); the new elements needed to support the

program once it is up and running (e.g., an employee concerns

needed to develop the program and to maintain its effectiveness.<p>



<Strong><EM>Task Plans</strong></EM><p>



The next section of the Business Case -- Task Plans -- provides

a good opportunity for the designer to lay out a step-by-step

progression for construction of the compliance program. Here,

the building blocks that go into the program are laid out and

allocated to those in the organization who will have a hand in

the programs development and operation.<p>



Some questions that need to be addressed in developing the

task plan include: who will identify the laws with which the

organization is concerned in terms of compliance? Who will

determine and set the compliance standards employees and

agents will follow in discharging their responsibilities to the

organization? Who in the organization will be designated the

high-level person with responsibility for overseeing the compliance 

program -- and who will make the selection? What new

training programs need to be implemented? How will a system

be developed to assure that employees can communicate their

concerns without fear of retaliation for having done so? What

procedures are in place or will be needed to deal with incidents

of noncompliance when they are discovered? What mechanisms

will be needed to perform regular quality control on the program

to determine that it is working, to implement changes as

necessary, and to keep abreast of prevailing requirements that

may be set by the Guidelines as they evolve? The combinations

of issues and tasks are seemingly endless and necessarily vary

with the nature of the organization.<p>



<Strong><EM>Deliverables</strong></EM><p>



Next, the organization should address the precise deliverables

it expects from this effort. This is another way to focus the

attention of the task teams on what they are expected to

produce. Chief among them will be the compliance program document

itself--a document that meets the expectations of the Guidelines

and is effective in terms of its capability to deter, discover,

and deal with problems that may arise. Subsidiary to this are

the various components that contribute to the program's makeup:<p>

&iuml; a written schedule of compliance standards corresponding 

to the legal obligations imposed upon the organization, presented 

as a whole, or by operating area of the organization, depending 

upon its culture and needs;<p>&iuml; written procedures that prescribe the organization's

rules for legal compliance, what is to be done when

there is uncertainty about one's obligations, and

organizational responsibilities for supporting legal

compliance, e.g., line management's role in carrying

out policy, when to consult the lawyers, etc.;<p>&iuml; a communications and training program to assure

employees and agents are not only familiar with what

is expected of them but also know how to achieve

the desired ends;<p>&iuml; a phone-in hot-line and a staff to man it along with

detailed standards and procedures about the hot-line

capable of communicating to the workforce how it is

to be properly used;<p>&iuml; an audit program designed to monitor the

organization's compliance with applicable laws and

to report incidents of noncompliance;<p>&iuml; a mechanism or program of follow-up that assures

that problems are promptly and decisively addressed

and corrected; a set of procedures for the organization 

to follow in the event a problem is encountered,

e.g., reporting the incident to the regulatory authorities;<p>&iuml; a quality control program that regularly identifies

shortcomings in the program and plans for their

correction; and<p>&iuml; a clear and concise policy on discipline for those who

fail to comply with the organization's program -- as a

means of deterring noncompliance in the first instance, 

and dealing with that which may eventually

occur despite the program.<p>As in the case of Task Plans, the combinations are endless

depending upon the nature of the organization.<p><Strong><EM>Prerequisites</strong></EM><p>The Prerequisites section of the Business Case focuses

management's attention on what is required to make the process

work. The first prerequisite should be a clear, consistent, and

visible statement by management indicating its commitment to

and support for the process of developing and operating the

compliance program. In the view of the author, without clear

and ever present management commitment, the vitality of the

program and the employees' willingness to incorporate its

expectations into their work habits will have little chance

for lasting success.<p>The Prerequisites section should also identify where consents

to specific actions may be needed. For instance, an aspect of the

proposed plan may conflict with the terms of a license or permit

or other commitment to a regulatory authority, requiring that the

organization discuss this with the regulatory authority or alter its

plan to avoid the conflict.<p><Strong><EM>Major Drivers</strong></EM><p>Under Major Drivers, the organization should identify the

reasons why the program is being undertaken:<p>&iuml; the organization's commitment to its investors, its

customers, its employees, and the communities in

which it resides or serves;<p>&iuml; improved image of the organization; management of

the risks attendant to noncompliance with applicable

laws; and<p>&iuml; the laws themselves and, of course, the Sentencing

Guidelines.<p>This will help in graphically reminding the managing body of

the organization why this effort is being undertaken.<p><Strong><EM>Cost</strong></EM><p>Last, but certainly not least, is the section on cost. Best

estimates should be used here with contributions from all staff

involved in developing the program. The organization should

separately list in-house and outside resources.<p><H3>ORGANIZING A TEAM</h3>Once the plan for developing and implementing a compliance 

plan is approved by the organization's managing body, it

is time to staff the project. The planning document should have

identified the staffing needs in terms of resources, and delegated

to the staff discrete tasks to perform in the implementation

process. This discussion explores in more detail the specific role

played by each of the disciplines that make up the implementation team.<p>

<Strong><EM>Management</strong></EM><p>Management's role doesn't end with the approval of the plan

of implementation. If the effort has any hope of long term

success, management must be a visible, active participant

throughout the process. No one in the organization will take

seriously the commitment to compliance if that commitment is

not graphically demonstrated through management's active

participation in the effort.<p>Line management and employees may view the project as one

that conflicts with their already overburdened schedules. Unless

upper management is present to reinforce the importance of the

project, there will be a natural tendency to put it on the back

bummer. Not only is this conclusion reached through common

sense, the Sentencing Guidelines themselves envision high-level

management as a key player in the process of developing and

maintaining the plan. The second criterion for a compliance plan

under the Guidelines dictates that a high-level person or persons

in the organization be given responsibility for overseeing the

plan. United States Sentencing Guidelines, Sec. 8A1.2 cmt. n.3(k)(2).<p>

<Strong><EM>Lawyers</strong></EM><p>Their role in the process is obvious, but worth outlining

nonetheless. Legal support is required from the very outset of

the process:<p>&iuml; to dissect the Sentencing Guidelines so their requirements 

and expectations are understood;<p>&iuml; to participate in the conduct of legal audits needed

to determine where, and to what extent, the organization 

needs to address the crimes that are subject to

the Guidelines -- as well as other requirements of

federal, state, and local law that should be addressed

while the organization is engaged in this effort;<p>&iuml; to draft the compliance standards together with

representatives of the organization's operating areas.

The objective here is that the standards meet both the

requirements of the Guidelines as well as the requirement 

that they be concise, easily understood, and

uncomplicated enough to be meaningful to those

individuals who have to rely upon them for guidance;<p>&iuml; to develop support programs required by the Guidelines, 

such as the employees' concerns line, communications and 

training programs, monitoring audits,

and reporting procedures.<p>To accomplish the task and make it real and meaningful, the

lawyers assigned to the process should have experience in

regulatory compliance, employment matters, criminal law as it

applies to white collar crime and organizational conduct, and,

above all, a thorough understanding of the organization. The

lawyers will not function by themselves; rather, they will be

assigned to support the efforts of the other team members.<p>

<Strong><EM>Auditors</strong></EM><p>Traditionally, audit staff is important because of its understanding 

of ethical behavior and systems of internal controls.

Its assigned task in the organization is to participate in the

development of the code of conduct and systems of internal

controls designed to detect departures from prescribed standards 

of care. Hence, their importance in the compliance plan

process is critical.<p>The audit staff can be of enormous value in bringing together

principles of business ethics and industry custom, which form

a good staring point for the organization's effort. Moreover, the

audit function plays a key role in the operation of the plan as it

goes forward. The audit staff can man the employee concerns

line, as well as develop audit programs to monitor the

organization's compliance.<p><Strong><EM>Human Resources</strong></em><p>As the process of plan implementation moves along, Human

Resources personnel ("HR") will need to become involved. The

roots of the program will be anchored in the organization's

work force. Someone with an understanding of, and responsibility

for, the behavioral health of the workforce should therefore

assist in designing the program.<p>HR's role is to ferret out conflicts in the process that could

frustrate the plan or other existing programs of the organization.

The organization can anticipate that the plan may call upon

employees to do something contrary to a prevailing labor

agreement, call for an amendment to other company policies, or

somehow conflict with employee rights or prevailing employment laws. 

The fundamental task of assuring consistency within

the organization will go to the HR staff.<p>HR will also be assigned the task of developing clear, concise

communication material about the program for circulation throughout 

the workforce. Last, HR's role includes developing training

programs -- in concert with other operating groups in the organization 

that will inform the workforce of the organization's

expectations and how to satisfy those expectations.<p><Strong><EM>Security</strong></EM><p>During the process of implementation, the issue of background 

checks will need to be addressed. See United States

Sentencing Guidelines, Sec. 8A1.2 cmt. n.3(k)(3). Security

personnel are ideal for this purpose, as they possess an

understanding of the methods used to investigate personnel

histories. Security personnel will also be invaluable in

developing investigative procedures -- along with the lawyers

and the audit staff -- necessary to deal with an event of

noncompliance.<p><Strong><EM>Risk Management</strong></EM><p>Traditionally, this group is thought of as the organization that

buys the insurance needed to deal with anticipated risks; but

they also possess a keen understanding of the organization's

workings, and are trained to spot processes that may enhance

the probability of a risk's occurrence. Characterized in this way,

the Risk Management group is a very useful supporting resource

for the process of plan design and implementation.<p>

<Strong><EM>The Workforce</strong></EM><p>The majority of the organization's employees will not be

directly involved in the design and implementation of the

program. They are, however, as important as those groups

discussed above. The success of the plan relies on the

willingness of employees to accord it the respect it deserves.

Without commitment from the workforce, the plan will never

succeed. A recent example illustrates this point.<p>In the winter of 1992, a devastating explosion shook the South

Mountain Mine in Wise County, Virginia. Seven miners were

killed. Subsequent investigations disclosed that the miners may

have purposely blocked the orifices on methane gas detection

devices. Federal and state mining law required the presence

and use of this methane detection equipment -- so did company

procedures. Nevertheless, the miners neutralized the equipment.

The reason why may never be known, but it provides good fuel

for speculation.<p>One reason may be that the miners never bought into the

requirements, even though the requirements were designed to

protect them. This exemplifies why it is important to gain

employee buy-in on requirements such as legal compliance.

Unless the requirements are made part of the organization's

culture, there will always be members of the workforce willing

to short circuit the process, thus, exposing the employees and the

organization to the consequences.<p>All employees, therefore, need to be involved from the very

beginning of the process. The employees need to know that

management is committed to the program -- that the program

is designed for their protection, as well as that of the organization. 

They also need to know and understand their role in

making it work. This requires that they understand the personal

consequences if the process doesn't work through some act or

omission on their part.<p><H3>SETTING UP THE PROGRAM</h3><Strong><EM>A Necessary First Step</strong></EM><p>The entry point for program implementation is the announcement 

of the process to the employees of the organization. The

organization should also make announcements to its agents, as,

under the Guidelines, the organization is also vicariously liable

for their acts.<p>Announcements at the beginning are important and preferable for

several reasons. First, it is management's first opportunity to

communicate its commitment to the process. Management has the

opportunity here to describe the process, why it is being

undertaken, the expected outcomes, benefits, costs, and

sacrifices. Moreover, management will have the opportunity to

explain up front the system of accountability, expectations, and

responsibilities imposed on all employees by the process.<p>Second, management will have the opportunity to deal with

and mitigate at the outset the potentially destructive effects of

the organization's grapevine. Every organization has one and it

is important to acknowledge it and the influence it may have on

the success of program implementation. Some employees will

have already heard about the Guidelines through snippets of

information they read in industry journals. Relying on this

information, many may form the wrong impression based upon

the emphasis placed upon the Guidelines by the media, e.g., it

is a way to send people to jail and so scapegoats will abound.<p>Other employees may wonder why their organization is not

doing something about the Guidelines; misconstruing silence as

a sign of management's ineptness or utter disregard for an

important issue, thereby undermining confidence. An early

announcement, before the program is even designed, will

demonstrate the importance and commitment placed by managent 

on the process.<p>Third, by announcing management's intentions up front, an

opportunity is created to gain employee buy-in through 

empowerment. The announcement should not merely be a one way

communication to the employment body. The organization

should ask its employees to think about how they perform their

jobs and to communicate their concerns for the program to the

implementation team. Management's willingness to incorporate

employee input, and to consider employee concerns can make a

big difference in the chances for the program's success.

Employee involvement is a fundamental step in encouraging

employee buy-in.<p>After the initial announcement, line management should discuss

the process as part of the staff meetings they hold with their

departments. The dialogue should continue throughout the

process of implementing the program so the importance of the

effort remains paramount.<p>

The team assigned the task of implementing the program should

also make a speclal point of visiting those areas of the

organization whose participation in the process is fundamental. For instance, in order for the managers of specific operating

plants to understand and communicate their concerns regarding

the program, they must be involved early on in the process. In

turn, the task team should consider management's concerns and

change their plans, when appropriate, to accommodate them.<p>

Throughout the implementation process, management should

send out communications to the work force -- either directly or

through line management -- giving brief status reports on how

the process is progressing. Keeping the process in the mind of

the workforce is another way to demonstrate the emphasis

management places on compliance. The HR staff should be

assigned the task of developing these communications in

conjunction with the lawyers assigned to them.<p>

<Strong><EM>Setting Up Compliance Standards</strong></EM><p>

"The organization must have established compliance standards 

and procedures to be followed by its employees and other

agents that are reasonably capable of reducing the prospect of

criminal conduct." United States Sentencing Guidelines, Section

8A1.2 emt n.3(k)(1).<p>

The implementation task team's first assignment is to develop

clear, concise compliance standards that are relevant to the

operation of the organization. Section 8C2.1 of the Sentencing

Guidelines enumerates the crimes subject to the finer provisions

embodied in the Guidelines. Chapter Two of the Guidelines

contains many others. Many of the crimes, however, will not

pertain to the activities of the organization. For instance, if

the organization is not a publicly-held corporation, the crimes

relating to insider trading will have no impact. So why address

them?<p>The implementation task team, therefore, needs to review the

applicable crimes described in Section 8C2.1 and Chapter Two

against the organization and its activities to determine the high,

medium, and low risk items. The attorneys, along with the

assigned representaaves from the operating areas, can perform

this task when conducting a legal audit. Attorneys familiar with

the legal requirements attendant to the crimes identified in

section 8C2.1 and Chapter Two should meet with the operating

areas to determine if, how, and to what extent the organization's

activities could interrelate with the crime. In this way, a risk

assessment is performed and a meaningful compliance standard

for crimes relevant to the organization is developed.<p>

To this point, we have talked solely in terms of the crimes

enumerated under the Guidelines. It is a good idea not to limit

the scope of the effort to the Guidelines' crimes. Recall that

not all federal crimes are included in Section 8C2.1, nor are

State and local offenses, or items that comprise civil violations

of laws and regulatory requirements. It is of questionable sense

to develop a compliance plan that only deals with federal criminal 

issues where there may be other equally significant compliance

considerations not applicable under Section 8C2.1 of the Guidelines.

While the task team is addressing the Guidelines, it should

also address the issue of organizational compliance with all risk

areas. This may lengthen the process, but in terms of efficiency

and dollars, it makes sense. One way to address this is to

perform the project in phases, with the Guidelines and other

high risk areas given priority.<p>

There exists no set pattern describing how these compliance

standards should be set down. Some plans approach the issue

by discussions in broad terms. The organization's structure may

not be complex enough to warrant in-depth discussion. It may

suffice merely to state that it is organization's policy to comply

with all laws applicable to the organization's activities. Although

one cannot totally fault this approach, most organizations will

need to develop a more detailed plan to demonstrate the

organization's commitment and to make the compliance standards 

meaningful and understandable.<p>

Whether the details appear in the plan document or in

operating procedures referenced in the plan document is a

matter of choice. What is important is that a clear statement of

proper conduct is communicated to the workforce. This

statement will act as a starting point for supporting training

programs and, where need be, as the basis for disciplinary action

in the event of noncompliance.<p>

In an optimum sense, the more detailed the better. The

organization, however, must take care to ensure complex

compliance requirements are easily understood by those who

must use and adhere to them. An example illustrates this point.

Let's say Widget Co. manufactures Widgets at its factory. The

plant is situated next to a river, and plant processes require water

to cool plant machinery. Therefore, Widget Co.'s plant consumes 

water from the river, circulates it through plant machinery, 

and then redeposits it in the river. To do this, Widget Co.'s

environmental department has filed for and obtained a permit

to use and discharge the river water. The permit is issued under

the Federal Clean Water Act and prescribes detailed operating

limits imposed on Widget Co.'s plant.<p>

Under this set of circurnstances, is it enough for the compliance 

plan to provide that Widget Co. will comply with applicable law? 

Although a good starting point, how does the plan

ensure the objectives of both Widget Co. and the Clean Water

Act are met? Something more is needed. Understanding this is

important at the beginning. Management will be understandably

concerned if the task team proposes a compliance program

document that is several volumes thick -- and thereby slated to

sit on a shelf gathering dust.<p>

Therefore, in developing the compliance document, the task

team needs to address the nature of the deliverable they are

creaang. There are a variety of opaons: a short concise

document expressing the organization's intent; something more

detailed; or a mix of the two--meaning a concise declaration

of the organization's policy, cross-referencing into detailed

operaang instrucaons established and rnaintained in compliance 

with the plan at the operational level. For example, Widget

Co.'s compliance document might look something like this:<p>

&iuml; A brief policy statement issued by management,

declaring the organization's intenaon to comply with

the expectations of applicable law, and including a

discussion of the reason why this is important to the

organization, what areas of the law are related to the

organization's operations; a statement of the responsibilities 

placed upon employees and agents to satisfy

this declaration of the organization's policy; and a

statement indicaang the consequences to the employee 

or agent who fails to abide by the standards.

Finally, the document should direct the user to consult

with operating procedures.<p>

&iuml;Detailed and precise operating procedures keyed into

the compliance program that delineate the way in

which employees are expected to comply with applicable laws. 

These are developed at the operating level

between representaaves of each unit and attorneys

assigned to them who are familiar with the applicable

legal requirements. Not only would these protocols

address what the law says, but how the law applies to

the organization. For instance, in terms of permits

issued to the organization under authority of the law.<p>

Applied to Widget Co., this format presents a more meaningful 

approach. At the very top of the organization is Widget Co.'s

declaration of its intention to comply with the law; thereby

establishing each employee's responsibility. Beneath, is a

specific instruction designed and implemented for the Widget

Co. plant. The instructions highlight limitations imposed on the

plant by law and by the permit, and address plant parameters for

operating within those tolerances. Widget Co.'s employees

know what is expected of them and how to satisfy those

expectations.

Plant management, with HR support, can develop routine

training programs to keep employees aware of the way they are

to perform their jobs. There is established a defined basis for

monitoring the operations of the plant to assure compliant

acaviaes; and, should the need arise, there is a definite basis to

reprimand and discipline employees who fail to follow the

prescribed procedure.<p>

In preparing the compliance standards, management may

express concern about the natural propensity of people to go

ahead and do things not expressly proscribed by the terms of the

compliance standards. Everyone seems to have a little lawyer

in them. Employees seem to look for opportunities to test or

hone their skills by searching out loopholes in established

policies. There can never be a guaranty that a well described

standard will be ironclad. Someone will perceive a hole in it

somewhere. Therefore the answer to this concern lies in a

combination of remedies:<p>

&iuml; the standard should be carefully drafted in a way that

makes its objectives understandable hereby conveying 

the spirit of the objectives to the employee;<p>

&iuml; once it is written, it should be reviewed by others

with differing perspectives who may see consequences

not apparent to the draftsman;<p>

&iuml; the compliance plan should make it clear that the

rules set forth are not all-encompassing, and employees 

are expected to use good sense and judgement

in performing their jobs. If there is a question of what

is right, they should consult with their management;<p>

&iuml; the compliance standards should be underwritten by a comprehensive training program that exemplifies

management's objectives so there can be little room

to doubt what is expected by the standards.<p><H3>CONCLUSION</h3>You may not agree that a programmatic approach is needed

in order to begin the process of developing a compliance plan.

Assuredly, the Business Case approach is not the end-all option.

What it does symbolize, however, is the need to put pencil to

paper before running off to set up a compliance program.

<hr><p>



