<html><head><title>Seminars - Officer and Director Liability for Inadequate Legal Compliance Program</title>
</head> <BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#FF0005">
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/smb.gif" BORDER=0>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<h2>Officer and Director Liability for Inadequate Legal Compliance Program</h2>
<!--- full_start: 638--->
<H2>Corporate Compliance: Standards For The 21st Century</h2>

<H3>Seminar Library File</h3>

<H1>Preventive Law Reporter, Summer 1995</H1>

<h5>Copyright&#169;1995 Preventive Law Reporter</h5>

<H4>By RICHARD S. GRUNER</h4>

<H5>Professor of Law, <A HREF="http://www.whittier.edu/www/lawhome.html">Whittier College School of Law</a><br>

Los Angeles, California</H5>



<EM>RICHARD GRUNER is a former inside counsel to the IBM

Corporation and consultant to the U.S. Sentencing Commission

concerning corporate sentencing standards.</em><p>



Legal compliance programs involve systematic efforts by

corporations to detect and prevent offenses by corporate

employees and other agents. These programs identify,

facilitate and encourage lawful conduct by corporate employees, 

as well as monitor legal compliance results. Compliance

programs can further corporate interests in many ways, including 

reducing the frequency of illegal conduct1 influencing

prosecutorial discretion to withhold corporate charges for

employee offenses, minimizing corporate penalties for com-

pleted offenses, satisfying demands by board members and

others for information on corporate legal compliance and

implementing ethical norms in business operations. Compliance

programs can also avoid civil liabilities, strengthen civil claims

and enhance corporate reputations among customers, suppliers, 

employees and communities.<p>



Developing standards for corporate officer and director

liability recognize compliance programs as central concerns in

corporate governance systems. Under the American Law Institute's

1994 <EM>Principles of Corporate Governance (Principles)</em>, the failure

of corporate officers and directors to institute and periodically

assess compliance systems in corporate organizations can form

the basis for personal liability of the officers and directors.

This liability would be in the amount of corporate losses

(including fines and punitive damages) suffered in a situation

where an effective program would likely have prevented the losses.

An examination follows of these liability standards and the types

of compliance systems that will shield officers and directors from

this potentially large type of liability.<p>





<H3>CORPORATE LEGAL COMPLIANCE OBLIGATIONS</h3>



As a legally recognized actor with many of the powers of an

individual, the Principles recognize that a corporation "[i]s

obligated, to the same extent as a natural person, to act within

the boundaries set by law." <EM>Principles</em>, Sec. 2.01(b)(1). 

Top corporate managers must direct corporate activities within these

boundaries. Sec. 4.01(a) (Comment d).<p>



Beyond an obligation not to knowingly cause corporate

employees to violate the law, corporate directors and officers

also have affirmative duties to establish effective compliance

sterns to ensure that firm activities are generally conducted

lawfully and that illegal aberrations in corporate operations are

detected and stopped. Sec. 4.01(a)(1)-(a)(2)(Comment c). While

legal compliance in day-to-day corporate operations need not

be overseen directly by corporate directors and officers, monitoring 

duties concerning legal compliance must be responsibly

delegated. Directors and officers must react affirmatively once

they receive evidence that company compliance programs are

not operating properly. Sec. 4.01(b)(Comment b).<p>



<H3>MANAGERIAL DUE DILIGENCE CONCERNING LEGAL COMPLIANCE</h3>



<Strong><EM>Measuring Due Diligence</em></strong><p>



A useful definition of due diligence in operating corporate

compliance programs can be developed from these standards.

Corporate directors and officers should be deemed to have

undertaken due diligence in good faith in conjunction with the

corporate activities initiated and maintained under their leadership. 

This will be the case if directors and officers institute

effective compliance measures which are sufficient to support

a good faith belief that corporate activities are being conducted

lawfully.<p>



Framed this way, due diligence concerning compliance

programs is sufficient action to support a reasonable belief that

corporate activities initiated and overseen by directors and

managers are being conducted "within the boundaries set by

law." This is another way of saying that officers and directors

must see that their firms have positive management programs

which, upon reasonable inquiry, appear to be adequate to

insure compliance in corporate operations.<p>



At the heart of every effective program is the recognition that

compliance, like other aspects of corporate performance, is

ultimately a responsibility of the corporate line managers who

control day-to-day business operations. The essential objectives

of a compliance program are to insure that line managers give

attention to compliance matters in their oversight of corporate

operations and that compliance efforts are integrated with other

day-to-day management practices and procedures.<p>



<Strong><EM>Standards for Officer and Director Liability</strong></em><p>



Corporate officers and directors risk personal liability for

inadequate compliance systems based on these individuals' lack

of due care in instituting and monitoring such systems. Under

the Principles, suits claiming damages on this ground may be

governed by three types of standards:<p>



<Strong><EM>Business Judgment Rule</strong></em><p>



Where individual directors or officers evaluate the need for a

compliance system and make an affirmative decision about the

appropriate scope of such systems (even if this decision is to

adopt few if any compliance mechanisms), these actions will

generally be protected under the "business judgment rule."

Under this rule, if directors or officers have undertaken

reasonable fact gathering and evaluation prior to making a

decision about the scope and adequacy of a compliance system,

that decision will not be a basis for personal liability of the

directors or officers unless the decision is irrational.

Sec. 4.01(c).<p>



<Strong><EM>Simple Negligence</strong></em><p>



Where directors or officers have not affirmatively addressed

compliance systems, they will not gain the protection of the

business judgment rule. Instead, their inaction in implementing

these systems will be evaluated under a simple negligence

standard. If an ordinarily prudent person would have implemented 

preventive compliance systems in a like position and

under similar circumstances, directors and officers who fail to

adopt such systems will be found to have breached their duty

of care. Sec. 4.01(a).<p>



<Strong><EM>Affirmative Duty to Act</strong></em><p>



If particular officers or directors have specific information

indicating the inadequacy of present compliance mechanisms

(for example, knowledge that existing systems failed to detect

a recent offense or failed to respond correctly once such an

offense was detected), and the officers and directors do not react

by making an inquiry and seeking to improve the compliance

systems, these corporate leaders may face personal liability for

their negligent reaction to manifest compliance system failures.

Officers' and directors' duties of care include "the obligation to

make, or cause to be made, any inquiry when, but only when,

the circumstances would alert a reasonable director or officer to

the need therefor. The extent of such inquiry shall be such as the

director or officer reasonably believes to be necessary."

Sec. 4.01(a)(1).<p>



This rule establishes a special negligence test that avoids a

general duty to inquire about corporate misconduct, but which

compels action once an officer or director gains special knowledge 

suggesting misconduct on the part of corporate employees

that could be stopped or prevented by improved compliance

practices. In essence, this rule enforces a corporate counterpart

to the old adage "every dog gets one bite." Obviously, corporate

insiders with greater information about compliance problems

and system failures will tend to face liability under this standard

more often than outside directors with fewer corporate contacts

and lesser knowledge about operating conditions.<p>



Under each of these three standards, a breach of duty by

directors or officers must be linked to a corporate loss in order

to produce liability. That is, it must be shown that the lack of a

compliance system was a legal cause of corporate losses due to

criminal activity or other misconduct that might otherwise have

been detected and stopped through more substantial compliance

efforts. Under the Principles, an officer or director who breaches

his or her duty of care is liable for corporate losses legally

caused by the breach. A breach of duty is the legal cause of

losses if (i) compliance with the duty of care would have been

foreseeable to an ordinarily prudent person in a like position to

that of the defendant and in similar circumstances. It is not a

defense to liability in these cases that damage to the corporation

would not have resulted but for the acts or omissions of other

individuals such as the individual offenders whose misconduct

caused the corporate losses. Sections 7.18(a) & (b) (1994).<p>



<Strong><EM>Derivative Rights of Shareholders</strong></em><p>



Liability for the failure to institute and maintain an adequate

compliance program can be asserted in the name of a corporation 

through a derivative suit initiated by a corporate shareholder. 

Sec. 7.01-.17. If successful, this type of suit will

result in the personal liability of a director or officer in the

amount of the corporate losses that might have been prevented

through more substantial compliance efforts. Section7.18(a).<p>



Because these suits typically will not assert knowing or illegal

misconduct by corporate directors or officers (since the liability

of these parties is premised on their lack of due care in

establishing preventive programs rather than on direct participation 

in the illegal conduct leading to corporate losses), the

personal liability of officers and directors based on inadequate

provisions for compliance programs may be subject to indemnification 

or insurance reimbursements. Under the <EM>Principles</em>,

indemnification of corporate officials or directors found liable to

their corporation would only be possible under court order and

only where a court determines that such indemnification is fair

and reasonable. Sec. 7.20(b)(1)(D), (c)(2). A corporation may

purchase insurance for officers and directors with broader

coverage,but may not acquire insurance that would furnish such

parties with protection against liability for "conduct directly

involving a knowing and culpable violation of law or involving

a significant pecuniary benefit obtained by an insured person to

which the person is not legally entitled." Sec. 7.20(b)(2).<p>



<Strong><EM>Operational Features of Compliance Programs Reflecting Due Diligence</strong></em><p>



In order for officers or directors to justify a finding that

Corporate operations are generally being conducted lawfully, a

compliance program should have several features. In general,

an adequate program that supports confidence about corporate

compliance will be one that has the following characteristics:<p>



&iuml; Performance demands imposed by the system are well understood and 

generally met by corporate employees;<p>



&iuml; The performance required by the system is effective

in satisfying legal requirements; and<p>



&iuml; The system fosters an operational emphasis on

preventing legal offenses rather than on detecting

offenses after the fact.<p>



The scope of performance controls and monitoring that is

necessary to make a compliance program effective will depend

on the extent of corporate activities within a firm, the diversity

of those activities and the nature of the legal risks raised by

those activities. The more likely legal violations are in terms of

these factors, the more extensive a firm's compliance practices

should be in order for top managers and directors to be reasonably

assured that compliance is being maintained.<p>



Likewise, the more extensive the history of offenses is in a

particular firm or industry, the more extensive compliance

practices should be to maintain a reasonable certainty that

additional offenses of a similar sort are being prevented. Finally,

where a firm's activities threaten illegal conduct with particularly

harmful consequences (such as, for example, illegal waste

discharges by a chemical manufacturing firm that would threaten

a nearby town), the public dangers involved will require

expanded compliance efforts to achieve a reasonable certainty

of compliance. In such settings, the extreme public risks

associated with firm activities will raise the level of compliance

efforts necessary to achieve a reasonable certainty of legal

compliance.<p>



<H3>CONCLUSION</h3>



Legal compliance systems are increasingly considered by

sentencing courts and prosecutors evaluating substantiality of

corporate crime prevention efforts. Under the Principles, these

same systems have central importance in determining the

personal liability of corporate officers and directors for corporate 

losses stemming from illegal employee activities and other

misconduct that compliance programs can prevent or mitigate.<p>



Beyond their impact on corporate and personal liability for

completed employee offenses, corporate compliance programs

can be valuable means to prevent or stop such offenses. These

programs have important benefits whether viewed simply as

management tools for reducing offenses, as means to qualify for

favorable prosecutorial or sentencing treatment when offenses

occur or as means to shield corporate officers and directors from

potential personal liability. Managers who ignore compliance

programs are taking unnecessary chances with corporate assets

and futures.<p>



The development of compliance programs is a one-time

process that requires a comprehensive view of the legal standards 

governing firm operations and a sensitivity to the managerial 

techniques needed to direct, monitor and control compliance 

activities. By adopting careful measures to combat and

react to employee misconduct, firms can manage legal risks and

minimize corporate criminal and civil liability amidst increasingly 

complex legal requirements.

<hr><p>



<CENTER><I><A HREF="http://www.courttv.com/download/seminars/form1.html">

Submit your question or comment to the discussion</i>.</a></center>



