<html><head><title>Seminars - Greatness of the Risks Requires New Compliance Effort</title>
</head> <BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#FF0005">
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/smb.gif" BORDER=0>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<h2>Greatness of the Risks Requires New Compliance Effort</h2>
<!--- full_start: 637--->
<H2>Corporate Compliance: Standards For The 21st Century</h2>

<H3>Seminar Library File</h3>

<H1>Preventive Law Reporter, Winter 1991</H1>

<h5>Copyright&#169;1991 Preventive Law Reporter</h5>



<H3>The U.S. Sentencing Commission Guidelines:<br>



<H4>By THOMAS B. LEARY</h4>

<H5>Partner, Hogan & Hartson, Washington, D.C.<br> 

For 11 years, Mr. Leary was General Motors Corp. assistant

general counsel in Detroit. He received an economics degree

at Princeton and his law degree from Harvard.</h5>



<EM>Editor's Note: The following article was written prior to the

passage of the Federal Sentencing Guidelines for Organizations.

The actual guidelines thus differ in their detail from the

analysis presented below. We nonetheless wanted to include this

article in our library because it presents an excellent background

and interesting overview of the Federal Sentencing Guidelines.</em><p>



The United States Sentencing Commission recently

submitted to Congress a set of guidelines for

comprehensive reform of the criminal penalties

that will be imposed on organizations, including corporaions, 

convicted of Federal crimes. These guidelines become

law on No. 1, 1991, unless Congress intervenes -- which is

highly unlikely. When this happens, the sanctions for a

wide range of corporate crimes will be far more inflexible,

and far more harsh, than anything that corporations have

experienced before.<p>



The commission was created by Congress in 1984, primarily 

because of a perception that there was an unfair

disparity in the jail sentences imposed on individuals in the

federal systems. The commission promptly proposed individual 

guidelines, designed to achieve greater uniformity,

and they became law in 1987. The commission then turned

its attention to corporate sentences, notwithstanding the

fact that there was no evidence of congressional concern

about disparity in this area and relatively little experience

to serve as a guide.<p>



The commission floated multiple drafts over a three-year

period, and received comments from literally hundreds of

companies and their trade associations, before it submitted

proposals to Congress this year. The final proposals are

complex and difficult to apply, but the overall thrust is

clear: corporate penalties will be much higher.<p>



To sentence a convicted company under the proposed

guideline scheme, the judge must perform some alternative

calculations and then apply the alternative that yields the

highest penalty. First, the judge is supposed to calculate a

"base fine" by reference to a "fine table." The fines in the

table range from $5,000 to $72,500,000, depending on the

nature of the offense. This is not the most serious threat

because generally most corporate offenses will be in the

lower range.<p>



The judge is also supposed to calculate an alternative

base fine, however, which is measured by the gain to the

corporation or the loss that is caused if the offense is

deliberate. The precise language is "to the extent the loss 

was caused intentionally, knowingly, or recklessly." The words 

sound restrictive, but in other areas of statutory interpretation 

they sometimes are not applied in a restrictive way. It is too 

early to tell whether sentencing judges will pay any attention to

these words of limitation when contemplating fines based

on the harm caused by a crime.<p>



There is no cap on this amount; base fines in the billions

are theoretically possible. The greater of these alternative

base fines is then subjected to a multiplier, of up to four

times, which varies according to the "Culpability Score" of

the defendant. This score depends on individual factors like

the criminal history of the company, if any, the involvement

of top management, and the degree of cooperation with the

prosecutor. All of these penalties are imposed on top of full

restitution for potential victims of the offense.<p>



Sentencing Commission Guidelines do provide for a

possible mitigation of severe penalties, however, if the

defendant corporation has "an effective program to prevent

and detect violations of law." The elements of an effective

program are also spelled out in the guidelines.<p>



The specific credit for compliance programs is consistent

with a basic concept, often articulated by the commission's

chairman, that the guidelines should offer a "carrot" and

a "stick" -- a carrot to reward corporations that intensify

their efforts to comply with the law and a stick to punish

severely those that do not.<p>



There is controversy about the extent to which the

guidelines really do meet the stated objective of rewarding

corporate compliance programs. This article explores the

issue in further detail. Whatever the shortcomings of the

guidelines in this regard, however, corporations have no

choice but to intensify their compliance efforts. We also

identify the specific elements of a compliance program as

set forth in the guidelines.<p>



As mentioned above, the guidelines provide that the base

fine is subjected to a multiplier, which varies according to

the "Culpabilily Score" of the defendant corporation. If

there are no aggravating or mitigating factors, the 

corporation's score will be 5 points, and the base fine multiplier

will range from 1x to 2x.<p>



A court's finding that there was "an effective program to

prevent and detect violations of law" will reduce the

culpability score from 5 to 2 (other things being equal), and

the new multiplier will range from 0.40x to 0.80x. In effect,

the fine range with a qualifying compliance program is

only 40 percent of the fine range without it.<p>



There are significant limitations on the compliance

credit, however. In the first place, a defendant cannot

qualify for it if "high-level" management of the company

or a unit of the company, or an individual with compliance

responsibilities, "participated in, condoned, or was willfully

ignorant of the offense."<p>



Participation of lower-management personnel with "substantial 

authority" creates a "rebuttable presumption" that

the defendant did not have an effective compliance program.

Even without a detailed discussion of the precise meaning

of these various terms, it is obvious that this first limitation

will bar compliance credit in many cases.<p>



Second, the compliance credit is available only if the

company reports "the offense to appropriate governmental

authorities" within a reasonable time after it has become

aware if it. In some areas of regulation the failure to report

is itself an offense and this limitation will not be significant.

In other areas it will be significant -- for example, if the

company is inhibited from reporting by the risk of civil

litigation.<p>



Because of these limitations, some people have argued

that compliance credits will not be available in many cases,

and that therefore companies need not concern themselves

with what the guidelines say about compliance programs.

The premise may be correct, but the conclusion is not. Next

we discuss the reasons why it is imperative for companies

to intensify their compliance efforts.<p>



Notwithstanding the difficulty of qualifying for com-

pliance credits under the guidelines, prudent companies

will intensify their compliance efforts for the following

reasons:<p>



<H4>&iuml; The Downside Risks Are Greater</h4>



The risks of criminal prosecution are escalating, even as

the penalties become more severe. Congress increasingly

authorizes criminal sanctions for violations of complex

regulations, and the Justice Department openly claims that

criminal fines are expected to make ever larger contributions

to federal revenues.<p>



The risks of exposure are compounded by the fact that

corporations are criminally responsible for the acts of their

employees, even though those employees may have acted

directly contrary to management instructions and may have

been principally motivated by the desire for personal gain.<p>



Moreover, some statutes provide for "strict" criminal

liability, which means that a company can be convicted for

violating a regulation even though the event was genuinely

an accident and no one, at any level, was even negligent.

The new regulatory crimes are not intuitively obvious, and

companies cannot simply rely on the good common sense

or moral discrimination of their employees.<p>



In these circumstances, it would make sense for companies

to intensify their compliance efforts even if the Sentencing

Guidelines did not provide any credit at all.<p>



<H4>&iuml; The Threat of Probation</h4>



The absence of a compliance program is not an aggravating 

circumstance by itself, but the guidelines instruct a

judge to impose probation "if, at the time of sentencing, an

organization having 50 or more employees does not have an

effective program to prevent and detect violations of law."<p>



If a company is put on probation for that shortcoming,

it will thereafter have to implement a compliance program

under judicial supervision. This involves potentially bur-

densome disclosure, reporting and monitoring obligations.

The court may even hire "experts," at the company's

expense, to investigate the company's ongoing compliance

efforts.<p>



In other words, a company that takes a chance and does

not attempt to implement a qualifying compliance program,

may have to implement one under court supervision if it

commits a crime. Judicial supervision is not likely if the

defendant has previously made good-faith compliance

efforts because "failure to prevent or detect the instant

offense, by itself, does not mean that the program was not

effective."<p>



<H4>&iuml; Possible Aggravating Factors</h4>



We have already mentioned that a company cannot get

credit for compliance efforts if top management people

were involved in the offense. Beyond that, however, this

involvement is also an aggravating factor which requires an

upward adjustment in the culpability score.<p>



For example, if a high-level person in a company (or

unit) with over 5,000 employees "participated in, condoned,

or was willfully ignorant of the offense," the score is

increased by 5 points. A par score of 5 would be increased

to 10, and the fine multipliers would be doubled.<p>



Individuals are "willfully ignorant" if they "did not

investigate the possible occurrence of unlawful conduct

despite knowledge of circumstances that would lead a

reasonable person to investigate whether unlawful conduct

had occurred." This is a simple negligence standard.<p>



It could be argued someday that a failure to implement

a compliance program is by itself evidence of willful

ignorance. But even if courts do not go that far, it seems

obvious that top managers cannot exercise due care without

some knowledge of the criminal regulations applicable to

their activities and some efforts to prevent criminal conduct

by their subordinates. This means that intensified compliance 

efforts are imperative -- if not to qualify for the

mitigation in sentencing, then at least to avoid aggravating

circumstances.<p>



<H4>&iuml; Shareholder Liability</h4>



The Sentencing Guidelines offer credit for qualifying

compliance programs and specify the content of the programs 

in general terms. If a company has no such program

and happens to be involved in criminal proceedings,

shareholder suits are likely and they will be difficult to

defend.<p>



It would be most unappealing to argue that the company

did not bother to implement a qualifying program because

compliance credits are hard to obtain. Even if a compliance

program would not have affected the sentence, a plaintiff

could easily argue that it might have prevented the offense

in the first place.<p>

<hr><p>

The Guidelines provide general instructions for an

"effective" compliance program. These instructions may

be summarized as follows:<p>



"The organization must have established compliance

standards and procedures .... " What this means, as a

practical matter, is that a company must canvass its potential

criminal exposure across the board and implement compliance 

programs for the likely risks. There needs to be a

formal record of these efforts, and appropriate written

policies need to be developed.<p>



It probably does not mean that all compliance efforts for

all potential risks have to be formalized with a lot of

paperwork, but it does mean that there has to be some

record to show that particular risks were considered and

given attention, albeit informal attention. The larger the

company, the more complete this record has to be.<p>



Specific high-level managers must have "overall responsibility" 

for compliance. No single individual (like a general

counsel) has to have responsibility for all compliance

matters -- and this is probably not a very good idea anyway.<p>



But responsibility for compliance in each area of potential

criminal exposure must be in the job description of some

high-level manager. And since (to avoid aggravating circumstances) 

it will be in a company's interest to have a

narrow definition of high-level management, this means

that very senior people will have to take an interest in law

compliance.<p>



The company should take "care not to delegate substantial

discretionary authority to individuals" with "a propensity

to engage in illegal activities." Since repeat offenders in the

corporate setting are probably very rare, this may be of

limited practical importance for sentencing.<p>



This provision may, however, have an important in

terrorem effect on employees because it suggests that any

criminal conduct could have serious consequences for their

future employment anywhere in their industry -- even if

they are not individually charged.<p>



The standards and procedures must be communicated

"effectively" by "training programs" or "publications."

This means that a paper program is necessary but not

sufficient. The precise form of communication, and the

level of effort required, will vary from company to company

and from crime to crime.<p>



This provision will require both very careful planning

and careful documentation of decisions. Any effort -- 

reasonable at the time -- is going to look inadequate in the

light of hindsight if a crime is committed, and the rationale

for the decision to undertake or not undertake particular

compliance initiatives will be important. In this area -- as

in other areas of corporate governance -- the quality of

records is likely to become as significant as the quality of

decisions.<p>



The company must have "monitoring and auditing

systems reasonably designed to detect criminal conduct,"

and have a publicized "reporting system" that will enable

employees to report offenses by others "without fear of

retribution. "<p>



This is something new. Existing compliance programs

in many companies are not designed to detect offenses

effectively, and not many companies have publicly 

announced (as opposed to informal) procedures for the

protection of whistleblowers.<p>



Standards must be enforced by "appropriate disciplinary

mechanisms, including, as appropriate, discipline of individuals 

responsible for the failure to detect an offense."<p>



The reference to "appropriate" discipline surely means

that a corporation can extend the same leniency to employees

who report themselves as prosecutors extend to corporations

which report themselves. Otherwise, an important source

of information will dry up, and overall compliance efforts

will suffer. The reference to discipline of individuals for

failure to detect an offense means that attention to com-

pliance issues will necessarily become the responsibility of

a broad segment of management.<p>



The program should be appropriately modified after

detection of an offense. This particular provision seems

self-evident, as do the subsequent comments that the "requisite 

degree of formality" depends on the size of the

organization, compliance programs must be tailored to the

particular risks of a company's business, and that a company

should learn from its prior history.<p>



Two final comments, however, are noteworthy. First, as

previously mentioned, failure to detect a single offense

"does not mean that the program was not effective."

"Recurrence of [similar] misconduct" by the company,

however, "casts doubt on whether it took all reasonable

steps to prevent such misconduct." You get one bite of the

apple, not two.<p>



Second, it is important for the company "to incorporate

and follow applicable industry practice." This means that

it will be prudent for companies in similar lines of business

to pool information on their compliance programs.<p>



<H3>Conclusion</h3>



The new Guidelines for Sentencing of Organizations not

only sanction greater penalties than companies have experienced 

before but also, as a practical matter, impose greater

and sometimes unprecedented compliance burdens. Corporate 

counsel need to make a ground-up examination of their

present compliance efforts, and reshape them to conform to

the standards set out in the guidelines -- more on account

of the greatness of the risks than the greatness of the

rewards.

<hr><p>



