<html><head><title>Seminars - Survey of Government Imposed Compliance Programs</title>
</head> <BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#FF0005">
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/smb.gif" BORDER=0>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<h2>Survey of Government Imposed Compliance Programs</h2>
<!--- full_start: 636--->
<H2>Corporate Compliance: Standards For The 21st Century</h2>

<H3>Seminar Library File</h3>

<H1>Preventive Law Reporter, Winter 1994</H1>

<h5>Copyright&#169;1994 Preventive Law Reporter</h5>

     

<H4>By KIRK S. JORDAN</h4>

<H5>President, Compliance Systems Legal Group; Warwick, Rhode Island</h5>



<EM>EDITOR'S NOTE: Kirk Jordan is the President of Compliance

Systems Legal Group and serves on the National Center for

Preventive Law Commission on Corporate Compliance Standards. Mr. Jordan 

gratefully acknowledges the research assistance of Todd Ericson, a student 

at the Universiity of Denver College of Law, and Michele Salazar of the 

<A HREF="http://www.pacificrim.net/~ncpl/">NCPL</a> in the research of 

consent decrees and the preparation of this article.</em><p>



On November 1, 1991, the Federal Organizational Sentencing Guidelines 

became law. The Guidelines provide organizations with significant 

incentives to establish "effective" corporate compliance programs to 

prevent and detect misconduct.<p>



In the three years since the Guidelines' enactment, however,

organizations have struggled with the question of how to design

and implement compliance programs that will be deemed

"effective" by the govemment and the courts. Unfortunately, the

Guidelines themselves do not provide all the answers. Although

they list seven "minimum" criteria for an organization's compliance 

program, the Guidelines do not provide a precise formula

for effective compliance, opting for a flexible approach that

allows organizations to tailor their programs to their own culture

and business operations.<p>



While the Guidelines' flexible approach has advantages, it has

also left many organizations uncertain about whether they have

taken the right steps in the design and implementation of their

compliance programs. Organizations looking for additional

guidance will find it worthwhile to review the consent decrees

and plea agreements that other organizations have reached with

federal agencies since the Guidelines became effective. Our

survey of such agreements revealed that many impose a

comprehensive compliance program or enhancements to the

organization's existing program.<p>



This article briefly reviews the surveyed consent decrees and

plea agreements that impose compliance programs. It then

summarizes the principles that organizations can glean from the

imposed compliance programs and, perhaps, apply to their own

situations.<p>



<H3>TYPES OF AGREEMENTS IMPOSING COMPLIANCE PROGRAMS</h3>



In the three years since the Guidelines became effective,

compliance programs have been imposed in connection with

consent decrees and plea agreements covering a variety of

underlying crimes. Although our survey was not exhaustive,

agreements settling antitrust offenses, usually involving price

fixing, make up the largest single group of cases in which

compliance programs were imposed. The organizations involved in 

antitrust settlements were from diverse industries,

including waste disposal companies, hospitals, a physicians'

association, health care providers, munitions manufacturers,

automobile body repair shops, airlines and an airline tariff

publishing company.<p>



Since the enactment of the Guidelines, compliance programs

also have been imposed in connection with the settlement of

various environrnental offenses, including violations of the

Clean Air Act, Clean Water Act, the Emergency Planning and

Community Right to Know Act (EPCRA), the emergency release

reporting requirements of the Superfund law and hazardous

waste violations. In other cases, a defense contractor agreed to

the imposition of an enhanced compliance program in connection 

with the company's settlement of potential criminal fraud

charges. Compliance programs also were imposed in connection 

with broker-dealers' settlements of securities laws violations, 

a large insurance company's settlement of charges that its

agents engaged in misleading sales practices and a supermarket

chain's settlement of wage and hour law violations.<p>



Our survey suggests that the three most comprehensive

compliance programs imposed in the last three years were in

connection with settlements by C.R. Bard, Inc., National Medical

Enterprises, Inc. (NME) and Denny's, Inc. The C.R. Bard

agreement settled charges in connection with Bard's manufacture 

and shipment of adulterated heart catheters. The NME

agreement settled health care fraud charges arising out of

activities at NME's psychiatric and substance abuse facilities. The

Denny's consent decree settled civil allegations that the restaurant 

chain systematically discriminated against customers on the

basis of race in violation of federal public accommodations laws.

The fines imposed on Bard ($61 million), NME ($379 million)

and Denny's ($54 million) are by far the largest ever levied for

the types of offenses underlying each case. Moreover, the

compliance programs imposed in the Bard and NME cases are

designed to prevent and detect violations of all laws affected hy

the companies' respective business activities, not simply the

laws at issue in the underlying settlements.<p>



<H3>COMPLIANCE PROGRAM PRINCIPLES DISTILLED FROM THE AGREEMENTS</h3>



Although the surveyed agreements involve organizations

from different industries and a variety of underlying offenses,

the compliance programs imposed contain recurring elements. As

one would expect, the principal elements of the compliance

programs follow the Guidelines' criteria. Many of the programs

go even further, however; they flesh out the Guidelines' criteria

by mandating specific polices, procedures and systems designed 

to ensure "effective" compliance. Admittedly, these

programs were imposed after a major compliance failure, and must

be considered in that context. Nevertheless, these compliance

programs, which bear the imprimatur of various regultory and

enforcement agencies and the courts, may offer valuable insight

into what those entities expect organizations' compliance

programs to look like.<p>



<H4>Establish a Formal Compliance Management and Oversight Structure</h4>



<Strong>Empower a high level manager or managers to direct

the organization's compliance program.</strong> The compliance

programs imposed under consent decrees and plea agreements

consistently require the establishment (or reaffirmation) of a

formal compliance management and oversight structure. The

structure usually consists of the appointment of one or more

senior managers to serve as a compliance or ethics officer and

visible senior management support for, and involvement in, the

compliance process. Often, the structure also includes a special

committee of senior managers and/or the board of directors to

oversee the company s compliance program.<p>



Under Bard's compliance program, for instance, a new

compliance officer, called a "Compliance Coordinator", is to

have direct, open access to senior management and to a special

board committee charged with ultimate responsibility for compliance 

matters. Bard's compliance officer is directed to report

regularly to the board committee regarding the company's

compliance program and whether he has received the full

support and cooperation of the company's senior management.<p>



Denny's agreed to hire a "Civil Rights Monitor" with broad

powers to oversee the design and implementation of the

company's compliance program. For example, the monitor is

directed to establish a compliance training and communication

program for Denny's employees and agents, implement a

system to test Denny's compliance with public accommodation

laws, and investigate and document any customer or employee

complaints of racial discrimination.<p>



Compliance programs imposed under the antitrust consent

decrees almost uniformly require the company to appoint an

antitrust compliance officer wl1o is charged with supervising and

implementing the company's program to comply with the

antitrust laws. A company which settled charges under the Fair

Labor Standards Act (FLSA) agreed to designate a labor standards 

ombudsman to coordinate company-wide compliance with the law.<p>



Several large organizations that settled securities, environmental 

and government procurement law violations agreed to

appoint regional compliance officers and/or compliance officers at 

each of the organization's facilities. Those officers

typically report to a top compliance officer or to a compliance

committee at the organization's headquarters.<p>



<Strong>Directly involve the organization's board of directors.</strong>

The compliance programs of several organizations require the

creation of special committees of the boards of directors,

sometimes comprised solely of independent outside directors.

These committees have ultimate oversight responsibility for

the companies' compliance programs. A board compliance committee

and, in some cases, the entire board, is typically charged

with reviewing and formally adopting the company's compliance 

standards, procedures and systems, interacting regularly

with senior management and/or the company's compliance

officer(s) regarding compliance issues and reporting periodically 

to the full board.<p>



<Strong>Actively involve Senior Management in the organization's

compliance effort.</strong> Under Bard's compliance program, senior

management is required to participate actively in the

oversight and implementation of the company's program. At

every board meeting, Bard's chief executive officer will report

on the company's compliance with applicable laws and regula-

tions. Other surveyed compliance programs establish manage-

ment committees made up of senior executives to provide

corporate direction to the companies' compliance programs and

to act as liaisons with compliance officers.<p>





<H4>Carefully Delegate Substantial Discretionary Authority</h4>



Several of the imposed compliance programs address the

issue of the delegation of substantial discretionary authority. In

these cases, the companies are required to adopt policies and

procedures designed to prevent the delegation of substantial

authority to anyone whom the companies know or should know

is likely to break the law.<p>



Under Bard's program, for example, substantial discretionary

authority is given "only to individuals whom [Bard] is confident

will not engage in illegal activities." Bard's compliance officer

will review annually the company's delegation of substantial

discretionary authority by considering information in personnel

files, the results of company audits, managers' opinions and

surveys of companies with which Bard does business. Following

the review, Bard's compliance officer will recommend to senior

management appropriate changes in policy and procedure.<p>



Under its compliance program, NME will not hire anyone

whom the company knows or should know has been convicted

of a criminal health care offense. The company also agreed that

if any employee or contractor is charged with a criminal offense

or proposed for debarment from work with the government,

NME will immediately remove that person from any responsibil-

ity for NME's business operations. The employee or contractor

also will be terminated upon a subsequent conviction or

debarment.<p>



In another example, a broker-dealer agreed to implement

procedures to identify salespeople with substantial disciplinary

histories or who have been the subject of significant customer

complaints. Approval of senior compliance managers is

required before any such salespeople are hired.<p>



<H4>Adopt Compliance Standards and Procedures Tailored to the Organization's Business Operations</h4>



As one would expect, the compliance programs imposed

pursuant to consent decrees and plea agreements typically

require organizations to adopt or revise existing compliance

standards and procedures that are designed to detect and

prevent the recurrence of the kinds of offenses underlying the

settlements. A large securities broker-dealer, for example,

agreed to review and revise its policies and procedures to

address specified securities laws violations. The consent decrees

entered in settlement of antitrust violations, which generally

prohibit price fixing, are themselves usually incorporated into

the companies' compliance standards.<p>



Denny's will review and, if appropriate, revise its written

policies to ensure that they promote nondiscriminatory behavior

on the part of employees and agents. A defense contractor

agreed to overhaul its procurement policies and procedures and

to adhere to the principles of the Defense Industry Initiative on

Business Ethics and Conduct. Similarly, a company that agreed

to an environmental consent decree adopted an environmental

compliance manual. And Bard, a maker of medical devices, will

utilize various compliance standards and procedures in its

program, including a code of ethics for health care providers and

institutions.<p>



<H4>Effectively Communicate the Mandatory Standards and Procedures</h4>



<Strong>Distribute the compliance standards and consider requiring 

certifications.</strong> The majority of the imposed compliance programs 

require company compliance personnel to

distribute the company's compliance standards and procedures

to existing employees and agents. New employees and agents

must also promptly receive the standards and procedures after

they are hired or retained. At several companies, each employee

is required to certify in writing, on an annual basis, that he or

she has reviewed, understands and agrees to abide by the compliance 

standards and procedures.<p>



<Strong>Provide formal training in the organization's compliance 

standards.</strong> The overwhelming majority of compliance

programs surveyed also mandate some form of training in the

company's compliance standards and procedures. The principal

goal of such compliance training is to ensure that employees and

other agents are familiar with applicable laws and regulations,

and with the company's procedures for the reporting and

investigation of compliance violations.<p>



Some compliance programs require all employees to undergo

compliance training, while a second group mandates training for

employees whose responsibilities involve compliance with the

laws underlying the settlement. A third group of programs

explicitly requires compliance training only for managerial and

supervisory employees.<p>



The most comprehensive compliance programs, imposed on

Bard, NME and Denny's, require training of virtually all employees. 

As is true in a majority of the other programs surveyed, the

Bard and NME programs also require that compliance training

be administered annually. Under Denny's program, the required

training is "a necessary condition for the continued employment" 

of the applicable employees and agents.<p>



A consent decree settling environmental offenses under

EPCRA and Superfund's emergency release reporting requirements 

requires that certain managers with significant

compliance responsibilities receive eight hours of training. In

that case, internal environmental auditors must receive eighty

hours of initial training, followed thereafter by sixteen hours

annually.<p>



<Strong>Communicate the company's commitment to compliance

using supervisors and other managers.</strong> Supervisors at

Bard and NME must discuss the company's compliance standards 

and procedures with their employees. They must inform

supervised employees that strict compliance with the company's

standards is a condition of employment, the violation of which

will result in appropriate disciplinary action, including possible

dismissal.<p>



Bard and NME also agreed to post prominently notices that

detail the companies' commitment to compliance with all

applicable laws and regulations. Bard's notices must designate

the procedure for reporting and investigating possible misconduct.<p>



<H4>Use Customized Measures to Achieve and Measure Compliance</h4>



<Strong>Conduct internal audits under the direction of independent 

auditors.</strong> Many of the compliance programs require

companies to conduct internal audits of the business activities

that gave rise to the underlying offenses. A common requirement 

for such audits is that the auditors be independent; that is,

the auditors must be either outside consultants, or if internal,

they must not report to the individuals or facilities being audited.

The compliance programs imposed in connection with the

settlement of environmental crimes typically require an outside

consulting firm to audit the companies' facilities to measure

compliance with the environmental laws and regulations at

issue. Before selling or transferring any psychiatric or substance

abuse facility, NME will retain an independent third party to

conduct a comprehensive review of health care law compliance

at the facility. The civil rights monitor at Denny's is directed to

develop and implement tests, using discrete groups of black and

white "customers," to monitor Denny's compliance with the

federal public accommodations laws. At least half of the tests

must be conducted by an independent, qualified civil rights

organization.<p>



The Bard compliance program sets forth a detailed legal

compliance auditing scheme. Internal auditors will conduct

both financial and nonfinancial audits to promote legal compliance. 

Independent, outside auditors also will conduct annual

financial and nonfinancial audits with respect to legal compliance. 

All of the Bard audit results will be provided to the

compliance officer and the appropriate board committee.<p>



A large securities broker-dealer must have outside auditors

conduct "statistically valid" surveys of customers to test how

effective the broker-dealer's new "sales practices" supervisory

procedures are in achieving compliance. Other audit provisions

include a supermarket chain's agreement to conduct regular

internal audits of the company's compliance with the FLSA, the

subject matter of the chain's consent decree.<p>



<Strong>Establish a misconduct reporting system for employees

and agents.</strong> Several of the surveyed compliance programs

require the establishment of a misconduct reporting system that

employees and agents may use to report known or suspected

violations of the law or company compliance policy.<p>



In Bard's case, the compliance officer is required to establish

and oversee a widely publicized reporting system that employees

may use to report (anonymously, if preferred) misconduct or

impropriety relating to the company's operations. Although

Bard's employees will not be punished for making good faith

reports, the company's reporting system mandates that employees 

report suspected or confirmed misconduct.<p>



A defense contractor's program requires that the telephone

numbers of members of the company's business ethics committee, 

composed of the compliance officer and other senior

managers, be publicized to all company employees. A Supermarket 

chain will establish an internal dispute resolution procedure 

by which employees may report alleged FLSA violations

Under a plan adopted prior to the implementation of its

compliance program but implicitly approved by the Department

of Justice, NME established a telephone "hotline" system for

employees and patients.<p>



<H4>Enforce the Standards and Procedures with Consistent, Case-Specific Discipline</h4>



<Strong>Establish formal disciplinary systems.</strong> The Bard compliance 

program imposes a disciplinary system for compliance

violations that tracks the language of the Guidelines' criterion.

Under Bard's program, the compliance officer is charged with

establishing a consistent, company-wide disciplinary system,

documenting all disciplinary actions the company takes for

violations of its compliance standards and reporting annually to

company management about the disciplinary system. Disciplin-

ary decisions will be made by appropriate Bard officials in

consultation with the company's compliance officer.<p>



A large securities broker-dealer's compliance program requires 

the company to implement systems to communicate to

appropriate managers in the law and compliance departments

any customer complaints or disciplinary actions taken against

company salespeople or other employees. These managers are

charged with recommending appropriate discipline, including

possible dismissal. If the disciplinary recommendation is not

accepted, the compliance committee of the board is to be

notified promptly.<p>



<Strong>Consider including compliance Issues in employee performance 

appraisals.</strong> Two of the surveyed compliance programs mandate 

that supervisors' and managers' performance

appraisals consider their efforts to promote compliance and

ethical behavior at the company. In a related provision, Bard

promises that employees who perform regulatory, medical or

quality assurance functions will not receive any compensation

that is tied to product approvals or the company's financial

performance.<p>





<H4>Respond Reasonably Aftrer the Detection of an Offense</h4>



<Strong>Promptly investigate known or suspected offenses.</strong> 

Several of the programs surveyed specifically require the company to

respond promptly to violations of the company's compliance

policies and procedures, and to take action to prevent further

similar offenses. Following a violation or a suspected violation,

Bard's compliance officer will conduct an investigation, and

make an appropriate recommendation to senior management, which

will render a decision. Bard's compliance officer will prepare a

memorandum detailing the investigatlon, recommendatlon and

decision; and a copy will be forwarded to a committee of the

board of directors. Denny's civil rights monitor is charged with

investigating any complaints of discrimination by customers or

employees and any reports of discriminatory actions or conduct

at the company.<p>



<Strong>Report a substantlated offense to the appropriate

governmental or regulatory agency.</strong> To receive credit for a

compliance program, the Guidelines require a company to

report a substantiated criminal offense to the appropriate

governmental authorities after an internal investigation. Several

of the surveyed programs closely track these requirements. For

instance, if the investigation undertaken by Bard's compliance

officer reveals a violation of the law, Bard's written policy

requires the company to voluntarily and promptly report the

violation to the appropriate governmental agency. Similarly, if

Bard learns that any statement that the company previously

made to a governmental agency is materially incorrect, the

company will promptly report and correct the error.<p>



NME's compliance program requires the company to report

any "credible evidence" at any of NME's facilities of a civil or

criminal violation of the laws governing federally funded health

care programs. A company that settled EPCRA and Superfund

violations will notify the EPA of any reportable event uncovered

during the company's environmental audit. Similarly, a defense

contractor will notify the government within sixty days if the

company's ethics and compliance officer learns of any credible

allegations of criminal conduct within the company or a

subsidiary company.<p>



<Strong>Modify the compliance program to prevent further

similar offenses.</strong> Following a violation, the Bard compliance

program will be modified to the extent possible to prevent

similar offenses in the future.<p>





<H3>GOVERNMENTAL AND JUDICIAL INVOLVEMENT IN THE COMPLIANCE PROGRAMS</h3>



A final point that emerges from the surveyed compliance

programs is that if an organization's compliance program is

imposed in connection with a consent decree or plea agreement,

the government or the courts are likely to be substantially

involved in the ensuing compliance program. For example,

under many of the programs, companies are required to make

periodic reports to the court or governmental agencies involved.

Similarly, many programs call for the appointment of monitors

or consultants, who will report to the government or the courts

on compliance at the organization.<p>



In the Bard case, for example, an "independent outside consultant,"

both acceptable and reporting to the FDA, is granted full and

unannounced access to many of the company's records, employees and

operations in order to monitor Bard's compliance. The consultant

will issue an annual report to the FDA regarding the consultant's

inspections, findings and recommendations. Bard also will prepare

separate annual reports to the FDA, which will analyze Bard's

compliance with FDA regulations during the preceding year and

disclose whether Bard's audits uncovered any violations. These

reports are to be signed by top management officials and the

compliance officer.<p>



For five years, NME will file an annual "Compliance Report"

with the Department of Health and Human Services. The

Compliance Report, which must be certified by NME's compliance 

officer, will describe the company's compliance program

during the preceding year.<p>



For four years, Denny's civil rights monitor will prepare semi-annual 

reports to the Department of Justice describing the

company's compliance activities and any complaints received

and/or investigations undertaken by the monitor in the preced-

ing six months. The monitor's report also will set objectives to

ellmlnate any discriminatlon concerns identified. Denny's is

also required to report on the company s training and testing

programs, and detall the company's advertisements and promotional 

material to ensure that they comply with the consent

decree.<p>



In a final example, the board audit committee of a defense

contractor has been directed to study measures to ehance the

company's compliance programs. in doing so, the committee must

solicit recommendations from the United States Attorney's Office

and other governmental agencies and provide a draft report to

the agencies for comment.<p>



<H3>CONCLUSION</h3>



It is our experience that many organizations simply do not know

how to determine if their compliance programs will be deemed

"effective" under the Guidelines. The principles outlined above,

sanctioned by the government and the courts through consent decrees

and plea agreements, point to some of the critical areas that

organizations should consider in designing and implenmenting their

compliance programs. As for oorganizations that have not yet

focused on internal comliance, the cases considered above also

teach that now is the time to make organizational compliance a

priority.<p>



<H3>Survey of Consent Decrees:<br>

Additional Noteworthy Points</H3>



<Strong>Communication of information.</strong> In a case where a company had made

repeated fraudulent statements to customers, the FTC has required

the company to provide a "risk disclosure" document for every

customer's signature. The company must also make a risk disclosure

at the beginning and the end of any paid radio advertisements that

are more than five minutes long.<P>



<Strong>Avallability of counsel for advice to employees.</strong> 

Four of the surveyed consent decrees require communication to the employees

that the company's legal advisors are available to confer witll

them about the final judgment and the applicable laws.<p>



<Strong>Use of independent consultants.</strong> In several decrees, 

both the EPA and the SEC have required outside consultants to establish

compliance policies and procedures. In one instance, the SEC

required the offending company to retain a consultant "not

unacceptable" to the SEC to conduct an extensive review of the

company's policies and procedures. The company must then implement

all of the changes or programs the consultant recommends. If the

company finds any of the recommended  changes burdensome, it can

submit an alternative plan to the consultant, who determines the

final plan. All of the consultant's recommendations must be

implemented with six months of the final report. One year later,

the consultant must review the success of the new policies and

procedures.<p>



<Strong>Audit requirements.</strong> Eleven consent decrees require the compliance

officer to make annual status reports to the regulatory agency.

This implies that an annual audit would be necessary, but details

are not given as to how it should be conducted.<p>



<Strong>Audit of customers.</strong> The SEC has required a security sales firm to

audit its customers over a three-year period to test the

effectiveness of its sales practice supervisory procedures.<p>



<Strong>Access to company records and officials.</strong> Eleven consent decrees

require the offending companies to give appropriate regulatory

agencies access to documents relevant to the consent decree. The

agencies also have the right to interview corporate officers and

directors.<p>



<Strong>Company Size.</strong> How large does a company have to be before a formal

program is required? Not large, apparently. Three small automobile

dealerships in Casper, Wyoming (population 50,000) were prosecuted

by the Department of Justice for antitrust violations in a scheme

to fix prices for auto body repair in the Casper trade area. The

consent decree included a formal compliance program for all three

businesses.<p>



In a case of inadequate monitoring of problem assets, the Office

of Contract Compliance required a bank with only twenty-eight

million dollars in assets to implement a written compliance

program. The program must include an independent loan review

system, increased audit staff and a a three-year capital plan.<p>



The SEC may be specifically targeting smaller organizations.

Mathew Fink, president of the Investment Company Institute,

has noted that the SEC is shifting its inspection emphasis from

the 100 largest mutual fund complexes to smaller fund complexes

because of their lack of sophistication in compliance programs.<p>



These cases may be anomalies. They seem to indicate, however,

that in the eyes of some regulatory agencles, a company

does not have to be a Fortune 500 company to need a compliance

program.<p>



<Strong>Technology and Compliance.</strong> With the pace of teclmological

change accelerating, organizations must anticipate the

attendant possibilities for noncompliance. A major life insurance

company was prosecuted when its sales people began producing

"custom" sales literature from laptop computers in the homes of

prospective customers. The company did not foresee that technology

could lead to the production of fraudulent sales literature. Any

sales literahlre that did not originate from or was not

specifically approved by the company was subsequently banned.<p>



<Strong>Non-business activities.</strong> A company should not assume its

liability will be limited hecause illegal conduct lies outside its

usual business activities. The EPA prosecuted a mining company for

violations of the Clean Air Act. In the process of closing

an old mine, the company destroyed some buildings in a manner that

did not comply with the EPA's asbestos-control requirements. The

EPA's consent decree added an asbestos-removal provision to the

company's compliance program.

<hr><p>



