<BLOCKQUOTE>
<h2>Creating a Compliance Culture in the Workplace</h2>
<!--- full_start: 635--->
<H2>Corporate Compliance: Standards For The 21st Century</h2>

<H3>Seminar Library File</h3>

<H1>Preventive Law Reporter, Winter 1994</H1>

<h5>Copyright&#169;1994 Preventive Law Reporter</h5>



<H4>By LAURA L. MONTY</h4>

<H5>Manager, Corporate Environmental Compliance<br>

Huntsman Chemical Corporation</h5>



<EM>LAURA MONTY is currently responsible for environmental

compliance programs for Huntsman Chemical's manufacturing 

sites worldwide.</em><p>



Beginning in the early 1970's, the seeds of what would

prove to be profound changes in the basic US business

terrain emerged in the form of new regulations, global

competition and the resultant pressures on productivity. Over

the ensuing 25 years, businesses were increasingly challenged

on many fronts, particularly in the areas of return on capital,

quality, worker safety, process safety and environmental

compliance.<p>



As businesses quickly discovered, these issues are inextricably

linked. Action on any one issue can affect performance in the

other areas, while neglect of any area can threaten the long-term

viability of a business. Moreover, these challenges must be met

within the framework dictated by tough global competition,

which has resulted in lean organizations with even leaner

resources. Like a zero sum game, safety, quallty, environmental

and process safety issues are not only integrally related, but

often compete for the same limited resources.<p>



Corporate compliance programs typically have not been

formulated to account for the realities of managing daily

activities at a plant site. Programs which consist primarily of

strict policy demands ("all employees must comply with all

applicable laws and regulations") and documenting that such

demands were communicated to employees are of diminishing use.<p>



The problem faced by plant management is not whether to

comply, but what to comply with and, more importantly, how

to achieve compliance with limited resources. This article will

describe one approach to creating a "compliance culture" in a

real-world setting, and discuss why the success of any

compliance program depends on its ability to provide an ongoing

process of continuous improvement.<p>



<H3>THE CHANGING BUSINESS ENVIRONMENT</h3>



In the past two and a half decades, as performance demands

in areas such as safety, quality and environmental compliance

increased, classical management structures were stretched to

their limit. Many businesses held on to these classical structures

for several years, placing more people and financial resources

on the table to meet these new requirements. Functional

specialties were augmented or created to grapple with the new

'wrinkles" in the business terrain. This approach, however,

proved difficult to maintain in the face of increasingly severe

global competition.<p>



New tools were clearly needed to respond to these challenges. 

Answers emerged in the form of continuous process

improvement and management systems such as 

<A HREF="http://www.iso.ch/9000e/forum.html">ISO-9000</a> to

address productivity and quality issues. Due to a recognition of

common elements, quality and productivity systems were

integrated early in their development process.<p>



Some business and industry groups also developed management 

systems, to address environmental, health and safety (EHS)

concerns, such as the chemical industry's Responsible Care&AElig;

codes of management practice. Unlike their quality and productivity 

counterparts, however, EHS systems matured. as specialized 

and isolated processes.<p>



The impact of this isolated development has been most visible

at the point where a majority of compliance issues arise, at the

plant site, with predictable results. Specialized compliance

knowledge, such as the understanding of environmental permits

and regulations, is retained inside the EHS group, while most

process knowledge is retained in the operational unit. Consequently, 

the operations staff often have little awareness of

process changes which could create a non-compliant condition,

while the EHS staff have little knowledge of operational issues

or future plans.<p>



To ensure compliance, the EHS staff are forced to function as

police officers rather than advocates, which increases their need

for both monetary and personnel resources. Crises erupt,

consuming time and resources and preventing the development

of balanced, cost-effective solutions. Compliance must then be

achieved through the implementation of detailed procedures

and control systems, resulting in increased cycle times and

negative productivity. These types of responses serve to perpetuate 

the common sentiment that compliance is a necessary

evil that impedes production rather than an integral part of an

operation.<p>



Noting the similarities among management system elements

for quality, productivity and EHS compliance, proactive businesses 

have begun to seek the "Grand Unification Theory" of

compliance. An integrated system would allow compliance

elements in each of these areas to be merged into a total

business management system.<p>



An integrated management system has several obvious advantages 

which maximize the probability of success. There is a

greater likelihood of ownership by line operations, because a

single system is simpler for people to understand and manage

and thus may be viewed as making their job easier.<p>



A single system also makes more effective use of limited

resources by eliminating duplication of effort and speeding the

implementation process. The program of the month" syndrome

can be avoided because new system elements are added to an

existing framework. Any compliance program which is embedded 

into mainstream management functions has a greater

likelihood of success than its non-integrated counterpart.<p>



The design of an integrated system and its acceptance by the

workforce is critical to its success. Fortunately, there is no need

to reinvent the wheel. Several existing management system

models can be expanded to include compliance elements.

Although they vary in detail, all solid management systems have

several common elements which should be considered when

designing a compliance program.<p>



The elements discussed below are drawn from basic quality

management system principles developed by the 

<A HREF="http://www.cimio.co.uk/STEP/prodex/BSI.html">British Standards

Institute</a> and the <A HREF="http://www.iso.ch/welcome.html">International 

Organization of Standards (ISO)</a>.

As will become apparent, these principles apply equally well to a

compliance program as they do to a quality program.<p>



To illustrate how an integrated program based on these

principles functions in the workplace, each element will be

discussed with respect to an actual compliance process developed 

at a plastics manufacturing plant located in Alabama. At

this facility, an ISO-9002 quality process was being implemented

to achieve full certification for the site manufacturing operations.

Because all internal quality management systems were being

aligned with the ISO standards, it was an ideal opportunity to

attempt to integrate elements of compliance.<p>



The specific elements being integrated were in the areas of

safety, environmental compliance and process safety. These

areas were priorities because EHS regulatory compliance issues

are directly linked to operating variables in the manufacturing

process.<p>



<H3>POLICY STATEMENT</h3>



A management system should have a clear policy statement

which defines the business objectives and commitment. To

promote integration and still keep the policy statement a

reasonable length, a business may have separate sub-policies

which specifically address quality, safety, compliance, and so

on, with each supporting the overall objectives.<p>



These policy statements should receive visible support from

management and be communicated throughout the organization.

All employees, including new hires, should receive training

to promote understanding and awareness of the commitment

required.<p>



At the Alabama site, plant policy and goals were established

They became the guiding principles for the ISO-9002 effort and

were later expanded to include safety, process safety and

environmental compliance.<p>



<H3>ORGANIZATIONAL STRUCTURE</h3>



A management structure which gives appropriate personnel

the authority to control key elements is needed within the

organization. ISO requires a site to have a central coordinator

with overall responsibility for the entire quality management

system. An integrated system may have several coordinators,

who are responsible for a piece of the management system (i.e.,

environmental compliance, quality, etc.).<p>



Additional people are needed at the unit level to maintain the

system documentation, ensure that the system is functioning to

identify non-conformances and implement appropriate corrective 

actions, and work with management to review the system

periodically for effectiveness. In an ISO 9002 system, area

representatives are appointed to coordinate these tasks for

their specific area of the plant. The number of area

representatives at a plant site is discretionary and will depend

upon the size and complexity of the site.<p>



In a program similar to ISO area representatives, volunteers

from each operating area at the Alabama plant formed a special

group called environmental representatives. These were individuals

who assumed responsibilities for environmental compliance in

addition to their usual operating duties. After general and

area-specific training, the environmental representatives promoted

environmental compliance awareness in their operational units,

acted as communication links between the EHS group and their

units, and provided a "first line of defense" for compliance with

permits in their units. In this way, the environmental

representative network pushed compliance responsibilities to the

operating floor to help achieve real compliance improvements.<p>



<H3>MANAGEMENT RESPONSIBILITY</h3>



Management plays a significant role in the success of a

management system. It is responsible for obtaining the resources 

needed to ensure that the system functions properly.

Management should regularly examine the policies and procedures 

that make up the system and meet with the plant staff to

set goals, measure progress, analyze system performance and

review the results of internal audits. The purposes of managemnt 

review are to ensure appropriate actions are taken to

correct undesirable trends or changes and to encourage and

reward desirable performance.<p>



At the Alabama site, the plant manager and his staff set

measurable goals that covered all aspects of the manufacturing

process. Example of these goals included process measurements, 

such as first pass yield and turn-around times; environmental 

criteria, such as emissions per pound of product and

number of spills; quality measurements, such as customer

complaints; and safety criteria, such as the recordable rate of

injuries and the number of lost time accidents.<p>



The total team was involved in setting the site goals. Manufacturing 

management participated in setting environmental and

safety goals, while EHS personnel help set quality and productivity 

hurdles. In this manner, a high level of ownership

developed across the organization for all policies and goals.<p>



The management review process which was already in place

for ISO was used to review performance according to the

integrated goals, rather than quality goals alone. Utilizing Pareto

analysis and trend charting, the team defined problems and

developed and tracked corrective actions.<p>



The involvement of the plant manager was instrumental in

ensuring the system stayed fresh and the commitment to the

overall process did not slip. The site manager also ensured that

each successive achievement became the basis for the next

cycle's goal setting. In this way, management reviews drove the

continuous improvement that is essential to the efficacy of the

ISO process.<p>



<H3>SYSTEM DOCUMENTATION</h3>



The management system should be documented in sufficient

detail to show how the system will produce the desired result.

Each step of any process that can affect the desired system

outcome should be documented in a procedure and included in

a system manual.<p>



In a truly integrated system, each procedure should cover all

aspects of quality, productivity, and EHS compliance. As a

business begins the process of integration, however, each

component may have its own manual, with sections and layouts

conforming to a master format. A comprehensive document

control procedure with scheduled reviews for revision is critical

to ensure that policies and procedures are kept current.<p>



At the Alabama site, environmental representatives received

resource books that were specific to their areas of responsibility.

The resource book included the documentation for environmental 

compliance with copies of area permits, emission points,

waste streams and applicable <A HREF="http://www.epa.gov/">EPA</a> 

and <A HREF="http://www.osha.gov/">OSHA</a> regulations.<p>



When the resource books from each area were combined,

they formed the basis for a site environmental manual. Taken

together, the safety, quality, environmental and process safety

manuals documented the entire site management system. The

long-term goal was to have fewer separate procedures for any

single aspect of the system (e.g., a safety procedure), because

each aspect of the site goals would be covered in the operating

procedures themselves.<p>



<H3>INTERNAL AUDITING</h3>



A good management system documents the critical procedures 

and verifies, through its internal audits, that the procedures 

are understood and followed. To be effective, internal

audits should document the non-conformances found, the

corrective actions required, the date of implementation, and the

person responsible. Auditors should be trained in auditing

methodology and independent of the activity being audited.<p>



Auditing can also be a powerful tool to advance integration

efforts. Tailored audit protocols can mix quality, productivity,

safety and environmental checkpoints into a single process

review.<p>



This approach was utilized at the Alabama site. The ISO-9002

internal auditing protocol was expanded to add compliance

elements that were concrete, understandable, easily determined

by checklists or physical inspections, and critical to compliance

with either regulatory requirements or area permits.<p>



Audits were not performed by managers. After receiving

training in how to conduct audits, engineers, operators and

secretaries from across the site performed the task. The auditing

function enhanced site compliance activities by providing solid

improvements in detecting and correcting deficiencies.<p>





<H3>CORRECTIVE ACTION AND FOLLOW UP</h3>



The findings of internal audits, together with any other

observed system failures, should be used to assess the appropriate 

actions needed to eliminate undesirable results. Corrective

actions should be documented and analyzed to confirm that the

causes of the problems have been correctly identified and

removed. Consistent follow-up is required to obtain closure on

all recommended corrective actions. In this way, the process is

continually improved.<p>



The Alabama site used this method of corrective action and

follow-up as another pathway to integration by broadly defining

the term "non-conformance". The site defined non-conformance 

to mean any condition that led to results incompatible with

the overall site goals. In this way, chemical spills, accidents, and

permit excursions were addressed side-by-side with product

quality defects, customer complaints and missed deliveries.

When a non-conformance was detected, the team responded

and corrected such non-conformances within a single corrective

action process.<p>



This approach tended to weld all the important factors for

operation of the business, including compliance, into a single

powerful concept. The importance of safety and environmental

non-compliance corrective actions was elevated due to better

visibility across the site and to the broadened understanding of

their importance in the total operation.<p>



<H3>TRAINING</h3>



The importance of training to achieve the desired results cannot

be overstated clearly as the responsibility and activities to

support compliance are shifted downward in an operating

organization the need for both general and specific job training

increases. Further, in many instances such as OSHA's Process

Safety Management (PSM), regulations training is not only

essential but required by law. Since the PSM regulations are

also management-system based, an integrated approach to compliance

is particularly suited to achieving these standards.<p>



Management at the Alabama plant recognized the importance of

training and provided resources for focused training as an

integral part of the compliance program. The importance of

compliance was already a given well designed training programs

filled an important need by helping employees at the site

understand the specific compliance requirement of their jobs.<p>



Once the process of delegating compliance was implemented,

the demand for training within the organization increased as more

personnel become involved in the detection and correction of 

non-conformances. As a result, the EMS professionals found that their

roles shifted from "compliance enforcers" to those of consultants

and trainers, which leveraged their compliance efforts manyfold.<p>



<H3>CONCLUSION: SUCCESSFUL IMPLEMENTATION</h3>



Simply stated, the goal of a successful compliance program is to

ensure that all employees within a business understand how their

job duties can affect compliance. Like quality, compliance must be

achieved at every point where work is proceeding and decisions are

being made. As was seen in the example site program in Alabama,

when compliance knowledge and responsibilities are shared broadly

among many individuals in a business, Compliance is enhanced.<p>



 At most businesses, a significant cultural change will be required

to achieve individual accountability for compliance. The

individuals charged with defining and implementing a compliance

program need first to understand the attitudes that prevail in

their particular organization before they can begin to shape them.

Training and knowledge are the primary tools to help change

attitudes. People with changed attitudes in turn seek more

knowledge and training. The establishment of these training and

awareness resources begins the cycle of continuous improvement.<p>



 The improvement cycle will, over time, move the organizational

culture toward higher levels of integration. Once the process toward

a compliance culture begins, this change drives itself. In the face of

increasing regulation and tougher global competition, the choice

for most organizations will not be whether they should attempt to

create an integrated compliance culture within their operating

organizations, but when they should begin.



<hr><p>



