<BLOCKQUOTE>
<h2>Nuclear Weapons Systems and Compliance Programs</h2>
<!--- full_start: 634--->
<H2>Corporate Compliance: Standards For The 21st Century</h2>

<H3>Seminar Library File</h3>

<H1>Preventive Law Reporter, Winter 1995</H1>

<h5>Copyright&#169;1995 Preventive Law Reporter</h5>



<H4>By HERBERT I. ZINN, Esq.</h4>

<H5>Arizona Public Service Company<br>

Phoenix, Arizona</h5>



Have you ever thought what it must have been like to sit in the

control room of a nuclear missile silo at the height of the Cold

War, just waiting for the alarm to go off? Sitting around a

hundred or more kilotons of nuclear destruction must have been

scary enough. But think what must have gone through the crewman's

mind as he whiled away the long, dreary hours -- waiting for the

unthinkable to happen. Will it scare either guy into not shooting

first; will it fire when I push the button; will it hit the

target after its long journey? And not least of all -- will it do

what it was designed to do?  Vaporize the target?  What will it

be like the day after?<p>



If you think about it, running a compliance program is a lot like

living in a nuclear missile silo.  You never really know if the

system you've designed will work until it is tested.  A clean

record concerning criminal prosecutions or civil claims is no

real test of a compliance program's effectiveness;  just like an

absence of nuclear war is no real test of the missile's

capability as a weapon. Compliance programs and nuclear missiles

are very similar in this respect: they are meant to deter some

undesired consequence. You hope to God you never have to rely on

them, but you will never really know for sure if they can

effectively achieve their objectives unless they are actually put

to the test.<p>



Metaphors aside, the threat of criminal prosecution, third party

lawsuits, gigantic litigation expenses and adverse public image

is the stuff that drives many companies to develop compliance

programs. No one knows for sure they will really work, even

though everyone starts from the same point -- a review of the

checklist for effective compliance programs set forth in <a href=../../../../download/seminars/fsg1.html>Section

8A1.1</a> of the Organizational Sentencing Guidelines (FSGs).<p>



Those in the know may even venture to consider the provisions of

the Draft Sentencing Guidelines For Environmental Crimes,

developed in the wake of the FSGs. (As of this writing, they are

still in draft form.)  Will orthodox observance of the

commandments of these two tablets assure an organization that it

will be insulated from the consequences of legal noncompliance?

Most assuredly not. Those who build their program on the model

described in the FSGs are merely framing out a house that will

have no walls, utilities or furnishings.<p>



<H3>What Is Meant By <I>Effectiveness?</i></h3>



Before effectiveness can be determined, it must be defined. Every

organization has a different notion of the word, based upon its

culture and objectives. Some say effectiveness means a program

that will get up to four points credit off the fine calculations

described in the FSGs. Those organizations stand the greatest

chance of testing their definition and their programs because

they have missed entirely the purpose of a compliance program. In

so doing, they sacrifice effectiveness and they court disaster.<p>



A second school of thought suggests that effectiveness is defined

by the program's ability to ward off criminal convictions. This

too misses the point. Investing the time to develop a compliance

program that addresses only one category of risk is like going to

the shoe store and purchasing only one shoe. You are going to

realize something is wrong shortly after you leave the store.

Why go to the trouble of developing a program if its jurisdiction

does not spread out to all kinds of risk that the organization

may confront: criminal, civil, legal and ethical alike?<p>



There are also those who define effectiveness on a broader scope.

They see its value as a way to proactively address all sorts of

risks, and in doing so, they are apt to wield their program based

on narrow constructions of their legal rights. As a result, they

throw out any notion of using their program to do the right

thing. In the end, they may win the battle, or even the war, but

the cost is enormous. Perhaps almost as costly as it would have

been to strike a settlement early on in the controversy and be

done with it.<p>



A fourth and emerging view among compliance scientists is that

effectiveness is defined on a very broad, multi-faceted front:<p>



&iuml; By the organization's ability to proactively perceive its

risks in every area of endeavor in which it functions and to

adjust its activities in a way that comports with the

expectations of the standards to which it is subject;<p>



&iuml; By the program's ability to spare the organization from

costly lessons, in terms of fines, damage awards and litigation

costs;<p>



&iuml; By the program's ability to build a culture in the

organization that is renowned for its appreciation of laudable

conduct; and,<p>



&iuml; If needed, by the program's ability to convince a

prosecutor to decline to prosecute (and, as a corollary, its

ability to convince the Court that, indeed, the organization is

entitled to the maximum consideration of its program under the

FSGs in terms of point reductions).<p>



<H3>How Can A Compliance Program Demonstrate Effectiveness?</h3>



Let's assume then that you buy into the definition that an

effective compliance program proactively manages risk, controls

litigation costs and avoids costly fines and damage awards.  How

do you know that your program effectively pursues these

objectives? Obviously, the absence of suits, fines and/or legal

fees is not the litmus test. One way to tell if you have an

effective compliance program (albeit in this writer's opinion not

the best way) is to test it against the provisions of the FSGs

and the Draft Environmental Guidelines.  The FSGs describe the

effective compliance program model in very strategic terms, laid

out in <I>Section 8A1.2(3)(k)</i> as seven basic criteria:<p>



<H5>Established compliance standards;<p>



Oversight by high-level personnel in the organization;<p>



Due diligence in the selection of employees and agents

who possess substantial discretionary authority;<p>



Training and communications;<p>



Monitoring and auditing;<p>



Non-discriminatory discipline; and<p>



Reasonable response to an occurrence of noncompliance

when it is discovered.</h5>



These are expressed in broad, strategic terms because they really

only give a hint at one approach to effectiveness. The criteria

purposefully do not take into consideration how they would work

in a variety of situations, such as differing organizational

size, industry or activity. The FSGs do instruct the Court to

consider their application based upon the size and sophistication

of the organization. However, that does not help the practitioner

understand how to proactively address effectiveness in the

design, implementation and management of the program.<p>



Nevertheless, these criteria are accepted in many quarters as the

bare minimum that must be considered when you undertake the

creation of a compliance program. In other words, <I>you are

courting with disaster if your program does not at least reflect

some aspect of each of these seven commandments</i>.<p>



The simple point here is that in terms of effectiveness, <I>the

devil is in the details</i>. A rigid, uninspired adherence to the

FSGs' definition of effectiveness will not only lead to

ineffectiveness, but also to a result opposite to what was

intended. Some very basic, good ideas about organizational

culture are reflected in the seven criteria that make sense.

Obviously, there needs to be something more. Let me suggest that

the <I>something more</i> starts with a thorough appreciation for

organizational culture. A commitment must be made to mold the

culture to deal with the little details upon which effectiveness

depends, to the extent of identifiable deficiencies that can

contribute to wrongdoing.<p>



In my opinion, the most important ingredient in assuring

effectiveness is the commitment of the highest authority in the

organization to a culture in which compliance thrives. Coupled

with a commitment (in terms of accountability, resources and

follow-through) at all personnel levels, it assures that the

vision of effective compliance is indeed appreciated as a core

value of the organization. It must be clearly appreciated by

everyone in the organization that if an employee or agent does

not agree with the philosophy of compliance endorsed as a value

of the organization, they had better consider employment

elsewhere. Harsh, yes, but so are the consequences if this

commitment does not translate into action.<p>



This may sound vanilla-coated, but why bother creating a

compliance program if you are not dedicated to its effective

operation? Even if the management of your organization considers

orthodox compliance to be an inappropriate invasion by government

into corporate management, consider this simple rationale for

effective compliance: if nothing else, it can be an important

cost management tool. If economic survival is an issue for the

organization, given today's competitive business environment,

then there is ample reason to be serious about compliance.

Economic survival is itself reason to take compliance very

seriously because noncompliance is a wasteful sink hole for

corporate dollars that could be better utilized elsewhere.<p>



In determining if the Draft Environmental Guidelines alter the

conclusion reached to this point, I think not. The Draft

Guidelines suggest to me a better appreciation by the draftsmen

for the facets of organizational culture that contribute to a

successful program in that they formulate strategies that make a

lot of sense. Pick up any book or article on effective compliance

programming, you will likely find the principles in the Draft

Guidelines are already there in some form or another. In articles

and texts, however, they are less threatening than they are in

the stone-like reality of an official guideline published by an

agency of the government.<p>



So, again, I come to the conclusion that effectiveness cannot be

prescribed, dictated or even measured based upon words on a page.

In this respect, neither the FSGs nor the Draft Environmental

Guidelines are useful tools in measuring effectiveness. The

essential ingredient to the "Secret Sauce" of effective

compliance rests on an intangible that can never be measured from

a page. That ingredient is the organization's adoption of a core

value that places adherence to <I>the right thing</i> very high up on

the list of accountabilities for employees and agents. In this

way, there is no mistaking the fact that in times of conflict

between the compliance core value and other values defined for

the organization, compliance will not be sacrificed, compromised

or watered down. Vanilla? Yes. Hard to administer? Yes. A little

unrealistic?  Maybe.  But why bother if you do not start at the

beginning?<p>



You can only make things worse for you and your organization if

the commitment to compliance is a mere charade. The risks extend

out beyond the direct fines and penalties that will inevitably

come your way. Indirect costs include:<p>



&iuml; The excessive cost of dealing with the incident;<p>



&iuml; The adverse impact on your organization's reputation in

your industry and in the community at large;<p>



&iuml; Increased costs of doing sloppy business, such as

interest on borrowings, lower market value of stock, higher

insurance premiums and higher workers compensation; and<p>



&iuml; The increased risk of shareholder dissatisfaction leading

to removal of executive management and directors, derivative

suits, etc.<p>



Truly effective compliance cannot be defined in terms of point

scores when your organization gets fined.  It must and does mean

something much more fundamental.<p>



<H3>Some Ways A Program Can Be Made To Work Effectively</h3>



I suppose at this point, to convince you that there is some truth

to this, I had better produce some worthwhile suggestions. In my

opinion, a compliance program has a chance to be effective if the

major emphasis is on proactivity. I do not mean to suggest that

reaction to incidents is not important, but the prime directive

of an effective compliance program should not be to react

appropriately to events of noncompliance. It should be to

minimize, if not eliminate, the opportunity for the noncompliance

to happen in the first place.  With this in mind, here are some

suggestions for ways to bolster the preventive aspects of the

program and its effectiveness.<p>



<H3>Common Sense Rules</h3>



"Common sense" is defined in three ways:<p>



&iuml; What value does the rule have to the employee who has to

live by it and use it;<p>



&iuml; What language is used to communicate the meaning and

intentions of the rule; and<p>



&iuml; What examples are offered to help the employee understand

the setting in which the rule is to be employed and the objective

to be achieved?<p>



The rules must take into consideration the organization's risk.

But at the same time they must recall that <I>people</i> create those

risks and have to be instructed and trained to identify  and

reduce them  in a predetermined way.<p>



Instead of setting out a brightline rule in your code of conduct,

consider a brief discussion in plain English about an employee's

job risks, why the risks need addressing and what can be done

about them. Then set down the rules, so there is some

appreciation for the issues.<p>



Another core issue is to make certain that every type of employee

receives the same message. In other words, front-line employees

should not be made to strictly follow rules while managers bend

them. Front-line employees will pick up the hypocrisy very early

-- breeding morale problems, inordinate risk takers and

whistleblowers galore.<p>



<H3>"Z Team" Type Involvement</h3>



"Z Teams" are a phenomenon of the reengineering craze. A "Z Team"

is a task group brought together to study and achieve a

particular result. Issues are considered from different

perspectives in the organization (including professionals,

management and support staff), as well as individuals with

differing job skills and backgrounds. In theory it creates a

better product in the sense that all relevant perspectives are

brought to bear on the formulation of solutions to common

organizational problems.<p>



If you expect a variety of different personalities to read the

same rule and get the same meaning from it, why not involve a

sampling of the variety in the formulation of your rules and in

the creation and management of the program? It may seem

complicated, but if managed correctly, it needn't be. You can

also gain an important element of effectiveness: the more cross-

boundary the fingerprints are on the program, the more likely it

will gain support and buy-in throughout the organization. Chances

are the product will be more reflective of the sub-values found

in differing areas of the organization.<p>



This type of involvement can be as simple as establishing

compliance teams in each department that are charged with taking

the rules and studying them to identify those that are relevant

to the workings of the department. By making front line employees

responsible for implementing the compliance program in the

department, you create a valuable tool.  Employees are exposed to

the rules in a meaningful way. They are made to think about them

and apply them to their jobs in ways that are meaningful to co-

workers. They also gain the opportunity to give feedback where

there are problems, instead of letting the problems persist

unknown or unremedied.<p>



<H3>Effective Management Oversight</h3>



Many organizations subscribe to the <I>"Flavor of the Month"</i>

Syndrome. They implement a new program or idea, expecting it to

be followed, but do little if anything in the follow-through to

support or assure its operation as intended.<p>



In the compliance context, follow-through can be defined

according to these considerations:<p>



&iuml; Establishing expressed accountabilities throughout the

organization's management to assure that compliance is a core

value similar to cost management,  customer service,  good

operating results and profitability.<p>



&iuml; Working hard to avoid double standards. Nothing impresses

employees more about management's insincerity than a code of

conduct that is like two sets of books -- one to apply to the

employees (generally with strict results) and one to apply to the

management and officers.<p>



&iuml; Direct, routine and visible involvement of executive

management in compliance issues to assure that the importance of

the subject is not lost as the organization's environment evolves

and changes. This can be achieved through one-on-one meetings

with executive management as they visit with departments or

through regular communications throughout the organization using

all sorts of media.<p>



&iuml; Routine Board review of compliance performance to

identify problems, issues and concerns. This should be led by

independent members of the Board who are not officers of the

organization. They may be a little more immune from the politics

of day-to-day management and may also bring in fresh

perspectives.<p>



&iuml; Visible celebration by management of good results

(discussed in more detail below).<p>



&iuml; Good listening skills. Employee concerns need to be

considered seriously by management and are treated with the same

degree of concern as if the message was delivered by angry

stockholders.<p>



<H3>Outside Critiques</h3>



Do you really care about the quality of your system of internal

controls? Why not ask others in your industry to critique your

compliance program? Some industries have established forums where

members meet to address the formulation of strategies to deal

with compliance issues. Others monitor trade organizations to

determine what is being done in the industry.<p>



Consider going an additional step. Locate one or more members of

your industry who are willing to work with you, conduct a best

practices study of their programs and decide if what you've

learned would be worth considering for your organization. Then

take this step further. From time to time, invite your neighbor

to do an informal review of your program and provide you with a

critique.<p>



Why would another organization want to cooperate with you on

this? Aren't they short enough on resources as it is, without

taking on the added responsibility of auditing your company? The

answer may lie in your willingness to reciprocate the favor free

of charge, thereby avoiding expensive formal audits by outside

experts for both parties.<p>



At first blush, this will drive legal counsel nuts. How can you

advocate the creation of non-privileged audits that suggest

shortcomings in your compliance program by third parties who are

not bound to secrecy, who may not be credible in their opinions

and who may inartfully draw conclusions that set illusory

standards? These are valid concerns, and now that we have

identified them, go about dealing with them rather than using

them as a rationale to discredit this approach. For example, pick

your partners carefully after considering their expertise and

reputation for compliance.<p>



If you are so privilege conscious, have your respective in-house

or outside counsel anchor the exercise. If you are still dubious,

agree up front not to create a paper trail. It is healthy to

proactively seek out criticism of one's program. The harm is not

identifying the shortcoming, and failing to promptly address its

correction when it is uncovered.<p>



<H3>Ample Real-Time Recognition For Good Performance</h3>



Actually, this aspect of effectiveness is a revisitation of the

role and importance of management in compliance programming. A

reward system rests principally upon management and its

willingness to use material gratitude as a way of promoting

desired conduct and performance.<p>



The most frequent complaint I hear about recognition is that it

comes too late rather than that it is too little. The easiest

thing to say is "job well done," but this is often difficult for

some managers. Desired performance and habit needs to be promoted

and encouraged.  Reward is the way to do that and "real time"

reward works best.<p>



Simply defined, "real-time" reward is recognition that happens

when the desired conduct is witnessed. Some reward systems merely

catalogue good performance, and annually, the employee hears

about something good or bad he did almost a year later. "Real

time" reward works to remind the employee at the time of

performance that desired performance was appreciated. The result

will likely be that the employee will seek to repeat the

performance to ensure eligibility for more recognition.<p>



If you want to build trust, encourage employees to take notice of

the legal and ethical aspects of their jobs and to hunt out

issues that may be risks to them and their organization.

Encourage performance not with the threat of discipline, but with

the offer of thanks that comes from a reward system that is

designed to reinforce the objectives of the compliance program.<p>



<H3>Excellence in Communication</h3>



Too often, organizations take for granted the resources tied up

in communications.  Excellence in communication is developed, but

never used to capacity. For instance, some companies invest in

state-of-the-art video systems but never use them as the

principal means to get messages to employees. Or they employ

substantial staffs of workers to write articles that miss

opportunities to include valuable messages that promote

compliance. Many organizations don't have effective

communications about compliance because they miss simple

opportunities to weave a compliance message into mainstream

communications that are delivered to the workforce.<p>



Another dimension of excellence in communication is frequency.

This is not daily feedings of compliance news, but more than an

annual refresher. At a minimum, effective compliance

communication takes into consideration at least these factors:<p>



&iuml; More frequent communication in areas of higher risk to

the organization, its employees and agents.<p>



&iuml; Prompt communication when incidents occur, to ward off

the ill effects of the rumor mill and the resulting confusion and

adverse effects on morale. This needs to be tempered by and

coordinated with your program's response plan in order to

preserve applicable privileges and other timing concerns.<p>



&iuml; Employment of plain-English "war stories" that employees

and agents understand and can relate to in their job capacities.<p>



&iuml; Explicit accountability of leaders and managers to

regularly share information with employees that is needed to

enable them to do their jobs in a compliant way.<p>



&iuml; Diversity in the way messages are delivered. Redundancy

is not wasteful: if it gets the message across, it is cost

beneficial.<p>



<H3Down-Top Feedback</h3>



This is effective communication revisited, too. To me, the

correct definition of communication is <I>the exchange of ideas or

information</i> -- meaning that for communication to work, it has to

be two-way in nature.<p>



Returning messages in an organization is very, very important.

They are the way to determine if your message was understood or

even received. They convey to you shortcomings in the quality,

accuracy or completeness of the message that may require that you

re-adjust what it is you are saying to your employees. They are a

morale-building vehicle.<p>



Employees who know that they can talk to their management, share

their views and, most importantly, have their views heard and

acted upon, tend to buy into management's goals and form a

stronger bond for the overall benefit of the organization.<p>



Conversely, it can be a devastating element on the morale of the

workforce to realize that management could not care less about

their opinions, concerns or knowledge. It breeds contempt for

management and, worse, costly litigation in the form of

employment suits and whistleblowing proceedings.<p>



<H3>Fast, Sincere Reaction to Concerns</h3>



Let's not overlook sincerity in terms of the organization's

response to concerns raised by employees. I confess this is a

little bit redundant, but it is worth emphasizing from another

perspective. Most often, actions speak louder than words. People

need little convincing about one's intentions when they see them

graphically depicted in one's deeds. The same goes for

organizations, too. A truly effective compliance program is

characterized by compassion for those employees who raise <I>bona

fide</i> concerns in the form of a question about how to apply a

rule, or an employee who raises a concern that a violation has

occurred.<p>



<H3>Practice Drills</h3>



If you don't come from an industry that confronts material

emergencies from time to time, the notion of emergency drills may

seem foreign. Nuclear utilities undertake them routinely to

sharpen the skills of their personnel, to make certain the

emergency program works in keeping with reality and to provide

important feedback on the quality of the emergency program so

that needed corrections can be made.<p>



Why not try a practice drill to test your compliance program's

effectiveness? It doesn't have to be something elaborate. It

doesn't even have to be something that is undertaken company-wide

at the same time. Select departments or areas (especially high-

risk areas) can challenge each other to determine how the program

works in real situations, to test employee familiarity, to

identify shortcomings and to communicate them to "Compliance

Central" for consideration and follow-up.<p>



<H3>Reactive Elements And Their Relevance To Effectiveness</h3>



To this point, I have confined our discussion to proactivity as

the key factor of effectiveness.  This should not be taken as an

implication that effectiveness is in no way measured by the

reaction to incidents of noncompliance. If this were true, then

the provisions of the FSGs that consider the quality of how an

organization responds would have no meaning.<p>



Reaction is, of course, the more difficult aspect of compliance.

It comes at a time when circumstances have framed your options

for you. You may not be at liberty to take any course of action

except those that are inherently distasteful, e.g., calling up

the regulatory authorities and disclosing that someone on your

staff has violated the law.<p>



Nevertheless, the quality of reaction is an important element in

a program's effectiveness.  Though I do not place as much value

on it, this discussion of effectiveness would be incomplete

without explaining how reaction can make your program effective.<p>



Reaction needs to be genuine. Too often, the first thing that the

organization does is commission a team of lawyers to recast the

facts in a way that favors not dealing with the incident. This

creates a pattern or habit that applies to close calls and clear

violations alike.  It is distasteful to have to call one's

regulator and self-report. But if you are going to run an

effective compliance program, you need to buy into the model that

calls for decisive action when wrongdoing is discovered.  This is

the scary end of the compliance business.<p>



Consistency also plays an important role. When an issue of non-

compliance arises, assuming it is covered by the rules set by the

compliance program, then it should be resolved according to the

rules. Otherwise employees will be left asking whether there has

been a slight of hand, or how the rule is intended to apply if

not to the situation in question.<p>



As hard as this may be to swallow, the organization should be

open and honest with employees about the incident. To the extent

the employees can be provided with information, they should be

briefed (which will cause the lawyers fits). But considering your

employees are also members of the community, and if an incident

arises and is broadcast into the community, they may well be

accosted by neighbors who want to know what they know about the

incident. This is a dangerous issue to deal with, but it should

be dealt with by a program that considers itself effective.<p>



Don't transfer responsibility for the decision-making process to

lawyers. I am a lawyer myself, and so my remarks here should not

be taken as bashing. The plain fact is that lawyers should do no

more than facilitate the making of decisions. To subordinate

responsibility to lawyers for appropriate reaction is an exercise

in irresponsibility.<p>



If the culture of the organization tends toward frank, open

relations with the organization's regulators in good times, there

is no reason to alter this strategy when some adversity enters

the relationship. If you have spent lots of time creating good

relationships, rely on them when things go wrong; instead of

putting up a barrier of lawyers between you and the people whom

you tried so hard to impress with your credibility and good

intentions.  If you have a good story to tell, do so, and don't

hide information behind attorney-client privileges and work

product protection. Of course, this is a generalization. Under

some circumstances, the best defense relies upon the ability of

your lawyer to buy you time or advocate your position. But to

polarize your relationship right-off the bat without considering

the personal side of relations may cost you dearly in terms of

the end result.<p>



<h3>Conclusion</h3>



So, there you are, sitting hunkered down and snug in your bunker.

You are protected by the hope that when the missiles start

flying, your defensive shield will protect you and your

organization from annihilation -- or at least severe penalties,

costs and adverse publicity.  You take comfort in the fact that

you paid a lot of dollars to have some experts develop this

compliance thing for your company. Based on the experts'

reputation, you have no reason to believe that if things go sour,

it will not work as advertised.<p>



You leaf through the compliance manual at page after page of

procedures and guidelines that are supposed to be followed by

your employees if something goes wrong. Something, however, is in

the back of your mind nagging at you. <I>When was the last time we

had a drill to test the systems and see if they work as we

intended them to work? Does everyone on the team understands his

or her role in the process?</i> The nagging persists: <I>when was the

last time I went over the rules in our code of conduct? I don't

even remember the rules that apply to me and my department. I

wonder if the other members of my department are as ill prepared

as I am?</i>  Makes you feel that you have a very effective weapons

system there, does it?<p>



The fact of the matter is no program or system is worthy of the

title "effective" if it is not tested and challenged regularly to

make certain that it is designed to meet the evolving threats

that it is intended to overcome. Moreover, effectiveness begs at

the issue of how much attention you have paid to the prime

details that drive your program. Such details include risks that

your organization confronts, the culture of your organization,

the role of management in the process and its relationship with

the front-line, the appreciation for input from all members of

the team and the willingness to do the right thing even when it

is distasteful to do so.<p>



In this respect, an effective compliance program is indeed scary.

The scary part is in the realization that if things go wrong and

you have to use it, it will be distasteful -- but its use will

afford you the protection you designed it to achieve. Like a

nuclear weapon system, a compliance system is scary because it

depends upon your commitment to live with the process, push the

buttons in sequence and roll with the process no matter what.

Like a nuclear weapons system, a compliance program's

effectiveness resides in the things you hope you may never need

to test in reality. Faith in its scariness and commitment to stay

with the program are what buys you the maximum protection it can

afford.

<hr><p>

